<DOCNO> AP880421-0006 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-PUSH 1stAdd a0409 04-21 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-PUSH, 1st Add, a0409,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: PUSH network.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On the other side of the ledger, PUSH improved business
opportunities for blacks by persuading corporations to sign
``covenants'' promising jobs and franchises to minorities _ often
after PUSH threatened or carried out boycotts of a company's
product.
   From the start, on Christmas 1971, Jackson vowed the group would
``picket, vote and if necessary engage in civil disobedience'' to
achieve its goals.
   Williams, now a member of the Atlanta City Council, recalled
Jackson had quit as head of a similar group, Operation Breadbasket,
an arm of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, after
clashing with SCLC leaders over expenditures and Jackson's
independent streak.
   Jackson built PUSH into a network with chapters in 32 cities,
taking in $16.8 million from 1975 to 1986, the last year for which
state financial records were filed.
   He also used the PUSH platform to take on the administrations of
several presidents and the city hierarchy of Chicago on a range of
issues, from U.S. policy in Central America to contracts for
minority-owned businesses.
   PUSH's Saturday meetings are part of Chicago's political
landscape, mixing the gospel flavor of a Southern church revival
with Jackson's stirring speeches on the day's hot issues.
   From the PUSH pulpit, Jackson pressured companies, such as
Burger King and Coca-Cola, to sign minority opportunity compacts.
   ``Jesse was instrumental in making a lot of opportunities
available _ by that I mean distributorships, getting blacks placed
in jobs in chain stores,'' said Dempsey Travis, a Chicago
businessman and Jackson supporter.
   PUSH officials have long been secretive about the group's
sources of money, other than to say it is supported by individual
memberships that now cost $20 a person and donations from
businesses.
   Some of the corporations that signed covenants with PUSH also
contributed money to help sponsor its annual convention or other
activities. Coors Brewery, for example, gave $20,000 last year to a
major PUSH scholarship fund-raising event in Chicago.
   In 1977, Jackson broadened PUSH's mission by starting PUSH-Excel
to get inner-city youths to study harder. He spoke in packed school
gymnasiums nationwide, with students joining in his trademark
chant: ``I am ... somebody!''
   After Jackson fired up the students, PUSH-Excel worked with
local school officials to set up special clubs and programs to help
keep the youths motivated.
   But federal auditors later contended that government money
received from 1979 to 1982 went for such layouts as $211 for music
and flowers for a 1979 press party in Los Angeles; ``$650 for
Christmas cards purchased for a related organization''; $28 for
funeral flowers, and $15 for a parking ticket.
   The government has referred PUSH-Excel's $1.2 million debt to
the Justice Department for collection.
   ``As of now, we haven't been able to resolve it,'' said Justice
spokesman Amy Brown.
   PUSH-Excel dramatized Jackson's strengths, and weaknesses, said
Ernest House, an education professor who has just finished writing
a book about Jackson and the student-motivation program.
   ``Jesse had a lot of very good ideas. He has trouble carrying
them through _ that has been his problem,'' said House, who is
director of the policy studies laboratory at the University of
Colorado at Boulder.
   ``They went through three or four directors, one right after the
other, and this was part of his difficulty in administering the
program,'' House said.
   By 1986, PUSH-Excel's revenues, which peaked at $2.6 million in
1980, had dropped to $209,071 and the group ended the year with a
$1.5 million debt, including the money owed to the government.
   Operation PUSH wasn't much better off. It started 1986 with a
$339,056 deficit, but took in enough money to reduce the debt to
$84,914 by the end of the year, according to its annual report
filed with the state.
   The Rev. Willie Barrow, PUSH's national executive director, did
not return repeated telephone calls asking for information about
the organization's current financial status.
   Frank Watkins, Jackson's longtime aide and spokesman, said he
understood the group had succeeded this year in nearly erasing its
deficit.
   Although Jackson was PUSH's driving force, his supporters say he
shouldn't be blamed for organizational problems in areas delegated
to subordinates. Jackson himself has said he didn't get involved in
mechanical details.
   ``If there was anything sloppy about Jesse's management, it was
that he could not afford paid, competent people to deal with the
various functions of accounting and management of government
programs,'' said Bishop H.H. Bookins, a leader in the African
Methodist Episcopal church and a Jackson supporter.
   ``Jesse's main thrust was at raising funds to keep the
organization afloat. So it was impossible for him to be a hands-on
manager of things,'' he said.
   Jackson supporters point to the success of his 1988 presidential
campaign as evidence he can recruit able people to assist him.
   Leon Davis, who worked as PUSH's national executive director in
1972, said he sees a different Jackson today.
   ``From the time I worked with Jesse, it seems to me he has grown
tremendously and his campaign points out one thing _ he has
delegated authority. ''
</TEXT>
