<DOCNO> AP880421-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BicoastalEconomy Bjt   04-21 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bicoastal Economy, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Belt, Mountain States' Income Catching Up With Coastal States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government statistics may be signaling the
beginning of the end of a mid-1980s trend that saw booming growth
in coastal states outstrip the rest of the country, economists say.
   Residents of densely populated coastal states like Connecticut,
New Jersey, Massachussets and California continued to have the
highest average incomes in the nation last year, the Commerce
Department said Wednesday.
   States like Mississippi, West Virginia, Utah and Louisiana that
are dependent on farming, mining or oil were at or near the bottom.
   Connecticut was the highest-income state in the nation, with an
average of $20,980 earned for every man, woman and child in 1987.
That was more than double the $10,204 income in Mississippi, the
perennial last-place finisher.
   Also as in the recent past, income growth was strongest in the
Northeast and weakest in energy and mining states.
   But, Rudolph E. DePass, an analyst with the Commerce Department,
says the figures show growth is accelerating in the Southwest and
Rocky Mountain regions and slowing elsewhere.
   The national average in 1987 was $15,340, up 4.8 percent from a
year earlier. Taking the 4.4 percent inflation rate into account,
it was the worst gain since the recession year of 1982.
   That was reflected in even the healthiest regions. The growth of
income in New England fell from 7.6 percent in 1986 to 6.7 percent
last year. Income growth slipped from 6.5 percent to 6 percent in
the Mid-Atlantic states.
   However, income growth in the tottering Southwest increased from
0.9 percent to 2.2 percent. It improved in the Mountain states from
3.5 percent to 3.6 percent.
   ``I think it's signaling the end of the bicoastal economy,''
said Mark Zandi, an economist with the Wefa Group, a
Philadelphia-area forecasting service.
   ``The bicoastal trend came to the forefront in 1984 and
continued on through most of the first half of 1987. Since last
summer ... the bicoastal phenomenon has been on the wane,'' Zandi
said.
   ``As we move into 1989 and 1990, it will become a thing of the
past, almost as the Sun Belt-Frost Belt phenomenon waned in the
middle 1980s,'' he said.
   Zandi cited these reasons:
   _The increase in exports, which are growing as the falling
dollar makes U.S. goods cheaper overseas, will boost manufacturing
in the Midwest and in parts of the South.
   _Oil and commodity prices are on the way up, brightening
prospects for the Oil Patch, Farm Belt and mining states.
   _Growth in the economy's service sector _ which had benefited
financial centers like New York, Boston and Los Angeles _ is
slowing. The effects of the October stock market collapse are more
severe there than elsewhere.
   _Eastern states and California, which rode the growth of high
technology firms, are running into a tight labor market, making it
likely that companies will look to expand elsewhere.
   ``We can expect to see slower growth in the bicoastal states and
stronger growth in the states in the middle,'' Zandi said.
   New Jersey, with income of $20,067, ranked second in 1987 and
Masschussetts, with income of $18,926, was third. The District of
Columbia, with income of $20,303, would have been second if it was
included in the rankings.
   Alaska, which took over the No.1 spot from Connecticut at the
start of the oil boom in 1973 and held it until 1985, fell to fifth
in 1987. Its average income actually fell 0.7 percent last year to
$17,886.
   Rounding out the top 10 were New York, Maryland, California, New
Hampshire, Illinois and Virginia.
   Seven of the 10 states with the lowest per capita income were in
the South. In addition to Mississippi, they were West Virginia,
Arkansas, Louisiana, Alabama, South Carolina and Kentucky. Utah,
New Mexico and Idaho _ energy and mining states _ were also in the
lowest 10.
   Other than Alaska, Wyoming was the only state where average
income declined in 1987, by 0.1 percent to $12,759. But the
shrinkage was not as bad as the state's 1.1 percent decline in 1986.
</TEXT>
