<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Kenya-Everest,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenya Plans Everest Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenya plans to become the first African
country to send an expedition to Mount Everest, the world's highest
peak.
   Kenneth Matiba, minister for transport and communications, said
a team of 15 to 20 climbers will attempt to scale the mountain in
autumn of 1990.
   ``As a sporting nation, this is one sport I feel we must
increase our participation in,'' Matiba said on Wednesday.
   He led a five-man Kenyan expedition up the 20,500-foot Island
Peak of the Himalayas in Ocotober 1986.
   ``At that time we were happy to climb anything higher than what
we have in Kenya,'' said Matiba. ``But I got the idea that we
should send a team up Mount Everest and approached the Nepalese
authorities.''
   Mount Kenya, this East African nation's highest mountain and the
second highest on the continent, is 17,156 feet high.
