<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AutoTalks     04-21 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Wants Japanese-Style Pay For Japanese-Style Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Chrysler Corp. wants its workers
to accept Japanese-style production, its executives should accept
markedly lower, Japanese-style pay, the United Auto Workers' chief
negotiator said Wednesday.
   The remarks by UAW Vice President Marc Stepp came in the third
day of Chrysler contract talks and a day after Chrysler disclosed
that Chairman Lee Iacocca earned $17.9 million in 1987 in salary,
cash and stock bonuses and money earned exercising stock options
granted when Chrysler stock was a fraction of its present value.
   Iacocca's 1987 earnings made him the highest-paid auto executive
for the second year in a row. In 1986, when he earned $20.6
million, Iacocca also was the nation's highest-paid executive.
   ``Executive compensations have gotten completely out of hand.
... It makes it extremely difficult for us to sit down in a
rational manner and try to negotiate a decent contract,'' Stepp
said, adding that after hearing about Iacocca's pay, workers called
union officials demanding higher pay and other benefits.
   Chrysler Vice President Anthony St. John, the company's chief
negotiator, said Tuesday that Chrysler has asked union leaders to
support a company push for adoption of so-called Modern Operating
Agreements at all plants.
   The Japanese-style MOA system organizes workers into teams, uses
them for a variety of jobs instead of a single defined task and
reduces the number of workers needed to fill in for absentees,
inspect products and correct mistakes.
   ``We think it is only fair that since they ask us to go to a
Japanese production system such as MOAs and team concept ... it is
fair for them to go to the Japanese system in terms of
compensation,'' Stepp said.
   Japanese managers earn six to eight times more than Japanese
workers, while American managers earn about 18 times more than
their workers, and in Iacocca's case, 27 times, Stepp said.
   Chrysler workers earn $14.43 an hour including cost-of-living
adjustments, or gross base pay of about $30,000. Stepp also said
that before Japanese workers are laid off or their pay is cut,
Japanese managers take a pay cut.
   The Chrysler contract expires Sept. 14. It covers 59,000 active
workers and 7,000 on layoff in 15 states and 65,000 retirees.
Negotiators return to the table Monday prepared to bargain
continuously until a contract is reached, Stepp said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
