<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0989</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump, who scored a public relations coup
over City Hall by rebuilding the Central Park skating rink, has
been invited to try again.
   This time, the federal government is suggesting that the
mega-developer show the city how to fix the closed-down
Williamsburg Bridge.
   At the invitation of Alfred Dellibovi, head of the federal Urban
Mass Transportation Administration, Trump plans to bring his
engineers to the deteriorated span today to study how to get it
back into operation.
   There was no immediate reaction from Mayor Edward I. Koch, who
in recent years has been trading insults with Trump regularly over
how the city is run.
   In a letter to Trump, Dellibovi lauded him as a builder whose
projects come in ``on time, under budget and built to last.''
   In 1987, Trump showed up Koch and the city bureaucracy when he
took over repair of the skating rink and finished the job in five
months and under budget. The city had spent 7{ years and $12
million on what was supposed to take 2{ years and $4.5 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOREHEAD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss America Kaye Lani Rae Rafko and
pageant finalist Laurie Keller have some advice for up-and-coming
pageanteers: Don't worry about your wardrobe when a good belly
dance can do the trick.
   ``Just remember, the people in the audience don't have the guts
to do what you're doing,'' Miss Rafko told the 18 contestants in
the Miss Morehead State University Pageant on Tuesday night.
   ``Don't be intimidated by the others' wardrobes,'' said Miss
Keller, who was Miss Kentucky 1985 and a top-10 finalist for Miss
America. ``I've seen some girls go out in a $50 suit and win the
whole thing.''
   Miss Rafko, the special guest of the pageant, performed the
belly dance act that helped her win the title.
   ``They all told me, `Just be Kaye Lani and you'll do fine,'' she
said of her seven-year quest for the crown. ``Then they said,
`Hawaiian Tahitian dancing will never make it to Atlantic City.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTICELLO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broadcast executive Ted Turner, who has
tried in the past to tame the broadcast industry, pleaded no
contest to illegally importing wild mountain lions and was fined
$1,500.
   Turner, 49, also was ordered to produce public service
announcements for two wildlife groups after entering the plea
Tuesday in Jefferson County Court to three counts of importing the
animals to his plantation near here without a permit.
   The charges were filed last month after one of the lions brought
from a plantation in South Carolina was hit by a vehicle on
Interstate 10.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bess Myerson, the former Miss America and former
city official who is under indictment, may have developed a keen
interest in the law.
   According to New York Newsday, Miss Myerson is among the
students taking a preparation class for the Law School Admission
Test at the Stanley H. Kaplan Educational Center here.
   ``We're not allowed to divulge who our students are. We promise
confidentiality,'' Kaplan said Wednesday.
   Newsday reported that Miss Myerson _ who goes on trial in
September for allegedly trying to fix the divorce trial of her
boyfriend, convicted felon Carl ``Andy'' Capasso _ indicated she
was interested in going to law school.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin, responding to a plea by Nancy
Reagan, has asked ``every mover and shaker in this part of the
world'' to a $5 million breakfast to help make the first lady's
anti-drug dream come true.
   The former talk show host and entrepreneur will be host of a May
2 gathering at his Beverly Hills home. He hopes to raise half the
$10 million needed to start up the Nancy Reagan Center for drug
abuse.
   In addition to Mrs. Reagan, the 50 guests at the ``power
breakfast'' will include oilmen Marvin Davis and Armand Hammer,
publisher Rupert Murdoch, developer David Murdock, and producer
Grant Tinker.
   Griffin, describing the group as ``every mover and shaker in
this part of the world,'' said he wants to have the center ready
for the Reagans' move back to Los Angeles after they leave the
White House in January.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert von Karajan, the world-famous maestro of
the Berlin Philharmonic, has canceled a weekend concert appearance
because he is ill, a spokeswoman for the orchestra said.
   Karajan, who celebrated his 80th birthday on April 5, had been
scheduled to conduct the orchestra in a concert on Sunday in West
Berlin.
   Also on his schedule is a concert tour next week in Japan.
   ``He won't appear at the Sunday concert, but we are assuming he
will be traveling to Japan since he has not canceled out on that,''
spokeswoman Birgit Alter said Wednesday.
   George Schaefer, director of the Philharmonic, said the
flamboyant maestro is suffering from a stomach flu.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Garrey Carruthers is taking a look at
the effects of New Mexico's speed-limit increase from 55 mph to 65
mph with the help of a radar gun installed on the dash of his state
car.
   Carruthers said he used the radar gun Tuesday on a drive on
Interstate 25 from Santa Fe to Albuquerque.
   ``I find the lion's share (of the drivers) are content with
65,'' he said. ``But 65 doesn't give you license to go 85.''
   Carruthers was one of the first governors to order the
replacement of 55 mph signs with 65 mph signs on rural stretches of
interstate highways after Congress approved the change a year ago.
   The governor said he was only conducting research, not handing
out citations.
</TEXT>
