<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialMoney     04-21 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Money,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Notches Best Fund-Raising Month Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is moving up to the fund-raising
league of Gov. Michael Dukakis, who has consistently outpaced all
other Democratic presidential candidates, new financial reports
show.
   Dukakis last month raised a total of $3.4 million, including
$621,098 in federal matching funds. Jackson reported raising $2.8
million, including $330,189 from the federal matching account. It
was Jackson's biggest ever fund-raising month.
   In money that came directly from contributors, Jackson took in
$2 million, to Dukakis' $2.4 million.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who was expected to suspend his
campaign today, ran up a debt of $1.6 million during March. He took
out $1.5 million in loans, including $40,000 in a personal loan to
the campaign.
   Gore borrowed the money to spend on the March 8 Super Tuesday
series of 20 primaries, on which he had pinned his hopes.
   He then borrowed another $100,000 more this month before
Tuesday's New York primary, where he pulled a disappointing 10
percent of the vote, trailing far behind Dukakis and Jackson.
   Dukakis has taken no loans. Jackson borrowed $250,000 during
March.
   Gore's overall receipts for March were $3.4 million, of which
$336,312 was matching funds, his report showed.
   Because he received less than 10 percent of the vote in two
previous successive primaries, Gore lost his eligibility for
federal matching funds under election law. He would have to get an
unlikely 20 percent of the vote in Pennsylvania's primary next week
in order to re-establish his eligibility.
   Among Republicans, former TV evangelist Pat Robertson borrowed
$410,000 to keep his campaign afloat during March, including a
$25,000 loan from himself to the campaign.
   He has had to lay off most of his staff and almost totally
eliminate other campaign expenditures because he was up against the
maximum $27 million spending cap that the FEC imposes on candidates
who receive federal matching funds.
   He ended March with $1.4 million in debts and only $61,890 in
cash on hand.
   Robertson spent $7.8 million during March repaying some of his
previous bank loans. He has conceded that Vice President George
Bush will win the nomination but Robertson technically remains a
candidate.
   Bush's fund-raising crew has closed up shop, having raised the
maximum $27 million that primary candidates can spend. During
March, he raised $1.7 million, of which $247,118 was in the form of
federal matching funds.
   He ended the month with $3.6 million in the bank to cover close
to $1 million in outstanding obligations. At the end of March he
had spent $18.9 million against the base spending cap of $23
million, plus the maximum $4.6 million allowed for fund-raising
expenses.
   Bush's treasurer, Fred Bush, said earlier this month that
overall fund raising for the campaign had hit $30 million. That
included $3 million for legal and accounting costs, which are not
subject to the spending limit.
   Robertson reported raising $2.3 million during March, of which
$896,551 was federal matching funds, and $873,444 was money from
contributors.
   With the expensive June 7 California contest still down the road
and a handful of others before it, the remaining Democrats will be
refocusing on fund-raising efforts.
   Dukakis ended March with $1.7 million in cash on hand to cover
$697,162 in bills.
   Jackson had $865,946 in the bank and $678,973 in debts.
   Gore ended the month with a debt of $1.6 million, and $416,603
in cash on hand.
   GOP contender Jack Kemp, the congressman from New York who
dropped out of the race during March, was left with a debt. He
ended the month $672,826 in the red, but was anticipating more than
$500,000 in federal matching funds to help retire that. He had only
$57,741 in the bank, after raising $604,586 during the month.
</TEXT>
