<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     04-21 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Accuse Woman Of Poisoning Deaths As Trial Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of putting cyanide into
non-prescription pain remedies that killed her husband and another
woman was deeply in debt and wanted more from life than her
marriage could provide, a prosecutor said.
   ``This is about her anger, her frustration ... her obsession,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida said of Stella Nickell in
opening statements Wednesday before a U.S. District Court jury.
   Mrs. Nickell, the first person in the United States charged with
causing death by tampering with over-the-counter capsules, plotted
the killings to collect insurance money but failed in her attempt
to make them look like random murders, Ms. Maida said.
   Mrs. Nickell is charged in the June 1986 deaths of her
52-year-old husband, Bruce Nickell, and of Susan Katherine Snow,
40, both of Auburn, by putting cyanide in capsules of
Extra-Strength Excedrin. The prosecution has suggested no links
between the victims except the way they died.
   She also faces three counts of tampering with a product involved
in interstate commerce in the tainting of capsules in two
Extra-Strength Excedrin bottles and an Anacin-3 bottle that were
recovered in stores in Kent and Auburn, suburbs between Seattle and
Tacoma.
   The deaths resulted in a nationwide tampering scare, and
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers recalled all its
non-prescription medicine sold in capsule form.
   Defense attorney Thomas Hillier said that there were reasonable
explanations for many of the prosecution's points and that much of
its case was circumstantial.
   Ms. Maida contended that Mrs. Nickell had an ``obsession of
several years in duration'' to kill her husband.
   The FBI was contacted in January 1987 by Mrs. Nickell's
daughter, Cindy Hamilton, who said her mother had been researching
drugs and contract killings for several years, according to the
prosecutor.
   Hillier said Mrs. Nickell would take the stand to contradict her
daughter's statements.
   Ms. Maida also noted that Mrs. Nickell was found to have checked
out five library books that discussed cyanide and poisonous doses.
   Hillier said Mrs. Nickell got the books because they contained
information about poisonous plants, and she was concerned about
potential danger from local toxic plants to her granddaughter and
children for whom she babysat.
   Hillier also played down the couple's marital problems, saying
they were due to financial stress. Although Nickell became a
permanent state employee in January 1986, the couple was heavily in
debt and faced foreclosure on their trailer home, he said.
   Ms. Maida said Mrs. Nickell became a suspect after investigators
found dozens of her fingerprints on library books about poisons and
after she pushed medical authorities for a more specific cause of
death after they ruled that Nickell, a heavy smoker, died from
emphysema.
   Mrs. Nickell stood to receive $31,000 from her husband's state
life insurance policy if he died of natural causes, but $136,000 if
the death was accidental, as in cyanide poisoning, the prosecutor
said.
   Edward Sexton, a King County police officer, testified Wednesday
that Mrs. Nickell told him her husband took Excedrin for several
days before his death, as many as four at a time, for severe
headaches.
   Paul Webking, Sue Snow's husband, testified that his wife took
two Excedrin capsules daily. ``It has a lot of caffeine in it. She
would take Excedrin instead of drinking coffee.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
