<DOCNO> AP880421-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-L'AmbianceAnniversary Bjt   04-21 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-L'Ambiance Anniversary, Bjt,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Year Later, Families, Survivors Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after a partially built
apartment building collapsed, families, workers and rescuers who
toiled for nine days in the fruitless search for survivors remain
tormented by the loss of 28 lives.
   ``In all of my 22 years as an attorney and in all of the
hundreds, if not thousands of cases I have been involved in, never
have I seen the emotional effect lingering as long as I have in
this case,'' said Richard Bieder, lead counsel for the victims'
families.
   ``To what do I attribute that? I guess I would have to say to
the enormity of the loss and the fact that the loss seemed so
purposeless,'' Bieder said.
   One survivor, William Pelkey, 44, of Prospect, was standing 20
feet away when the L'Ambiance Plaza apartment complex fell in a
thundering roar on April 23, 1987. His employer, the Waterbury
Foundation Co., lost 11 workers.
   Pelkey stayed in construction work, but says he's more cautious
and is disturbed by noise.
   ``I never talk about it,'' he said. ``None of us do.''
   June Page of Hamden said she struggles daily with the memory of
her son John's death. Page, 30, was married but had no children.
   ``The hard thing is where do you go now? ... They murdered him
as far as I'm concerned,'' Mrs. Page said quietly.
   L'Ambiance Plaza collapsed in less than 10 seconds on a Thursday
at 1:37 p.m., not long after workers had returned from lunch.
   Within hours, an army of volunteers, many of them workers from
construction jobs around booming Connecticut, gathered at the site
of what was to have been a 16-story apartment building near
downtown.
   Floodlights were set up for the round-the-clock rescue effort,
the families of missing men waited in a nearby school, and the
Salvation Army set up canteens to serve the rescue workers and
relatives.
   In the first few days, hopes remained high that someone would be
pulled alive from the wreckage. Sensitive microphones designed for
searches in mining accidents were used to hunt for signs of life in
the rubble. But nine days later, the last body was removed.
   Jonathan Best, Bridgeport's director of emergency medical
services, said the city carried on the nation's biggest rescue
ever. The $7.3 million effort included 4,000 workers, 30 ambulance
services, 500 emergency medical services workers, and 700 bottles
of oxygen.
   ``I've been to plane crashes, bombings and subway fires, and
I've never seen people as badly injured as I did then,'' Best said.
   Best, 33, said he tried to shield people from the gruesomeness
of the search for bodies and recoveries. Only he and four others
removed the body parts.
   At one point, Best said, he and the four others needed
professional help. But a social worker listened to them for a few
minutes ``and lost it so we had to have him removed,'' Best said.
   Counseling was offered to the rescue workers, but it could not
mitigate all the effects of the disaster.
   Best said his EMS staff has had a 50 percent attrition rate
since the collapse. One paramedic quit on the scene after she, not
knowing she was talking to the father of a high school student
working on his spring vacation, abruptly told him the boy was dead.
   Last October, federal investigators concluded that the collapse
was triggered by a bracket that bent under heavy pressure, and the
U.S. Department of Labor assessed a record $5.11 million in fines
against contractors.
   It also led to congressional hearings in Washington that
examined the work of the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration. The Justice Department is considering a request by
the Labor Department that criminal charges be brought against one
contractor.
   In Connecticut, prosecutors decided not to press criminal
charges.
   The Pages and other victims' families have filed lawsuits
against the city, the owners of the project and a subcontractor
that performed the lift-slab construction technique. More lawsuits
are expected.
   Page's father, Lowell, was silent during a recent interview in
the family's home. He sat staring at lottery tickets in his hand,
but when talk turned to the collapse, tears welled up in his eyes.
   Page's brother Lowell, also a construction worker, said John did
not feel comfortable at the site.
   ``He was pulled off another job to go there because they had to
meet their quotas, to make sure so much work was done so they could
get paid,'' the brother said.
   ``He was just a gentle boy,'' Mrs. Page said. ``I wish he'd
never gone into construction.''
</TEXT>
