<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-Drugs     04-21 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Drugs,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Says No To Senate Anti-Drug Funding Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted overwhelmingly in favor of
finding more drug-fighting money within current budget limits, but
Democratic leaders said they would raise the limits if President
Reagan agrees.
   The House voted 412-0 on Wednesday to oppose a Senate initiative
to expand the war on drugs by increasing the spending and tax
limits in the budget agreement between the president and
congressional leaders.
   The Republican-sponsored motion instructed House budget
negotiators to insist the drug war be waged within the domestic
spending constraints guiding the $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 spending
blueprint now in a House-Senate conference committee.
   It would be ``far more easy and more dramatic to raise spending
and taxes for the war on drugs,'' said Rep. William Thomas,
R-Calif., who offered the motion. But ``this is absolutely the
wrong time to abandon that (budget pact) framework.''
   The Senate, in passing its version of the fiscal 1989 budget
last week, added a $2.6 billion trust fund above current spending
limitations that could be tapped if the president and Congress
declared drugs a dire emergency.
   President Reagan had proposed and both the House and Senate
budgets already included increases in drug enforcement and
education, a popular issue in an election year.
   The Senate, however, added the amendment to increase the funding
further. Sponsors said that could be financed through tougher
enforcement of tax laws and government debt collections.
   House Budget Committee Chairman William H. Gray III, D-Pa., said
he had no objections to the non-binding action. But he said the
budget pact left room for changes if the leaders and the president
decided there were a ``dire emergency.''
   And House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, told reporters Wednesday
he would favor raising the budget agreement's spending caps for
fighting the drug problem if the Reagan administration agreed.
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III told a Senate subcommittee
last week that the government should cut other spending if it
wanted to increase the drug effort. But he did not rule out
reopening the budget summit if the president and the others agreed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
