<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaRepublicans     04-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada Republicans,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Camp Will Dominate State GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old guard of the Nevada Republican Party
is on the outside looking in as the GOP readies for a state
convention controlled by supporters of former television evangelist
Pat Robertson.
   Convention preliminaries start here today with meetings of
platform, credential, resolution and bylaws committees. And 600 to
650 delegates _ at least two-thirds of them Robertson supporters _
should be on hand when the general session convenes Friday.
   The Republicans will adopt what's expected to be a generally
conservative platform at the convention, ending Saturday, and also
complete the process of picking a 20-member delegation to the
national GOP convention this summer in New Orleans.
   At least 16 of those national convention delegates will be
Robertson delegates. And even though Vice President George Bush is
continuing to roll toward the Republican presidential nomination,
Robertson's Nevada coordinator says it's possible the entire Nevada
delegation could be for Robertson.
   It's also possible that such Nevada GOP luminaries as national
party chairman Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., Rep. Barbara Vucanovich,
former Sen. Paul Laxalt and others won't be on the 20-member
delegation to New Orleans.
   By the time the state convention ends this weekend, all top
party offices could be filled by a solid slate of Robertson
supporters, among them Robertson coordinator Steve Wark, who is the
only announced candidate for state Republican Party chairman.
   Wark says he wouldn't have sought the chairmanship if the
incumbent, Sally Vitkus-McKinney of Las Vegas, hadn't decided to
bow out. He also says his first effort will be to make party
regulars feel welcome instead of ousted.
   ``We're not taking a cavalier attitude,'' he says. ``This is an
evolutionary process of party politics ... We desperately don't
want anyone to feel that they've been kicked out. They haven't
been.''
   On the other hand, says Wark, ``If Pat Robertson thought it was
important to have all 20 Nevada delegates to the national
convention, it would be that.''
   Robertson is to address the state convention Friday, the same
day Fahrenkopf speaks.
   Besides Wark, the other Robertson supporters who are candidates
for various state GOP offices include Judy Cresenta of Reno for
national committeewoman and Leonard Saye of Las Vegas for national
committeeman.
</TEXT>
