<2ND_LINE>AM-Freeway Pileup,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>39 Vehicles Collide Under Blinding Glare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Weatherpage Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CITY OF INDUSTRY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blinding afternoon glare and
driving rain caused 39 vehicles to smash together in a stretch of
the Pomona Freeway during rush-hour Wednesday, injuring 19 people,
authorities said.
   ``It was real nasty,'' said motorist Pat Rich, whose car caromed
among several others.
   Eight separate accidents occurred in the westbound lanes, and
one involved 20 cars, said Los Angeles County fire Capt. Dennis
Miller.
   ``It was raining real hard. The glare from the sun was coming in
and everybody was driving directly into the sun,'' he said. ``There
was a tremendous glare.''
   Seven ambulances were required, and the freeway and nearby ramps
were shut down for about two hours, he said.
   A hazardous materials team also was called when one of three big
rigs involved in the crashes began to leak diesel fuel, Miller said.
   He said one of the 19 injured was hurt seriously.
   The City of Industry is 25 miles east of downtown Los Angeles.
