<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Army-Layoffs     04-21 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Army-Layoffs,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Plans To Fire 2,600 Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army will soon begin firing up to 2,600
civilian workers around the country, but remains optimistic
Congress will help avoid furloughs for up to 150,000 more, a top
general says.
   Maj. Gen. James F. McCall, the Army's budget director, said
Wednesday in an interview the service would have to reduce its
civilian workforce from 412,000 to 400,000 by Oct. 1, the start of
the 1989 fiscal year.
   That reduction is part of a cut in strength ordered by Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci to meet the terms of a
deficit-reduction agreement with Congress last fall.
   ``You can't get those 12,000 people down solely by way of hiring
freezes, reductions (in temporary workers) and early outs,'' the
two-star general said.
   Although the number of layoffs needed is still subject to
change, the current estimate ``is about 2,500 to 2,600
reductions-in-force ... to get 12,000 people off the rolls,''
McCall said.
   The Pentagon disclosed in its fiscal 1989 budget plan last
February that all the services would face reductions in civilian
employment and that all but the Navy would see actual cuts in
military strength as well.
   The Army has said it will slash 8,600 active-duty positions this
year to reach a new level of 772,300. McCall's comments are the
first to detail the precise impact on the civilian side.
   The general indicated it would be premature to discuss the
number of layoffs being planned at individual Army facilities, but
said there were 25 to 30 bases around the country that would face
civilian cuts.
   He said the dismissals were designed to meet the spending target
set for the next fiscal year. They must be implemented soon because
the service must start fiscal 1989 on Oct. 1 at the reduced
employment level.
   Cuts to this year's budget, however, are equally severe and
furloughs of civilian workers will be required this summer if
Congress doesn't approve a legislative proposal submitted within
the past month.
   That bill would provide the Defense Department with expanded
authority to transfer funds among different accounts and to carry
certain funds over from year to year, McCall said.
   ``We have had indications from at least five (Army) commands
that without any relief, they would need to furlough to maintain
their level of readiness,'' the general said.
   ``That furlough, in its worst case, (would be) as high as
150,000 people ... for varying lengths of time from three to 15
days.''
   McCall said he is optimistic Congress will grant the flexibility
to avoid furloughs because the Pentagon is not asking for an extra
appropriation.
   Congress must act by June, however, if the Army is to avoid the
huge furloughs that would be needed to help make up for a $2.8
billion cut to its original request of $21.3 billion for operations
and maintenance spending this year.
   Roughly 70 percent of all the Army's civilian workers are paid
from that account, which also holds the money for readiness
training for the active force, McCall said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
