<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Four Killed, 50 Held Hostage During Attempted Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS MOCHIS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six gunmen who were caught robbing a
bank on Wednesday killed four people and took 50 hostage, a witness
said.
   Police surrounded the Banamex bank and were negotiating with the
gunmen who said they would kill their hostages unless they received
safe passage to an unidentified location, the witness, Ramiro
Guerrero said.
   The standoff began in the Gulf of California coastal town at
12:45 p.m. (3:45 p.m. EDT) when a bank alarm alerted police a
robbery was in progress, said Guerrero, the news editor at the
Noroeste newspaper in Los Mochis.
   The gunmen wounded policeman Roberto Soto Cruz when he entered
the building and they disarmed and captured a second unidentifed
policeman.
   The gunmen then attempted to leave the bank, using Soto Cruz and
customer Marco Antonio Estrada as a shield, the editor said.
Antonio Estrada was killed and Soto Cruz received more wounds when
the escape attempt resulted in an exchange of gunfire between
police and the gunmen.
   Soto Cruz died several hours later at a local hospital after the
gunmen allowed Red Cross officials to escort him from the building,
the witness said.
   The other two people killed were identified as Manuel Andoval
Rendon, a subdirector at the bank who died of a gunshot wound to
the chest, and bank cashier Rosi Maria Padilla, 22, who reportedly
was shot in the face.
   Guerrero said some of the 50 hostages also may have been wounded.
</TEXT>
