<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirSafety     04-21 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Safety,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former FAA Head Engen Attacks DOT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Federal Aviation Administration chief
Donald D. Engen says the agency must be given more independence,
saying needed safety rules were bogged down in the bureaucracy
during his tenure.
   Getting some regulations approved by the Department of
Transportation was like ``a maddening shell and pea'' game Engen
told the Senate aviation subcommittee Wednesday.
   Some safety rules could be tied up for months because of the
slowness of the department, he said. The answer is to remove the
FAA from the department, he said, as the presidential Aviation
Safety Commission recommended Monday.
   ``Rules for a technical field such as aviation must be timely,''
he told lawmakers. ``Safety is often at issue and additional DOT
requirements in the laborious rulemaking process can subvert the
goal of safety from a timeliness as well as a technical accuracy
standpoint.''
   Engen's comments clashed with Transportation Secretary James H.
Burnley IV, who told the same subcommittee last month that to get
regulations out of FAA ``it has been necessary to use the
bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod.''
   Although Engen has been critical before of the Transportation
Department's handling of FAA proposals, he has not been as
expansive, nor has he previously directly clashed with a department
official.
   Transportation Department officials at the hearing Wednesday
rejected Engen's contentions, and gave reporters documents they
said challenged some of the claims he made.
   Engen left his job July 2 for what he called personal reasons.
   Asked by a reporter whether his complaints to the subcommittee
had prompted his departure, Engen said, ``You'll have to draw that
conclusion, not me.''
   The former administrator and DOT officials also sparred over
events surrounding decisions Engen said he made.
   In one instance, Engen told the panel he blocked The Boeing Co.
from removing two of the 10 emergency exits on its 747 jetliners to
add extra seats. Engen said he rejected the manufacturer's request
because it would have been less safe for passengers. He also said
the Transportation Department ``was strangely silent'' while the
matter was being decided.
   ``There was no waffling, no coziness between government and
industry,'' he said.
   But Transportation Department spokesman Bob Marx gave a reporter
a copy of an Aug. 6, 1985, letter from then-Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth H. Dole to Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y., stating
that ``at my request'' Engen was pursuing the issue.
   A June 10, 1985 letter to Mrs. Dole from Henry A. Duffy,
president of the Air Line Pilots Association, expressed ``our
disappointment and concern regarding Admiral Engen's endorsement of
the overwing emergency exit deactivation on Boeing 747 aircraft.''
The letter asked Mrs. Dole to block FAA approval of the plan.
</TEXT>
