<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-PersianGulf     04-21 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Persian Gulf,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Considering Expanded Protection Role In Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some congressmen are urging the Reagan
administration to have the U.S. Navy extend its protection in the
Persian Gulf to randomly chosen ships not flying the American flag.
   ``The purpose is to keep any attacker off guard, off balance,''
Sen. John Warner, the ranking Republican on the Senate Armed
Services Committee said in today's editions of The Washington Post.
   Warner, of Virginia, said such a policy would deter attacks
because aggressors would not be sure if their actions might draw
fire from the United States. No advance notice would be given of
which ships would receive protection.
   Unidentified administration officials quoted by the Post said
the White House is considering the broadened role in the gulf
following U.S. attacks this week on Iranian oil platforms that
brought violent retaliation attempts from Iran's navy.
   Congressmen have expressed concern about the U.S. role in the
gulf, where American warships protect Kuwaiti tankers flying the
U.S. flag.
   Senate Armed Services Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., has suggested
the United States could maintain a more neutral appearance in the
Iran-Iraq war if the gulf were divided into zones, with each one
protected by a different nation's navy.
   The Congressional Research Service told a House panel Wednesday
that America's allies are doing more than is publicly perceived to
help protect the flow of oil in the Persian Gulf.
   Five European nations and the Japanese have all increased their
Persian Gulf efforts in the past 12 months to try to meet the
threat posed by the Iran-Iraq war, said Stanley Sloan, a CRS
analyst.
   Sloan's assessment differed from the view of Rep. Patricia
Schroeder, D-Colo., who said the public believes the allies should
do more in the troubled region.
   Schroeder chairs the House Armed Services panel on allied
burden-sharing, which has been looking at help provided by U.S.
allies.
   Sloan told the House panel ``there has been substantial
evolution of allied attitudes toward their military role in the
Persian Gulf'' in the past year. That change came after the U.S.
Navy began escorting 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers.
   ``Great Britain, France, Italy, Belgium and the Netherlands sent
additional naval contingents to the Persian Gulf region to
demonstrate that they appreciate the threat of instability in that
region to Western interests,'' Sloan noted.
   In addition, Japan took a number of steps, even though that
nation is prohibited by its American-written constitution from
military operations far beyond its shores.
   Japan offered to buy a $10 million navigation system for the
Arab nations of the Persian Gulf region, announced that it would
increase economic aid to Jordan and Oman by $500 million, and said
it was willing to contribute to United Nation's peace efforts in
the region, Sloan said.
</TEXT>
