<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSStudent     04-21 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Student,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Rally Around AIDS Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junior high school students rallied around
a student who has tested positive for the AIDS virus, shouting down
a small group protesting his admission to the school.
   ``Go home!'' students yelled at the eight people protesting
12-year-old DeWayne Mowery's attendance at Clinton Junior High
School.
   Police twice had to separate the eight protesters from about 200
angry students and parents.
   Wanda Webber, whose son is a ninth-grader, slammed on her brakes
and got out of her car to deride the protesters as ``disgusting.''
   Members of the group ``do not know what they are talking
about,'' she said. ``They are shaming the town. They are shaming
this community. They are showing the whole world how ignorant they
are.
   ``Ignorance and petty fear, that scares me more than AIDS,'' she
said.
   DeWayne was the center of protests last year when he tried to
enter Lake City Middle School, an incident that led to his
testimony before the presidential AIDS commission earlier this year
in Nashville.
   Health officials have said that DeWayne, who has shown no
symptoms of the syndrome, apparently contracted the virus from a
clotting factor he uses in treatment for hemophilia. The substance
is made from a blood component.
   The school's staff members, students and parents have attended
special classes organized by the principal, Harold Heath, to learn
about AIDS and hemophilia, which is characterized by uncontrolled
bleeding.
   The students ``are probably the most informed group of
7th-8th-and 9th-graders in the country on what this boy has, what
it can do and how it can be transmitted,'' Heath said.
   ``Our science teachers have done a fantastic job,'' he said.
``These kids are equipped with a lot of information.''
   During lunch Tuesday, several students erected signs on the
school grounds saying, ``DeWayne is not hurting us. You are,''
``Parents get educated,'' ``Innocence can't kill: ignorance can.
Welcome to CJHS, DeWayne,'' and ``Don't be ignorant. Get the
facts.''
   Another sign said, ``Fight with facts. Rumors spread faster than
AIDS.'' Near the end of the school day, students gathered to yell
``go home'' at the protesters.
   Last fall, DeWayne's parents pulled him out of Lake City Middle
School after they said they had received threats. After removing
him, he had been taking classes alone at a special school.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring. As of April 11, 33,060
people have died of AIDS in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
