<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     04-21 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendants Say Judge Makes `Mockery' of Their Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three defendants in the Iran-Contra case say
the judge made ``a mockery'' of their rights by devising ``woefully
inadequate'' procedures to determinine if prosecutors illegally
used their congressional testimony.
   In an unusually harsh attack, defense attorneys challenged the
procedures U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell adopted for a
hearing on whether prosecutors took evidence from the compelled
congressional testimony of Lt. Col. Oliver L. North, former
national security adviser John M. Poindexer and businessman Albert
Hakim.
   The lawyers asked Gesell to reconsider his denial of their
requests to question individual grand jurors and witnesses to
determine if independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh's investigation
was tainted by exposure to the congressional testimony of North,
Poindexter and Hakim.
   The procedure for next Monday's hearing ``makes a mockery of the
orders of the United States District Court for the District of
Columbia compelling defendants' testimony'' before Congress, the
defense said in a brief filed Wednesday.
   Defense attorneys threatened to file an appeal. They also asked
Gesell to postpone the hearing while he reconsiders how to conduct
it.
   ``The procedures established by the order for determining
whether or not there has been or will be any direct or indirect use
of defendants' immunized testimony are woefully inadequate,'' the
defense said.
   The three defendants are charged with conspiring to illegally
divert to Nicaraguan rebels some of the profits from the sale of
U.S. arms to Iran.
   A fourth defendant, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord, gave congressional testimony without the so-called ``use
immunity.''
   At a hearing last week, Gesell rejected defense requests for a
wide-ranging inquiry into Walsh's investigative methods and
procedures.
   But the judge ordered Walsh to tell the court what steps he took
to insulate his staff and the grand jury from the extensive
publicity surrounding the defendants' testimony on Capitol Hill.
   Gesell also invited the defense, if it could, to produce a grand
jury witness who changed his story after hearing congressional
testimony.
   ``We think we can draw blood fairly quickly,'' Barry Simon, one
of North's lawyers, told Gesell at the hearing.
   The latest motion was filed a day before today's deadline for
the defense to give Walsh the name of the witness it plans to call
at next Monday's proceeding.
   Lawyers for the three defendants contend that publicity of last
year's congressional hearings made it impossible for Walsh to
shield his staff and grand jurors from the testimony, some of which
was given under the condition that it could not be used against
them in criminal prosecution.
   ``Certainly common sense tells us that there is vitually no
prospective witness in this case who has not been exposed to, and
to some degree influenced, by defendants' immunized testimony,''
the joint defense motion said.
   ``This case is an omelet from which the tainted immunized
testimony can never be unscrambled,'' attorneys Brendan V. Sullivan
Jr., Richard W. Beckler and N. Richard Janis said in the motion.
   Gesell has said he would dismiss the case if Walsh fails to
prove he didn't use evidence from the defendants' congressional
testimony.
   But the defense said the judge's methods for making that finding
``appear designed to ensure that any dismissal of the indictment
will only follow a protracted trial with its grave risks to our
national security and its inherent financial and emotional trauma
both for the defendants and for the nation.''
   The judge has indicated he would like to start the trial in
July, while the defense wants to delay the proceeding until next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
