<DOCNO> AP880421-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FetusReduction     04-21 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fetus Reduction,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Destroying Fetuses in Some Pregnancies Saves Babies, Raises
Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors believe they can ultimately save babies'
lives by selectively destroying some fetuses while sparing others
in the same womb, but one ethics expert calls it ``a tragic
practice.''
   The procedure has been performed in women who are pregnant with
several fetuses, often as a result of fertility drugs or test-tube
fertilizations.
   The chances are slim that four or more fetuses would survive and
be healthy. So the strategy is to terminate all but two of them in
a procedure called ``selective reduction.'' The two remaining
fetuses face reasonably good odds of growing to be healthy, normal
infants.
   ``In patients who choose to undergo selective reduction during
the first trimester, the procedure may offer an option to save the
lives of a number of desperately wanted infants,'' wrote Dr.
Richard L. Berkowitz and colleagues from Mount Sinai School of
Medicine in New York.
   Their report, published in today's New England Journal of
Medicine, describes the use of the procedure in 12 pregnancies.
Seven of the women had healthy twins, while one had a healthy
single baby. Four others had no live-born infants.
   They also acknowledged, however, that selective reduction raises
important ethical questions. Others agreed.
   In an editorial in the journal, Dr. John C. Hobbins of Yale
Medical School said that even those who think abortion is sometimes
justified ``must wrestle with the concept of sacrificing some
fetuses so that others can survive.''
   The Rev. Richard McCormick, a Roman Catholic priest who teaches
moral theology at Notre Dame, said in an interview that ``in the
vast majority of cases, that is morally wrong.''
   McCormick said the procedure is morally acceptable only after
accidents, such as inadvertant overdoses of fertility drugs, that
result in so many fetuses that none is likely to survive.
   ``A case can be made for doing it when it's the only life-saving
alternative available,'' McCormick said. ``Even then, everybody
feels chilly about it.''
   Arthur Caplan, a medical ethics expert at the University of
Minnesota, called it ``a tragic practice'' and ``a very sad
intervention.''
   Doctors who perform test-tube fertilizations often implant
several embryos in hopes that one will survive, but sometimes more
may grow.
   Caplan said doctors who perform these fertilizations should
implant no more than four embryos so that they minimize the risk of
multiple fetuses, and physicians also should be careful to
prescribe the minimum effective dose of fertility drugs.
   ``Once you are stuck in a situation, it's morally defensible to
do it,'' he said of selective reduction. ``But you should do
everything you can to avoid that situation.''
   In his report, Berkowitz noted that in the past, couples have
had only two choices: take their chances on a successful outcome or
abort the entire pregnancy.
   However, he said the decision to have selective reduction is
also hard for parents anxious to have babies. It should only be
done if they are prepared to lose the entire pregnancy.
   In the 12 cases described, the doctors selectively destroyed all
but two fetuses in each woman. In most cases, this was done by
injecting potassium chloride into the fetal hearts. Of those who
received the procedure, two of the women had each conceived six
fetuses, one had five, five had four and four were carrying
triplets.
   Berkowitz said that women who carry four or more fetuses are
ideal candidates for the approach because of the high risk of
complications. However, triplets ``are in a gray area and present
an enormous dilemma for both the patients and their physicians.''
   He said it should not be done with twins, since chances are good
that both will develop to be healthy babies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Networks-Projections     04-21 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Networks-Projections,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC News President Disenchanted in Projections Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Come November, NBC might not abide by its
handshake agreement with Congress not to project a winner in the
presidential election until all polls have closed.
   NBC News President Lawrence K. Grossman said Wednesday he is
``uncomfortable'' with the agreement, which was elicited by
sponsors of legislation to establish a nationwide uniform poll
closing time.
   ``We're very concerned about it and we'll re-evaluate it before
the election in November if there's no progress made (on the poll
closing bill),'' Grossman said Wednesday.
   NBC's decision could put pressure on the two other networks to
abandon the policy, stated in an informal agreement with Congress
as part of a push for a uniform national poll closing time.
   Meantime, NBC is abiding by the policy, although ``NBC Nightly
News'' anchor Tom Brokaw said Tuesday night during coverage of the
New York primary almost two hours before polls closed that
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis ``may well be headed for
victory.''
   ``Nightly News'' has been making similar statements about trends
in races throughout the primary season.
   ABC's Peter Jennings and CBS' Dan Rather both said Tuesday night
during their broadcasts that they could not predict the election
because polls were still open in New York. The polls closed at 9
p.m.
   NBC's report followed a local WNBC-TV newscast predicting
Dukakis as the winner statewide and Jesse Jackson as carrying New
York City.
   Grossman insisted the NBC report did not violate the agreement
with Congress because it wasn't technically a ``projection.''
   In a 1985 letter to Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash., Grossman, like his
counterparts at ABC and CBS, vowed NBC would ``not use the exit
poll data we gather to suggest the probable winner in any state
until polls in that state have closed.''
   The letter was part of an agreement sought by Swift and Rep.
William Thomas, R-Calif., to help their legislation proposing a
uniform poll closing time in presidential election years.
   Swift criticized NBC's Tuesday evening report for not being true
to the ``spirit'' of network policy. ``However, one might argue the
letter of it,'' Swift said in a statement.
   He praised ABC and CBS for explicitly stating that they would
not make a prediction until the polls closed.
   ``It is my hope that this is just an error and that NBC News
will reaffirm its policy and that the other news operations will
not see this incident as cause to abandon their policy or
practice,'' Swift said.
   ``It's a very frustrating situation,'' said Tom Bettag,
executive producer of the ``CBS Evening News.''
   ``I think somebody's got to seriously rethink how this all
works. It is very frustrating to be in the position we were in last
night, knowing that your opposition has for weeks been
characterizing elections. It's a very uncomfortable position to be
in.''
   By the time the networks go on the air, they usually have exit
polling data upon which they could accurately predict the outcome
of the election. Release of such information theoretically
disenfranchises voters still waiting to cast votes. In a
presidential election, polls in Western states are still open after
polls on the East Coast and in the Midwest have closed.
   Ironically, it was not the networks but then-President Jimmy
Carter who sparked the most controversy when in 1980, he conceded
the presidential election to Ronald Reagan before polls on the West
Coast had closed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
