<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Exit-By-Exit 1stLd-Writethru a0480 04-21 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit-By-Exit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mysteries of Texas Highways Probed in New Travel Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The 288-page ...' to delete extraneous coma
after word `wife.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a state where thousands of empty miles promise
little more than highway hypnosis, and today's culinary special may
be a bowl of truck-stop chili, relief is in sight for the
culturally bereft.
   A new guidebook takes some of the mystery out of the seemingly
endless ribbons of roadway in the Lone Star state by detailing
motels, restaurants, gas stations, convenience stores and bank
machines at every Texas freeway exit.
   ``Just gathering the information was a monumental effort,'' said
Bill Cima, who probed the delights of 2,400 exits during a
four-month, 7,000-mile jaunt to assemble ``Sunset Highway Services
Directory, Exit-By-Exit.''
   His Baedeker of the beaten track is a must, for example, at exit
761-761A in west Houston, where finicky tourists must decide
whether they want to get gas at the Shell, Mobil, Conoco, Gulf or
Exxon stations.
   Hungry motorists can eat at Platters or Steak & Ale or perhaps
pick up something at the 24-hour Stop N Go. Sunbelt National bank
also is at the exit.
   The 288-page soft-cover book also includes Arizona and New
Mexico, and Cima and his wife eventually want to write a 10-book
series covering the entire country. But mostly, except for about 50
pages, the guide concerns Texas, which Cima said ``has its own
character and personality.''
   Shortly after drivers reach Exit 0 at the Texas-New Mexico
border, he points out, there's an anti-littering sign: ``Don't Mess
with Texas.''
   ``That says it all,'' Cima said. ``It's very clear when you
enter Texas, you've entered the Lone Star State.''
   The Cimas' inaugural effort two years ago was a similar book
about California. Cima's wife, Saundra, an airline flight
attendant, came up with the idea after repeatedly driving home to
San Diego from Los Angeles and worrying about where to pull off the
freeway if her car broke down.
   Cima, a former Navy test pilot, cruised every Texas freeway and
many other highways with three other drivers, getting off at each
exit to make note of the services available to motorists.
   ``That was the only way to get complete information,'' Cima said
recently from his base in San Diego.
   Besides restaurants, motels and service stations, the listings
include shopping centers, hospitals and police stations. A second
driver later retraced most of the routes to verify the information.
   ``The Southwest really seemed like a pretty good idea,'' he
said. ``With all the RV (recreational vehicle) traffic and all the
people coming to Arizona, New Mexico and Texas from the North, it
seemed like a logical extension of California.''
   ``As it turns out, California has more exits than Texas,'' he
said. ``California had 2,800. But obviously there are more miles of
driving in Texas. The exits come a little closer in California, so
that makes the book a little more valuable commodity in Texas.''
   About 50,000 copies of the book, priced at $12.95, are being
distributed to bookstores in Texas.
   ``We hope to sell a lot more than that,'' said Cima. ``The book
should be good for about two years. Things aren't changing all that
rapidly. What you see is a few more businesses will pop up.
Everything we have listed is going to be there in a few years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0064 </DOCNO>
