<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VoteFraud     04-21 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vote Fraud,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elections Board Asks Inquiry into Reporter's Multiple
Registrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district attorney has been asked to bring
charges against a television reporter who registered five times for
this week's primary election to underscore the potential for fraud.
   In a report broadcast Wednesday, WCBS-TV's Barbara Nevins told
how she registered to vote in the city boroughs of Manhattan,
Brooklyn, Queens, Staten Island and in suburban Nassau County,
using similar names and friends' addresses.
   Ms. Nevins said she got three voter registration cards and was
admitted to vote at five polling places Tuesday, although the
report stressed she voted only once.
   On Wednesday, Ms. Nevins interviewed Bea Dolen, executive
director of the city's Board of Elections, who conceded that the
computer registration process may need to be updated.
   After the reporter left, Mrs. Dolen contacted District Attorney
Robert M. Morganthau and asked him to prosecute the reporter for
felony violations of the election law. It is illegal to give false
information to election officials or to obtain a false registration.
   ``What she did is against the law,'' Mrs. Dolen said. ``She is
admitting on television that she committed two Class-E felonies.''
   Gloria Montealegre, a spokeswoman for Morganthau, confirmed that
he spoke with Mrs. Dolan, but said no investigation had been
started. She said he had no further comment.
   The report did not suggest that widespread fraud had been
committed in Tuesday's primary, but stressed that an organized
campaign to rig a local election might work.
   Ms. Nevins admitted she broke the law, but said it was the only
way to test the potential for fraud.
   Mrs. Dolen claimed that fraudulent registration was rare, but
breaking the law on television would encourage others to do it.
   ``I told her, `If you go on television, people who have never
thought about doing something like this will think about doing so.'
I think she's really out of line,'' she said.
</TEXT>
