<HEAD>Deukmejian Finally Endorses Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian has endorsed Vice
President George Bush for the Republican nomination for president
saying he hadn't endorsed Bush earlier because he had pledged he
would remain neutral for the June 7 California primary.
   But since all of the other Republican candidates have withdrawn
from active contention, it is now appropriate to endorse Bush,
Deukmejian said.
   Deukmejian said Bush ``is unmatched in terms of the experience
and in terms of the leadership he has demonstrated'' and that the
vice president ``has demonstrated his strong support and loyalty to
President Reagan and to Republican ideals.''
   Asked by reporters at a news conference if he had supported Bush
from the start, or had favored one of the other GOP contenders,
Deukmejian briefly replied, ``I'm going to keep that to myself.''
   The California governor has been mentioned as a possible vice
presidential running mate with Bush.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Restore Michigan Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Michigan Senate has decided to
reinstate a presidential primary to replace the caucuses used in
1984 and this year to distribute delegates to the Democratic and
Republica national conventions.
   The bill, which had been the subject of several months of
delicate bipartisan negotiations, passed overwhelmingly in a 32-5
vote on Wednesday and was sent to the House.
   The legislation, which is expected to pass in the House, would
restore the closed primary for the 1992 presidential elections,
requiring voters to declare their party preference 30 days before
the election.
   ``A closed primary is better than no primary at all,'' declared
Sen. Dick Posthumus, R-Alto, the bill's sponsor.
   Sen. Vernon Ehlers, R-Grand Rapids, compared the bill to this
year's caucus system and said: ``It's much better to have the
direct participation of the people.''
   But ``It's going to reduce dramatically the number of people who
will vote in that primary,'' said Sen. Joseph Conroy, D-Flint.
   Michigan launched its latest presidential primary to allocate
delegates to the national presidential conventions among the
various White House hopefuls in 1972. Democrats quit using the
primary after 1976 because their national rules prohibited open
primaries, and the GOP dropped it after 1980.
   The primary has been estimated to cost the state about $5.2
million.
</TEXT>
