<HEAD>Top Ohio Democrats Stay Neutral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio's top Democrats say they will remain
neutral despite Michael Dukakis' New York primary victory making
him the front-runner for the party's presidential nomination.
   In fact, they differed Wednesday on whether the Masschusetts
governor had locked up the party's nomination based on his showing
in New York.
   Sen. John Glenn said Dukakis seemed virtually assured of the
nomination, but Gov. Richard Celeste and Ohio Democratic Chairman
James Ruvolo cautioned, however, that it was too early to count out
Jesse Jackson.
   ``I would presume at this point it looks like Dukakis is going
to be the candidate,'' Glenn told reporters during an informal
morning briefing in Washington. ``I don't think there's a whole lot
of doubt about that. The New York thing almost locks it up for
Dukakis, or comes close to it.''
   Celeste said a crucial battle looms June 7 in California, where
he noted that a Democratic front-runner has not won a primary since
1972.
   ``It's not over, although Dukakis got a big boost going into
Pennsylvania and Ohio,'' Ruvolo said of the New York results.
   However, Ruvolo said he would not endorse a candidate prior to
Ohio's May 3 primary because he wants to see that Jackson ``has a
fair shot'' in Ohio.
