<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-21 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Recovers, Stock Prices Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
today, recovering most of its losses from the day before, while
stock prices slipped back slightly.
   The dollar closed at 124.30 yen, up 0.40 yen from its close of
123.90 yen Wednesday, when it lost 0.47 yen. It had opened the day
at 124.27 yen and fluctuated in a narrow range between 124.20 yen
and 124.36 yen.
   ``Trading was quiet without particular incentives to stimulate
the market,'' said a dealer at a major commercial bank, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Except for transactions of light amounts by some trading houses,
most investors sidestepped the market, partly because of possible
intervention by the Bank of Japan, he said.
   The Bank of Japan does not officialy comment on its market
activities.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
issues, a 207.09-point winner Wednesday, lost a light 35.93 points,
or 0.13 percent, to end the day at 26,828.16.
   Traders said investors, already inclined to stay on the
sidelines as the holiday season approaches, were even more cautious
because of developments in the U.S. bond and stock markets. The
Tokyo market will be closed on April 29, and May 3-5 for national
holidays.
   Other than some activity in speculative issues, trading was
lackluster, the traders said.
   Volume on the first section trade was estimated at 650 million
shares, down from 1 billion shares Wednesday. Declining issues
outpaced advancers 501 to 402, while 155 issues were unchanged.
   Among the major losers were steels and shipbuildings.
Electricals, nonferrous metals, oils were also lower. Some of the
autos rose.
</TEXT>
