<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RareHatch     04-21 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rare Hatch,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare Chicks Hatched In Captivity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two chicks of a bird species found only on
an island off East Africa have been hatched here, wildlife
authorities said.
   The chicks _ Mauritius kestrels _ were displayed Wednesday at
The World Center for Birds of Prey south of Boise.
   One was hatched Tuesday and the other on April 13, are the first
kestrels to be hatched in captivity in the United States, officials
said.
   ``This is a real accomplishment,'' said Bill Burnham, director
of the center.
   He said the birds exist only on the Indian Ocean island of
Mauritius.
   The birds were on the verge of extinction when the Boise-based
Peregrine Fund began studying the species in 1973. Through captive
breeding in Mauritius, the population has grown to more than 70
birds.
   In Mauritius, destruction of the forests in the Black River
Gorge resulted in reduction of the kestrel's favorite food, a
tree-dwelling lizard. It also is located in the middle of a cyclone
belt.
   Kestrel experts like Willard Heck, who is raising the newborns,
said one key to the their survival may lie in forcing them to live
on other islands and to eat a wider variety of food.
   In Idaho, Heck is using forceps to feed the chicks quail that is
ground up like hamburger. The chicks have an excellent chance of
survival, he said.
   Heck hopes to release the kestrels in Mauritius next fall. They
weigh less than an ounce now, and will weigh about half a pound
when fully grown.
   The Peregrine Fund is a non-profit organization founded in 1970.
Known best for its pioneering work in preventing the extinction of
Peregrine falcons, the center has expanded its focus to preserving
raptors worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
