<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BayWhale     04-21 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bay Whale,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gray Whale Entertains Ferry Passengers in S.F. Bay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A whale with a flare for the dramatic wowed
ferry passengers on the San Francisco Bay, blowing air, waving its
tail and diving under the boat.
   The whale _ dubbed by the ferry crew as ``Flukey'' in reference
to the flukes that make up a gray whale's two-pronged tail _ is
thought to be the same young 25-footer seen this week swimming
around Angel Island and away toward Alcatraz Island, ferry
officials said.
   Passengers on the ferry got out of their seats to watch the
orange-brown juvenile whale with a crown of barnacles, as it dived
beneath the boat.
   Mammal experts said it is not unusual for a young gray whale to
cruise the bay this time of year. This ones seems to be lingering
longer than most, however, they said.
   ``We see a whale in the bay probably once every year, but never
one that hangs around this much,'' said Mick Beatie, one of two
captains running the Larkspur Ferry on Wednesday morning. ``That's
the unusual part about it.''
   The whale, estimated to be 5 years old, could have accidentally
come into the bay on an incoming tide or merely been curious, said
Steve Cooper, education director of the Oceanic Society Expeditions
of San Francisco.
   Thousands of gray whales, an endangered species, are in the
midst of a migration from the warm shallow calving lagoons of Baja
California, in Mexico, to the cool waters of Alaska, where they
will feed during the summer.
</TEXT>
