<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingMarines     04-21 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Marines,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families of Missing Marines Say It Is Difficult to Give Up Hope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOMASVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has ended its search for two
Marines missing in the Persian Gulf, but relatives of the fliers
say it is difficult for them to give up hope.
   ``It's awful to say we've given up,'' said Bob Hill, father of
Capt. Kenneth Hill. ``At the same time, our son has a 4-year-old
who has to be told something _ and we assume it will be that he's
not going to see his daddy again.
   ``I can't imagine it being a week from now and life could still
be like this. Just how do you live with a story that has no
conclusion?''
   A White House spokesman announced Wednesday that the Navy had
ended its search for Hill, 33, of Thomasville, and Capt. Stephen
Leslie, 30, of New Bern.
   The two offically were declared missing.
   The news came little more than a day after the families of both
men learned they had failed to return from a night patrol mission
in the gulf.
   The two Marines, stationed at New River Air Station, were aboard
an AH-1 Cobra helicopter Monday and were to have returned to the
guided missile cruiser Wainwright following the flight. Iran claims
it shot down the helicopter down, but the Pentagon denies that.
   ``We don't blame anyone for calling off the search,'' Bob Hill
said Wednesday afternoon, as tears welled in his eyes. ``We knew
they couldn't keep nine ships out there endlessly.
   ``But we don't know how people are supposed to get through times
like these. At times we're OK. At other times, we feel like the end
of the world has come.''
   ``We're just holding on to faith that Stephen and Ken (Hill)
will be home soon,'' Kenneth Hill's wife, Lora, said. ``We love him
and we want him to come home. But sometimes we don't always get
what we want.''
   A member of the Leslie family, meanwhile, was feeling a mixture
of sorrow and pride.
   ``He told the family if he ever got lost or didn't come back to
remember that he was doing what he wanted to do, and to hold on to
that thought,'' said Leslie's younger sister, 24-year-old Kris.
   ``The waiting has been the worst part. ... We are a close-knit
family and we are banding together,'' Ms. Leslie said.
   Leslie and his wife, Lisa, live in Jacksonville and the couple
is expecting its first child, Ms. Leslie said.
   ``We're very numb right now,'' Ms. Leslie said.
</TEXT>
