<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf in first item bgng ``But EPA ...'' and inserts
3rd graf bgng ``However Moore ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Preliminary Test Results Show Tumors In Mice, EPA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says
preliminary results from new tests show that a controversial
chemical used to regulate the growth of apples does cause tumors in
mice.
   But EPA Assistant Administrator John A. Moore, in an Arpil 8
letter to the International Apple Institute, said the agency does
not yet have enough information to make a decision on what to do.
   However Moore said in the letter, obtained by The Associated
Press on Wednesday, that a decision could be announced as early as
fall on whether to ban use of the chemical.
   The chemical, daminozide had been used on about 40 percent of
the nation's apple crop. Applied in the summer, it slows growth,
makes apples ripen together, deepens color and lengthens storage
life.
   The agency began studying daminozide in 1980 and proposed to ban
it in 1985, but decided to order new studies when its own
scientific advisers said it had not proved its case. It did lower
the permissible residues in apples and the amount that may be used
in orchards.
   ``I hope that it is clear from the information provided in this
letter that we do not yet have enough information'' to decide what
to do about daminozide, Moore wrote.
   Uniroyal Chemical Co. of Middlebury, Conn., which manufactures
daminozide has told apple growers it remains confident that the
chemical, sold under the trade name Alar, eventually will be
cleared.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supermarkets to be Allowed to Offer Rainchecks, Substitutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grocery shoppers will be able to get
rainchecks or substitutes from their supermarkets on advertised
items, under a new Federal Trade Commission rule.
   Although those are common practices of many businesses, they
have technically been illegal for supermarkets a under rule adopted
in 1971.
   Super markets were expected to have enough stock on hand of
advertised items to meet ``reasonably anticipated demand'' and
could have been fined before the FTC rule change.
   The commission voted 3-2 Wednesday to amend that rule to permit
grocers to offer rainchecks or to substitute items if they run out.
   In addition, if grocers want to advertise something they know is
in limited supply, they would be allowed to clearly state in the
ads that supplies are limited.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Torture Victim Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs subcommittee has
unanimously approved a bill that would allow U.S. residents who are
victims of torture overseas to seek civil damages in federal court.
   All torture victims, either foreign aliens or American citizens,
living in the United States would be covered once they had
exhausted all legal remedies in the country where the torture
occurred.
   The families of victims of political killings also would be
entitled to seek damages under the bill.
   Persons who actually committed or ordered torture or political
killings could be sued if they visit the United States.
   The measure, sponsored chiefly by Reps. Gus Yatron, D-Pa., Peter
W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J., and Jim Leach, R-Iowa, has been endorsed by
the American Bar Association and Amnesty International USA, which
told a March 23 subcommittee hearing the bill would help deter the
``human rights epidemic'' of torture which is practiced
systematically in 30 countries.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New AIDS Data May Show Spread In Asia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new report shows AIDS is ``smoldering'' in
Asia, according to the Agency for International Development.
   Dr. Jeffrey Harris, the agency's AIDS coordinator, said at a
congressional hearing on Wednesday, that new data received earlier
this week from the World Health Organization on intravenous drug
users in Bangkok, Thailand, put their infection rate at 16 percent
in the first three months of this year.
   The same group had only a 1 percent infection rate last year,
said Harris.
   ``There's a fire raging in the Caribbean,'' Harris said. ``It's
smoldering in Latin America and it may be beginning to smolder in
Asia.''
   Bradshaw Langmaid, chairman of the agency's working group on
AIDS cited prostitutes who are often the sexual partners of addicts
in Thailand, a favorite vacation spot for many people in Asia, as
the likely spreaders of the deadly immune system disease.
   In a statement submitted to the foreign operations subcommittee
of the House Appropriations Committee, Langmaid said, ``in general,
Asian governments view AIDS as a less urgent problem and have moved
more slowly to undertake AIDS prevention and control efforts.''
</TEXT>
