<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-21 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pacific Storm System Brings Rain, Wind, Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge storm system produced scattered showers and mountain
snowfall across the West today after pelting California with hail
and stirring up damaging winds.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered late Wednesday from
western Oregon into the central California valleys. Southern
California had localized flooding Wednesday and was expected to
receive 1 to 2 inches of rain overnight.
   A combination of rain and glare from the setting sun caused a
39-car accident on the Pomona Freeway Wednesday that injured 19
motorists, one seriously, in the City of Industry, 25 miles east of
Los Angeles.
   A funnel cloud or tornado tore up the roof of a home, uprooted
trees and hurled a refrigerator from a porch into a ditch Wednesday
in Bear Valley, northwest of Los Angeles.
   Snow was expected to continue falling today in the mountains of
Southern California, with 4 to 8 inches expected down to elevations
of 5,000 feet. Late Wednesday, when snow was limited mostly to
elevations greater than 6,000 feet, Big Bear measured 5 inches of
new snow and Mount Wilson and Lake Arrowhead reported nearly 3
inches.
   The storm system causing the rain and snow extended from the
central coastal states into the Pacific west of Baja California.
   Showers and a few isolated thunderstorms occurred from the
northern Plateau region into northern Arizona. Wind gusts of 54
miles per hour were clocked at Lander, Wyo., Wednesday evening as
showers moved into the area.
   A winter storm warning for as much as a foot of snow continued
this morning for elevations above 6,500 feet in northern Arizona.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered early this morning
across much of South Dakota into the Nebraska panhandle.
   Rain showers were also scattered from the eastern Great Lakes
and upper Ohio Valley to the middle Atlantic Coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included more than a half-inch at Cedar City, Utah, and more than a
third of an inch at Salem, Ore.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in
Nebraska, South Dakota and much of the area west of the Rockies,
with snow in higher elevations; widely scattered thunderstorms in
eastern Oklahoma; and scattered showers in Kentucky, northern
Tennessee, eastern New York state and New England.
   Highs were expected in the 50s or 60s across most of the nation,
except 70s or 80s in the Southeast and from the southern Plains to
southeast New Mexico, 90s in western Texas, 40s or lower along the
Canadian border from New England to Montana and 30s or 40s in
northern Arizona.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 22
degrees at Sawyer Air Force Base near Marquette, Mich., to 76
degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 fair; Boston 39 fair; Buffalo 36 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 56 fair; Cincinnati 46 fair; Cleveland 38 fair;
Detroit 33 fair; Miami 66 fair; New York 47 cloudy; Philadelphia 46
cloudy; Pittsburgh 43 cloudy; Portland 29 fair; Washington 48
partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 36 cloudy; Chicago 37 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
67 fair; Denver 54 fair; Des Moines 41 fair; Indianapolis 39 fair;
Kansas City 53 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 32 fair; Nashville 52
fair; New Orleans 62 foggy; St. Louis 52 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 59 partly cloudy; Anchorage 37 cloudy; Las
Vegas 51 cloudy; Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 69 cloudy; Salt Lake
City 47 windy; San Diego 54 showers; San Francisco 54 partly
cloudy; Seattle 50 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 36 cloudy; Toronto 36 windy.
