<DOCNO> AP880421-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-PoolReport     04-21 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool Report,0987</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alarms And Tension As U.S. Awaits Possible Iranian Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS JACK WILLIAMS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occasional alarms and tension
kept sailors alert aboard this guided-missile frigate in the
Persian Gulf as the United States waited for signs of new Iranian
attacks.
   Senior officers analyzed the tactical and technical data still
flowing in on Monday's battles with Iran in the gulf. Meanwhile, a
search was called off for a U.S. Marine helicopter carrying a
two-man crew that vanished hours after the day-long exchange of
gunfire on Monday had ended.
   Officers on the Jack Williams, flagship for one of the three
surface action groups of three ships each, said there was nothing
to support Iran's claim that the AH-1 Cobra gunship was shot down.
   It was the third U.S. helicopter lost in the gulf since July
1987, when the Reagan administration began providing naval escort
for 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers re-registered under the Stars and
Stripes for protection from Iranian attack.
   The 200-plus crew members of the Jack Williams were still
putting things back in order _ cleaning equipment, weapons and
passageways _ in the wake of Monday's action.
   In the course of it, Iran fired five missiles at the Jack
Williams and two destroyers sailing with it. Navy officers said
they were Chinese-made Silkworm missiles fired from anti-ship
batteries along the Strait of Hormuz for the first time. The
Pentagon said it had not determined what type of missile was fired.
All five missiles went awry, their guidance systems confused by
aluminum chaff fired into the air by the U.S. ships.
   The 3,700-ton frigate, operating in the southern gulf, remained
at Condition 1-Alpha, the second-highest level of alert in the
Navy, below General Quarters.
   The Williams' skipper, Cmdr. Edward Mann, 42, of Bucks County,
Pa. said: ``We can do this for a month if necessary, because we
have trained, organized and planned to do it _ we came here ready
for the long haul.''
   An alarm sounded at midmorning Wednesday when the ship's radar
picked up a signal that the Combat Information Center evaluated as
a Sea Hunter radar system, one that Iran is known to possess and
that can be used to locate a missile target.
   Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke, a spokesman for the Navy's Joint Task
Force Middle East, said the radar twitch would be analyzed to
determine where it originated.
   The missile destroyer Joseph Strauss and the destroyer O'Brien
are also part of Desron 22, the Destroyer Squadron Command aboard
this warship. O'Brien's home port is San Diego, Strauss is based at
Pearl Harbor.
   Also Wednesday, the Jack Williams warned off an Iranian C-130
aircraft, whose pilot at first ignored the ship's radioed
challenges and then answered by saying: ``We are an Iranian
warplane, doing our duty.''
   A voice, speaking accented english, then said: ``Martyr, do your
duty.''
   Minutes after the C-130 landed at Iran's nearby Abu Musa Island,
the frigate went to General Quarters as a precaution against the
possibility that a canister of CS, a non-lethal type of riot
control gas, had been dropped in the area. A team checked the ship,
and found no indications any such canister had been dropped.
   The ship also received brief reports of Iranian speedboats
attacking commercial vessels in the Strait of Hormuz and the
discovery of two floating mines, apparently by the French navy
farther north.
   British and Italian minesweepers also were understood to be
taking part in mine-hunting operations in international waters of
the central gulf.
   Capt. Donald Dyer, commander of Desron 22, said the mines
apparently were floating rather than moored, and were found 70
miles southwest of where the U.S. guided-missile frigate Samuel B.
Roberts was severely damaged last week.
   The United States accused Iran of laying the mine that damaged
the Roberts and retaliated by shelling two Iranian oil platforms.
After that, Iranian attack boats went on a rampage and U.S. naval
forces and neutral shipping. U.S. forces sank or damaged six
Iranian warships.
   The Jack Williams crew on Wednesday hashed over the events, the
first combat experience for all expect the captain, Cmdr. Edward
Mann, and Master Chief Petty Officer Joseph Johnson.
   The crewmen, whose average age is about 22, appeared generally
united in believing that the U.S. action against Iran was proper.
   ``Nobody wants to kill people but you can't just let them run
over everybody,'' said Petty Officer 2nd class Larry Doyle, 20, of
Zanesville, Ohio.
   Doyle, the ship's storekeeper, was a communications man on the
bridge throughout those hectic hours, when missiles left the sky
criss-crossed with trails and deck officers shouted ``Silkworm
inbound!'' as the lumbering projectiles were spotted visually or by
electronic means.
   Also on the bridge was Seaman Edwin Rivera, 25, who lives with
his wife in Mayport, Fla., home port of the Jack Williams.
   Rivera, who keeps a diary of everything that has happened on his
frigate's gulf excursion, said the situation was scary. ``But the
worst was when our own missile was fired and we didn't know it was
going to happen. it took everybody by surprise,'' he said.
   Gunner's Mate David Talbert, 18, said he was manning the
Williams' 76-mm deck gun during the excitement and found it ``the
same as always when we're at General Quarters.
   ``But there's a helpless feeling in there _ not knowing what's
going on is worse than something happening,'' said Talbert, whose
class at Northwestern High School in Springfield, Ohio, will
graduate in June.
   Some sailors asked members of a Pentagon news media pool aboard
the frigate to let their relatives in the United States know that
they were all right.
   ``That's the most important thing, to let them know that,'' said
Doyle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
