<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Parliament     04-21 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Parliament,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Of Commons Suspends Maverick Legislator For 20 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Commons barred a militant Scottish
member from the next 20 working days of Commons business for
damaging the 16th-century staff that symbolizes the speaker's
authority.
   Legislators voted 463-26 Wednesday night to suspend Ron Brown, a
left-wing member of the socialist opposition Labor Party.
   Brown grabbed the ornate 5-foot-long mace in the Commons on
Monday night and dropped it in front of the sergeant-at-arms in an
angry protest over government cuts in welfare payments.
   The suspension vote followed Brown's refusal Tuesday to read out
a formal statement of apology for his behavior.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Labor Party hierarchy voted to ostracize
Brown from any role in party activities for three months. It is the
first time in 21 years that Labor leaders have taken such action.
   The decision must be approved by a ballot of Labor's 229 elected
representatives. Their decision takes effect only when Brown
returns from any suspension agreed by the Commons.
   ``The whole thing is a storm in a tea cup,'' the 47-year-old
Brown told reporters before the vote. ``I have a job of work to do,
and I will still do it even if I am suspended.''
   At the end of debate Monday night, Brown marched from his seat
in the back benches on to the floor of the Commons, threw papers in
the face of a junior government minister, then picked up the
16-pound mace from its resting place at the foot of the table
behind which Commons officers sit.
   What happened next is disputed.
   The Times of London and other news media witnesses said Brown
threw the mace on the floor, causing an estimated $1,890 worth of
damage to the silver-gilt staff, before storming out of the
chamber. Brown says he accidentally dropped the mace.
   The mace is officially part of the Crown Jewels. Its presence in
the Commons indicates the legislative body is in session.
   News reports said Labor Party Leader Neil Kinnock is exasperated
that the antics of rebel Laborites are distracting attention from
Labor's attacks on government moves to reform the post-World War II
welfare benefits system.
   Brown and other militants have vowed to use ``guerrilla
tactics'' to disrupt the Commons, in which Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservatives have a comfortable majority of 102.
   Unruly legislators now routinely hurl insults at each other and
shout down opponents, ignoring appeals for order from Speaker
Bernard Weatherill.
   Last month, Weatherill banned a Scottish National Party
legislator for five days for screaming abuse that caused an
unprecedented suspension of budget day proceedings.
   The uproar was prompted by the government's announcement that it
was slashing income tax for top wage earners from 60 to 40 percent.
</TEXT>
