<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Explosion,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 22 Die In Bus Explosion In Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramilitary rangers accidentally set
off a phosphorus bomb on a passenger bus in northeastern Thailand,
killing at least 22 people and seriously injuring 20, police said
today.
   Among the dead was a 2-year-old girl, they said.
   Col. Sittisak Intomya, provincial police commander, said five
rangers seated at the rear of the bus ignored pleas from other
passengers to put away the bomb as the bus traveled in Nonsoong
district, 200 miles northeast of Bangkok. He gave no details on how
the bomb was detonated, but said the men were believed to have come
from Pakthongchai ranger base.
   The colonel quoted witnesses as saying one ranger escaped after
the explosion. He did not specify if the other rangers were killed
in the blast.
   Phosphorus is poisonous and mixes easily with oxygen and ignites
spontaneously at room temperature.
