<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar opened firmer against major foreign
currencies in Europe today and was holding steady in early trading,
dealers said. Gold prices fell.
   European dealers said there were no fundamental reasons for the
dollar's rebound, although they said the U.S. currency was getting
some support from fears that central banks would step in to stop
any slide.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 124.30. Later, it was also
quoted at 124.30 yen in London.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _ 1.6682 West German marks, up from 1.6635
   _ 1.3780 Swiss francs, up from 1.3745
   _ 5.6660 French francs, up from 5.6490
   _ 1.8715 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8630
   _ 1,240.25 Italian lire, up from 1,234.50
   _ 1.2302 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2283
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8872, cheaper for buyers
than $1.8930 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $453.50 a troy ounce and
at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
slightly higher recommended price of $454. Late Wednesday's bid
price was $456.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $454.80, down from 457.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.04 to close at a bid $454.90.
   Silver was quoted in London Thursday at a bid price of $6.43 a
troy ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.46.
