<DOCNO> AP880421-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleTest     04-21 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Test,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Cautiously Optimistic About Booster Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apparently flawless test-firing of
the space shuttle's redesigned booster rocket has improved the odds
of NASA meeting its goal of resuming manned space flight in
mid-August, officials say.
   Wednesday's two-minute firing of the 126-foot rocket went
smoothly, but spokesmen for NASA and Morton Thiokol, which
manufactures the booster, say it will take a week to 10 days to
verify the test was a success.
   A cursory inspection of the rocket afterward indicated the
redesigned seals in the booster's joints prevented an escape of hot
gases despite deliberately built-in flaws.
   ``It's a happy day for a lot of people,'' said Royce Mitchell,
solid rocket program manager for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. ``So far, it looks excellent.''
   In a post-test briefing, Alan McDonald, Morton Thiokol vice
president for engineering, displayed a graph on which nearly
identical curves compared engineers' predictions with a preliminary
test evaluation taken from electronic monitors.
   ``Unless you're about only eight millimeters away, you can't
tell any difference,'' McDonald said.
   Barring discovery of problems as the rocket is dismantled,
Wednesday's success means Morton Thiokol must conduct only two more
full-scale tests, in June and July, before NASA can proceed with an
August launch of the shuttle Discovery.
   It would be America's first manned space flight since the
shuttle Challenger exploded 70 seconds after liftoff on Jan. 28,
1986, killing seven crew members.
   ``It's like finally winning the quarterfinals of the NCAA,''
McDonald said of the test.
   The critical concern is whether super-hot gases escaped the
flawed seals. A presidential commission blamed the Challenger
disaster on a joint between segments of the booster rocket whose
seals failed, allowing gases to escape and ignite the space craft's
exterior fuel tank.
   Since then, engineers have added a third O-ring to the seals and
a metal lip, or capture feature, to contain gases that may leak
around the joints linking the four segments of the rocket.
   The case-to-nozzle joint also has been strengthened with 100
radial bolts to prevent vibration during launch, part of a redesign
planned before the Challenger exploded. This joint attaches the
nozzle to the aft segment.
   In the middle joint, engineers left a gap one-tenth of an inch
wide between two sections of insulation to see if it would seal
itself, under pressure from the expanding gases, as it has in
short-duration tests.
   A second flaw was placed in the adhesive binding insulation
inside the case-to-nozzle joint. A tiny ``blowhole'' was created to
allow gases to reach the ``wiper'' O-ring, which was installed as
part of the new design to keep the adhesive in place. However, it
also acts as an additional seal to protect the primary and
secondary O-rings. In the short-duration tests, gases have hit the
wiper ring but have not gone past it.
   McDonald said the flaws were more severe than anything likely to
occur during manufacture or assembly.
   ``It is, indeed, a fail-safe. If at any time gas gets beyond the
point we expect it to, the joint still is going to perform,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EditorKilled     04-21 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Editor Killed,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Journalists Outraged By Killing Of Newspaper Columnist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican journalists say the shotgun
slaying of a satirical columnist is part of a pattern of
intimidation, and a colleague said he might ask Mexico's federal
government to take over the investigation.
   Hector Felix Miranda, the 47-year-old co-editor of Zeta, was
killed while driving to work Wednesday morning, said District
Attorney Francisco Dominguez.
   Police said they had not determined a motive.
   According to a spokesman for the state prosecutor's office in
Tijuana, a brown pickup truck with a camper shell pulled alongside
Felix's car. Shots were fired from an automatic 12-gauge shotgun.
   ``This cowardly act increases the climate of insecurity in which
Tijuana journalists live,'' said Enrique Garca Sanchez, city editor
of Tijuana's oldest daily, El Heraldo. He said he would go to
Mexican President Miguel de la Madrid if state investigators do not
solve the case.
   Five Mexican journalists have been killed this year, and 35 have
been killed in the past decade.
   Last year, Zeta's offices were sprayed with bullets from a
passing car. No one was injured and police never found those
responsible.
   Herman Baca, president of the San Diego-based Committee on
Chicano Rights, said Wednesday a letter asking for an investigation
into the slaying was being sent to de la Madrid.
   ``This assassination poses the greatest threat to freedom of the
press in Mexico,'' Baca said. ``There's been a large number of
other journalists who have met a similar fate, and it's obvious
that it has become a pattern to silence the independent press in
Mexico.''
   Jesus Blancornelas, who co-founded the weekly Zeta with Felix in
1980, speculated that the killing was an act of political revenge.
   ``The government said that it respects freedom of expression and
that the police are among the most advanced,'' Blancornelas said.
``We hope that both those things might be demonstrated.''
   Felix, known as ``Felix the Cat,'' wrote for the weekly Zeta,
which has a circulation of 60,000 throughout Baja California. His
column, ``A Little Bit of Something,'' often accused government
officials and business people of arrogant behavior.
   ``He was a satirist. He was very well-known and popular here in
the state,'' said Miguel Cervantes, a writer for Zeta. Cervantes
said Felix had no known enemies and called the shooting ``an act of
cowards'' aimed at muzzling the press.
   Felix's murder follows by two months the still-unsolved slaying
of Manuel Burgueno Orduno, editor of the monthly political magazine
Deslinde, in the Baja California coastal resort city of Mazatlan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
