<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Heathrow     04-21 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Heathrow,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops in Armored Cars, Tanks Tour Heathrow Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers patrolled Heathrow Airport today in
armored cars and tanks in a high-profile, anti-terrorist measure
one day after the hijackers of a Kuwaiti jetliner freed 31 hostages
in Algeria.
   The airport's operators said the patrols, carried out regularly,
were intended to familiarize soldiers with security at Heathrow and
were not a response to a specific terrorist alert.
   The soldiers, wearing battle dress and carrying weapons, set up
checkpoints with police along the airport's perimeter road and at
entrances to the terminal buildings, the British Airports Authority
said.
   The British army has held exercises at Heathrow, the world's
busiest airport in terms of international traffic, since the twin
terrorist attacks at Rome and Vienna airports on Dec. 27, 1985, in
which 20 people were killed.
   Police armed with submachine guns also began patrolling Heathrow
within days of the assaults by Palestinian terrorists. It was
believed to be the first time police in mainland Britain had been
seen displaying automatic weapons. Such official shows of force had
previously been known only in strife-torn Northern Ireland.
   Kuwait said nine Shiite Moslem hijackers were promised safe
passage to Iran or Lebanon after freeing 31 remaining passengers
aboard a Kuwait Airways 747 on Wednesday in Algiers. Two Kuwaiti
hostages were killed during the 16-day hijacking.
</TEXT>
