<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Speakes     04-21 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speakes,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speakes Says Book Not `Kiss-and-Tell'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential spokesman Larry Speakes
said today he made up quotes from President Reagan out of loyalty
to the president, and the adverse reaction to it has been a ``total
surprise.''
   Speakes said he disagrees with Reagan that his book ``Speaking
Out'', which covers his six years at the White House and reveals
the quote-manufacturing, constitutes ``kiss and tell.''
   Speakes, appearing on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, also said he does
not fault the president for forgetting he told him about the phony
quotes while Reagan was in Geneva with Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev. Speakes said in the book that a comment he provided as
having been made by Reagan to Gorbachev was never said, and another
quote he gave as Reagan's actually was said by Secretary of State
George Shultz.
   ``I did it on the spur of the moment. I did it in order to serve
the president. I did it as an act of loyalty to the president,
certainly not as an act of disloyalty to the president,'' Speakes
said.
   The furor over Speakes' confession led to his resignation last
week as chief spokesman for Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York _ a job
he took after leaving the White House.
   Reacting to Reagan's criticism of books written by a string of
former administration officials, Speakes said he doesn't think any
of the books, including his, falls into the category of ``kiss and
tell.''
   Such a book would ``have a little more juicy-type items in it
that are a little bit more punchy,'' said Speakes.
   As a former journalist, Speakes was asked if he did not know
that making up quotes would be controversial.
   ``No, it was a total surprise,'' he said. ``A lot of people have
told me that's done all the time in Washington, that you supply a
few quotes.''
   Speakes, who told a Washington Post forum on Tuesday that he had
been ``overzealous'' and ``misguided'' in concocting the quotes,
said today he did not know whether the sin was in the doing or in
the telling about it.
   ``It's hard for me to decide what I'm being critized for,'' he
said.
   Speakes defended his book as an honest account that he hoped
would ``contribute something to the long-term value of insights
into the Reagan administration.'' He said Reagan's presidency was a
watershed because he has ``changed the way we think about
government.''
   Speakes said he was pleased with indications that the book is
selling well and said he planned to continue giving public speeches
and promoting the book. ``I'll just let the dust settle a little
bit and look at opportunities in the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
