<HEAD>Pratt & Whitney Calls For Checks After Accident In Seattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pratt & Whitney, maker of the engine involved in
an accident that forced an emergency landing at Seattle-Tacoma
International Airport, has asked users of the same model engine to
check their fuel filters.
   Federal crash investigators have been looking into whether a
loose fuel filter on a Horizon Air de Havilland Dash 8 might be
linked to Friday's engine fire and emergency landing in which 19
passengers were injured.
   ``Pratt & Whitney has gone out with an all-operator's wire
telling them to check their fuel filters to make sure they're on
tight,'' said Bob Benzon, lead investigator for the National
Transportation Safety Board team.
   The manufacturer sent telegrams to the operators Wednesday.
