<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DemjanjukConfession     04-21 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk Confession,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guard Says Demjanjuk Confessed To Serving At Death Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk, convicted of being a
brutal Nazi death camp guard despite his insistence that he was a
victim of mistaken identity, admitted his guilt two years ago, a
U.S. marshal says.
   Demjanjuk, a former Cleveland autoworker who was found guilty
Monday by an Israeli court of war crimes, said in the hearing of
Lee Koury and another marshal accompanying him from a federal
penitentiary in Springfield, Mo., to Israel in February 1986:
``They don't understand. It was war. I had to do it.''
   ``The statement was made almost like he was thinking out loud,''
Koury said Wednesday. ``He was sort of looking out the (airplane)
window. The statement was not made to the deputy or me.
   ``It was an admission of guilt. But I didn't think much of it at
the time. I knew that Demjanjuk had fought losing his citizenship
and being extradited. But I did not know that he had denied that he
was who they believed he was.''
   And Deputy Marshal Richard Schroeder said: ``It was clear to me
that when he realized he was really going to Israel, he was trying
to justify to himself what he had done. He was trying to
rationalize.''
   Demjanjuk was convicted of being the Treblinka death camp guard
known as `Ivan the Terrible'' for his brutality. Ivan helped
operate the gas chambers at the camp in Nazi-occupied Poland, where
850,000 Jews were killed in 1942 and 1943. According to testimony
at the 14-month trial, Ivan often exceeded the atrocities ordered
by his superiors, beating prisoners on their way to the gas
chambers with a metal bar or bayonet.
   He is to be sentenced Monday and could receive the death penalty.
   Two days after their arrival in Israel, Koury, the U.S. marshal
for the Western District of Missouri, said Israeli prosecutors
interviewed him and Schroeder for four hours about Demjanjuk's
statement. Both officers were listed as trial witnesses, though
they were never called to testify.
   He said they also were asked by the Justice Department and the
Israeli government not to mention the statement until after the
case was resolved.
   Koury and Schroeder said Demjanjuk struck them as a man who knew
his time was coming.
   ``I remember that when we landed in Israel, he turned and looked
me square in the eyes and said, `You've brought me here to be
hanged,''' Schroeder said.
   ``He seemed a little apprehensive as we were handing him over to
Israeli authorities,'' Koury said.
   But the only emotion he showed, the marshal added, ``was when he
made that statement: `They don't understand. It was war. I had to
do it.'''
</TEXT>
