<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RacialHarassment     04-21 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racial Harassment,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Look At Possible Civil Rights Violations in Harassment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black businessman was hospitalized after
he swallowed pieces of glass and part of a mouse at a restaurant he
had been warned to avoid, he and his mother say.
   Oliver ``Sterling'' Mason III, 20, owner of a gift shop in a
Holiday Inn, complained to Anne Arundel County police last week
that he had received racist letters and an anonymous warning
telling him not to eat in the hotel again.
   He lost consciousness after taking a bite of a crab dish Tuesday
at the Holiday Inn restaurant.
   Maura Vonasek, a spokeswoman at Anne Arundel General Hospital,
said Dr. Daniel McCabe found scratches in Mason's mouth and upper
esophagus. More X-rays will be analyzed today, she said. Mason was
released Wednesday.
   A police report confirmed that pieces of a mouse and glass were
found in food retrieved from the restaurant by Mason's mother,
Griselda Mason, 44, of Ellicott City.
   Mrs. Mason said her son had sent his crab dish back to the
kitchen to be reheated. When the food was returned, Mason took a
bite and they both heard a ``crunching sound,'' she said. He began
to choke, stood up, grabbed his throat and vomited, she said.
   An official of the hotel said in a statement Wednesday he
disputed Mason's story.
   ``Our investigation of the matter and interviews with our
employees gives us no reason whatsoever to believe that there is
any truth to Mr. Mason's charges of either discrimination or
contaminated food,'' Jaap van der Vorm, vice president of
Alexandria Management Co., which owns the hotel and restaurant.
   ``No one on the property ever saw the contaminated food. The
hotel staff did call the rescue squad when Mr. Mason appeared to
suffer a seizure in the restaurant. ... At this time we are not
ruling out the possibility of a hoax,'' van der Vorm said.
   Mason last week filed a complaint with police over six letters
filled with sexual and racist innuendo. He said he believed the
anonymous letters came from a hotel employee.
   County police decided the letters did not constitute a threat
under state law and referred the case to the FBI as a possible
civil rights violation.
   City Councilman Carl Snowden demanded the U.S. Justice
Department investigate whether Mason's civil rights were violated.
The Justice Department said it would.
</TEXT>
