<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bankston     04-21 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bankston,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules State Can't Execute Underage Killers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia law prohibits the execution of murderers
who were under the age of 17, the state Supreme Court has ruled.
   The court's decision Wednesday prohibits the state from seeking
a death sentence against Clinton Bankston Jr., who was indicted in
Clarke County for two murders alleged to have been committed when
he was 15 years old and for three slayings when he was 16.
   Bankston is charged with murder in Athens in the April 1987
knife slayings of Glenn and Rachael Sutton, two retired University
of Georgia professors; and the August 1987 hatchet slayings of
Sally Nathanson, 59, her daughter, Helen Nathanson, 22, and Mrs.
Nathanson's sister, Ann Orr Morris, 63.
   His attorneys say Bankston will plead innocent by reason of
insanity.
   At issue in Wednesday's Supreme Court ruling was a statute
dealing generally with capital cases which includes this provision:
   ``When it is shown that a person convicted of a capital offense
without a recommendation for mercy had not reached his 17th
birthday at the time of the commission of the offense, the
punishment of such person shall not be death but shall be
imprisonment for life.''
   Bankston's attorneys had filed a pre-trial motion to prevent the
district attorney from seeking the death penalty, but it was
rejected by the trial judge.
   The court said that the context of the statute did raise a
question whether the Legislature intended only to block the the
death penalty for those under 17 who were charged with capital
crimes other than murder, such as rape, kidnapping and armed
robbery.
   However, it said a 1977 U.S. Supreme Court decision effectively
blocked the death penalty for all but murder cases.
</TEXT>
