<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     04-21 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christians and Shiites Clash, Two Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Shiite Moslem militiamen
battled with rockets and machine guns in south Beirut today, and
police said two people were killed and five wounded.
   Police said Shiite gunmen from various factions and Justice
Minister Nabih Berri's Amal movement fought the right-wing
Christian Lebanese Forces militia for about an hour.
   A police spokesman said he did not know what sparked the clash,
the second in four days between the Shiites and the Lebanese Forces.
   But it flared after the Syrian-backed Amal said it had thwarted
a bizarre plot by the Lebanese Forces to assassinate Berri.
   The independent An-Nahar daily quoted an unidentified Amal
official as charging that the Christians had assigned a maid
working at Berri's home to assassinate him with an
``explosives-rigged jacket.''
   An Amal official contacted by The Associated Press said the
An-Nahar report was true.
   He refused to disclose the woman's whereabouts or say whether
she had voluntarily informed Amal of the alleged plot. The Lebanese
Forces declined comment.
   Berri is Syria's main ally in Lebanon. The Lebanese Forces, led
by Samir Geagea, is at odds with Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon.
   A strike called by the General Confederation of Labor Unions was
partially observed today, reflecting disunity among workers on how
to combat a severe economic crisis.
   Representatives of the 300,000-member confederation toured
Beirut's Moslem and Christian sectors and other cities trying to
muster support for the strike.
   The unions seek a 300 percent pay raise. They rejected the
government's offer of a 75 percent increase.
   The Lebanese economy, once the most flourishing in the Middle
East, has been torn by 13 years of civil war. Inflation is rampant,
unemployment growing and the Lebanese pound has collapsed.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said about 50 percent of Moslem and Christian areas
were closed.
   Some schools, restaurants, movie theaters, gasoline stations and
other businesses stayed open in Beirut. Union officials led
supporters in two demonstrations urging the government to respond
to their demands.
   ``We are hungry, we want to eat,'' the estimated 3,000
demonstrators chanted.
</TEXT>
