<DOCNO> AP880421-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   04-21 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0576,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Stop Bombarding Each Other's Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf: ``The unofficial.... to CORRECT day to Wy,
sted Tuesday. Pick up 4th graf pvs: ``During their...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq observed a cease-fire today
in their seven-week ``war of the cities'' after Iraq fired missiles
into the holy city of Qom and said it would stop firing if Iran
also did.
   Iran's navy commander said his warships fought a ``heroic
battle'' against U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf on Monday and
charged the Americans fired on his men in the water after they
abandoned their vessels.
   The unofficial cease-fire, which Iraq said would begin at
midnight (4 p.m. EDT Wednesday), appeared to be holding despite an
all-out mobilization declared by Iran to confront the United States
and Iraq.
   During their 7{-year war, Iran and Iraq have observed several
temporary cease-fires when one side offered to stop firing if it
had the last shot. The bombardments usually resume after a short
period.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said Iraqi
troops fired two long-range missiles into Qom at 11:45 p.m. and
said they would be the last if Iran did not retaliate.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, said several civilians were killed and others wounded when
the missiles exploded in residential areas of the holy city, 100
miles south of Tehran and the seat of Iran's religious hierachy.
   The Iraqis earlier fired missiles into Tehran, the central city
of Isfahan and the southern city of Shiraz. IRNA reported civilians
were killed, but gave no numbers.
   Since the latest flareup in the war of the cities began Feb. 29,
hundreds of civilians have been killed in missile, air and
artillery attacks. Iran and Iraq have pounded each other's cities
intermittently since 1984.
   IRNA said Iranian forces killed or wounded 300 Iraqis and
captured more than 250 in the Shemiran mountain region of Kurdistan
in northern Iraq on Wednesday.
   Iraq said its forces were mopping up Iranian pockets of
resistance in the southern Faw peninsula, which it recaptured from
Iran over the weekend.
   At United Nations headquarters in New York, Iran on Wednesday
told the U.N. Security Council that Iraq used ``cyanide, nerve and
mustard gases'' on a large scale during the battle in the Faw
peninsula.
   The U.S. frigate USS Jack Williams went on alert Wednesday after
an Iranian C-130 transport plane ignored a warning as it approached
the vessel in the gulf.
   ``We are an Iranian warplane, doing our duty,'' the pilot
responded.
   ``Martyr, do your duty,'' added an unidentified voice.
   Minutes after the plane landed at Iran's nearby Abu Musa Island,
the frigate went to ``general quarters,'' the Navy's highest alert,
and crewmen investigated whether the plane had dropped a canister
of CS riot control gas on the ship. Nothing was found.
   The Iranians' clashes Monday with the U.S. Navy and the
unexpected Iraqi recapture of Faw, the first major Iraqi offensive
in two years, have clearly jolted the Iranians.
   Tehran Radio said all volunteers, known as ``basij,'' should
report to bases throughout the country ``and get ready for
departure'' to the battlefront.
   The U.S. Navy destroyed two Iranian oil platforms, sank an
Iranian patrol boat, crippled two frigates and damaged three other
attack boats on Monday. It was the worst U.S.-Iran clash since the
Navy buildup last July to curb Iranian attacks on shipping.
   The Iranians said they lost 44 men in Monday's clashes. There
were no reported U.S. casualties, but the two-man crew of a Marine
helicopter was missing.
   IRNA quoted Iranian Rear Adm. Mohammed-Hussein Malekzadegan as
saying the Americans fired on crewmen from the frigate Joshan who
had jumped into the water and killed several.
   The agency also quoted an unidentifed naval officer as saying
the Americans shot missiles at Iranian crewmen in lifeboats and
killed several, including a marine who had rescued six of his
comrades.
   A U.S. Navy officer aboard the Williams, which was involved in
Monday's fighting, said the captain of the Sabalan, the other
Iranian frigate damaged in the battle, was ``a real fanatic.''
   ``He's the one who shoots holes in the tankers in the Strait of
Hormuz, then says, ``Have a nice day,''' said the officer, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
