<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Military-Philippines     04-21 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military-Philippines,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Scouting Alternative Sites for Philippines' Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD GRAVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military teams are scouting Pacific and
Southeast Asian nations for alternative sites in event new military
lease agreements can't be reached with the Philippines' government,
says America's top Pacific military commander.
   There is a ``serious-minded, success-oriented approach to the
alternatives,'' Adm. Ronald J. Hays said.
   Hays said in an interview Monday that he has been surprised at
the intensity of issues being debated in the review of the 1947
Military Bases Agreement under which the United States maintains
facilities at Clark Air Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller
installations in the Philippines. The agreement expires in
September 1991.
   ``However, I'm still optimistic about reaching an agreement. The
economic security and political implications associated with our
departure would be astronomical,'' Hays said.
   He declined to identify nations which might host U.S. military
bases.
   ``The problem is that the nations who are forthcoming to us on a
private basis and who will readily concede that indeed bases at
Clark and Subic are important are unwilling for a variety of
reasons to go public and to take an official public position of
support for the United States,'' said Hays.
   The admiral said it would cost $10 billion or more to duplicate
the facilities in the Philippines. However, he said that less than
half that amount might be available to prepare alternate bases,
which would mean a reduced U.S. presence in the region.
</TEXT>
