<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolicemanKilled     04-21 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Policeman Killed,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Officer's Slaying, Ambulance Response</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they have no suspects in the first
killing of an officer this year, but authorities also opened an
investigation into why the ambulance carrying him bypassed the
hospital nearest the shooting.
   Henry Ford Hospital officials said they were prepared to treat
Officer Paul Dunbar Jr. after being alerted by Emergency Medical
Service dispatchers but he never arrived.
   Dunbar, 31, died in surgery at 4 a.m. Wednesday at Detroit
Receiving Hospital.
   Mayor Coleman Young said the city would investigate
communications between Ford Hospital, EMS dispatchers and the
ambulance that picked up Dunbar at the shooting scene.
   Dunbar was found shortly after 3 a.m. with a gunshot wound to
his chest in front of a home on the city's north side, Officer
Allene Ray said.
   Police had no suspects, said Officer Fred Zaharoff.
   Neighbors quoted anonymously in the Detroit Free Press today
said Dunbar was shot outside a house where ``crack'' cocaine has
been sold in recent weeks. Unidentified police sources were quoted
in the newspaper as saying Dunbar was the subject of an internal
drug investigation. Zaharoff refused to confirm that.
   Zaharoff also said police were not directly involved in the
ambulance investigation. Ford Hospital is about one mile from where
Dunbar was found; Receiving Hospital is three miles away.
   Brian Cheatham, a Ford Hospital spokesman, declined to speculate
whether the additional time needed to take Dunbar to Receiving
Hospital might have given surgeons time to save the officer's life.
   Calls to EMS officials were referred to Robert Berg, a spokesman
for Young, who did not return telephone calls.
</TEXT>
