<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha 1stLd-Writethru a0580 04-21 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Botha, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Proposes Expanded Black Political Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE quotes, details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha today
proposed including blacks in the electoral college that chooses the
president and possibly in the Cabinet.
   In a major speech to Parliament, Botha stopped far short of
proposing full black voting rights or abolition of apartheid
legislation.
   But he said his National Party would stick to its widely
criticized program of slow-paced reforms despite claims from the
increasingly powerful far right that most of the 5 million whites
oppose even modest concessions to the black majority.
   Botha's proposal to include blacks on the electoral college
would, if implemented, mark the first time that blacks had a direct
voice in the selection of South Africa's president. He gave no
details about how much strength blacks might be given on the
college.
   Botha also suggested that the Cabinet might be opened to people
not serving in Parliament. This would clear the way for
participation by blacks, who are excluded from Parliament.
   Botha's initiatives appeared unlikely to ease international
pressure on South Africa for an end to apartheid, which establishes
racially segregated residential areas, health services and schools
and deprives the 26 million blacks of a vote in national affairs.
   But domestically, Botha's message seemed to be that his
government would not be intimidated by the success of the
extreme-right Conservative Party in three recent parliamentary
by-elections.
   ``I appeal to everyone to remain calm, to restore balance and to
recognize each other's rights,'' he said. ``If we wish to live
together peacefully in this beautiful land, the time has come to
reflect on what unites us instead of emphasizing that which divides
us.''
   Botha reiterated his government's longstanding proposal for
creating a national advisory council on which he and his top
Cabinet ministers would negotiate with black leaders on drafting a
new constitution that would bring blacks into the central
government.
   ``We are not committed to the name, the form, the composition or
the functions of such a body,'' he said. ``We are committed to the
concept of a forum for deliberation.''
   Most prominent black leaders have rejected Botha's overtures to
participate in the national council. They say the government first
must free imprisoned black nationalist leaders like Nelson Mandela
and lift restrictions on major anti-apartheid organizations.
   Botha became South Africa's prime minister in 1978. That
postition was abolished in 1984 with the adoption of a new
constitution, and he was installed as president.
   In his speech, Botha proposed that the office of prime minister
be revived to handle day-to-day governmment affairs so the
president could be freed to concentrate on major policy matters and
ceremonial duties.
   Botha said political progress in South Africa would be impeded
by continued foreign pressure from the ``international brotherhood
of persecutors.''
   He also chided anti-apartheid clergymen, such as Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu, for their increasingly vocal opposition to
the government and their continuing calls for punitive sanctions.
   ``They take the lead in isolating the republic in economic and
other fields, without caring in the least about the detrimental
results,'' Botha said. ``They accordingly play into the hands of
the ANC.
   The outlawed African National Congress is the major guerrilla
movement fighting the government.
   The president said only a small fraction of South Africa's
Christians supported the anti-apartheid stance of Tutu and other
clergymen affiliated with the South African Council of Churches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
