<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Israel     04-21 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Israel,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Administration Prods Israel to Move to Peace Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, in a statement
issued on Israel's 40th anniversary, prodded Israel and other
nations in the Mideast ``to move ahead and get to productive peace
negotiations.''
   President Reagan ``remains convinced that our peace initiative
is balanced and offers the only realistic basis on which to make
progress,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in a
statement.
   The statement was issued after Reagan signed a U.S.-Iraeli
memorandum that formalizes the two nation's consultative groups and
their strategic cooperation. The groups meet periodically to
discuss joint military and security assistance, as well as economic
development issues.
   The Oval Office meeting, reportedly attended by Vice President
George Bush and Isaeli ambassador Moshe Arad, was closed to
reporters.
   The memo, Fitzwater said in a statement, ``reflects the enduring
U.S. commitment to Israel's security. That commitment will never
flag.''
   ``The president knows that a strong Israel is necessary if peace
is to be possible. He also knows that Israel can never be truly
secure without peace.''
   The statement noted that Secretary of State George Shultz has
been asked to pursue the U.S. peace initiative in the region and to
seek ``a comprehensive settlement which will assure Isareli
security and provide for the legitimate rights of the Palestinian
people.''
   Shultz has shuttled among the Israelis and Arabs in recent weeks
with little success in promoting the U.S. peace plan.
   ``The president reiterates his appeal to the leaders in the
region not to miss this opportunity to move ahead and get to
productive peace negotiations. This has been an objective that
Israel has fervently sought over the last 40 years,'' Fitzwater's
statement said.
</TEXT>
