<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NavajoBaby     04-21 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navajo Baby,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Custody Hearing, Denounced as Kangaroo Court, Reconvenes
Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUBA CITY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tribal judge said his dismissal of an
attorney left him with no choice but to delay a hearing in a
custody dispute between the Navajos and a California couple over a
9-month-old Navajo girl.
   Judge Manuel Watchman of Navajo Tribal Children's Court on
Wednesday recessed Allyssa Keetso's temporary custody hearing for
48 hours after he disqualified a court-appointed lawyer from
representing the child.
   ``Certainly a child has the right to be represented adequately
at these proceedings, and that was the bottom line of this whole
thing,'' Watchman said after the hearing.
   A tribal lawyer said it was likely another attorney would be
named by Friday.
   Attorney Robert Walters was dismissed after he entered a motion
to dismiss the temporary custody proceeding.
   Violet A.P. Lui, an attorney representing the tribe, declined
comment.
   Karen Diakun, a tribal spokeswoman, said Watchman placed the
baby temporarily in the custody of Rick and Cheryl Pitts of San
Jose, Calif., the non-Indian couple who have cared for her since
birth and who want to adopt her.
   Watchman also ordered them to stay on the reservation, Ms.
Diakun said.
   Patricia Keetso, 21, Allyssa's mother, was pregnant and single
when she contacted the Pittses through a newspaper ad. She lived
with them before and after Allyssa was born and has said she wants
the couple to adopt her daughter.
   Susie Keetso, the baby's grandmother, said, meanwhile, that
tribal representatives had pressured her to sign papers seeking to
bring Allyssa to the reservation for the custody hearing.
   Ms. Diakun said one reason the tribe entered the custody issue
``was a strong desire expressed by the grandparents that they
wanted the child returned to the reservation.''
   But Mrs. Keetso said she always has wanted the Pittses to adopt
Alyssa. ``The way they talked at me, it seemed like they were just
going to put me in jail or something like that,'' she said.
   The tribe intervened in the adoption proceedings under the
Indian Child Welfare Act, which gives tribes jurisdiction under
certain circumstances to determine custody in adoption proceedings.
</TEXT>
