<HEAD>Planes Collide, Two Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with victims' identities.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VERGIATE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small planes collided over northern
Italy today and one crashed into a house. Two people in the other
plane were killed when it crashed into a field.
   Firefighters said the two people aboard a Cessna 150 that
crashed on the outskirts of Vergiate were killed instantly. The
town is near Lake Maggiore about 30 miles northwest of Milan.
   Two people aboard a Siae Marchetti 260 TP that crashed into the
roof of a two-story house were injured and rushed to a hospital.
   The house was badly damaged, but no one was home at the time of
the crash, firemen said.
   Police said the planes collided while preparing to land at a
small air field.
   Authorities identified the dead as Alberto Cattalan, 40, the
instructor who piloted the Cessna, and his apprentice, Giacomo
Nisoli, 25, both Italians.
   Those injured, whose condition was said not to be serious, were
identified as Italian pilot Silvano Galli, and former Dutch air
force pilot Rudolf Herman Friderich, from Leiden. Both are 57 years
old.
