<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede PHILADELPHIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls On Supporters To Help Him `Go Forward'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 4 grafs with Jackson at high school, picking
up in 3rd graf pvs, The Democratic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, boosted by a
Philadelphia newspaper's endorsement, plunged into a series of
north Pennsylvania campaign stops today, five days before the
state's Democratic primary.
   First stop was Williamsport, where he donned a sweatshirt and
gave enthusiastic students his familiar lecture on avoiding illegal
drugs and teen-age sex leading to pregnancy.
   His speech was delayed for a few minutes as students crowded to
the front of the Williamsport Area High School gymnasium to get
photos of Jackson in a sweatshirt with ``Williamsport'' on the
front.
   The night before, Jackson staged a rally at a plaza across from
Philadelphia's City Hall, where a crowd of 3,500 cheered and called
``We want Jesse.''
   The Democratic presidential contender appeared undaunted by his
defeat in New York Tuesday at Michael Dukakis' hands.
   ``We have come a long way, and we will not turn back,'' he said.
``We must go forward. We are almost there. You keep on holding on.
I want to lead our nation beyond racism, beyond sexism, beyond
anti-Semitism.
   ``I give you a choice ... I am the alternative in the Democratic
Party,'' he said.
   Jackson was taken aback when told the Philadelphia Daily News,
an afternoon paper with a circulation of about 252,000, was giving
him its endorsements in today's editions.
   ``I don't believe it!'' he said.
   In its editorial, the Daily News said, ``Nominating Jesse
Jackson sends a message to the world, which is not made up of
elderly white businessmen, no matter what Reagan thinks.
   ``Social change doesn't happen instantly,'' the editorial said.
``It took 32 years after the nomination of Al Smith to elect a
Roman Catholic president. If it's going to take 32 years after the
first black nominee, it's past time to get started, especially
since the black man is the only candidate who seems to understand
the soul of his own party.''
   The same newspaper on Wednesday, joined by the Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette, published a poll that showed Jackson running 40
percentage points behind Dukakis in Pennsylvania. There are 178
Democratic delegates at stake in the primary.
   Jackson declined to comment on the poll, saying, ``I do not
follow opinion polls, I mold opinion. And that's why I am a leader.
I will take my case to the people.''
   Jackson arrived in Philadelphia Wednesday afternoon, and was
greeted by Mayor W. Wilson Goode, the first black mayor in the
nation's fifth largest city.
   Four years ago, the mayor supported Jackson's opponent, Walter
Mondale, but he made an early endorsement of Jackson this year.
   Jackson went to the Philadelphia Nursing Home to visit AIDS
victims. In the lobby he greeted employees and residents, stopping
briefly at the elevator to shake the hand of Gregory Graland,
paralyzed by a bullet in his spine, who was lying on his stomach on
a stretcher.
   ``He said to me, `Hi brother, keep up hope,''' Graland said. ``I
said thank you. I meant to wish him good luck but he went by so
fast.''
   After a half-hour session with a dozen AIDS patients, Jackson
brought victim Drew Aller, 29, into the lobby.
   ``We need to shift the focus from hysteria to health care,''
Jackson said, urging that more resources be devoted to helping
victims of acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``I'm here because I care,'' he said.
</TEXT>
