<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first, New York-dated item in PM-Names to UPDATE
throughout with Trump taking tour of bridge today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump, who scored a public relations coup
over City Hall by rebuilding the Central Park skating rink, today
offered the same deal for repairing the closed Williamsburg Bridge.
   The real estate mogul took a tour of the decaying, 85-year-old
span, then said he would be willing to put up an estimated $250
million, which the government would repay, for repairs. Trump
rebuilt the Wollman Skating Rink under a similar arrangement.
   ``An easy solution is to spend a lot of money but if you can
spend a little money and get the same results for it, or a better
result, that's what I'd be here for,'' Trump said.
   The bridge was closed last week when city transportation
officials found cracks in its beams. An inspection is under way to
determine the extent of the damage, and officials have said the
bridge will be closed at least three weeks.
   Alfred A. DelliBovi, head of the federal Urban Mass
Transportation Administration, had invited Trump to examine the
bridge, and joined him for today's tour.
   In a letter to Trump, Dellibovi lauded him as a builder whose
projects come in ``on time, under budget and built to last.''
   In 1987, Trump showed up the city bureaucracy when he took over
repair of the skating rink and finished the job in five months and
under budget. The city had spent 7{ years and $12 million on what
was supposed to take 2{ years and $4.5 million.
</TEXT>
