<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cicippio     04-21 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cicippio,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photo of Gaunt Hostage Worries Relatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph J. Cicippio, who has been held
hostage in Lebanon for 19 months, has never looked so thin as in a
photograph released this week, relatives said.
   ``This picture sort of shows that he is getting very weak, from
what I can see,'' said Thomas Cicippio, one of five brothers living
in Norristown.
   Cicippio said Wednesday the photograph was ``very distressing''
to the family, particularly because a French hostage released in
November reported that Cicippio was in good health.
   ``He's got a distant look, and I've never seen him so thin. He
really looks down and out to me,'' he said.
   A group calling itself the Revolutionary Justice Organization
included the photograph with a threatening statement delivered to a
Beirut newspaper, warning of retaliation for U.S. military action
in the Persian Gulf this week.
   The photograph showed Cicippio, 57, wearing a navy blue track
suit. He was looking directly into the camera, but he wasn't
wearing his eyeglasses.
   Thomas Cicippio said a U.S. State Department official called
Tuesday to tell him about the photograph released by the group
claiming to hold Cicippio and Edward Austin Tracy, a Vermont writer
abducted in West Beirut in October 1986.
   ``They just informed us there was a new photo released of Joe
and that there were more threats on his life. We haven't heard any
more since then,'' said Cicippio, 64, a retired postal worker who
has acted as spokesman for his family since the abduction Sept. 12,
1986, of his brother, acting comptroller of the American University
of Beirut.
</TEXT>
