<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia-HumanRights     04-21 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Human Rights,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Government Rejects Amnesty International Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amnesty International report on human
rights accuses Colombia's armed forces of political repression and
murder, but government officials criticized the study as one-sided.
   ``There have been only a few occasional faults or excesses, and
these have been punished as an example for others,'' Colombia's
defense minister, Gen. Rafael Samudio Molina, told reporters
Wednesday.
   In a report released Wednesday, the London-based international
human rights organization accused Colombia's armed forces of
engaging in a ``policy of terror and political murder.''
   The report said the armed forces plunged the country into a
``human rights emergency'' by extending political repression to
encompass not only leftists but anyone who failed to support the
government forces.
   Alvaro Tirado, President Virgilio Barco's adviser on human
rights, said, ``if the Amnesty International report shows the armed
forces and the government as the only sources of violence in
Colombia, then it is one-sided.''
   Former Foreign Minister Alfredo Vasquez Carrizosa, president of
the Colombian Committee for Human Rights, said he did not share the
opinion of Amnesty when it charged the ``existence of a deliberate
policy of political murder'' in the armed forces. He said he had
``no evidence for these charges.''
   ``There are paramilitary groups,'' he said. ``These have been
denounced since 1983 by the attorney general. ... My question is:
Why has there been no investigation of those paramilitary groups?''
   Amnesty said that in July and August political repression in
Colombia entered ``a new phase, and the country is in the grip of a
human rights emergency.'' In those two months anonymously authored
`hit lists' of prominent Colombians were published and a wave of
killings of students, university lecturers and human rights leaders
in Medellin was reported.
   Amnesty said ``hundreds of case studies show that killings and
`disappearances' blamed on the `death squads' were in fact carried
out by police and military personnel.''
</TEXT>
