<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KennedyFiles 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 04-21 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Files, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0578, a0540,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Assassination `Polka Dot Dress' Story Was Lie, Witness
Said</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd-4th grafs, `Meanwhile, a ...,' with 2 grafs to
change reference to former prosecutor, CORRECT that Compton
interviewed by telephone from Washington home.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly released police files reveal
that the young woman who reported a ``girl in a polka dot dress''
running from the scene of Robert F. Kennedy's assassination
admitted two weeks later that she had lied.
   ``You know, I thought I was supposed to see more _ more than I
did,'' the woman, Sandra Serrano, says in microfilmed documents in
the Los Angeles Police Department that could lay to rest 20 years
of controversy over the report.
   Meanwhile, a former prosecutor said he is certain no photographs
or investigative matter important to the investigation of the June
5, 1968, assassination were purposely destroyed by police.
   ``There just wasn't any reason for anyone to just deliberately
destroy something that had any significance,'' the former
prosecutor, now Judge Lynn D. Compton of the 2nd District Court of
Appeal, said Wednesday by telephone from a home he has in Lopez,
Wash.
   The files, opened at the state archives on Tuesday, contain a
certificate that shows 2,410 police photographs were burned on Aug.
21, 1968. Chief archivist John Burns speculated the photos may have
duplicated others still in evidence. But he said the files contain
no such statement.
   A large portion of the documents deals with Miss Serrano, a
college student who reported that she had confronted the woman on
the night of Kennedy's shooting at the Ambassador Hotel in Los
Angeles.
   The files showed that Miss Serrano first told her story to
officers at 4 a.m. June 5 at police headquarters in Los Angeles.
She was one of hundreds of witnesses interviewed.
   Miss Serrano, who said she was chairman of the Youth for Kennedy
chapter in Pasadena, said she came to the hotel that night to hear
Kennedy speak but left the Embassy ballroom because it was too
crowded.
   She recalled being seated on a step outside when ``I thought it
was a backfire of a car. ... I thought I heard six shots, six
backfires.
   ``About half a minute later this girl comes tearing down the
stairs saying _she said, `We shot him. We shot him.' And I said,
`Who did you shoot?' And she said, `Senator Kennedy.'''
   She said she had seen the same girl earlier in the evening and
she was clad in a white voile dress with dark polka dots.
   She stood by her story for a time and even went with police to
the Ambassador Hotel for a reenactment of her actions, the file
showed. But on June 20, 1968, when she was reinterviewed by police
after failing a lie detector test, she declared, ``The whole thing
was a lie.''
   She suggested that she and other witnesses who told police about
the polka dot dress had created the story while waiting to be
interviewed by police. She blamed the pressures and excitement of
the event for her actions.
   And she indicated she almost began to believe her own
fabrication.
   ``I don't know why I said it. ... It just fitted. ... I really
thought there was something behind it. I was conned,'' she said.
   The following day, June 21, police canceled an all-points
bulletin for a woman in a white polka dot dress.
   However, the story did not die, and triggered years of
controversy over whether Sirhan Sirhan, the man convicted of
killing Kennedy, had acted alone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
