<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Arizona-Women     04-21 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arizona-Women,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Votes to Drop `Male' Requirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that Rose Mofford has been governor
for more than two weeks, a Senate committee has decided it's time
to change the constitutional provision that bars her from holding
the job.
   The proposed amendment passed 7-0 by the Senate Government
Committee on Wednesday would drop the word ``male'' from the list
of qualifications to be governor, attorney general, treasurer,
secretary of state and school superintendent.
   The amendment has already been approved by the House. If passed
by the Senate, it would go on this fall's election ballot.
   As she voted for the bill, Sen. Carol Macdonald said that when
she read the Arizona Constitution recently, ``I came to this clause
and I about had a stroke.''
   Mrs. Macdonald said she realized the U.S. Constitution took
precedence over the provision but added, nonetheless, ``I think it
ought to be changed.''
   Committee Chairman John Mawhinney drew groans from other panel
members when he joked, ``I wonder whether we could discuss the
appropriateness of whether we ought to allow females to hold these
offices.''
   Sen. Alan Stephens wondered how much it would cost to hold the
public referendum, but added that the proposal was ``something
that's long overdue.''
   Mrs. Mofford became governor April 4 when Evan Mecham was
removed from office on his impeachment conviction by the state
Senate. She had been secretary of state since 1978.
</TEXT>
