<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Switzerland-Spy     04-21 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Switzerland-Spy,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Spy Freed After No Evidence of Swiss Activities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he spied for the Soviet
Union in West Germany was freed and expelled due to insufficient
evidence he spied in Switzerland, the Federal Prosecutor's Office
said Thursday.
   The 41-year-old engineer, a Spanish national, admitted passing
documents from a technical institute to the KGB for years while
living in West Germany, according to the prosecutor's office.
   But an investigation into his Swiss activities was dropped due
to lack of evidence, the statement said.
   The man was barred from re-entering Switzerland, the office
said. A Zurich resident since 1985, he worked in the research
department of a Swiss electronics company.
   The office did not release his name or reveal his whereabouts.
   Deportation to West Germany was ruled out by international
agreements forbidding extradition for political crimes, it said.
   Zurich police detained the man March 23 on a tip resulting from
a sweep by West German authorities that netted 10 suspected Soviet
agents the week before.
