<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MechamReimbursement     04-21 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Reimbursement,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Bills State for Recall Campaign Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham has sent the state
a $230,717 bill for his recall campaign expenses, including office
rent, a down payment on a fund-raising letter and legal fees.
   The bill lists expenses incurred by the former governor from
Feb. 1, the date then-Secretary of State Rose Mofford called the
recall election, to April 4, when Mecham was convicted by the
Senate of impeachment charges and removed from office. Mrs. Mofford
became governor.
   Under the state constitution, public officials facing a recall
election are allowed to bill the state for reasonable campaign
costs.
   But the constitution does not outline what action should be
taken if the recall election is canceled, Attorney General Bob
Corbin said.
   The May 17 election was canceled by the state Supreme Court on
April 12.
   State Treasurer Ray Rottas said he has no authority to pay the
bill without an appropriation from the Legislature.
   Bills have been introduced to pay Mecham anywhere from $75,000
to $150,000 for campaign expenses, but legislators have not
seriously discussed either proposal.
   Mecham's bill, sent this week to Rottas, includes as
``reasonable election campaign expenses'':
   _ $28,543 in payroll costs, including $8,280 to Edith
Richardson, who was put on unpaid leave from her job as a Mecham
special assistant on Nov. 9 to coordinate recall activities.
   _ $3,600 in rent payments for his Glendale office, located in a
building he owns and has occupied since shortly after the House
voted Feb. 5 to impeach him. Mrs. Mofford, who was named acting
governor because of the House vote, had offered Mecham space in
state buildings, but he rejected it because he said it was not
sufficient.
   _ $65,000 to Jameson Campaigne, an Illinois political
consultant, for the deposit on the March fund-raising letter that
went to 100,000 conservatives nationwide.
   _ $3,018 in legal fees to Robert L'Ecuyer, an attorney who did
research work on Mecham's impeachment trial and also was a witness
on a charge Mecham misused public money by loaning $80,000 to the
his Glendale auto dealership.
   _ $25,250 to David Hill Research Consultants for a survey.
   _ $56,328 to American Comnet for a ``campaign media contract.''
   Rottas said he sent a letter Wednesday to Senate President Carl
Kunasek and House Speaker Joe Lane saying the bills are ``all
there, and now what are we going to do about it?''
   Kunasek said he believes the issue ``should be clarified one way
or another.''
   ``My question is what happens if we don't _ do we all get thrown
in the slammer?'' Kunasek asked.
   Lane has said that he is not against paying reasonable expenses
incurred by Mecham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
