<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ad Reaction,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Criticized for Using Famous Figures in Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gasoline company's advertising
campaign using images and doctored quotes from Martin Luther King
Jr., Che Guevara, Mao Tse-tung and Mohandas K. Gandhi has prompted
angry public reaction.
   Full-page newspaper ads by the Jet company display a familiar
picture of Guevera, the Bolivian guerrilla, and quote him saying
``someone's gotta clean up the discount jungle.''
   King's vision of a racism-free world characterized by his famous
``I have a dream'' speech is exploited in a pledge that the company
will not discriminate against any make of car that pulls into its
stations.
   The Aftonbladet newspaper reported scores of readers called in
to protest that the ads were ``distasteful'' and ``an insult.''
   A leading marketing figure, Lars Hall, cautioned against abusing
a name.
   ``You should be especially careful when it comes to deceased
people. They never have an opportunity to say no,'' he told the
Dagens Nyheter daily.
</TEXT>
