<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cuba-O'Connor 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-O'Connor, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0553,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor Says His Mission Accomplished</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UDPATE with O'Connor comments. Pick up
4th graf pvs: ``About 2,000...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said
today his mission in Cuba was accomplished after a midnight meeting
with Cuban leader Fidel Castro, whom he described as responsive.
   The two discussed the relationship between church and state in
this atheist nation.
   The meeting in the presidential palace lasted until about 2:30
a.m., O'Connor said. Castro received O'Connor at about 11 p.m.
after the cardinal celebrated an evening mass in Havana's Roman
Catholic cathedral.
   ``We discussed the general relationship between the church and
government here. We discussed the possibility of building bridges
for peace,'' O'Connor told reporters as he toured medical clinics
in Havana.
   He said Casto was especially laudatory of Catholic nuns in Cuba
and said the Cuban leader expressed delight at the idea of getting
visas for more to come to the country.
   ``I feel that the mission was accomplished, that the president
recognized clearly my primary purpose for coming here, and that was
to show my solidarity with the bishps of Cuba and to show that the
church in the United States and the church in Cuba and throughout
the world is one church,'' he said.
   Earlier today, thousands of worshipers filled the cathedral for
the Mass.
   About 2,000 people poured into the 284-year-old cathedral in
Havana's colonial district for O'Connor's first Mass in the
capital. Church bells rang and the applause was deafening as a
procession of 75 white-cloaked clergymen walked slowly toward the
altar, singing the hymn ``Pueblo del Rey,'' or ``Land of the King.''
   As the cardinal neared the altar, a man grabbed his hand and
kissed it.
   The procession included all seven of Cuba's Roman Catholic
bishops and Monsignor Raul del Valle of the New York archidocese, a
Cuban native who returned to his homeland on Tuesday for the first
time in 27 years.
   ``There has been a mistake,'' O'Connor said jokingly in Spanish,
addressing the huge crowd. ``You've welcomed me as a pope, but I am
only a cardinal, a poor cardinal.''
   Reporters barely got a chance to hear the cardinal speak before
they were hussled to a bus and taken to the presidential palace.
Gerald Costello, editor in chief of Catholic New York, a weekly
Catholic newspaper, briefed reporters at the palace on the
cardinal's remarks.
   O'Connor departed from his prepared text several times, once to
introduce del Valle, who he said was suffering from cancer.
   ``We have great hope that there could be a miracle and we hope
so because he is an inspiration, he's a saint and an inspiraton,''
the cardinal said.
   O'Connor also called it a ``miracle'' that del Valle had been
allowed back in Cuba after leaving in 1961 for the United States.
He thanked the Cuban government for allowing Del Valle to visit his
homeland.
   Repeating the theme of his four-day Cuban trip, O'Connor said
the church must be allowed to serve as a ``bridge'' between people,
regardless of political ideology.
   ``I hope that peace will come to the peoples of the United
States and the peoples of Cuba,'' O'Connor said. ``But peace is not
possible without justice for everyone.''
   O'Connor is the first American cardinal to visit Cuba since
Castro came to power in 1959 and this was his first Mass since
arriving in Havana on Tuesday.
   He is in Cuba as a guest of the Roman Catholic Church to help
celebrate the 200th anniversary of the birth of the Rev. Felix
Varela. The priest, who served in New York City from 1823 to 1853,
is considered a Cuban hero in the struggle against Spanish colonial
rule.
   The cardinal is scheduled to leave Cuba on Friday morning for
New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
