<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Earthquake     04-21 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earthquake,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Quake Rocks Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake shook northern San
Diego County early today, causing no damage but the rumbling
awakened some residents, authorities said.
   The quake registered 3.3 on the Richter scale and was centered
in the Palomar area 30 miles north of downtown San Diego, said John
Minsch, a geophysicist with the U.S Geological Survey's Earthquake
Information Center in Golden, Colo.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude, or the height of quake-generated shock waves recorded
on a seismograph.
   Some 40 people called radio station KMLO in nearby Fallbrook to
report they felt the 1:15 a.m. temblor, said station employee Neil
Mars.
   ``It woke a lot of people up,'' he said, adding that the calls
came from as far north as Oceanside and eastward to Rancho
California near the San Diego-Riverside county line.
</TEXT>
