<DOCNO> AP880421-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BibleQuiz Bjt   04-21 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bible Quiz, Bjt,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Teen-ager Wins International Old Testament Quiz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two-hour battle neared its climax. Tension
was palpable. Rhythmic chants from fans urged on the competitors,
who wiped sweat from their brows as the interlocutor spoke like the
voice of the Chronicler.
   When it was over, the annual International Bible Quiz had its
first American victor in 15 years. Jeremy Weider had won the World
Series, the Super Bowl, the World Cup of Old Testament scholarship
for Jewish teen-agers.
   ``I'm elated,'' said the 17-year-old from Monsey, N.Y. ``I
studied so hard for this. Two hours of Bible reading every day for
seven months. But I never thought I'd win.''
   Weider, a religious Jew who attends Yeshiva University in New
York, shared first place with Zehava Heder, an Israeli with an
identical point total.
   Contestants were given more than 20 questions involving
intricate details of quotations from the Jewish Bible, which is the
Old Testament of the Christian Bible. The last question was posed
by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who asked them to identify 10
quotations about visions of peace.
   The co-winners were among hundreds of Jewish teen-agers from
around the world who came to Jerusalem for the contest, which is
held every year on Independence Day and broadcast by Israel
television.
   ``This is a really big deal,'' said Noga Harom, 19, of New York
City borough of Queens, who finished second last year. ``It's a
huge honor. I mean, these are the very best Bible students in the
world.
   ``Usually only the Israelis win because they're so well-trained.
Now the underdogs have taken it. It's a World Series upset.''
   ``Thank heavens the pressure's off,'' said Noah Feldman, 17,
from Cambridge, Mass., who placed fifth this year. ``It was so much
work.''
   An audience of nearly 1,000 attended the contest in a Jerusalem
theater.
   As the field was reduced to seven finalists, fans grew more
boisterous in support of their favorites.
   One group chanted the name of one contestant, ``Oren! Oren!'' as
though at an athletic event.
   ``Sshh!'' an elderly man admonished. ``You're at a Bible quiz,
not a football game!''
   Competitors were the winners of regional contests from 19
countries, including Israel, the United States, Canada, South
Africa, Ireland, France, Spain, Hungary, Yugoslavia and Argentina.
   The competition is sponsored jointly by the Israeli Education,
Defense and Religion ministries and Jewish organizations.
   Weider and Heder, the co-winners, received elegant sets of
religious volumes.
   Many teen-agers in the audience said they were glad they gave up
holiday picnics and barbecues to attend.
   ``What a great way to celebrate Independence Day,'' said Paula
Posner, an 18-year-old student from Toronto. ``It really gives you
a sense of pride.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
