<1ST_LINE>r i BC-CampaignAbroad     04-21 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Comments on Outcome of New York Primaries</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is what some newspapers and political commentators around
the world had to say Thursday about the outcome of the New York
Democratic primaries:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Guardian of London (liberal): ``It was the dirtiest, most
dangerous race so far: and some of the details of the result are
concomitantly disheartening. The blacks of New York voted for Jesse
Jackson. The Jews (after particularly unpleasant broadsides from
Mayor Koch) voted against him. There's a clear racial divide in the
final primary accounting, with too much potential for bitterness
left behind. Cheerfully, however, the winner and runner-up were in
action yesterday stressing harmony and unity. Dukakis and Jackson
have the opportunity to make something good out of something bad;
and they see the need.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Vittorio Zucconi writing in La Repubblica of Rome
(left-leaning): ``The New York of racial grudges, ... of too much
money and too much misery, accomplished with brutality, perhaps
with honesty, that which the rest of America had not yet dared to
do: it told Jesse Jackson and the black population that their
challenge to the sky cannot be accomplished.
   ``The black Icarus of American politics saw his wings melt when
he got too close to the sun of victory. He will keep on flying, he
might even score some victories in the remaining 50 days of
primaries before California ... but the duel for the conquest of
the White House seems a private affair between George Bush and
Michael Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Alberto Pasolini Zanelli in Il Giornale of Milan
(conservative): ``The anti-Jackson pact, upheld by nobody and
actually denied by everybody, is already operative: the
`establishment' within the Democratic party has closed ranks behind
Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Ennio Caretto in La Stampa of Turin (moderate): `` ... in New
York, the melting pot of the superpower, America voted against
Jackson and against what they wrongly thought he represented. ...
America saw in the black leader both adventure _ the friendship
with Arafat and Castro _ and revolt: in other words the claim of
socio-economic equality.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SINGAPORE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Business Times: ``The acrimonious New York primary campaign is
over. And, finally, the Democrats have a reasonably clear
front-runner for the presidential nomination, Massachusetts
Governor Michael Dukakis. Still, from a long-distance perspective,
American politics appears to be suffering from a despairing lack of
leadership. At the beginning of the marathon campaign, Americans
had the luxury of choosing from a gaggle of candidates. Yet, the
voters seem to waffle, first to this one then to that one. The
problem appears not to have been too many possibilities but the
lack of a distinct choice. ...
   ``Now that the field has been presumably narrowed to just two
front-runners _ Dukakis and Vice President George Bush, whose
Republican nomination needs only the sound of a gavel _ perhaps the
candidates can stop defending their electability and start showing
their leadership qualities. The voters are waiting, and the rest of
the world is watching.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRAZIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _O Estado de Sao Paulo (conservative): ``Dukakis' victory in New
York and his brilliant conquest of the lead in the arduous primary
races are due less to Jackson's flaws than to the qualities of the
governor of Massachusetts. The American voters see in this austere
man, so opposed to demagoguery that he becomes even boring by the
criteria of the mass media, the image of security and honorability
they want to see connected with the presidency, an institution
eroded by scandals in recent times.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWITZERLAND</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Le Matin of Lausanne (independent): ``The dwarf has grown up.
This time, Michael Dukakis posted a decisive victory. The
Massachusetts governor has cleared all hurdles for the Democratic
Party nomination in July. ... He triumphed in the state of Mario
Cuomo, the non-declared favorite; despite the hostility of Mayor Ed
Koch, who supported Albert Gore; despite the popular charisma of
Jesse Jackson, who carried the black vote. The support of the
Jewish community, which holds so much power in the United States,
from now on is an important trump card in his campaign.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Neue Zuercher Zeitung of Zurich (conservative), on the
possibility of Jackson becoming Dukakis' running mate: ``If he did,
Dukakis could write off his ambitions right now. He has to get a
Western or Southern conservative onto his ticket unless he wants to
follow Mondale's hardly advisable example of four years ago. ...
For the same reason, it is unlikely that Jackson will play
kingmaker in Atlanta, or will receive and accept an offer for a
Cabinet post.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GREECE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Avriani of Athens (left wing), saying Dukakis has failed to
take a position on Greece's regional disputes with Turkey and the
Cyprus problem: ``Listen Michael, the Greek immigrants will vote
for you and help you economically ... but you had better take a
stand now. You have to say now that if you get elected you'll kick
the Turks out of Cyprus and secure our borders.''
</TEXT>
