<2ND_LINE>AM-Rice Statue,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rice Students Gets Probation for Moving Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rice University senior was placed on probation
and told to pay $1,500 for rotating a statue of the school's
founder.
   Patrick Dyson, 23, called the discipline reasonable but said he
has no regrets about the prank he carried out with 10 other
students.
   ``It was in the true spirit of college pranks and of a great
engineering school,'' he said, adding that he still expects to
graduate May 7.
   ``It was a fun thing to do, to make people smile and laugh. No
one has criticized us,'' he said, ``except for the president and
the proctor. And it's their job to criticize us for it.''
   E.C. Holt, the school's proctor and chairman of the civil
engineering department, said ``there was the potential for all
kinds of bad things to happen.''
   The 58-year-old statue of William Marsh Rice, which normally
faces east, rests atop a granite base containing an urn holding the
founder's remains. After the prank on April 12, it faced west.
   The fine represented the cost of turning the statue back to its
customary direction.
</TEXT>
