<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EyeGouge     04-21 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eye Gouge,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Put Building Inspector's Eye Out Gets Maximum Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who put out the eye of a
building inspector who told him his fence was too high received a
maximum seven-year sentence after writing to a judge that the
victim was lucky he wasn't shot.
   Samuel Duran, 41, of Los Angeles was sentenced to seven years in
prison Wednesday for mayhem and assault with a deadly weapon,
stemming from the May 11 maiming of Calvin O'Daniels, 62, a
building inspector who told him his fence was too tall.
   Superior Court Judge Meredith Taylor imposed the maximum term
after a letter from Duran was read in court that said O'Daniels
``is complaining about his eye. He is lucky he didn't get shot
instead. ...''
   Duran also wrote that the city inspector ``came to rearrange my
attitude. Believe me, he tried. He got his face rearranged,
instead.''
   The letter then asked for leniency in sentencing.
   ``I believe Mr. Duran is smugly satisfied with what he did,''
Ms. Taylor said as she handed down his sentence.
   Duran, who was convicted March 29, was also fined $5,000
Wednesday. He yelled, ``I won't pay a damn penny to this court,''
as he was taken into custody.
   According to trial testimony, O'Daniels' right eye had to be
removed and he lost half the sight in his left eye after Duran beat
him with his fists and a shoe.
   Duran maintained throughout the trial that O'Daniels had started
the fight after demanding a bribe.
   Duran's wife, Theresa, and his two children wept during the
sentencing. They each wrote letters to the judge saying Duran is a
model husband and father.
   Duran will be eligible for parole in 3{ years.
</TEXT>
