<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-UniversalHealthCare 1stLd-Writethru a050</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Universal Health Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Set To Sign Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with signing, picking up 4th
graf pvs, `The bill ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis today signed into law a
bill that will make Massachusetts ``the nation's laboratory'' in
ensuring that health insurance is available to all residents by
1992.
   Dukakis, who has cited the measure in his campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination, said the first-in-the-nation
law will ``erase the uncertainty too many people face when they or
a loved one becomes ill but lack the means to pay for the cure.''
   In written remarks for an elaborate Statehouse signing ceremony,
the governor said, ``We have good reason to rejoice today, as we
again become the nation's laboratory.''
   The proposal makes Massachusetts ``the nation's pathfinder
blazing a trail that leads to affordable quality health care for
every man, woman and child.''
   ``We have made a start here at home,'' he said. ``Now we must
make it work. And then we must carry the message of health care for
all across the country so that the other 49 states join us.''
   Only Hawaii, which has a federal exemption allowing it to
mandate employer health coverage, currently has anything comparable
to the Massachusetts law.
   However, the new legislation, which Statehouse aides say has
generated inquiries from more than 20 states, goes beyond Hawaii's
approach by offering health security both to working and
non-working residents.
   The Massachusetts proposal to make health insurance available to
all by 1992 will cost the state $645.2 million over the next five
years, according to figures released Wednesday by Dukakis.
   The bill, the outcome of a nine-month legislative struggle,
comes two years after Massachusetts voters endorsed a non-binding
referendum by a 2-1 margin urging Congress to ``enact a national
health care program (that) ... is universal in coverage.''
   The thrust of the bill is to provide coverage to an estimated
600,000 Massachusetts residents under age 65 currently without
health insurance _ about one out of every 10 people in the
commonwealth.
   The plan is to do this in stages and through a variety of
approaches _ from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults
and children to state-brokered pooled insurance for small
businesses and individuals.
   Dukakis health policy adviser Catherine Dunham said she hopes
the coverage will begin operations July 1, the start of the fiscal
year.
   The plan passed the Legislature last week by narrow margins
blamed on the deletion of some special interest amendments and
lingering doubts about how much the law will cost.
   Although fully prepared to sign the law, Dukakis as late as
Tuesday was telling reporters he didn't know the bill's ultimate
cost. Dukakis acknowledged Wednesday that there had been ``some
confusion'' about health care costs.
   ``Sorry I didn't have the information yesterday. But I'm not a
technocrat, I'm a leader,'' Dukakis said, joking about his national
image as a dispassionate, hands-on manager.
   On Tuesday, the governor swept to victory in New York's primary,
solidifying his chances of becoming the party's nominee in next
fall's presidential election.
   Even the chief drafters of the bill, the Senate and House Ways
and Means committees, were unable to agree on the measure's cost.
The Senate placed the state's cost at about $550 million and the
House estimated it as high as $1.2 billion.
   Dukakis presented figures Wednesday showing the state's share of
the plan would rise from $34.5 million this fiscal year to $195.4
million in fiscal 1991.
   The state's share is expected to drop to $162.7 million in
fiscal 1992, according to the governor's figures. But Dukakis and
Dunham said state costs beyond fiscal 1989 are hard to estimate
because they will depend on how many employers decide to offer
health plans as a result of the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Higgins-Text     04-21 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Higgins-Text,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Statement on Higgins</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Higgins, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the comunique
released Thursday by the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth and
translated from Arabic by The Associated Press:
   In the name of God, the merciful, the compassionate.
   To our struggling people,
   To the freemen of the world,
   In addition to our previous communiques in which we explained
the espionage role of the agent Col. William Higgins and in which
we stated our determination to try this criminal after his
investigation is completed, we wish today to announce the following:
   1. The investigation of this criminal has been completed and we
will put it forth to the nation in the proper time.
   2. This criminal will be turned over today to the tribunal of
the oppressed to try him for the crimes he has committed on charges
leveled against him as follows:
   A. Spying for the criminal United States on our Lebanese and
Palestinian peoples.
   B. Active participation in American conspiracies against our
Moslem people through the following:
   1. Supervising the Pentagon team to combat Lebanese and
Palestinian Islamic organizations in Palestine and Lebanon.
   2. Collecting information and reporting to the Pentagon about
the military and political situation in south Lebanon along with
his personal views on the situation, which include all military
activities in resisting Israel and ways of bringing them under
control.
   3. Membership of an American coordination committee on Lebanon
and Palestine made up of the CIA, the Pentagon and the State
Department.
   4. Planning to set up an efficient information-gathering network
in the south to help further their conspiracies.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth.
