<HEAD>Woman Arrested After Ignoring Warnings To Return Books; Books
Still Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede, last graf to UPDATE with authorities saying five
of the books missing today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was arrested after failing to
return seven overdue library books says that she did return the
books, but authorities said today that five were still missing.
   Lorelei Bennett, 33, was arrested when she failed to acknowledge
a summons to appear in court to answer the charge of unauthorized
use of property, Kennebec County District Attorney David Crook said.
   ``It's unfortunate this had to go as far as it did,'' Oakland
police Sgt. Ralph Sabins said today. ``But when you fail to appear
in court it's more or less contempt of court and (authorities) have
to take action.''
   Bennett was released Tuesday on $54.80 bond, which included a
fee for the books, Sabins said.
   Bennett said police told her she would not have to answer the
summons if she returned the books, so she put five books in the
library's overnight deposit box. Two more books were later added to
the list of overdue books.
   Sabins said five of books were still missing today and that two
of those that were returned were badly damaged.
