<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0471 04-21 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 10 grafs with Dukakis comment on V.P., picking
up in 2nd graf pvs, Dukakis was; subs 5th graf pvs, Dukakis who;
cuts last 4 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, leading Jesse
Jackson in the Democratic presidential race, said today that
finishing second in the primaries does not entitle anyone to second
spot on the national ticket. He said that he alone, if nominated,
will pick his running mate.
   ``What you're looking for is somebody who, first and foremost,
could be a first-rate president if something happened to the
president. That's where you begin,'' Dukakis said in an interview
with The Associated Press.
   ``If I were to finish second, it wouldn't entitle me to anything
more than consideration, period,'' Dukakis said.
   He refused to discuss any individuals and tried to steer
questions about the vice presidency away from Jackson.
   ``I have spent literally zero time thinking about it. And I will
not, unless and until I have either won the nomination or it looks
as if it's pretty well in hand,'' Dukakis said.
   ``If that happens, then I will begin what I hope will be a
thoughtful and thorough process of selecting a running mate. But
I'm not going to do anything on that _ quite literally _ until the
California and New Jersey primaries are over,'' he continued.
   Dukakis, who leads in nominating delegates and in popular votes,
was asked about a statement from Jackson campaign manager Gerald
Austin that if Dukakis won the nomination the runner-up would
deserve ``consideration'' for the second spot on the ticket.
   ``The nominee makes that decision _ as he (Jackson) himself
said. And rightly so,'' Dukakis said.
   Since his solid victory in the New York primary over Jackson and
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. on Tuesday, Dukakis has become the focus of
speculation about his choice for a vice president.
   According to aides, Jackson and Dukakis have not discussed the
issue in any of their private conversations. Publicly, both men
insist that the question is premature until the nominating process
has produced a Democratic nominee.
   Dukakis was leaving tonight for Pennsylvania and Ohio for
campaign stops. Pennsylvania's primary is Tuesday; Ohio's is a week
later. The governor had events scheduled this evening in Pittsburgh
and Cleveland.
   Dukakis, who has been spending three to four weekdays in the
Statehouse each week while running his Democratic presidential
campaign, noted Wednesday that Vice President George Bush isn't in
a position to campaign full time either.
   ``I would assume and expect that the vice president has to spend
some substantial portion of his week making sure he knows what's
going on, that he's fully briefed,'' Dukakis told reporters at a
Statehouse news conference. ``So both of us have the same problem.''
   Dukakis, who bested Jackson by 14 percentage points in New York,
was treated like a conquering hero when he came back to Boston.
   Dozens of Statehouse staffers thronged the governor's outer
office shortly after noon and let out a cheer for the governor and
his wife, Kitty.
   ``We love you all,'' Dukakis responded.
   Later, at a Statehouse reception marking the enactment of a
state highway package, he won warm cheers from the legislators and
contractors assembled for the event.
   Transportation Secretary Frederic Salvucci introduced Dukakis as
``the next president of the United States.'' Dukakis grinned but
cautioned, ``Steady as she goes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
