<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugRaids     04-21 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Raids,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Man Shot In `Rock House' Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have resumed the use of battering rams
to bust fortified ``rock houses'' of alleged drug dealers, and one
suspect was shot when he pointed a gun at officers, authorities
said.
   L.C. Hadnott, 71, of Los Angeles, was in surgery Thursday at
California Medical Center, said administrative supervisor Marlene
Delp. Doctors were not sure whether his arm could be saved, she
said.
   The shooting in South Central Los Angeles occurred just after
the sweep of three alleged sites of rock cocaine sales began late
Wednesday, said police Officer Jim Farris.
   ``The elderly suspect was carrying a shotgun when officers broke
into the house where narcotics were being sold and pointed the
weapon at them,'' Farris said. ``One of our officers responded by
firing his shotgun, injuring the suspect.''
   Hadnott was arrested for investigation of assault with a deadly
weapon on a police officer, Farris said.
   Pamela Perkins, 26, of Los Angeles was also arrested. She was
booked for investigation of felony drug possession, Farris said.
   Police seized a small amount of drugs, three shotguns, two
pistols and a rifle in the raids, Farris said.
   The houses had been linked to violent street gangs, Farris said,
but he couldn't tie the suspects to a gang.
   The ``rock houses'' where dealers sell the type of cocaine known
as ``rock'' or ``crack,'' are primarily in impoverished
South-Central neighborhoods.
   Police began using the motorized battering ram because the
metal-fortified doors and windows made it difficult to get inside
to serve search warrants. Following court challenges by
civil-rights groups, police must now obtain a judge's permission
each time they want to use the ram.
</TEXT>
