<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0557 04-21 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agent Turns Gray When Courthouse Metal Detector Finds Slug in
Jacket Lining</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf, `Singer, clan ...,' with
morning testimony.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI agent learned how close he had come
to being killed in a shootout with a polygamist clan when a
.30-caliber slug was found in his jacket during a courthouse
security check.
   Agent Donald C. Roberts ``turned three ugly shades of gray''
Wednesday when the X-ray at the courthouse door found the slug in
the lining of his flight jacket, said Assistant U.S. Attorney David
Schwendiman. ``He was shocked.''
   Roberts, who had come to court to testify against members of the
clan, took the coat to the U.S. attorney's office and the slug was
cut out of the lining.
   The slug will be compared with six spent rounds retrieved at the
scene of the shootout and two .30-caliber rifles found in the
bedroom of defendant John Timothy Singer, U.S. Attorney Brent Ward
said.
   Singer, clan leader Addam Swapp, 27, matriarch Vickie Singer,
44, and Swapp's brother Jonathan Swapp, 20, are standing trial on
federal charges stemming from the Jan. 16 bombing of a Mormon
chapel and 13-day standoff that ended in the shootout.
   Today, the jury put on headphones for the second time in the
trial and watched on a television monitor a videotape of the
shootout that was taken by Summit County Reserve Deputy Grant J.
Evans, who had been stationed 500 yards away from the Singer
compound.
   The tape did not show any individuals running or shooting, but a
sequence of 11 gunshots was heard along with the deputy's surprised
reaction, ``Jesus Christ!'' The tape was a two-minute excerpt from
Evans' coverage of the gun battle.
   Summit County Detective Joe Offret, who had testified earlier,
was recalled to the stand. Offret said he was the first officer to
inspect the home where the FBI arrest team was stationed during the
shootout. When he examined the site, he found five .30-caliber
bullets, a number of bullet strike marks and a 9-mm casing.
   The gunbattle occurred as agents were attempting to capture the
Swapp brothers with attack dogs. State Corrections Lt. Fred House
was killed and Addam Swapp was wounded.
   Roberts had been with a team of surveillance agents stationed in
the home of Don and Miriam Jepsen when a second FBI team
implemented the arrest plan.
   Roberts said he was watching through a window when the Swapp
brothers walked back to the main Singer residence from a goat pen
and the order was given to release the dogs.
   Seconds later, Roberts testified, he heard a ``loud explosion of
gunshot immediately in front of my face'' and felt a sharp pain in
his upper chest.
   ``I recalled saying, `I'm hit! I'm hit!''' Another agent jumped
on Roberts and began searching for wounds but none was found.
Roberts then resumed his position in front of the window, he said.
   No bullet marks were found on the jacket or on his body armour
vest at the time, Roberts said, and he thought he had been hit by a
fragment of a wall.
   ``It was my impression that had I been hit with a bullet, it
would've penetrated the vest ... and I would not be here today,''
Roberts said.
   Earlier Wednesday, an FBI agent stationed with Roberts in the
Jepsen house testified that Jonathan Swapp pointed a rifle at him.
Agent Hal G. Metcalfe said Swapp knelt in the snow and aimed, but
the agent recalled seeing no muzzle flashes.
   ``I said to everybody, `Get down, get down. He's shooting at
us,''' Metcalfe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
