<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz-Rights     04-21 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Rights,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Assures Refuseniks They Won't Be Forgotten</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz assured two
dozen Jewish refuseniks and other Soviets with human rights
complaints Thursday that President Reagan and his successor will
champion their cause.
   ``It's built into us,'' Shultz said at a gathering at the U.S.
Embassy after listening patiently to stories of refused visas,
separated families and scientists who long ago stopped doing
sensitive work for the Soviet government.
   He also gave human rights ``the pride of place'' on his agenda,
leading off with the subject at his meeting with Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``I have to keep working at this, to keep striving, to never
give up,'' Shultz said.
   With a quaver in his voice, he continued: ``I can promise you
that the president, and whoever succeeds him _ it' built into us _
will keep working at these human rights problems.''
   Shultz said he would pursue the subject Friday with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   At about the same time that he was meeting with the refuseniks
invited to the embassy, others trying to press their emigration
appeals in a demonstration at the Lenin Library were dragged away
and taken to a police station in buses.
   The crackdown on an unsanctioned public protest may have been
intended as a warning against such demonstrations during Reagan's
visit here next month.
   Jewish emigration in March hit a 15-month high with 984 people
leaving the country. But Shultz is trying to force radical changes
in the way the Soviets handle applications for exit permits.
   He wants to ease the restriction on people who dealt with
classified subjects so they could not be denied visas for work done
many years in the past.
   And he wants the Soviets to stop permitting a family member to
block another adult's visa.
   Chicago-born Abe Stolar, a U.S. citizen, was a case in point.
Stolar will not emigrate unless his son, Michael, and
daughter-in-law, Julia, are granted visas, too.
   But Julia Stolar said her mother, from whom she is estranged,
has blocked her application, and thus kept all three Stolars from
leaving.
   As Shultz made his way around the living room of Max Robinson,
the U.S. consul general, people stepped forward to tell their
stories.
   Vladimir Tufeld, whose wife is in Johns Hopkins hospital in
Baltimore recovering from brain surgery, has been denied a visa for
11 years. He is an engineer who said he was last involved in
sensitive work 15 years ago.
   ``It's absolutely a lame excuse,'' Shultz told him.
   Tufeld carried color photographs of his son, a professor at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem, and his grandson.
   Benjamin Charny, a mathematician who said he worked on a space
program more than 17 years ago, has been refused a visa for nine
years. His family lives in Massachusetts.
   Lev Sheiba, a physicist from Leningrad, smiled and said his
daughter left two days ago, but he is still waiting for a visa.
   ``We are all hostages,'' Sheiba said. ``We are subjects for
bargaining.``
   Last year, at Passover, Shultz attended a Jewish seder at the
U.S. embassy. Several of the guests, including pianist Vladimir
Feltsman, have since left.
   He met two weeks ago in Jerusalem with a group of emigres,
including long-time refusenik Vladimir Slepak.
   Shultz offered their experience as a symbol of hope.
   ``I'd like to meet you again,'' he said. ``But not necessarily
here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
