<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     04-21 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preschool Molest,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McMartin Mass Molestation Trial Enters Second Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The McMartin Preschool molestation trial
started 368 days, 42 witnesses and $8 million ago, and attorneys
say it is likely to last at least a year more.
   And that doesn't include the 18-month preliminary hearing.
   ``Welcome to the year No. 2 of our trial,'' Superior Court Judge
William Pounders said Wednesday. The judge and attorneys then spent
an hour renumbering photographic evidence.
   Since jury selection started April 20, 1987, there have been
32,134 pages of transcript logged in Pounders' courtroom. Leap year
added an extra day.
   The prosecution, taking testimony from its 42nd witness, is
expected to rest its case late this summer. The defense has said it
hopes to take less than a year to present its side.
   Raymond Buckey, 29, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61,
are charged jointly with one count of conspiracy and separately
with 99 counts of molestation between them.
   The charges center on 14 children who were under their care at
the McMartin Pre-School in suburban Manhattan Beach.
   Charges against five other teachers were dropped in 1986.
   In court, there have been allegations of satanic rituals, animal
butchery, perjury, suppression of evidence and coaching of
witnesses. One witness was jailed for failing to show up to
testify, and another committed suicide the day he was to testify.
   Mrs. Buckey is free on bail but her son remains in custody, his
bail set at $3 million.
   Pounders has been praised for his control of the trial so far.
   ``I think this judge has made a difference as far as recognizing
and understanding the needs of the victims,'' said Deputy District
Attorney Lael Rubin.
   Six children testified during the first year of the trial.
Defense attorneys claim many of their answers were coached.
   A 13-year-old was asked Wednesday whether the ``secret room''
where he said he was molested was actually a classroom.
   ``I'm leaving open the possibility, but I don't remember it
being a place where children are taught,'' the child answered.
   ``The kids appear to have been so prepped for trial, their
testimony has been weakened,'' said attorney Dean Gits. ``There is
little or no spontaneity.''
   Seven children have yet to testify. The parents of the 14th
alleged victim have refused to let their child take the stand.
</TEXT>
