<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DeepPockets     04-21 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deep Pockets,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California High Court Says Limit on Damages Doesn't Apply to
Pending Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court dealt a
multimillion-dollar setback to businesses and insurers today,
ruling that the 1986 ``deep pockets'' initiative, which limited
damages for pain and suffering, did not apply to cases pending when
the measure passed.
   The 4-3 ruling was a victory for injury victims and their
lawyers in cases where the harm had occurred but the lawsuits had
not yet been completed by June 1986, when state voters approved
Proposition 51 by a 62 percent majority.
   One class of cases particularly affected by today's ruling is
asbestos lawsuits, many of which had been filed but not settled by
June 1986.
   The court ruled that the initiative was constitutional,
rejecting trial lawyers' claims that it discriminated unfairly
against injury victims. But in the key portion of the ruling, the
majority said the measure's new standards for determining
non-economic damages applied only to injuries suffered after the
initiative passed.
   The opinion by Justice John Arguelles cited ``the common-sense
notion that it may be unfair to change the rules of the game in the
middle of the contest.'' He also said new laws are generally
presumed to apply only to future cases.
   Proposition 51, sponsored by businesses, insurers and local
governments and opposed by trial lawyers, limits a defendant's
share of non-economic damages _ pain, suffering and emotional
distress _ to its percentage of the total fault.
   Under the initiative, if a company that is 40 percent
responsible for an injury, for example, has gone out of business by
the time of suit, the victim can collect no more than 60 percent of
the non-economic damages from the remaining defendants.
   Economic damages, such as medical costs and lost wages, are
still covered by the longstanding ``deep pockets'' rule, under
which one or all of the remaining defendants can be required to pay
100 percent of the costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DamagedPaintings     04-21 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Damaged Paintings,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Sprays Acid on Duerer Paintings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MUN4,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By UTA WINKHAUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man embittered about cuts
in his pension payments on Thursday seriously damaged three
paintings by German master Albrecht Duerer by spraying them with
sulfuric acid from a champagne bottle.
   Art restoration experts worked feverishly to save the
multimillion-dollar paintings.
   A 51-year-old homeless pensioner turned himself in to officials
at Munich's Alte Pinakothek museum after spraying sulfuric acid on
the Duerer classics ``Mourning of Christ'' and the ``Paumgartner
Altar,'' police said.
   Duerer, considered the most influential artist of the German
school, painted the works between 1496 and 1504.
   He told police he destroyed the paintings ``out of revenge''
because of decreases in his pension payments. Deductions had been
made from the man's pension to pay for similar attacks he made on
paintings in Duesseldorf and Hamburg, police said.
   The man described himself to police as ``psychologically
disturbed,'' according to police officials who asked not to be
identified, citing policy.
   Meanwhile, a Bavaria state art administration director told The
Associated Press that the damage done to the works was ``very
distressing.''
   ``The Altar alone is worth 70 million marks (about $40 million).
The value has sunk by at least 30 percent,'' said Hubertus von
Sonnenburg, director of the Bavaria state painting collections
organization. ``But in terms of art history you can't even assess
this damage.
   ``The paintings can certainly be restored. But there were so
many damaged areas _ one can never paint them over again so than
one doesn't see them,'' Sonnenberg added.
   Police said the pictures were as much as 70 percent destroyed.
   Art restoration experts from Munich's Doerner Institute rushed
to the museum shortly after the 10 a.m. attack.
   The paintings will have to dry out for at least two months
before the specialists can begin restoration work, said institute
chemist Johann Koller.
   The embittered pensioner was described by witnesses as a
``well-dressed gentleman'' who appeared to be just an ordinary
museum visitor. A school group came upon him as he stood before the
Duerer works, spraying the pictures with acid from a small
champagne bottle.
   When a pupil cried out to stop him, the man calmly put away the
bottle and turned himself in to museum officials, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
