<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RedArmy     04-21 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Red Army,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Police Ask Interpol to Help Seek Red Army Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Police Agency has asked Interpol to
aid the hunt for 26 suspected members of the Japanese Red Army to
try to prevent terrorist acts during the 1988 Olympics, an agency
official said Thursday.
   A list naming the 26 was sent Wednesday to Paris-based Interpol,
the International Criminal Police Organization, said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the list included updated portraits of seven members
based on information obtained recently by the Japanese police
agency.
   The official said police feared the revolutionary group would
carry out terrorist acts inside and outside Japan because of the
Olympic Games in neighboring South Korea.
   He said the request would help the search for Red Army members
in each of Interpol's 146 member nations.
   The National Police Agency also plans to distribute 10,000
posters and leaflets describing the wanted members to Japanese
embassies and offices of local companies abroad, including
airports, the official said.
   He said the list includes Fusako Shigenobu, 42, suspected of
masterminding the 1972 machine gun attacks at Tel Aviv's Lod
Airport that killed 28 people.
   Police in Naples, Italy, said Ms. Shigenobu may have been
involved in the explosion of a car bomb car outside a U.S. military
club in Naples last week. The blast killed an American servicewoman
and four Italians.
   Junzo Okudaira, another Red Army member, also is on the
international wanted list because he is suspected in the bombing,
the official said.
   The Asahi Evening News quoted an unidentified police official as
saying the Red Army sent a letter to a news agency in West Beirut
on Saturday saying it and Okudaira were not involved in the
bombing. The police official refused comment.
   He said Takamaro Tamiya, 45, who led a hijacking of a Japanese
domestic airliner to North Korea, also is on the Interpol list.
   Tamiya and eight other Red Army members hijacked an All Nippon
Airways jetliner in September 1970 and fled to North Korea after
freeing all the passengers.
   News reports said one of the hijackers recently died in North
Korea but did not give the cause of death.
   The Japanese police official said police were aware of a letter
that Tamiya apparently sent to Japanese news media last month. The
letter said that the remaining members in North Korea would ``go
anywhere if ordered'' to participate in terrorist acts.
   The officer declined to provide further details.
   The Foreign Ministry has said that a Japanese arrested April 12
on the New Jersey Turnpike with pipe bombs in his car also is
suspected of being a member of the Red Army.
   The Red Army is a radical leftist group formed in 1969 calling
for ``simultaneous world revolution.'' It was thought to have had
about 300 members at its peak. About 40 members are believed allied
with pro-Palestinian groups in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
