<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ArizonaRepublicans     04-21 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arizona Republicans,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Among Candidates For Convention Delegate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham, ousted from
office April 4 by the Senate, will be a delegate to the state GOP
convention and hopes to be picked as one of Arizona's 33 delegates
to the Republican National Convention.
   ``Of course,'' he replied with a smile Wednesday night when
asked whether he'd expected to be sent to the state convention from
his district meeting.
   As a precinct committeeman, Mecham automatically was among the
182 candidates on the ballot in his district for 38 slots at the
May 14 state meeting.
   He garnered 61 of 102 possible votes, and word of his win was
greeted with applause.
   Mecham, who has clashed with much of the state GOP's hierarchy,
said he had not tried to count votes in advance of the district
meeting.
   ``Heavens, if I've got to line up votes, I'm not interested in
going,'' he said. ``If I haven't earned the right to go to the
(national) convention, our party is in bad shape.''
   Mecham's name was on the list recommended by the Rev. Pat
Robertson's campaign but was omitted from the list of
recommendations circulated by supporters of Vice President George
Bush, who already has enough delegates from other states to ensure
nomination.
   The former governor said he expected to back Bush eventually,
calling him ``the only show in town.''
   Even if Mecham doesn't win a seat as a delegate to the national
convention, he probably could get in as a former GOP governor,
state chairman Burton Kruglick said.
</TEXT>
