<DOCNO> AP880421-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Election     04-21 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Candidates Already Looking To Debate And Second Round</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand and Premier Jacques
Chirac, leading candidates in the first round of the presidential
election Sunday, have piqued other hopefuls by arguing over terms
of a one-on-one debate.
   As the official campaign entered its last two days Thursday,
both the 71-year-old Socialist president and his 55-year-old
conservative premier already were setting their sights on the May 8
runoff.
   That attitude did not sit well with former center-right Premier
Raymond Barre, 64, running third in the polls.
   ``The game is not over,'' said Barre, adding he believed it was
``presumptuous, not to say curious'' for his competitors ``to set a
date for a debate before the French people have decided.''
   George Marchais, the Communist Party secretary-general,
expressed the frustration of other candidates: ``The day before
yesterday, yesterday and today, one question occupies the radio and
television commentaries: the Mitterrand-Chirac debate between the
first and second rounds.''
   ``In other words, the first round is already over,'' said
Marchais, whose party's candidate is Andre Lajoinie.
   French elections are run in two rounds. If, as expected, no
candidate wins an absolute majority Sunday, the two top
vote-getters face each other in a runoff.
   Under French law, no polls are allowed to be published in the
week immediately preceding an election. The last polls showed
Mitterrand with comfortable lead at about 35 percent to 37 percent,
followed by Chirac with 22 percent to 24 percent. Barre is third
with about 17 percent and extreme right National Front leader
Jean-Marie Le Pen has 12 percent.
   There are five other candidates in the first round.
   The polls vary widely, and some show as much as 20 percent of
the vote undecided.
   As the campaign for the first round drew to a close, discussion
focused on the date and format for an eventual debate.
   Mitterrand said he thought Thursday of next week would be fine
but added any confrontation involving a president and a premier
should be dignified.
   On Thursday, Chirac rejected Mitterrand's proposed debate date
and preferred ``the beginning of the second week'' between the two
rounds.
   ``It is not for one candidate to set the date and summon the
other,'' the premier said. ``This debate must occur at a moment
when the French people are really mobilized.''
   Responding with thick irony, Mitterrand said he was very open
about the date, but at the moment, he had nobody to talk to.
   ``I must address myself to the different candidates who could be
present in the second round,'' he said. ``That is a difficult
conversation to have seriously before Sunday night.''
   The polls indicated Mitterrand would defeat either Chirac or
Barre in the second round, though the gap was narrowing.
   A televised debate, which has become a tradition in presidential
politics, is vastly more important to Chirac, who hopes it will
help him gain ground. Mitterrand has much more to lose and must
avoid a serious gaffe.
   Chirac, head of the conservative Rally for the Republic party,
is a tough debater. Mitterrand no doubt has not forgotten how
Chirac ran roughshod over former Socialist Premier Laurent Fabius
in a televised debate before the 1986 legislative elections.
   Chirac says he doesn't want an American-style debate with the
two men questioned separately by a panel of journalists. He wants a
head-on confrontation. Mitterrand would prefer a less direct method.
   Analysts have called the presidential campaign lackluster and
without any real discussion of the issues. Candidates have spoken
about ``priorities'' and ``general orientations,'' but none of them
has proposed any refreshing new ideas on how to tackle France's
economic and social problems.
   Mitterrand is seeking a second seven-year term in the Elysee
Palace. Chirac, who also served as premier from 1974-76 under
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, is making his second run for
the presidency. Barre, who replaced Chirac as Giscard's premier, is
running for the first time.
   Mitterrand defeated Giscard in the presidential election May 10,
1981.
   On Friday the two-week ``official campaign'' ends. During that
period, each candidate has a specifically allotted amount of time
on radio and television, and campaign meetings intensify.
   No political advertising is allowed on radio and television. On
Saturday before the election, no campaigning is permitted.
   There are 38.3 million eligible voters.
</TEXT>
