<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Hijack,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Still in the Dark About Hijackers Whereabouts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is still in the dark
regarding the whereabouts of the nine hijackers who killed two
passengers aboard a Kuwaiti plane before releasing the hostages,
the State Department said Thursday.
   The United States is in touch with the government of Algeria,
where the hijacking ended Wednesday, as well as with Kuwaiti
authorities. Most of the 31 hostages were Kuwaitis, and the
hijackers had demanded the release of 17 prisoners held by Kuwait
for terrorist bombings.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the United
States does not know whether a deal was struck with the hostages.
   ``We remain unaware of specific arrangements which were worked
out to lead to the end of the hijacking,'' she said.
   Kuwait reportedly agreed to commute the death sentences of three
of the 17 Moslems whose released was being demanded by the
hijackers in return for the hostages' release.
   The hijackers were reportedly flown to Lebanon.
   ``We don't know where the hijackers are. We remain in touch with
the government of Algeria on this matter,'' Mrs. Oakley said. ``We
are also in touch with a number of governments that share our
concerns about bringing terrorists to justice.''
   ``The United States will not rest until the terrorists, the
murderers, the hijackers are brought to justice. Our objective is
to make sure they do not go unpunished,'' she said.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States is examining the possibility
of filing charges against the hijackers because one of the hostages
holds dual U.S.-Egyptian citizenship.
</TEXT>
