<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     04-21 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean President Says North Korea Will Soften Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo said Thursday
the 1988 Olympics in Seoul will force North Korea to change its
hardline communist policy and reopen a dialogue with South Korea.
   Roh said if North Korea changes its longstanding policy to make
the Korean peninsula communist through military force, South Korea
would move actively to improve relations.
   ``The Olympics are dictating changes in the situation of this
part of the world, and I, therefore, believe that North Korea's
policy would also inevitably change,'' Roh told a nationally
televised news conference.
   Roh said relations would reach an ``epochal turning point'' in
four or five years, and said he hoped he could lay a firm
foundation for unification.
   Despite the November bombing of a South Korean civilian airliner
in an attack South Korea blamed on North Korean agents, Seoul and
Pyongyang have been talking and must keep channels open, he said.
   Roh, who took office Feb. 25, did not say what channels the two
Korean states were using for dialogue. But he said, ``The most
effective way to solve problems is summit talks.''
   Roh's predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, proposed a summit with North
Korean President Kim Il-sung on many occasions, but the Pyongyang
government turned him down.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
anti-communist South Korea in 1945 at the end of World War II. They
fought a bloody civil war from 1950 to 1953.
   They have held intermittent talks since the early 1970s. Their
latest dialogue was broken off in 1986 when North Korea disputed a
major joint U.S.-South Korea military exercise.
   Relations took another nosedive last November when a Korean Air
jetliner disappeared near Burma, killing all 115 people on board.
   A North Korean agent in the custody of South Korean intelligence
authorities confessed in Seoul in January that she and a male agent
put a time bomb on the plane to disrupt the Olympics in Seoul.
   Roh deplored the bombing, but said his government still needs to
promote dialogue with North Korea to avoid a ``possibly more tragic
incident.''
   Roh also said increasing violence in the National Assembly
elections would be suppressed.
   ``Whoever violates the law and destroys democratic order must be
punished severely in the name of people,'' Roh said.
   Roh said his governing Democratic Justice Party needs a majority
in the 299-member National Assembly in elections next Tuesday.
   Top opposition leaders have said that if the party tries to rig
the elections, they will call for violent protests similar to those
in June that forced democratic reforms.
   ``The ruling party will face popular resistence and disobedience
if its irregularities and unfair campaigning continue,'' said
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung of the Party for Peace and Democracy.
   Rival opposition leader Kim Young-sam of the Reunification
Democratic Party said he would have to make a ``grave decision'' if
the government cheated.
   Roh was elected in December when the two Kims split the
opposition vote.
   Corruption and violence are among major campaign issues in the
legislative elections, the first test of public confidence in the
Roh government.
   Government officials say 15 people have been arrested for
involvement in campaign violence, including six members of Roh's
party. Another 120 people were charged but not jailed for violating
election laws, they said.
   In keeping with a campaign pledge, Roh publicly declared his
personal wealth at $693,000.
   The president also said he would lead a clean public life during
his single five-year term and would not tolerate any attempts by
his relatives to sell influence or make an illicit fortune during
his tenure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
