<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Demeanor     04-21 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Demeanor,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wins Praise For High-toned Demeanor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson accepted defeat in New York as
he has accepted his wins and losses in other states _ graciously
and with a call for Democratic unity.
   He praised the campaign of the winner, Michael Dukakis, and said
that during the rest of the primary season there must be ``a
measure of competition, a measure of cooperation'' as the Democrats
``keep our eyes on the bigger prize'' _ victory in the November
general election.
   It was consistent with the high-toned campaign Jackson has
carefully crafted, in which he has stayed above the fray, even
during the past week when under attack by New York Mayor Edward
Koch.
   His demeanor has been noticed within the Democratic Party where
once he was considered a polarizing force.
   ``I think Democrats all over the country are giving Jackson high
marks for his conduct during the campaign,'' said William Carrick,
who managed Rep. Richard Gephardt's presidential campaign until the
Missouri congressman dropped out last month. In fact, Carrick said,
Jackson has had a unifying effect on the race.
   ``From the very beginning of the year, Jesse has tried to keep
to the high road. He has not been critical. It's been a deliberate
conscious effort,'' he said.
   Jackson in 1988 stands in contrast to the candidate who in
earlier years attacked Democratic party rules as exclusionary,
alienated Jewish voters and cavorted around the world grabbing the
spotlight by meeting with controversial figures including Cuba's
Fidel Castro and Nicaragua's Daniel Ortega.
   ``In his earlier years he obviously was a protester. This time
he has grown tremendously and has grown into the protecter of the
high road,'' said Jackson adviser Bert Lance, who was a member of
former President Carter's inner circle.
   Jackson adviser Ann Lewis said many Democratic leaders had
commented to her about ``how tough it must have been not to
respond'' to Koch's assertions that Jews ``would have to be crazy''
to vote for Jackson, and Koch's allegation that Jackson lied about
his proximity to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. when King was slain in
1968.
   ``There's a real appreciation that he held back,'' said Lewis.
   And in fact, Jackson discussed it, she said. ``He said that it
was hard but he knew he was doing the right thing,'' and that he
had told her more than a year ago that he was determined not to
engage in negative campaigning.
   In New York, Jackson did say, ``Some people are making hysteria
while I'm making history.''
   The Jackson strategy, aimed at putting a Democrat in the White
House in November, also is devised to make Jackson a party insider
rather than the outsider he was in 1984.
   ``It's very important to him and his participation in the
campaign to be seen as a positive force for the party,'' Carrick
said.
   Jackson's campaign manager Gerald Austin said he saw a
``maturation process over the last four years,'' and said that
because of the way Jackson has conducted himself he is considered a
major player in party politics by the other major players.
   In debates among the Democratic contenders, Jackson has relished
the role of the peacemaker as some of his rivals squabbled. He has
insisted that Democrats should aim their fire at the Republicans,
and frequently contends internal party wrangling cost them the
White House in previous elections.
   Even after the Super Tuesday contests across the South, where
Jackson had reason to gloat after pulling the most votes and
polling second in the delegate count, he put in a plug for party
unity. He called on what was then a hefty field of Democratic
contenders not to ``self destruct'' by attacking one another.
   Not only does Jackson refrain from attacking his opponents, he
regularly telephones them, said campaign manager Austin.
   ``There's a kind of camaraderie that exists,'' he said.
   Jackson pledges that, as he did in 1984, he will work hard for
the Democratic ticket even if he is not on it.
   That would stand him in good stead down the road, especially if
a Democratic administration takes over. ``He's doing all the right
things for his future,'' Carrick said.
   Austin commented that Jackson, at 46, is still a young man, and
``he's going to be around for a long time.''
</TEXT>
