<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Higgins Bjt   04-21 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Higgins, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captors Says Higgins' to Be Tried On Spying Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Iranian kidnappers of Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins said Thursday the Marine officer will be tried
on charges of spying for the United States.
   ``This criminal will be turned over today to the tribunal of the
oppressed to try him for the crimes he has committed,'' the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth said in a typewritten
statement delivered to the Reuters news agency office.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was serving with a U.N. observer
group in south Lebanon when he was abducted by gunmen Feb. 17 near
the ancient port of Tyre, 50 miles south of Beirut.
   The statement came three days after the Christian-run Voice of
Lebanon radio station claimed Higgins was killed during clashes
between pro-Syrian and Iranian-backed Shiite militias in south
Lebanon earlier this month.
   It could not be known whether Thursday's communique was meant to
refute the radio report or set the stage for announcing Higgins'
death.
   Thursday's Arabic-language statement from the Shiite Moslem
group was accompanied by a black-and-white photograph of Higgins,
apparently to prove its authenticity.
   The picture showed the balding Higgins with a stubbled gray
beard, wearing a dark field jacket, his eyes looking down and away
from the camera. It was the first photograph of Higgins released by
his captors since his kidnapping. It was not known when it was
taken.
   The statement said among the charges Higgins faced was ``spying
for the criminal United States on our Lebanese and Palestinian
peoples'' and ``active participation in American conspiracies
against our Moslem people.''
   Higgins supervised a ``Pentagon team to combat Lebanese and
Palestinian Islamic organizations in Palestine and Lebanon,'' the
statement said.
   Both the United States and the United Nations have previously
denied earlier charges by the kidnappers that Higgins was spying
for the CIA.
   L. Paul Bremer, ambassador-at-large for counterterrorism, said
the kidnappers' latest charge ``is of course nonsense.
   ``Col. Higgins is not a spy. He was working for the United
Nations for a peaceful mission and we hold his hostage holders
responsible for his safety,'' Bremer told ``CBS This Morning.''
   In Washington, a State Department spokeswoman said a ``so-called
trial'' of Higgins ``can bring only further discredit to the
terrorists and their cause. ``The notion that the Organization for
the Oppressed on Earth ... has the right to try anyone is simply
grotesque,'' said spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   Higgins, the statement alleged, provided the Defense Department
with ``his personal views on the situation (in the south), which
include all military activities in resisting Israel and ways of
bringing them under control.''
   It claimed he was a member of what it called an American
coordination committee ``on Lebanon and Palestine'' made up of
officials from the Defense Department, the State Department and the
Central Intelligence Agency.
   The kidnappers released a videotape Feb. 22 in which the Vietnam
veteran and onetime aide to former Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger asked President Reagan to meet demands for his release.
   The kidnappers have demanded a full Israeli withdrawal from an
occupied enclave in south Lebanon and the release of all Lebanese
and Palestinian guerrillas held by Israel.
   The U.S. administration has refused to intervene with Israel
over the captors' demands and said Higgins' plea was made under
duress.
   Thursday's statement was the fourth from the group since it
claimed Feb. 19 that it had kidnapped him.
   Also Thursday, the wife of another American hostage, Alann
Steen, sent him her good wishes for his 49th birthday in an
advertisement published by the independent An-Nahar daily.
   Steen, a native of Boston, was a communications instructor at
the U.S.-affiliated Beirut University College when he was kidnapped
on Jan. 24 last year.
   ``Dearest Alann,'' said the published note from Virginia Rose
Steen, 30, of Jackson, Mich., who also works at the Beirut college.
``We love you dearly. We keep working and hoping with others that
you will be with us again soon.''
   There are nine Americans among the 22 foreigners held hostage in
Lebanon. Held the longest is American Terry Anderson, the chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
