<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 1stld-Writethru   04-21 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 1st ld-Writethru,a0528,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Reports Third Intrusion At Fuel Storage Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with military reporting intrusion.
ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. military said today that
unidentified intruders broke into an American military fuel storage
area near the Panama Canal for the third time in two weeks.
   Bill Ormsby, a civilian spokesman for the U.S. Southern Command,
said he did not know if sentries guarding the Arraijan Tank Farm
near Howard Air Force Base exchanged fire with intruders Wednesday
night.
   ``They are still being debriefed, and I don't have any details
myself,'' Ormsby said.
   However, Ormsby said he did not believe there were any injuries
in the incident. A Marine was killed in the first reported
intrusion on April 11 when he was shot by fellow guards.
   Ormsby said the 807-acre tank farm, about five miles west of
Panama City, was being guarded by members of the 193rd Light
Infantry Brigade, which is based in Panama.
   The soldiers replaced the Marines after the second reported
intrusion last week. In that incident, the Marines said they
engaged in a two-hour firefight with what they said were between 40
and 50 men dressed in black uniforms.
   The Marines involved in the first two break-ins had arrived in
Panama only the week before from Camp Lejeune, N.C., as part of a
1,300-man U.S. military build-up.
   The Panamanian government ridiculed U.S. accounts of the alleged
intrusions, saying the Marines had fired at ``swaying palm trees''
and shadows. It later filed a diplomatic protest over the incidents.
   The Southern Command still has not released a report of its
investigation into last week's incidents, but a source close to the
probe said it turned up ``no conclusive evidence.''
   The source, however, said small electronic sensors scattered
over the hilly, jungled reserve had detected the presence of
intruders, which tended to confirm the visual sightings reported by
the Marines.
   A Pentagon spokesman, Dan Howard, told reporters in Washington
early last week that the intruders appeared to be members of the
Panama Defense Forces.
   The Defense Forces are commanded by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
who is under criminal indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges. The Reagan Administration, along with civilian
opponents in Panama, has been seeking the general's ouster for
months.
   On Wednesday, the government revoked a month-old state of
emergency that curbed civil liberties after rebel soldiers
attempted to overthrow Noriega.
   The National Assembly voted to revoke the emergency decree at
the request of acting President Manuel Solis Palma, a local
television broadcast said. There was no immediate comment from the
government.
   The ``state of urgency'' permitted the Noriega-controlled
government to suspend a wide range of civil liberties, including
freedom of speech and assembly and the right to private property.
   The government invoked the decree on March 18, two days after
dissident officers tried to remove Noriega as head of Panama's
15,000-strong Defense Forces but failed and were captured.
   A U.S. military official said four high-ranking Panamanian
military officers would visit Fort McNair near Washington, D.C.
next week. High-ranking members of Noriega's staff are seldom
accessible to U.S. officials.
   In another development, Roderick Esquivel, ousted as vice
president by pro-Noriega lawmakers along with then-president Eric
Arturo Delvalle, appealed to Latin American governments to support
efforts to oust the general.
   In a letter released Wednesday, he said:
   ``We hope that the Latin American democracies will raise their
voice without euphemisms, show solidarity and help Panamanians to
break up this dangerous dictatorship.''
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle as the nation's
president.
   In February, Noriega was indicted on federal drug trafficking
charges in Florida. He has since successfully resisted U.S.
economic sanctions and an opposition campaign aimed at forcing him
out of office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
