<DOCNO> AP880421-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PennSenate Bjt   04-21 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penn Senate, Bjt,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrat Seeking To Buck GOP's Grip on Senate Seats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Vignola is heavily favored to win the
Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate on Tuesday. If he does, his
problems have just started.
   The nominee will be going against the well-known and well-heeled
Republican incumbent, John Heinz III, and against tradition.
Pennsylvania has not sent a Democrat to the Senate since Joseph S.
Clark won in 1962.
   Vignola, the former Philadelphia city controller, is the
best-financed of the four Democratic candidates and has the
endorsement of the Democratic State Committee.
   Potter County Commissioner Susan Kefover is his only active
opponent, but she has raised barely more than $5,000. Vignola's
campaign raised $133,352 between January and April.
   The other two candidates are John Logue, a professor of
political science at Villanova University, and economic consultant
Steven S. Douglas.
   Logue, who ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic Senate
nomination in 1982, bills himself as the only Democrat who can beat
Heinz. He says he seeks to ``promote world peace, to protect the
environment and to lower the budget and trade deficits.''
   Kefover says people have lost faith in government.
   ``We have to start giving more control back to local government
officials _ to help bring that confidence back and get us all back
in shape,'' she said during a recent campaign stop in Lancaster
County.
   Douglas, 36, ran unsuccessfully in the 1986 gubernatorial
primary and was supported by the organization of Lyndon LaRouche,
the political extremist who had sought the presidency.
   Heinz, whose campaign had $1.8 million on hand as of April 6
compared to $48,013 for Vignola, has no primary opposition.
   A Heinz-Vignola race would shape up as a rerun of the 1986 race
between Republican Sen. Arlen Specter and Democrat Bob Edgar.
   In both cases, the Democrat is a liberal from Philadelphia
making his first run for statewide office against an incumbent
moderate Republican who is better known and better financed.
Specter won 57 percent of the vote against Edgar.
   Workers in the Heinz and Vignola campaigns said they knew of no
public opinion polls that had been taken before the primary.
   Vignola's aides acknowledged that any voter preference poll
would likely show that their candidate is not yet widely recognized
in the western half of the state, a common problem for Philadelphia
candidates.
   Vignola is already campaigning against Heinz, with lines such
as: ``We need a senator to represent the people on Main Street in
Pennsylvania, not Wall Street.''
   Heinz, heir to 57 varieties of money from the Pittsburgh-based
pickle packing company, served two terms in the House, then poured
$2.9 million of his own money to win his Senate seat in 1976.
   Heinz has been silent during the campaign, but his aides sprang
to his defense when Vignola claimed Heinz voted against a highway
contruction bill important to Pennsylvania's turnpike improvement
program.
   Vignola said Heinz was one of 17 senators who voted against the
bill, which ultimately was vetoed by President Reagan. However, the
records show Heinz was not among the 17 who voted ``nay'' March 19,
1987.
   Heinz was absent because his plane from Pittsburgh was delayed,
aides said. He had a notation placed in the official record that he
supported the bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
