<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess     04-21 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karpov Assured of Share of SWIFT Chess Title</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former world chess champion Anatoly
Karpov was assured of at least a share of the SWIFT World Cup
Tournament title on Thurslday when Briton John Nunn drew an
adjourned game.
   With one round remaining, Karpov has 10{ points out of a
possible 15. Nunn and Soviet Valery Salov are tied with 9{ points.
Another Soviet, Alexander Beliavsky, is fourth with nine points.
   Karpov, who did not play Thursday, is widely expected to agree
quickly to a draw in his last-round game with Swede Ulf Andersson
on Friday to finish alone in first place and take the $20,000 first
prize.
   Even if Karpov were to lose Friday, Nunn and Salov could only
tie for first place. A win scores one point and a draw a half.
   In the first of the adjourned games completed on Thursday,
Dutchman Jan Timman and Nunn maneuvered in an endgame for two hours
before agreeing to a draw.
   A second unfinished game between Soviet Andrei Sokolov and
Timman was drawn after only a few minutes play.
   Timman, the third-ranked player in the world, moved up to 10th
place in the 17-man competition.
   ``In many ways, the standings here reflect the situation in
world chess. The Soviets are leading with an Englishman second,''
said Gennadi Sosonko, a Dutch grandmaster.
   At the 1986 Chess Olympiad _ the world team championship _ the
Soviets came in first with England second and the United States
third.
   The $104,000 SWIFT tournament is the first of six events spread
over two years that make up the inaugural Chess World Cup.
   Organized by the 2-year-old Grandmasters Association, the events
feature the world's top 25 players and a prize fund of $1.2 million.
   Each of the 25 grandmasters will play four of the six tournament
and their best three finishes will make up their final standing.
   World Champion Garri Kasparov did not compete in the SWIFT
tournament. He opens his World Cup campaign in Belfort, France, in
June.
   In the battle for second place Friday, Nunn will face Ljubomir
Ljubojevic of Yugoslavia while Salov will play Gyula Sax of Hungary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here are the standings before Friday's final round:
   1. Anatoly Karpov, Soviet Union, 10{ points.
   2. (tie) John Nunn, Britain; Valery Salov, Soviet Union, 9{
points.
   4. Alexander Beliavsky, Soviet Union, 9 points.
   5. (tie) Ulf Andersson, Sweden; Ljubomir Ljubojevic, Yugoslavia;
Lajos Portisch, Hungary, 8{ points.
   8. Jonathan Speelman, Britain, 8 points.
   9. Mikhail Tal, Soviet Union, 7{ points.
   10. (tie) Predrag Nikolic, Yugoslavia; Andrei Sokolov, Soviet
Union; Jan Timman, Netherlands, 7 points.
   13. Jesus Nogueiras, Cuba, 7 points.
   14. Yasser Seirawan, United States, 6{ points.
   15. Victor Korchnoi, Switzerland, 6 points.
   16. Gyula Sax, Hungary, 5{ points.
   17. Luc Winants, Belgium, 2{ points.
</TEXT>
