<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cowboy'sCasino     04-21 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cowboy's Casino,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One-time Rustler Gets Gaming License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted sheep-rustler with a
cowboy's grudge against rules and regulations won a gaming license
Thursday for a tiny rural casino.
   Jimmy Williams, 57, was approved by the state Gaming Commission
for a six-month temporary license to run two slot machines and a
blackjack game at the Golden Club in the isolated town of Austin in
central Nevada.
   Commission Chairman John O'Reilly warned Williams, who inherited
a one-sixth interest in the club from his mother, that he would
have to adhere to tough gaming regulations.
   O'Reilly told Williams he would be wearing two hats: ``One is
your cowboy hat and one is your gaming hat.'' He added that
Williams must follow the rules even though he's in a remote area.
   Commissioner Bob Lewis told Williams his application was ``a
refreshing break from the others we had to read.''
   Williams had told the commission's investigative arm, the state
Gaming Control Board, that he had many conflicts with brand
inspectors, the Bureau of Land Management and other regulatory
agencies.
   Sometimes, he said, he pleaded guilty just to get out of courts
and back to the hills.
   Williams said he spent 10 months in prison in 1962 for rustling.
He said he had hauled another rancher's sheep out of an area where
they were interfering with a camp he was running, and simply
released them elsewhere.
   ``I'm still looking for those sheep,'' joked Commissioner Lewis,
who grew up in the same central Nevada area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
