<HEAD>Billionaires Plead Innocent to Federal Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaires Harry and Leona Helmsley pleaded
innocent Thursday to federal charges of tax fraud.
   The real estate developer and his wife, the ``queen'' of the
Helmsley hotel chain's advertising campaign, pleaded not guilty to
similar state charges last week.
   The five-minute hearing before U.S. Magistrate Nina Gershon with
defense attorney Steven Kaufman calling the twin federal and state
indictments an unprecedented ``twofer _ two prosecutions based on
the same set of facts.''
   The Helmsleys, whose net worth is estimated to be $1.4 billion,
were released without bail, but must surrender their passports and
remain in the country pending trial. The same applied to two former
Helmsley employees who also entered please of innocent.
   The Helmsleys are due back in court April 29 for a hearing on
the indictment, which also charges Mrs. Helmsley with attempted
extortion.
   The federal charges accuse the Helmsleys of defrauding the
government of taxes by claiming by improperly deducting some $4
million in home renovation and other expenditures as business
expenses.
   Helmsley employee Frank Turco, 45, of Lutz, Fla., is charged
along with Mrs. Helmsley with attempted extortion of Helmsley
employees and contractors.
   Former Helmsley financial manager Joseph Licari, 51, of Oyster
Bay Cove was also named in both indictments.
