<DOCNO> AP880421-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Gore 3rdLd-Writethru a0693-a0700-a0704 04-21 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0693-a0700-a0704,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said today he would
suspend his campaign for the 1988 Democratic nomination and said he
would do ``everything I can'' to elect a Democrat as the next
president.
   In a graceful exit, Gore said he would technically remain a
candidate to permit his delegates to attend the Democratic National
Convention.
   But, he said in room crowded with supporters, ``I want no part
of a stop Jackson or a stop Dukakis movement. The only man I want
to stop is George Bush and we're going to stop George Bush.''
   Gore exited with a joke after a failed campaign that he said
lasted 10 months and a million miles.
   ``I was doing great until I turned 40,'' the Tennessee senator
said.
   Gore's withdrawal leaves only front-runner Michael Dukakis and
Jesse Jackson as active candidates for the Democratic nomination.
   Gore's campaign soared on Super Tuesday on March 8, when he
scored primary victories in Arkansas, Kentucky, North Carolina,
Oklahoma as well as his home state of Tennessee. But he was never
able to capitalize on his Southern success when the campaign turned
to the Midwestern and Northern states. When he got only 10 percent
of the New York primary vote on Tuesday, he decided to pull the
plug.
   Gore entered the race bidding to emerge as the type of moderate
Southern candidate who could permit the Democratic Party to capture
Southern states in the fall election.
   Nevada aside, virtually his only campaign success came in his
native region.
   ``I lost this race and that is a disappointment,'' Gore said as
his wife Tipper and other members of his family stood by his side.
   ``But some things matter to me more than winning _ helping my
party, serving my country, knowing when to keep fighting and
knowing when I've been licked.''
   Gore amassed 423 Democratic National Convention delegates during
his campaign, according to a count by The Associated Press. His
decision to suspend rather than formally quit the campaign means
they can attend the convention.
   Had he decided to withdraw, his delegates would have been
divided between Jackson and Dukakis.
   Gore spent his final hours as an active candidate trying to
retire his huge debt.
   He went to Texas on Wednesday for a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser
to pay off some of the more than $1.5 million in debts the campaign
has run up.
   Arriving in Austin, Gore told reporters, ``I'm in the midst now
of consulting with friends and supporters all over the country and
asking for their advice on how we can best continue the cause for
which I have been fighting.''
   At the dinner, he did not say whether he would withdraw. But his
speech had the sound of a last hurrah.
   ``I have learned from my opponents. I believe they have learned
from me,'' he said.
   And he talked about turning attention to the general election.
   ``These next few weeks will be a time for unity and a time to
look forward to the fall election,'' he said.
   The Tennessee senator praised both Jackson and Dukakis. He said
Jackson has ``reclaimed our party's passion for social justice''
and that Dukakis has ``shown a steady hand through a long and
trying campaign.''
   ``They are both good men and formidable candidates,'' he said.
   Gore's strategy for winning the nomination was unusual and
ultimately unsuccessful.
   He skipped the opening Iowa caucuses, where his message as ``a
raging moderate'' was not well-received.
   Then his campaign waffled on how much of an effort to make in
New Hampshire _ where his issue positions found a receptive
audience. By the time the money was poured into the Granite State,
it was too late to affect the outcome and he finished fifth in a
seven-man field.
   ``I always felt like, if anybody could pass up Iowa and New
Hampshire, he could,'' said Kathy Vick, Louisiana Democratic Party
chairman. ``That he was an exception to the unwritten rule that you
had to play in Iowa and New Hampshire.''
   Gore proclaimed that he would ``jump-start'' his campaign in his
home region on March 8, the Super Tuesday when every Southern and
border state but one held primaries.
   He did well that day, but so did Dukakis and Jackson,
splintering the political benefits of the massive regional primary.
   After that, Gore could not find a place to make a stand. He
skipped Michigan and Connecticut, but then put a chunk of money
into Wisconsin, where he once again finished behind the two
front-runners.
   New York was his last stand.
</TEXT>
