<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--AIDS-HealthWorkers     04-21 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--AIDS-Health Workers,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Health Workers' AIDS From `Unknown' Cause; Feds Say Risk
Still Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health care workers with AIDS are nearly twice as
likely as other AIDS patients to have contracted the disease
through ``undetermined'' means, federal health officials said
Thursday.
   They added, however, that the occupational risk to such workers
remains small.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported that 2,586
health care workers are known to be among the more than 50,000
Americans who have contracted AIDS. Health care workers make up 5.4
percent of the known U.S. AIDS patients and also make up a similar
percentage of the population at large _ 5.7 percent, the CDC said.
   But while only 2.8 percent of the nation's other AIDS patients
are classified as having gotten the disease in an ``undetermined''
manner, nearly twice as many of the health care workers with AIDS
fall into no known risk group _ 5.3 percent, or 135 in all.
   Reasons for the higher number of ``undetermined'' cases among
health care workers are unknown, the Atlanta-based CDC said. Those
reasons could include failure to disclose homosexual behavior, drug
abuse or other risk factors, ``the occupational risk of (AIDS)
infection as a result of blood exposure, or both.''
   The disease most often strikes homosexual men and injectible
drug abusers, and also is spread less frequently through
heterosexual contact or blood transfusions.
   Failure to disclose behavior which might have put them at risk
is something researchers consider when looking at ``all AIDS
patients with undetermined risk ... both health care workers and
non-health care workers,'' said Dr. Mary Chamberland, a CDC AIDS
specialist.
   ``Or, we may be seeing some occupational transmission in the
health care setting,'' she said. ``It's difficult to establish with
certainty how transmission occurred.''
   Most U.S. health care workers who have AIDS were infected
outside their job, but ``a small number of health-care workers have
been infected ... through occupational exposures,'' the CDC noted
in its weekly report.
   More than a dozen health care workers are documented to have
become infected with the virus that causes AIDS as a result of
their work _ usually by accidentally being pricked by a
contaminated needle. One health care worker is known to have gone
on to develop the deadly disease itself after he was infected in
such a manner.
   Scientific studies have shown that the chance of being infected
after a needle-stick exposure to blood from infected patients is
less than 1 percent, the CDC said.
   ``That data has not changed at all (in continuing studies),''
Ms. Chamberland said. ``The risk is still regarded as low, and it's
most closely associated with inoculation with (tainted) blood,
either in a needle-stick or in a cut with a sharp object.''
   The number of cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
reported in the United States is 59,491, including 33,280 cases in
which the person has died, according to statistics this week from
the CDC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
