<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Aspin-PersianGulf     04-21 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aspin-Persian Gulf,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Armed Services Chairman Says US May Have Overreacted</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States ``may have shot ourselves in
the foot'' by overreacting with this week's military attacks on
Iranian oil platforms and ships in the Persian Gulf, Rep. Les
Aspin, chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said in
remarks released Thursday.
   ``There is good reason to suspect that the mines that prompted
Monday's retaliation were not laid by Tehran authorities, but by
some Iranian radicals looking to start a fight,'' the Wisconsin
Democrat said.
   Aspin admitted that ``I cannot prove this. No one at this time
can prove who ordered the laying the of the mines _ or why.''
   Aspin's analysis was contained in a speech he will deliver
Friday morning to the Washington Forum, a private group. A text of
the speech was released Thursday evening.
   White House spokesman Bill Harlow, asked for comment, said, ``I
don't usually engage in debates over speeches.''
   At the Pentagon, officials said there would be no comment until
they had read Aspin's speech.
   ``We may have shot ourselves in the foot,'' said Aspin. ``Our
restrained policy in the gulf worked superbly until now. We had
shown sufficient force to convince Iran to back off, without
reacting so bloodily as to generate the `martyrs' that the
(Iranian) radicals use to inflame public passions.''
   Navy forces on Monday destroyed two Iranian oil platforms in the
southern Persian Gulf after a mine believed laid by Iran was struck
by the frigate USS Samuel B. Roberts on April 14. Ten sailors were
injured and the ship suffered hull damage.
   After the platforms were destroyed, Iranian ships and planes
attacked Navy forces and the Navy responded by sinking or damaging
six Iranian ships.
   The action won wide praise and support on Capitol Hill, both
from Republicans and Democrats. Aspin had not commented, but he
previously been a supporter of administration gulf policy.
   President Reagan, after the fighting, said, ``We've taken this
action to make certain the Iranians have no illusions about the
cost of irresponsible behavior. We aim to deter further Iranian
aggression, not provoke it.''
   But Aspin said more U.S.-Iran confrontations may lie ahead.
   The Navy has been escorting 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers and
Navy ships had previously destroyed Iranian oil platforms last Oct.
19 in retaliation for Iranian mine-laying efforts.
   Those strikes came after an Iranian ship, the Iran Ajar, was
caught by the Navy while laying mines. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci said Monday that mines in the area where the Roberts was
damaged ``were from the same series of those found on the Iran
Ajar, leaving no doubt the mines were sown by Iran.''
   Aspin asserted that the regime of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
``re-evaluated its Persian Gulf policy in January'' and decided not
to confront the United States any more.
   ``There is good reason to suspect that some irate (Iranian)
radicals decided to light a fire in the Persian Gulf,'' he said.
   ``It would not take more than a handful of Revolutionary Guards
to drop some mines in the gulf sea lanes,'' he said. ``They could
expect that if an American ship hit one, the United States would
retaliate and they could return to the glorious confrontational
days of yore.''
   ``If this theory is correct, the radicals have won,'' Aspin
said. ``With this week's shoot-up in the gulf, the regime's policy
of declaring victory and then turning its back on the gulf has
failed. It cannot ignore the American presence now.''
</TEXT>
