<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-US     04-21 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel, United States Sign Joint Memorandum of Understanding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel and the United States signed an
agreement on mutual cooperation Thursday, formalizing ties
established during the Reagan administration.
   The memorandum was signed simultaneously in Washington and
Jerusalem by President Reagan and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Describing the Reagan administration as ``the friendliest Israel
has ever known,'' Shamir said the five-year agreement formalized ad
hoc arrangements developed in the past few years.
   The memorandum formalizes the two nations' consultative groups,
which meet periodically to discuss joint military and security
assistance as well as economic development issues.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering, who attended the signing
ceremony in Jerusalem, hinted at disagreements between Shamir and
the U.S. government over current American peace efforts.
   ``Peace is as vital for Israel's security as military and
economic strength and we will continue to work with all the states
in this region to achieve that objective,'' he said.
   Shamir opposes a U.S. initiative to convene an international
peace conference and speed up negotiations leading to Palestinian
self-rule, and, later, a permanent peace settlement.
   Relations between Israel and the United States drew close after
the 1967 Middle East war, when Washington became Israel's major
supplier of arms after other Western arms-producing countries
refused to sell weapons to the Jewish state.
   In 1973, the United States airlifted weapons and ammunition to a
beleaguered Israel caught off guard when Egypt and Syria lauched a
surprise attack.
   Under the Reagan administration, civilian and military aid to
Israel has grown to $3 billion and ties have grown closer.
   In 1981, the two countries signed a secret agreement on
strategic cooperation which included provisions for military trade
and joint planning.
   In 1985, an economic accord was signed lifting trade barriers
between the two countries.
   In recent years, Israel has become a port of call for ships of
the U.S. Mediterranean fleet and has provided the United States
with land for a transmitter to beam Voice of America and Radio Free
Europe broadcasts to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
