<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Romer may be governor, but he's no boss. And
when it comes to Bruce Springsteen, the state's CEO says he's just
another fan.
   ``He talks about different themes, what it is to be home, what
it is to be married. It's a guy groping,'' said Romer. ``I'm doing
the same thing. Aren't we all?''
   Romer said he had not tried to set up a meeting with Springsteen.
   ``He's got his own life he wants to live, and I respect that.
I'm one of the multitudes,'' he said.
   Springsteen performed Wednesday at McNichols Arena to a crowd of
more than 17,000 people.
   ``I'm here because Roy (Romer) is here and the boss
(Springsteen),'' said Ron Roberts of Denver. ``Romer and I are the
only gray-haired guys here.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Eartha Kitt sings and speaks in
several languages _ a talent and a problem, she says.
   ``When I was growing up in Harlem,'' she said, ``a number of
people from the Caribbean were moving into the neighborhood. I
wanted to play with the children, and they all spoke Spanish.
Eventually, by talking about the games we were playing and that
kind of thing, I began to learn their language.''
   During shows this week, she sang in English, French and
Japanese. She talked in English, Spanish and French.
   Some people accuse her of putting on airs. ``The black people
think, `She thinks she's white,''' she said.
   ``My mother was black and Cherokee Indian. My father was white,
although nobody knows for sure who he was. Then my mother married a
black man who didn't want any `yellow gal' around the house. ...
She gave me away.''
   The outspoken singer was criticized for her trips to South
Africa despite that country's apartheid policies.
   ``I first went in 1974, because I was curious,'' she said. ``I
wanted to see for myself. And they're still holding that against
me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALCALA DE HENARES, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican novelist Carlos Fuentes,
a developer of the Latin American writing style known as ``Magic
Realism,'' on Thursday received the 1987 Miguel de Cervantes Prize
for Literature.
   King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia presented the prize at the
university in this town outside Madrid.
   Juan Carlos praised Fuentes' ``exemplary work of creation and
thought'' and ``his insistent vocation to narrate our present
problems and delve into our promising futures.''
   In November, a jury of writers and critics named Fuentes the
1987 recipient of the award, considered the Spanish-language
equivalent of the Nobel Prize.
   In his acceptance speech, Fuentes, 59, author of ``The Death of
Artemio Cruz'' (1964) and ``Terra Nostra'' (1975), emphasized the
importance of the Spanish language.
   ``It has been converted into a universal language, spoken,
written, read, sung, thought and sounded by a growing number of
people,'' he said. ``It is the strongest link in our commmunity ..
. and the language of imagination, love and justice _ not of
empire.''
   The prize is named for the author of ``Don Quixote,'' Miguel de
Cervantes and amounts to the equivalent of $90,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Greer Garson has honored the doctor who
cared for her late husband with an endowed professorship at the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical School.
   Her $1.5 million gift was announced Wednesday and honors Paul C.
Peters, chairman of the division of urology. Miss Garson's husband,
E. E. ``Buddy'' Fogelson, died in December following a lengthy
illness.
   Southwestern President Dr. Kern Wildenthal said he would request
that the University of Texas System Board of Regents appoint Peters
as first holder of the endowed chair.
   Miss Garson has apartments in Beverly Hills, Calif., and Dallas
and a ranch in Pecos, N.M.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential spokesman Larry Speakes
said Thursday his ``Speaking Out'' is no ``kiss and tell'' book, as
Ronald Reagan has called it.
   Such a book would ``have a little more juicy-type items in it
that are a little bit more punchy,'' Speakes said Thursday on the
NBC-TV ``Today'' show.
   Speakes said the controversy over the quotes he fabricated as
the president's ``was a total surprise.''
   ``A lot of people have told me that's done all the time in
Washington, that you supply a few quotes,'' he said.
   Speakes said in the book that a comment he provided as having
been made by Reagan to Mikhail Gorbachev while they were in Geneva
at a summit meeting was never said, and another quote he gave as
Reagan's actually was said by Secretary of State George Shultz.
   ``I did it on the spur of the moment. I did it in order to serve
the president. I did it as an act of loyalty to the president,
certainly not as an act of disloyalty to the president,'' Speakes
said.
   The furor led to Speakes' resignation last week as chief
spokesman for Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York _ a job he took after
six years at the White House.
   Speakes said he did not know whether the sin was in the doing or
in the telling about it. ``It's hard for me to decide what I'm
being critized for,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell M. Rabb has become the longest-serving U.S.
ambassador to Italy, the American Embassy said Thursday.
   Ambassador since June 27, 1981, Rabb surpassed the record of
Frederick Reinhardt, who served from 1961-68.
   In a ceremony Wednesday, Rabb, 77, said, ``Today, thanks to the
contributions of so many Americans and Italians, the ties of
friendship and understanding between our two countries are closer
and stronger than ever.''
