<DOCNO> AP880421-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Internment     04-21 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Internment,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese-American Expects Apology, No Reparations for Internment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese-American living in Japan said Thursday
he expects to receive an apology for being interned in the United
States during World War II, but not to get reparations as approved
by the U.S. Senate.
   Barry Saiki, 68, a retired U.S. Army officer working in public
relations in Japan, said reparations were justified because
Japanese-Americans lost possessions and five years of their lives.
   ``I think we'll get the apology,'' Saiki said in a telephone
interview. But he said he thought President Reagan would veto the
bill that eventually emerges from Congress.
   The chance that Congress would overturn a presidential veto was
slim, he said, ``therefore the possiblity of getting the reparation
is rather questionable.''
   The Senate passed a bill Wednesday to give an apology and
$20,000 in tax-free payments to Japanese-Americans who were rounded
up and placed in camps after the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor on
Dec. 7, 1941. The House passed a similar bill in September.
   The Japanese government had no official reaction to the Senate
action because it was a domestic U.S. issue, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Yoshifumi Matsuda told reporters.
   But Matsuda said he personally praised the Senate action because
he had been a consul general at the Japanese consulate in Los
Angeles and had worked on the issue.
   ``After many years, the justness and fairness are recovered
through democracy,'' Matsuda said. ``This is the way of American
democracy.''
   Saiki said he and his family were uprooted from their California
home in 1942 like thousands of other Japanese-Americans who fell
under suspicion after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
   He had been about to graduate from the University of California
at Berkeley, but instead ended up in a camp in Arkansas with his
mother and two younger brothers. His father was sent to a separate
camp for community leaders, he said.
   Saiki was inducted into the U.S. Army in 1944 and was
commissioned as an officer just as the war ended. His family was
able to move to Philadelphia where they worked as farm laborers,
living in the basement of an old house.
   After the war his family returned to California, again working
as farm laborers.
   ``From the day they were evacuated in 1942, in 1947, five years
later, they hadn't gotten back to prewar status,'' Saiki said.
``They had lost everything they had acquired up to 1942. ... I very
definitely feel it (reparations) is very justified.''
   He said his own military career in counterintelligence brought
him to Japan on four tours after the war, and he spent 10 years on
military duty in this country. Then, after he retired as a
lieutenant colonel in 1966, he returned here to work and has
remained ever since.
   Saiki is a member of the board of the Japanese-American
Citizens' League, which has about 150 members.
   ``Some of us are not in such pressing need for money,'' he said,
``but there are others who are. Half the people have died, and
every year the number is getting smaller. The people who deserved
the money and who need it are gradually dying.''
   Asked if he felt Japan had a role in the issue because its
attack on Pearl Harbor led to the internment, he replied: ``It's an
American problem. It's not because of Japan that it happened.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ImmigrationConference     04-21 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Immigration Conference,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS' No. 2 Man Says Amnesty Extension Deadline is Unnecessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent surge in the number of
immigration amnesty applicants shows that the program is working
and the May 4 deadline need not be extended, the immigration
service's No. 2 official said Thursday.
   ``We have had a rush of applications toward the end of the
program, so we're sure people are aware of the deadline,'' said
Mark Everson, Immigration and Naturalization Service deputy
commissioner. ``They've had 1{ years to collect their documentation
and come forward.''
   Everson, speaking at an immigration law conference sponsored by
three law schools, said a proposal to extend the amnesty
application deadline six months will have a harder time passing the
Senate than the House, where it passed Wednesday by 12 votes. He
said the Justice Department will urge President Reagan to veto the
measure if both houses approve it.
   ``It will send a bad signal to extend it,'' Everson told about
150 INS officials, immigration lawyers, scholars and clergy
involved in helping aliens file their applications. ``People
waiting in other countries will interpret it as a lack of resolve,
and they'll eventually come here with the thought that, well,
they'll take care of me someday, too.''
   Under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, people who
have been in the country illegally since before 1982 can apply for
amnesty from deportation and obtain temporary residency. Eighteen
months later, amnesty recipients may apply for permanent residency;
eventually they can apply for citizenship.
   Everson said the imposition of employer sanctions has cut down
on the number of undocumented immigrants. So far, 70 employers of
undocumented aliens nationwide have been fined a total of $250,000,
he said.
   The two-day conference is sponsored by the Texas Tech Law
School, the University of New Mexico School of Law and Arizona
State University College of Law.
   Sen. Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo., chief Senate author of the 1986
law, opposes the extention.
   ``Our numbers are right on target with the projections we used
when we passed the bill. I do not honestly see a need or
justification for extending the signup period,'' he said Wednesday.
   But during House debate, the chief sponsor of the extension,
Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli, D-Ky. said 1.2 million aliens have applied
for amnesty and 729,000 have received temporary residency cards.
   INS had hoped 2 million of the estimated 3 million total illegal
aliens in the country would apply for amnesty by the deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
