<HEAD>Leningrad Department Store Sustains Major Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire believed to have been started by an
arsonist swept through a Leningrad department store Thursday,
causing an estimated $2.5 million in damage, the Tass news agency
reported.
   Police have detained a suspect, but gave no identification or
explanation for why the individual would have set the Frunzensky
Department Store ablaze, the official news agency said.
   The state-run TV, which provided an unusual same-day report on
the fire, showed footage of a man in jeans and a brown jacket being
led away in handcuffs.
   The fire started at 4:17 a.m. and spread to the entire fourth
floor before it was contained about two hours later, Tass said.
   There was no mention of casualties, and the building presumably
was empty in the early morning when the fire broke out.
