<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CruiseIllness     04-21 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cruise Illness,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Study Says Many Cruise Illnesses Caused By Seafood Cocktail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Serious outbreaks of diarrhea
aboard cruise ships have become rare, but the most frequent known
culprit is a common delicacy: seafood cocktail, according to a
Centers for Disease Control suvey.
   Of 45 outbreaks investigated from 1975 to 1985, the most
frequently detected source was the seafood cocktails or salad,
according to a study by the CDC presented at a conference Wednesday
in Atlanta.
   Two-thirds of all cruises during those years docked in Florida
ports.
   ``It's a real popular food on cruises, and seafood is one food
which can be contaminated if it's not handled properly,'' said
David Addiss, medical epidemiologist and author of the report.
   Water was the second most common source of the outbreaks during
that 10-year-period, but Addiss noted that structural changes in
the ships' water systems have all but eliminated that problem.
   In 25 of the 45 cases, the cause could not be identified.
   Ship captains must radio to shore a day before they arrive at a
U.S. port and report the number of passengers complaining of
diarrhea. It is labeled an outbreak if more than 3 percent of the
passengers are affected.
</TEXT>
