<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare     04-21 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Opposes ABC Child Care Bill, But May Endorse
Alternative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration opposes a proposed
$2.5 billion child care bill, but may endorse other ways of helping
families with preschool children, Education Secretary William J.
Bennett said Thursday.
   Bennett said that while the administration doesn't like the Act
for Better Child Care (ABC), another bill giving a child care tax
credit to any taxpayer with preschoolers _ whether they are cared
for at home or elsewhere _ meets a series of principles he outlined
in testimony to the House Education and Labor subcommittee on human
resources.
   It is not yet clear whether the administration will propose its
own tax credit or support other federal initiatives to make day
care more affordable or available, Bennett said. Current tax law
allows a credit for children cared for outside the home.
   ``It's a matter of debate and discussion within the
administration right now,'' Bennett said.
   The ABC bill is backed by the Democratic leadership in Congress
and scores of organizations representing children, women, labor,
churches and medical personnel. It is sponsored by Rep. Dale
Kildee, D-Mich., and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.
   Three-quarters of the $2.5 billion in ABC money would help pay
the child care bills in families making up to 115 percent of a
state's median income. The rest would go for training and salaries
for child care workers, renovation of facilities and referral
programs for parents. A national advisory panel would develop
minimum federal child care standards.
   Conservatives including Phyllis Schlafly complained Thursday
that the ABC bill is too expensive and cumbersome, promotes
institutional care and discriminates against parents who stay at
home with their children. And they said the income cutoff in the
bill would let some families earning $40,000 get financial help.
   Another controversy centers on whether religious groups that
provide child care would be eligible for ABC grants. Kildee said he
is working for changes to make sure they qualify for money, but the
American Civil Liberties Union said the bill as it stands violates
the wall between church and state.
   ``This is one big new federal trough for churches,'' said Barry
Lynn, legislative counsel to the ACLU. ``Too many of them want it
and they're not willing to recognize the serious constitutional
issues here.''
   Another tax credit bill introduced by Rep. Clyde Holloway,
R-La., appears to meet the objections of both conservatives and
civil libertarians. It simply would give all families a credit of
$150 to $400 per preschool child. ``It offers more assistance and
more choice to more families with less cost to the government,''
Holloway told the subcommittee.
   Bennett said he personally favors the Holloway approach even
though some families might use the money for purposes other than
child care.
   He said the tax credit meets the administration criteria of
strengthening the family, treating stay-at-home mothers fairly, not
promoting any particular type of care, targeting funds to those
most in need and helping people without setting up a new
bureauracracy.
   Reflecting statements submitted for the record by Labor
Secretary Ann McLaughlin and assistant Health and Human Services
Secretary Sydney J. Olson, Bennett said the federal government
should not regulate day care centers, although ``I certainly see
the need for some kind of standards so the public and individual
families can have some security.''
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the National Association of
Manufacturers have endorsed the gist of a middle-ground proposal
sponsored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Rep. Nancy Johnson,
R-Conn.
   Their Child Care Services Improvement Act would give states $250
million in grant money for day care expansion and scholarships and
$100 million to start risk pools to limit liability. Another $25
million would be available to help home providers meet state
licensing requirements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
