<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Joke     04-21 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Joke,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Offers `Very Cynical' Joke Pegged To Middle East</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told what he conceded
was a ``very cynical'' joke Thursday as part of his response to a
question about the Middle East at a world affairs forum here.
   After pledging efforts to secure talks between Israel and its
Arab neighbors, Reagan said:
   ``I can't resist telling you a little joke. It's kind of cynical
_ very cynical in a matter of fact _ about the Middle East.''
   In the joke, a scorpion comes to a creek and asks a frog to
carry him across it, because scorpions can't swim.
   The frog says, ``Why, you'd sting me if I did.''
   The scorpion responds, ``That'd be silly because if I stung you
and you died, I'd drown.''
   ``Well, that made sense to the frog so he said, `get on,' and
started ferry him across and in midstream the scoprion stung him,''
the president said.
   As both were dying, the frog asked the scorpion, ``Why did you
do that _ now we're both going to die.''
   ``And the scorpion said, `This is the Middle East,''' the
president concluded.
   The joke was greeted with laughter and applause by members of
the World Affairs Council of Western Massachusetts.
   In answering a question about the Middle East, Reagan said that
``we are going to keep on trying as hard as we can'' to bring about
talks between the Arab states and Israel.''
   When asked whether the United States was willing to talk with
the Palestinians, Reagan said, ``Yes.'' He added that the United
States ``refused on principle'' to deal with Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yasser Arafat because he does not recognize
Israel's right to exist.
   ``What we are seeking is Palestinian leaders who will agree to
come together with the other Arab states,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
