<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WesternPresidential     04-21 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Presidential,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Western Lawmakers Urge Western Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight Democratic lawmakers representing
western states on Thursday released a letter urging their party's
presidential candiates to make western issues a basic part of their
campaign strategy.
   ``We believe that our region could be the key to winning the
White House this year,'' the congressmen said in letters intended
for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley of Washington, House Majority
Whip Tony Coehlo of California, and Assistant Senate Majority
Leader Alan Cranston, also of California, are among those
supporting the effort.
   ``In light of current polling data, as well as Democratic
statewide victories throughout the region, 1988 could be a
breakthrough presidential election year for the Democratic party in
the West,'' the letter said.
   ``The Republicans know this too, and are already talking about a
Western running mate,'' the congressmen said.
   Earlier this week, Republican chairmen from 18 western states
urged Vice President George Bush to select a westerner as his
running mate.
   Secretary of Interior Don Hodel, a native of Oregon, and
California Gov. George Deukmejian have been mentioned as possible
Republican vice presidential nominees.
   The Democrats' letter asked the party's candidates to meet with
western lawmakers in the next few weeks to discuss a western agenda
that includes such issues as Pacific Rim trade, energy policy,
natural resources, environmental protection and regional economic
development.
   The letter said there was ``no time to lose in formulating a
western strategy'' and that upcoming primaries could ``lay the
groundwork'' for a Democratic victory in the November general
election.
   The next western primary is Oregon on May 17, though several
states will have conventions to pick delegates before that date.
The nation's largest primary, California with 314 Democratic
delegates, is June 7. New Mexico's primary also is June 7.
   House and Senate members from Washington, Oregon, California,
Idaho, Arizona, Colorado, Montana, Hawaii and New Mexico signed the
letter.
