<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BudgetReport     04-21 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget Report,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Deficit Totaled $29.1 Billion in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government ran up a $29.1 billion
budget deficit in March, but the amount of red ink in the first six
months of the fiscal year was 3.5 percent less than the same period
last year, the Treasury Department said Thursday.
   The deficit last month topped a $23.9 billion shortfall in
February and a rare, $16.1 billion surplus in January, which
occurred because Social Security checks that month were mailed
early and were counted as part of December's spending.
   Analysts note that the budget imbalance is usually higher in
March than in other months because because people who owe taxes for
1987 generally wait until April to pay, while those due a refund
normally file early.
   For the first half of the 1988 fiscal year, the government has
run a deficit of $118.9 billion, 3.5 percent lower than the red ink
incurred for the same period a year ago.
   For the entire fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, the Reagan
administration is projecting a deficit of $146.7 billion, down 2.4
percent from the $150.4 billion deficit in 1987.
   However, others use less optimistic projections. The
Congressional Budget Office estimates the deficit will climb to
$157 billion.
   Last year, the deficit fell sharply because of an unexpected $28
billion windfall in tax payments made by people who sold off
long-term assets before the capital gains rates were increased
under the new tax law.
   Some analysts say there could be a second, smaller windfall this
year if people end up owing more in taxes for 1987 than they would
have under the old tax law. That, however, will not be known until
the government issues its budget report for April next month.
   In March, government revenue totaled $65.0 billion, while
spending totaled $94.1 billion. For the first half of the year,
revenues total $412.0 billion while spending amounted to $530.9
billion.
   As usual, the largest spending categories in March were the
military followed by Social Security, other programs in the
Department of Health and Human Services and interest on the
national debt.
   Military spending totaled $25.8 billion last month and $142.3
billion for the fiscal year so far, up 5.6 percent from the same
period a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled $18.4 billion last month
and $105.0 billion for the past six months, up 5.6 percent from the
same period in the 1987 fiscal year. Social Security is exempted
from budget limitations under the Gramm-Rudman law and is thus
generally showing faster spending increases than the other
categories.
   The other HHS programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, spent
$14.2 billion in March and $77.5 billion so far this budget year, a
5.9 percent increase over 1987.
   Interest on the $2.5 trillion national debt totaled $14.4
billion last month and $105.2 billion so far this fiscal year, an
increase of 9.6 percent over the same period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Animals-MedicalResearch     04-21 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Animals-Medical Research,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon, Actors Support Use Of Animals In Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart surgeon Michael DeBakey, along with
actors Helen Hayes and Tony Randall, spoke out on Thursday for
continued use of animals in medical research, arguing that animals
will play a major role in the search for a cure for AIDS and heart
disease.
   DeBakey, who was first to perform a successful coronary bypass
and the first to successfully use a partial artificial heart,
recalled that when he was in medical school more than 30 years ago,
``not a single cardiovascular disease could be treated
effectively.''
   ``Now, we have patients who are living reasonably normal lives
for 20 or 25 years after surgery,'' DeBakey said. ``The only means
by which we can do these things is in working in labs with
animals.''
   DeBakey and the others said they chose this week to state their
case to counter Laboratory Animal Liberation Week protests by
animal rights activists who oppose all use of animals in medical
research. Barring that, some are pushing for stricter controls on
the care and feeding of laboratory animals.
   Thomas E. Starzl, a transplant surgeon at the University of
Pittsburgh, said he, like the animal rights activists, abhors
cruelty to animals and said any incidents of poor treatment of
research animals are the exceptions rather than the rule.
   Randall began the news conference by saying he has worked with
the Myasthenia Gravis Foundation for about 20 years. Although great
strides have been made in treating the disease, a cure still has
not been found, he said.
   Both he and Hayes, who began raising funds for Jonas Salk's work
on a polio vaccine after her daughter died of polio, argued that
animals are necessary to medical research.
   ``If a cure is to be found for AIDS and heart disease, I see no
alternative,'' Hayes said.
   Janna Koch, whose 7-year-old daughter was born with a congenital
heart condition, said she ``was lucky. I didn't lose my daughter.
Through animal research, doctors were able to develop a pacemaker
for her.''
   Mrs. Koch, who is president of the Florida chapter of a group
called Incurably Ill for Animal Research, said medical research has
found cures for many diseases.
   ``We no longer have to live with diseases like polio,'' she
said. ``That's when animal research is taken for granted.''
</TEXT>
