<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mitchells-Wedtech     04-21 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mitchells-Wedtech,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitchell Appeal Goes To Full Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The full Supreme Court will consider a bail
request from two former state senators sentenced to prison for
their role in the Wedtech scandal.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall on Wednesday declined to act by
himself on a request by Michael and Clarence Mitchell for bail
pending their appeals.
   Toni House, a Supreme Court spokeswoman, said she did not know
if the justices would take up the motion at their regular session
Friday.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist had denied the bail request
Monday, so Clarence Mitchell had to report Tuesday to the
Lewisburg, Pa., federal prison to begin his 4{-year sentence.
   But lawyers for the brothers then submitted a new motion to
Marshall.
   Referring the question to the full court is a routine in such
cases. Having the full court decide prevents petitioners from going
from one justice to another seeking a favorable decision.
   The Mitchell brothers were convicted of fraud and obstruction of
justice for accepting $50,000 to block a congressional
investigation of Wedtech Corp., the now defunct New York City-based
defense contractor, which won multimillion-dollar contracts by
claiming it was substantially owned by minorities.
   The investigation was led by their uncle, then-Rep. Parren J.
Mitchell, D-Md., chairman of the House Small Business Committee. He
was never implicated in any wrongdoing.
   The brothers contend they have been denied bail because they are
black, while white defendants have been allowed to remain free.
They had appealed the bail issue from the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   Michael B. Mitchell, also a former state senator from Baltimore,
is to begin his sentence May 19, also at Lewisburg.
</TEXT>
