<HEAD>Attorney General's Wife Testifies to Grand Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ursula Meese, the wife of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, testified Thursday before a federal grand jury
investigating possible conflicts between her family's personal
finances and her husband's job.
   Mrs. Meese, who was accompanied by Nathan Lewin, the family's
attorney, did not respond to a reporter's questions, but Lewin said
she is cooperating with the panel.
   ``We are confident that everything will end up favorably to Mr.
Meese when the thing is concluded,'' Lewin said after Mrs. Meese
arrived at the U.S. Courthouse for her closed-door testimony.
   Independent counsel James McKay is supervising the grand jury,
which is looking into a broad range of issues involving Meese,
including his ties to attorney E. Robert Wallach. Wallach has been
indicted in the Wedtech Corp.in New York on charges of accepting
bring to use his influence with Meese.
   Meese appeared before the grand jury on Monday.
   McKay is known to be looking into Mrs. Meese's $40,000-a-year
job with the Multiple Sclerosis Society where she serves as a
development director for Operation Job Match, a program that finds
jobs for the handicapped.
   James Bierbower, the society's attorney, said McKay has
subpoenaed all of the group's records.
   Mrs. Meese's salary is underwritten by The Bender Foundation, a
tax-exempt philanthropy run by a Washington real estate family.
Mrs. Meese began her paid work for the society in January 1986.
   The Associated Press reported last week that a partnership
headed by Howard M. Bender, the foundation's vice president, owned
a building on which the government signed a $50 million lease for a
Justice Department office building in May 1987.
   Thirteen days after signing the lease, the Bender partnership
sold the building for a $22.6 million profit.
   Meese has denied any wrongdoing and said he didn't have anything
to do with the lease.
