<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     04-21 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Vows Revenge Against U.S. as Truce Halts `War of Cities'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Thursday buried 44 sailors killed
in battles with the U.S. Navy this week, and mourners declared that
the Persian Gulf would be ``Reagan's graveyard.''
   An informal truce appeared to have suspended a missile duel that
began Feb. 29 between Iran and Iraq and has killed hundreds of
civilians in the cities of both countries.
   Iraq got in the two last shots. Its official Iraqi News Agency
said two surface-to-surface missiles were launched at Qom, seat of
Iran's Moslem hierarchy, at 11.45 p.m. and they would be the last
if Iran did not retaliate.
   There were no reports of Iranian missiles being fired.
   Iran reported several civilians killed and others wounded at
Qom, 100 miles south of Tehran, but gave no figures. Iran and Iraq
have been at war since September 1980.
   Funeral processions were held at Bandar Abbas and Bandar
Bushehr, Iran's two major ports on the Persian Gulf.
   Hundreds of mourners were shown on Iranian television shouting
``Revenege! Revenge!'' as they buried sailors killed Monday in the
most serious engagement between Iran the Navy since President
Reagan ordered U.S. warships to the gulf to escort reflagged
Kuwaiti tankers in July.
   Young men waved banners reading: ``The Persian Gulf will be
Reagan's graveyard.''
   They shouted ``Death to America! Death to Reagan and Saddam!''
Iraq's president is Saddam Hussein.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Rear Adm.
Mohammed-Hussein Malekzadegan, Iran's navy commander, as saying the
sailors fought a ``heroic battle'' with the Americans. He claimed
U.S. forces fired on his men in the water after they abandoned
their stricken vessels.
   It said Malekzadegan spoke to journalists while inspecting the
frigate Sabalan, one of the ships damaged.
   No confirmed U.S. casualties were reported in Monday's
confrontation, but a Marine helicopter with a two-man crew is
missing. Iran claims to have shot it down.
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi said after a Cabinet meeting
Wednesday night: ``We will not forget the blood of the Iranians
shed by the U.S. mercenaries in the Persian Gulf. The U.S. should
know we will not tolerate the presence of the filthy Americans.''
   Monday's fighting began after the U.S. Navy destroyed two
offshore Iranian oil platforms. Reagan ordered the platforms
attacked as retaliation for a mine that blew a hole in a Navy
frigate last week and wounded 10 sailors.
   The Pentagon said an Iranian patrol boat was sunk, three armed
speedboats sunk or damaged and the frigates Sabalan and Sahand
disabled.
</TEXT>
