<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Lendl-Immigration 1stLd-Writethru a0710 04-21 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lendl-Immigration, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Immigration Bill for Ivan Lendl To Play in
Olympics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with subcommittee approval.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: Mazzoli said. DELETES 12th graf pvs,
Subcommittee approval, now redundant</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennis star Ivan Lendl on Thursday won a major
battle in his fight to play for the U.S. Olympic team this summer
when a skeptical House subcommittee voted to give the Czech native
immediate U.S. citizenship.
   The measure, which even proponents had given little chance of
passage earlier this year, was approved without opposition and sent
to the House Judiciary Committee.
   Subcommittee approval likely will lead to easy passage by the
full House, said Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., a member of the
panel and chief sponsor of the bill.
   But the legslation still would face serious obstacles in the
Senate, where Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the
Senate Judiciary immigration subcommittee, is wary of Olympic
exemptions.
   The subcommittee voted to speed up the citizenship of Lendl and
two lesser-known Olympic hopefuls by removing the five-year waiting
period permanent residents are required to go through.
   Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli, D-Ky., the panel's chairman who
regularly opposes Olympic bills, said he was ``sympathetic'' to
arguments that preventing Lendl from participating in the Olympics
would be a ``true hardship'' because an athlete's prime years are
limited.
   Mazzoli said, however, that he was concerned by the testimony of
U.S. Olympic Committee officials who said citizenship would not
automatically make Lendl eligible for the U.S. team.
   ``We're in kind of a Catch-22 in a way that we have to take
action without actual assurance that these people would compete
despite their world-class caliber,'' Mazzoli said.
   Mazzoli's consideration of the Lendl measure reflects a change
of attitude on Olympic citizenship bills.
   Last year, Mazzoli outlined a new rule of his Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration, refugees and international law that
viewed private immigration bills as an ``extraordinary remedy
available only to assist aliens with unusual problems and where
extreme hardship ... can be demonstrated.'' It noted that the panel
would be ``extremely reluctant'' to consider bills for Olympic
athletes.
   But Lendl supporters led by Morrison redoubled their efforts
this year when House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, pushed through a
special citizenship bill for a 21-year-old Canadian-born swimmer
living in Texas.
   Mazzoli said one of his concerns has been that the few athletes
who won citizenship from Congress in past years have been
unsuccessful in the international games.
   ``The one ski guy is still completing the course,'' Mazzoli said.
   But this year, for the first time, the subcommittee called in
U.S. Olympic Committee officials who vouched for the quality of
Lendl, along with Jens-Peter Burntd, an East German swimmer who
defected in 1985 and is living in Alabama, and Gagik Barseghian, an
Armenian wrestler who moved to California in 1986.
   The Olympics, which will be held Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in Seoul, will
include tennis as full sport for the first time since 1924. It was
a trial sport in 1984.
   Modified Olympic rules will allow professional tennis players
such as Lendl, the world's No. 1 ranked player, to compete.
   But Ronald T. Rowan, general counsel of the U.S. Olympic
Committee, said under International Tennis Federation rules, a
player first must represent his country in the Davis Cup before the
Olympics.
   Federation rules also say Lendl needs a special waiver to play
for the United States in the Davis Cup since he previously has
represented his native Czechoslovakia in those games. The next
Davis Cup is in July.
   ``They need the citizenship to argue on behalf of the waivers
and we create the citizenship without the knowledge that these
people will ever compete,'' Mazzoli said.
   Morrison rejected criticism that lawmakers are favoring athletes
such as Lendl, pointing to dozens of other special immigration
bills approved for non-athletes.
   ``We are put in the position of looking like we are taking care
of a few famous people, when what we're trying to do is balance one
arbitrary rule against another arbitrary rule,'' he said.
   Lendl, 28, moved to Connecticut in 1981 and received his
permanent resident status last year. Immigration law requires a
five-year waiting period before a permanent resident can become a
citizen.
</TEXT>
