<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrackHouses     04-21 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crack Houses,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Seeks to Raze Crack Houses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials frustrated with their inability to stop
drug dealing say they will prosecute the owners of 200 ``crack''
houses and hope eventually to demolish the buildings.
   Seven drug dens have been destroyed in suspicious fires this
year, the latest on Wednesday, fire department spokeswoman Cristy
Hickman said.
   ``People are taking the law into their own hands,'' said Pablo
Canton, Miami's assistant director of community development. ``Why
are they doing it? Because they don't see any solution in their own
neighborhoods.''
   Cases will be presented Friday to the Dade state attorney's
office involving two crack-house owners, who, Canton said, were the
easiest to prosecute. Under state law, the owner of an unsafe house
can be fined $500 a day until the problems is solved and serve a
60-day jail term.
   Vice Mayor Rosario Kennedy said Wednesday she also is trying to
pressure the county Unsafe Structures Board to be more diligent.
The county allows Miami to put 15 buildings at a time on the
demolition list _ while the city has hundreds it wants torn down.
   The city also said it will ask the county commission to allow it
to set up its own Unsafe Structures Board with the power to raze
buildings. The city says it eventually could recover the cost
through liens on the property.
