<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Panama-Marines     04-21 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Marines,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Reports Two Contacts With Intruders in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American troops guarding U.S. facilities in
Panama detected two groups of intruders his week and in one case
drew gunfire, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, said the
latest incidents occurred on Tuesday and Wednesday nights near
bases on the Pacific Ocean end of the Panama Canal.
   They followed two other incidents last week, in which one Marine
was killed accidentally and a group of Marines fired on what they
described as a group of 40 to 50 armed intruders.
   The incident Tuesday, the more serious of the two this week,
occurred around midnight near an ammunition storage depot next to
the U.S. Naval Station-Panama, Howard said. An Army sentry
stationed there spotted three men who had crossed ``inside the
perimeter of the site,'' he said.
   ``The guard's report indicated that the intruders wore berets
and carried small arms and bags. An intruder fired shots at the
(U.S.) guard. The guard returned the fire, remained at the sentry
post and requested assistance.
   ``The intruder then fired again. A Marine quick-reaction force
(of 12 men) was sent to reinforce and assist in the search of the
area. A security sweep of the area was completed during darkness
with negative results, but the investigation continues. There were
no casualties during the incident,'' Howard added.
   The second incident occurred around 8 p.m. Wednesday when three
U.S. sentries manning an observation post to the west of Howard Air
Force Base detected roughly 30 intruders approaching the base, the
spokesman said.
   ``The soldiers fired on the intruders, and they also fired two
Claymore mines as a diversion,'' he continued.
   Howard said those intruders then retreated, apparently without
firing any shots at the sentries.
   The spokesman disclosed the latest incidents in acknowledging
the Pentagon had been unable to establish conclusively that armed
intruders fired on Marines during one of last week's incidents.
   Military investigators spent several days combing the jungle
area where about 100 Marines fired at what they believed to be 40
to 50 armed intruders near a fuel tank facility.
   ``It's true that there were no expended cartridge casings
found,'' Howard said.
   Investigators did turn up, however, ``a couple of bottles of
insect repellent not used by U.S. forces; a used first-aid bandage;
a black-colored kerchief, and also the sweep there revealed several
well-established trails around the perimeter marked with slash
marks,'' he said.
   ``There is other evidence as well. There were also some sensors
set off in the area. But is it conclusive? I don't believe it is.
No final evaluation has been done on this at this point.''
   The Marines have been ridiculed by Panamanian military strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega, who accused them of firing at ``swaying
palm trees.''
   About 1,900 additional U.S. troops have been ordered to Panama
in the last several weeks to provide increased protection for
American bases and facilities near the Panama Canal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
