<2ND_LINE>AM-March Anniversary,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King's Widow Calls For Massive Turnout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Using the Lincoln Memorial as a backdrop, the
widow of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. on Thursday called for a
massive turnout for an Aug. 27 rally commemorating the 25th
anniversary of the March on Washington.
   It was at the memorial on that occasion, with a quarter of a
million people in attendance, that King delivered his ``I have a
dream'' speech.
   ``One score and five years ago upon this historic spot, a group
of leaders from a growing movement for jobs, freedom, peace for
Negro-Americans assembled,'' Coretta Scott King said. ``A lot has
happened since then and a lot has not happened since then.''
   She said the march this year is ``to help us rekindle the
passion of people for jobs, peace and freedom.''
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, said the anniversary march will call on
``drum majors for justice and friends of goodwill to regroup'' for
what he said was King's ``unfinished and unfulfilled dream that can
no longer be deferred.''
   The Aug. 27, 1963 march brought demonstrators from across the
nation to the Lincoln Memorial. King and nine other civil rights
leaders met with President John F. Kennedy in the White House.
</TEXT>
