<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Space-Canada     04-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space-Canada,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada To Build $1 Billion Crane System on U.S. Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada announced Thursday it will join the
United States in building a space station, a decision that was
hailed by the head of America's space agency as the beginning of a
new era in U.S.-Canadian cooperation.
   The $1.18 billion Canadian contribution _ about $1 billion in
U.S. dollars _ will be a Mobile Servicing System, in effect a
moving crane to unload visiting space shuttles or to move
satellites around.
   Canada thus joins the European Space Agency, which will spend $2
billion for a module to conduct micro-gravity experiments, as a
participant in the U.S. space station. The permanently manned
facility is expected to be in operation in Earth orbit in the
mid-1990s. Japan, the last partner, is said to be nearing agreement.
   Robert de Cotret, Canada's minister of science and technology,
called the space station ``the most significant international space
project of this century and the largest international technology
development project ever undertaken.''
   In response, James C. Fletcher, administrator of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, called Canada's decision
``the beginning of a new era of cooperation between our two
countries.''
   Fletcher said the Mobile Servicing System was a vital and
essential component for assembling and maintaining the station.
   ``Together we will build a permanently manned outpost in space
and together we will explore the enormous potential of space _
sharing the benfits for decades to come,'' Fletcher said.
   Canada designed and built the robot arm that is used on space
shuttles.
   NASA has said it will spend $16 billion to put up the space
station.
</TEXT>
