<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLOSlaying     04-21 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Slaying,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Won't Visit Damascus in Foreseeable Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat will not visit
Syria soon despite speculation the burial of his murdered deputy in
Damascus would signal a rapprochement with President Hafez Assad, a
PLO official said Thursday.
   George Habash, leader of the Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, said Arafat abandoned plans to attend
Khalil Wazir's funeral on Wednesday because there were no
guarantees of an official welcome or an audience with Assad.
   Wazir, 52, better known by his nom de guerre of Abu Jihad, was
gunned down by a commando unit that burst into his home in the
Tunisian capital of Tunis on Saturday.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and the Tunisians blamed
Israel for the slaying of Wazir, the PLO's coordinator for unrest
in Israeli-occupied territories. Miltary sources in Israel also
confirmed Israeli involvement.
   At the United Nations on Thursday, Israel boycotted a Security
Council meeting at which nations attacked it for Wazir's
assassination.
   Tunisian Foriegn Minister Mahmoud Mestiri asked the council to
condemn Israel for ``terrorist aggression'' against his nation in
Wazir's slaying.
   Wazir was buried Wednesday in the Yarmouk refugee camp outside
Damascus as hundreds of thousands mourned.
   His slaying and the key role he played in the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli occupation in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
spawned new efforts to end the 5-year-old rift between the PLO and
Syria.
   Long considered a pragmatic moderate within the PLO, Wazir was
widely respected even by Arafat's opponents in dissident
Palestinian factions.
   Arafat was expelled from Damascus in 1983 at the peak of a
Syrian-sponsored mutiny in PLO ranks, but the Syrian government had
said all PLO officials, including Arafat, were welcome to take part
in Wazir's funeral.
   Speaking in an interview at his headquarters in Damascus, Habash
said Arafat should have come for the funeral.
   ``If I were in his shoes, I wouldn't have missed this
opportunity,'' he said.
   The PLO dissidents have been based in Damascus, but the key
groups such as Habash's group and the Moscow-backed Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine reconciled with Arafat in
Algiers last year.
   Assad, Moscow's main Arab ally, has been under pressure from the
Soviets to reconcile with Arafat to forge a united Arab front for
an international Middle East peace conference it seeks to convene.
   Intensive contacts have been made in Damascus between Syrian
officials and PLO leaders since they arrived Tuesday for Wazir's
funeral.
   ``The Palestinian leadership agrees that the body of our great
struggler, Abu Jihad, should become a bridge for resuming relations
between the PLO and Syria,'' said Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of the
Democratic Front.
   PLO sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Syria
intends to reconcile with Arafat but that Syria's relations with
the United States appeared to be a stumbling block.
   The Syrians have been slowly mending fences with the United
States in recent months. Washington has been seeking Assad's
support for its latest Middle East peace initiative but refuses to
deal directly with the PLO until it recognizes Israel.
   Israeli sources said an Israeli commando team carried out the
killing of Wazir under the direct command of Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron,
military chief of staff, and took documents from Wazir's home in a
suburb of Tunis.
   They also told The Associated Press, speaking privately, that
the government approved the mission on two other recent occasions
but it was scrubbed both times for technical reasons.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Thursday said when asked about
the assassination: ``I suggest that we stop talking about this
because I don't want to continue discussing it. I don't think
anyone has anything to say about this.''
</TEXT>
