<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalBriefs     04-21 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What's In A Name?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tongue-twisting names that used to sound
strange to voters don't spell defeat at the ballot box any longer,
politicians say.
   Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., interviewed Wednesday night on PBS'
MacNeil Lehrer News Hour, was asked how Alabama voters would accept
Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis in November.
   Heflin said Dukakis' name, if the Massachusetts governor wins
the Democratic nomination for president, would not hurt him in
Alabama.
   Other candidates with ethnic names have fared well in the state,
Heflin said, mentioning John Katopodis, who has been elected to the
Jefferson County Commission in Birmingham.
   Katopodis said he was sorry he missed the television show.
   ``I was out cutting weeds, which is what every good ethnic
does,'' he said. ``I wasn't watching public television, that's for
certain.''
   Names don't carry the same weight as they did 30 or more years
ago, said Heflin.
   ``People in the South see the same television and get the same
print media,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``Names get to be
much more common.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Annapolis Mulling Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials reacted cautiously Thursday
to news that Maryland's capital city has been chosen to host a
presidential debate.
   Spokesman Thomas Roskelly told The (Annapolis) Capital that the
city received word from the Commission on Presidential Debates
confirming that Annapolis had been selected as a site.
   Roskelly said if the city accepts, the debate would be Sept. 14.
Three other cities, Pittsburgh, Winston-Salem, N.C., and Omaha,
Neb., have already agreed to host debates.
   However, Roskelly said, whether Annapolis can accept the offer
is still undetermined. ``We're excited, but we have to be
practical,'' he said.
   He said the city would have to promise the commission it could
meet 13 pages of conditions, including financial guarantees and
assurances that an adequate number of hotel rooms will be available.
   To meet the conditions, Roskelly said, the city will need
assistance from the state, Anne Arundel County and private
contributors.
