<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Koch-Cuomo     04-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch-Cuomo,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Advises Koch: Keep Mum on Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo scolded a crowd for booing
Mayor Edward I. Koch on Thursday, then, in an aside, gave his
former political rival some advice: ``Don't say anything about the
primary.''
   The incident came at a housing rally on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan two days after the state's Democratic presidential
primary, in which Koch raised the ire of many voters with his
outspoken attacks on Jesse Jackson.
   The result of Koch's remarks, Cuomo told reporters later, was to
give New York ``a black eye.'' He added that New York was
erroneously perceived as ``some hellhole of contention and
divisiveness.''
   Koch endorsed Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who finished a
poor third behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jackson.
Cuomo remained neutral.
   Cuomo was wrapping up his comments about extending the
Mitchell-Lama housing law when Koch arrived at the rally site.
``I'm with you, all the people up here are with you, the mayor of
the city of New York is with you,'' Cuomo said.
   At that, the crowd of 200 let loose as many boos as cheers, and
Cuomo briskly moved back to the microphone.
   ``Hey, wait, wait. Wait a minute. Wait,'' the governor called
over the crowd. ``Wait a minute. Wait a minute. You want to do me a
favor please?'' More boos erupted. ``You want to do me a favor?
Hold it!''
   Cuomo asked if the group wanted the housing program extended. It
cheered. He called Koch ``one of the strongest voices we have on
this Mitchell-Lama bill.'' He asked the crowd, ``How do you feel
about him in that issue?''
   The group cheered, albeit grudgingly. Koch stepped up and began,
``Governor _ how do you do this?''
   Cuomo, moving past Koch, muttered laughingly to the mayor:
``Don't say anything about the primary.''
   Koch chuckled. ``He's amazing,'' the mayor said. ``And he's a
good friend to have, when you need a friend.''
   Cuomo, asked as he left if he thought New York got ``a black
eye'' from the primary turmoil, said: ``Yes, I think we did get a
black eye. I think what happened is that Mayor Koch was perceived
as being critical of Jesse Jackson, and he attacked Jesse Jackson.
I wish he didn't.''
   Cuomo added: ``I think that there was no question that the
public impression was that this is some hellhole of contention and
divisiveness and everybody pushed everybody else. It is not true.''
</TEXT>
