<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HealthCare     04-21 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Care,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Universal Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis said ``today we make
history'' Thursday as he signed into law Massachusetts'
first-in-the-nation proposal to provide health insurance to all
residents by 1992.
   ``What we do here today can and must be done all over the United
States,'' the Democratic presidential front-runner told an
estimated 2,000 supporters crowded onto the Statehouse steps for
the signing ceremony.
   ``Today marks the day when working families, the unemployed, the
disabled, students and children with special needs don't go sick
because they can't afford to stay well. Those days in the
commonwealth are over,'' he said as the crowd applauded.
   ``From now on, when the sick land at the doorstep of our health
care system, the first question of them will be: `Where does it
hurt?' Not, `How will you pay?'''
   Only Hawaii, which has an exemption to federal law allowing it
to require employer health coverage, has anything comparable to the
Massachusetts law.
   However, the Massachusetts legislation, which Statehouse aides
say has generated inquiries from more than 20 states, goes beyond
Hawaii's approach by offering health security both to working and
non-working residents.
   In his speech, Dukakis didn't specifically mention whether he
would seek similar federal legislation if he became president, but
he did say: ``Today we make history. But there is more history to
be made.''
   ``As an American, I don't want my country to stand alone with
South Africa as the only two industrialized nations that do not
provide basic health security for their citizens.''
   The bill was the outcome of a nine-month legislative struggle
and comes two years after Massachusetts voters endorsed a
non-binding referendum by a 2-to-1 margin urging Congress to
``enact a national health care program ... universal in coverage.''
   The narrowly passed the legislature last week. ``The doubters
said a lot of things,'' Dukakis said. ``And they were wrong.''
   But doubters remain. Dr. David U. Himmelstein of Harvard Medical
School and spokesman for Physicians for a National Health Program
called the health care bill a first step but said it was ``a
Band-Aid approach when major surgery is needed.''
   And House Minority Leader Steven Pierce, a Republican, described
the bill as ``short-term gain and long-term pain. Mike Dukakis has
managed to pick up some short-term political gain at the expense of
long-term fiscal pain for the commonwealth.''
   On Wednesday, Dukakis estimated that the law's cost to taxpayers
would be $645.2 million through fiscal 1992, minus about $22.5
million in projected cost-cutting in Medicaid. Other estimates put
the cost to the state government in the next four years as high as
$1.2 billion.
   The thrust of the law is to provide coverage to about 600,000
Massachusetts residents under age 65 currently without health
insurance, roughly one of every 10 people in the commonwealth.
   This would be done in stages and through a variety of
approaches, from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults
and children to state-brokered, pooled insurance for small
businesses and individuals.
   By 1992, all employers with more than five full-time employees
must offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment
surcharge to help the state provide this coverage to the uninsured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Gulf     04-21 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Gulf,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adams Seeks Triggering Of War Powers Act In Persian Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., seeking to force a
Senate debate on the issue of ``war and peace'' in the Persian
Gulf, said Thursday he will introduce legislation to authorize the
continued presence of U.S. military forces in the gulf and set
rules for their use.
   Adams said he will also seek congressional action to trigger the
War Powers Act, which requires the removal of U.S. forces from
hostile areas within 60 days unless their continued presence is
specifically approved by Congress.
   ``In the last year we have deployed dozens of American ships in
the gulf,'' Adams said. ``We have spent tens of millions of
dollars. We have asked Americans to sacrifice their lives.
   ``But Congress has never authorized the deployment, never
appropriated any money, never clearly stated its support for the
policy that is being followed.''
   Adams said a number of individual senators have offered the
administration specific suggestions on changes or modifications in
U.S. Persian Gulf policy and some are being considered seriously.
   But he said that is not enough.
   ``The Senate as an institution has to give some guidance to the
administration,'' Adams said. ``... Congress has a right and a
responsibility to debate the policy being followed by the
administration as well as the right to consider alternatives.
   ``Only by engaging in a full and frank debate, only by working
with our colleagues and having the administration work with us, can
we refine our approach to the problem and strengthen our national
commitment to solve it,'' he said.
   The War Powers Act is a post-Vietnam attempt to apply a
congressional brake to unilateral presidential decisions to expose
U.S. forces to possible hostilities. It has been resisted by the
Reagan administration as an encroachment on the president's
authority as the nation's military commander in chief.
   Adams said he realizes an attempt to invoke it will be
challenged but said the act should be implemented because it
remains ``the law of the land.''
   ``I am not trying to force the withdrawal of American forces
from the Persian Gulf,'' Adams said. ``We have a right to be there
and a mission to perform there.''
   Adams said he is only seeking to protect the constitutional
right of the Congress to be involved in decisions to deploy U.S.
forces into areas of hostility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
