<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore 2ndLd-Writethru a0766 04-21 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0766,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore to Quit; Question Mark Remains on Delegates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 15th graf bgng ``Gore's withdrawal'' and final graf bgng
``He broke'' to CORRECT Super Tuesday wins to six sted five</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. gave up his 1988 White
House bid Thursday, offering the strong suggestion that he harbors
hopes of a future campaign and moving to protect the delegates he
has won so far.
   ``It hurts to have come so far and have fallen short,'' Gore
told a Senate office room crowded with supporters. ``But there will
be other days for me and for the causes that matter to us.''
   The Tennessee senator ended the race deeply in debt after waging
a long-shot campaign that challenged the traditional dominance of
Iowa and New Hampshire. It succeeded in the South, where he won
favor as a moderate, but fell flat elsewhere.
   Gore said he would technically remain a candidate to permit his
delegates to attend the Democratic National Convention.
   In suspending his campaign, he delivered some of the most
eloquent lines of his campaign, praising each of his opponents,
excoriating Republican George Bush, and pledging support for the
eventual nominee.
   ``I want no part of a stop Jackson or a stop Dukakis movement,''
Gore said. ``The only man I want to stop is George Bush.
   ``I will not be the Democratic nominee for president in 1988,''
Gore said. ``The nominee is going to be Michael Dukakis or Jesse
Jackson. I'm going to do everything I can to help them do what I
set out to do, and that is to put a Democrat in the White House.''
   Gore exited with a joke after a failed campaign that he said
lasted 10 months and a million miles.
   ``I was doing great until I turned 40,'' he said.
   Gore amassed 423 Democratic National Convention delegates during
his campaign, according to The Associated Press count. His decision
to suspend his campaign rather than quit the race means the two
remaining active candidates cannot pick up delegates he has already
won, but who have not yet been chosen.
   Under party rules, Jackson would have gained 34 of Gore's
delegates immediately, while Dukakis would have gotten 29. Illinois
Sen. Paul Simon's decision to suspend his campaign denied Jackson
another 47 delegates he would have inherited in this manner.
   Gore said he spoke with both Dukakis and Jackson and that both
were ``comfortable'' with his decision to hold onto the delegates.
He said the move would protect Democratic leaders who backed him in
states where delegates had not yet been chosen, naming Georgia as
an example.
   He said he planned no endorsement and repeated his oft-stated
contention that he has ``no interest'' in the vice presidential
nomination, though he left that door open.
   ``I'm not trying in any way to broker a convention that is not
going to be brokered anyway,'' he said.
   Gore's withdrawal was assured by his dismal third place showing
in New York, a 10 percent finish that capped six weeks of
frustration for Gore since his six-state victories on Super Tuesday
in the South. New York had become his last chance to get back into
contention.
   Gore is saddled with a debt of more than $1.5 million, run up in
borrowing for his campaign in Super Tuesday states and after that
in an effort to break through outside the South. His debt is the
largest of the 1988 presidential candidates who have departed the
race, although as a senator he is in a position to raise money to
retire the debt.
   He spent the night before his announcement in Texas, raising
money to repay the debt.
   Facing little support in Iowa and an appeal not in sync with
that state's left-of-center Democratic activists, Gore challenged
the assumption that candidates must do well in Iowa's caucuses. He
bypassed the state and blasted its process as a distortion, and
concentrated on the South.
   But Gore's campaign was marked by internal disorganization and
division, and a tendency to postpone decisions. Gore often made the
decisions himself from the road.
   One result was that Gore spent nearly the maximum amount
allowable in New Hampshire _ over $400,000 _ but did it late and
without an accompanying commitment of time and campaign staff to
campaign full force. The result was he was neither fully in nor
fully out there, and finished fifth in a seven-way race.
   He broke through with wins in six states in the South. But then
he went through the succession of Northern states, beginning with
Illinois and Michigan, largely an unknown figure and unable to make
any progress.
</TEXT>
