<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Danson-Oceans     04-21 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Danson-Oceans,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ted Danson Announces Formation Of Anti-Pollution Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Ted Danson, the bartender in the
television series ``Cheers,'' came to Capitol Hill on Thursday to
announce formation of a new environmental coalition he said is
aimed at stopping ocean pollution.
   Danson told a news conference that as president of American
Oceans Campaign, ``I am going to dedicate my resources and my
ability as an actor to focus attention on the plight of our
oceans.''
   He said the organization, based in Santa Monica, Calif., would
be pushing for enactment of legislation to set a national policy
for protection of the oceans, with emphasis on:
   _Reducing and then ending the dumping of toxics and sewage into
coastal waters.
   _Establishing national ocean parks to protect environmentally
sensitive and economically important shorelines.
   _Deferring offshore oil and gas development until there is a
national energy policy that emphasizes conservation and alternative
energy sources.
   The group's multipurpose goals were questioned by Carl Schmid, a
spokesman for National Ocean Industries, a trade group representing
companies involved in offshore oil and gas activities.
   ``I think it's important the American people realize this is a
facade to stop offshore oil development,'' said Schmid. He said
that some of American Oceans Campaign's directors, including
Danson's wife, Casey, are active in groups fighting drilling off
the California coast.
   ``They are using the other people, other groups and congressmen
to stop offshore oil,'' Schmid said. ``I would question how much
effort they're going to devote to sewage sludge, toxics and
plastics pollution.''
   Danson was not available to respond to Schmid's statement,
issued several hours after the news conference. Calls to American
Oceans Campaign offices in Santa Monica and Takoma Park, Md., were
answered by recording devices.
   Danson said that his interest in ocean ecology was stirred 18
months ago when he took his two daughters to a Santa Monica beach
and a saw a sign saying ``no swimming, water polluted.''
   ``We have always taken for granted that we can dump anything we
want into the oceans _ all of our wastes, all of our toxics _ and
assumed that it would always be absorbed,'' he said.
   ``That is no longer true,'' Danson said. ``Dead fish are washing
up on the beaches of the East Coast and beaches are being closed on
the West Coast.''
   Joining Danson at the news conference were Sens. Lowell Weicker,
R-Conn., Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Bob Graham, D-Fla., and Reps.
Leon Panetta, D-Calif., Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., Bill Lowery,
R-Calif., Jim Saxton, R-N.J., and Claudine Schneider, R-R.I.
   Among other entertainers listed as supporters of the
organization are Jeff Bridges, Danny De Vito, Ed Asner, Sally
Field, James Garner, Leonard Nimoy, Kirstie Alley and Ally Sheedy.
</TEXT>
