<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhoseUpbringing?     04-21 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whose Upbringing?,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman, Education Secretary Trade Remarks Over Family
Backgrounds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Child Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The normal pleasantries of a congressional
hearing were disrupted Thursday by a charged exchange between a
congressman and a Cabinet secretary over their family backgrounds.
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., opened a hearing on his major child
care bill by describing his own traditional upbringing. He said his
father worked at a Buick plant and his mother stayed home to take
care of her several children.
   Suggesting to Education Secretary William Bennett that their
backgrounds were similar, he commented, ``We must recognize that
very often there is no father in the family. ... We have to
recognize that changing family structure whether we like it or
not.''
   Several minutes later, when he got his turn to talk, Bennett
bluntly and unexpectedly took issue with Kildee's assumption that
they came from similar families.
   ``I did not grow up in Ozzie and Harriet's home or in a Father
Knows Best home. It might have been nice to,'' Bennett said,
creating a sudden hush in the packed hearing room.
   The education secretary said he came from a typical inner-city
broken family. ``My father left home when I was quite young,'' he
said. He and his brother were raised by his mother, Bennett said,
with the aid of informal child care arrangements.
   ``She held two jobs, my mother, and put in whatever time she
could'' with her children, Bennett said. ``She did this without
much benefit from the state or federal goverment, although she
could have used some help.''
   Moments later, Kildee started to describe the need for child
care in Flint, Mich., which he said has a 20 percent unemployment
rate. ``I have to walk through the real world,'' he said. ``I'm
invited to country clubs, but I don't go there often...''
   ``I do not belong to a country club, any country club,'' Bennett
broke in defensively. ``And Brooklyn (where he grew up) is every
bit as much the real world as Flint.''
   ``Let's not be confrontational. We're talking about children,''
Kildee replied, his voice rising in surprise.
   Bennett persisted. ``Some people believe all Republicans were
born rich...''
   ``I know Tom Tauke so I know that's not true,'' Kildee
interjected quickly, referring to the young Iowa congressman
sitting next to him. The room filled with laughter and the tension
broke.
   But Rep. Bill Armey, R-Texas, had the last word. He said he was
one of eight children of parents who both worked inside and outside
the home. In view of where he, Kildee and Bennett have ended up,
Armey said, the evidence is clear: ``No matter how you raise a
child, he can still go wrong.''
</TEXT>
