<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CigaretteSuit     04-21 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cigarette Suit,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Jury To Decide Conspiracy Claim In Cancer-Liability Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evidence in a closely watched cigarette
liability case is sufficient for a jury to consider whether three
cigarette manufacturers conspired to cover up the dangers of
smoking, and the trial should continue, a judge said Thursday.
   ``The evidence presented ... permits the jury to find a tobacco
industry conspiracy, vast in its scope, devious in its purpose and
devastating in its results,'' said U.S. District Judge H. Lee
Sarokin.
   At the same time, Sarokin dismissed a claim that the three
companies sued in the liability case _ Liggett Group Inc., Philip
Morris Inc. and Lorillard Inc. _ caused Rose Cipollone's lung
cancer by not marketing a safer cigarette.
   The judge's comments came in a 33-page opinion requested by the
cigarette makers, who asked for dismissal of the case and an end to
the trial that began Feb. 1.
   The companies are being sued by Mrs. Cipollone's husband,
Antonio Cipollone of Lakehurst, whose wife died at age 58 in 1984
after smoking for 40 years. Attorneys for Cipollone completed their
case two weeks ago, alleging that Mrs. Cipollone was a victim of a
campaign by the cigarette makers to undermine warnings about the
dangers of smoking.
   In the opinion that was quite pointed at times, Sarokin said the
jury should be allowed to consider the conspiracy and punitive
claims in the case.
   Sarokin said evidence indicated the companies conspired to
conceal and misrepresent information on the dangers of smoking and
to ``refute, undermine and neutralize information coming from the
scientific and medical community.''
   He said the evidence also indicated the companies tried to
``confuse and mislead the consuming public in an effort to
encourage existing smokers to continue and new persons to commence
smoking.''
   ``The jury may reasonably conclude that defendants were members
of and engaged in that conspiracy with full knowledge and disregard
for the illness and death it would cause, and that Mrs. Cipollone
was merely one of its victims,'' the judge said.
   As for punitive damages, Sarokin said: ``If the jury accepts the
plaintiff's version of the facts as to the conduct of the
defendants, it is difficult to envision a more compelling case for
an award of punitive damages.''
   Cipollone's attorneys said they were pleased with the opinion.
   ``The judge says we have a case for the jury,'' attorney Cynthia
A. Walters said.
   ``If a case should be won, this is it,'' she said, adding that
her side introduced as evidence secret internal cigarette company
documents never before made public. They included memorandums that
spoke of a public relations ``war'' against health-related charges
involving cigarettes.
   Chuck Wall, a spokesman for Philip Morris and Lorillard, took
exception to the tone of Sarokin's opinion.
   ``I do think there were flourishes there from the judge's pen
that went beyond the plaintiff's evidence,'' he said.
   Wall also said he believed the heart of Cipollone's case was
gutted by Sarokin's opinion. ``The conspiracy claim is very tenous
at best,'' he said.
   Sarokin dismissed a claim that the companies were liable for
Mrs. Cipollone's death on the basis they knew how to design a safer
cigarette but failed to. The judge said Cipollone's attorneys could
not prove Mrs. Cipollone would have smoked the safer cigaratte had
it been marketed.
   Ms. Walters said the dismissal of that claim, which the defense
contended was the heart of the case, was not a critical blow.
   ``We thought it was an important theme, not so much for this
case but for the broader implications in future cases,'' she said.
   Sarokin also dismissed a claim that the companies failed to do
enough research on the dangers of smoking. While there was ample
evidence that the research was inadequate, the judge said,
Cipollone's attorneys did not prove that this directly harmed Mrs.
Cipollone.
   Another claim, that the companies failed to warn smokers of the
dangers of cigarettes, was also dismissed against Philip Morris and
Lorillard, but the judge said the jury will be able to consider
that allegation in the case of Liggett.
   Sarokin said Mrs. Cipollone began smoking cigarettes made by
Philip Morris and Lorillard after 1966, when the federal government
began requiring warnings on cigarette packs.
   However, she smoked cigarettes made by Liggett prior to 1966 and
there is evidence ``from which the jury could infer that, prior to
1966, ordinary consumers were not adequately informed of the health
risks of smoking,'' he said.
   James Kearney, an attorney for Liggett, said the company was
``confident we will prevail on the basis of evidence that comes out
during our presentation.''
</TEXT>
