<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Health, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0787,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans To Have Checkups In Hospital Friday</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs grafs 9-10 pvs bgng: The spokeswoman ... with 6 grafs to
UPDATE with information on exams; picks up 11th graf pvs bgng: The
last ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will travel to Bethesda Naval
Hospital on Friday for a ``routine dental checkup,'' while his wife
Nancy has her first X-ray examination following breast cancer
surgery, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater disclosed Thursday.
   ``The president and Mrs. Reagan, en route to Camp David, will
stop briefly at the Naval Hospital at Bethesda for routine
radiological procedures,'' the spokesman said in a statement.
   Reagan ``will undergo a routine series of dental X-rays in the
dental clinic, while Mrs. Reagan will have her first post-operative
mammogram,'' the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater said the tests ``represent routine checkups, and are
not associated with any current physical findings or problems.''
   Mrs. Reagan had her left breast removed on Oct. 17, 1987, after
doctors discovered a quarter-inch cancerous lesion.
   Elaine Crispen, the first lady's press secretary, said the first
couple expected to be at the medical center in suburban Washington
for about an hour.
   ``It's Mrs. Reagan's six-month checkup, and the president
planned to use the time to get his dental X-rays taken, rather than
usually doing it at the White House,'' the spokeswoman said.
   Mrs. Crispen said the couple wanted to have the results of Mrs.
Reagan's exam before they left ``so they could send her off for a
comfortable, worry-free weekend.''
   The spokeswoman said White House physician Dr. John Hutton
planned to be present for Mrs. Reagan's exam. The mammogram is to
be conducted by a radiologist, Dr. Claudia Galbo, Mrs. Crispen said.
   Fitzwater said he expected to have some type of report on the
exams by late Friday afternoon.
   He added that the president will undergo ``no other
examination.''
   The spokesman said Reagan usually has a cleaning and checkup
every three months at the White House, but that the president
planned to have a ``panoramic'' X-ray done this time in order to
get a full-view picture of his mouth.
   Fitzwater explained that the White House has X-ray machines that
take pictures of part of the mouth, but does not have the larger
machine that pans the entire mouth area.
   The spokesman identified Reagan's dentist as Navy Cmdr. Dr.
James Judkins. He said the president has not had any complaint
about his teeth.
   The last time Reagan visited the hospital was in January, when
he underwent his annual checkup for colon cancer.
   It is the first time Reagan has gone to Bethesda for dental work.
   Reagan, who traveled to Springfield, Mass., on Thursday to
deliver a speech on U.S.-Soviet relations, appeared in good spirits
upon his return to the White House in the late afternoon. He
smiled, waved, and gave journalists a ``thumbs-up'' signal, but
refused to answer questions.
   Reagan went to Bethesda Naval Hospital Jan. 15 for a four-hour
examination to check against the recurrence of colon cancer.
   He has had regular checkups every January and June since he
underwent successful colon cancer surgery in July 1985.
   The January test showed no renewal of cancer and no growths. He
was proclaimed by Hutton at the time to be ``in excellent health.''
   Except for the last checkup in January, doctors have discovered
and removed small, fleshy growths known as polyps from Reaan's
colon. In each instance, the growths turned out to be benign.
   Reagan turned 77 in February and is the oldest man to be
president.
</TEXT>
