<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KidnappedBaby     04-21 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnapped Baby,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Baby Found Two Counties Away By Godfather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLBROOK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before Douglas Gerwitz was 24 hours old,
he had been taken from his mother, found 170 miles away by a police
officer who happened to be his godfather, and sent back to his
parents.
   Albert Cecil Duane Lewis, 25, and Judy K. Lewis, 32, were being
held by authorities in Holbrook, where the infant was found in the
back seat of a car, said Prescott Police Capt. Bob Reed.
   `It's a heck of a coincidence,'' said officer Douglas Newton
after he found his godson and namesake.
   The 4-hour-old son of Lisa and John Gerwitz, of the Payson area,
had been taken from Prescott's Yavapai Regional Medical Center
about 7 p.m. Wednesday. Police said a a woman masquerading as a
hospital laboratory worker told the mother she was taking the baby
for some tests.
   Hospital officials realized the child had disappeared about 45
minutes later when Mrs. Gerwitz asked a nurse when her son was
going to be returned to her, Prescott Police Sgt. Bill Clayton said.
   Just after midnight, Judy Lewis entered the Holbrook Police
Department and asked for traveler's aid, such as gas money and a
place to stay, Sgt. Stewart Bracke said.
   Newton was helping Ms. Lewis, who said she was alone, when he
discovered she actually was traveling with a man and a baby, Bracke
said.
   Police found the three matched the description of a man and
woman seen in the hospital, and the missing baby. They were able to
confirm the baby's identity three hours later.
   After little Douglas was examined at Holbrook Community Hospital
and pronounced in good health, authorities drove him back to
Prescott.
   He was reunited Thursday afternoon with his parents at the
hospital. Mrs. Gerwitz appeared briefly with the baby in her arms
to thank law enforcement officers, hospital personnel and others
who assisted in getting her son back.
   Newton knew the kidnapped baby's parents from high school,
Bracke said.
   Hospital administrator Michael Vitek said Lewis apparently
pulled off her masquerade as a laboratory technician by dressing in
a lab coat she probably picked up in the hospital's obstetrics area.
   ``Lab coats are in the nurses' lounge, and on hall trees in the
OB department. Hospital policy is that when our OB nurses go to a
different part of the hospital, they put on the lab coats to
minimize infections,'' Vitek said.
   Vitek also said hospital officials will review the ``entire
package of hospital policies relating to security of infants.''
   ``We expect to have some feedback from the investigators from
the Prescott police,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
