<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     04-21 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Threaten Development Projects; Farmers Demand Land Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels threatened Thursday
to attack any development projects funded by the U.S. and Canadian
governments on the impoverished island of Negros.
   In another development Thursday, about 10,000 militant farmers
marched through Manila to demand land reform.
   The National Democratic Front branch on Negros said U.S.- and
Canadian-financed projects there were being used as ``tools to
oppose the revolutionary movement.''
   The Front is the communist rebel umbrella organization.
   It said the projects were among targets singled out by the
rebels as they prepare to step up attacks on Negros, 300 miles
southeast of Manila. Other targets include military units,
multinational corporations and individuals considered ``enemies of
the people.''
   The threat came in a statement signed by rebel Roman Catholic
priest Frank Fernandez and sent to news media in Bacolod, Negros.
   Fernandez heads the Negros chapter of the Front.
   Hours later, suspected communist rebels shot and killed a
policeman and a militiaman in an ambush near a cemetery in Bacolod,
police said.
   The statement did not specify any single project and did not say
if the attacks will include assassinations of U.S. and Canadian aid
personnel.
   U.S. and Canadian aid officials were not in their Manila offices
Thursday and could not be reached for comment. It could not be
ascertained if any American or Canadian personnel were stationed on
Negros island.
   The U.S. Embassy said earlier it had stepped up security and
told its staff to take extra precautions after communist rebels
killed three Americans and a Filipino in attacks last October
outside U.S. Clark Air Base north of Manila.
   Another Front statement circulated during daylong marches and a
rally in Manila by the leftist Philippine Peasant Movement urged
farmers to join the 19-year-old insurgency. It said the rebels had
redistributed land to farmers in areas they control and that
``revolutionary land reform and armed struggle are the only ways to
free the farmers.''
   Several legislators, including President Corazon Aquino's
brother-in-law, Sen. Agapito Aquino, and priests and nuns joined
the protesters. They urged the farmers at a rally to pressure
Congress to pass a meaningful land reform law.
   Thursday's marches and rally were peaceful, and the protesters
dispersed at sundown without incident. But Jaime Tadeo, leader of
the protest, denounced the military for blocking thousands of
farmers as they approached Manila in motorcades early Thursday from
seven outlying provinces.
   The Most Rev. Teodoro Bacani, Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop of
Manila, said the church backed the farmers' demand for immediate
land reform and said there was a need to ``wake up ...
(legislators') consciences if they are asleep.''
   Last July, Mrs. Aquino decreed a nationwide land redistribution
program but left most details up to Congress.
   The Senate and the House approved separate land reform bills
last month but still have to reconcile differences in the two
drafts, which peasant groups say favor landlords.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
