<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     04-21 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>5,000 Workers Said to Protest Wages in Southeast Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 factory workers in southeast
Poland rallied Thursday, chanting ``Solidarity, Solidarity!'' and
demanding pay raises to offset recent price increases, an
opposition spokeswoman said.
   Activist Ewa Kubema said the rally took place in front of
management headquarters of the sprawling Stalowa Wola heavy
machinery plant, 95 miles southeast of Warsaw. It employs 18,000
people.
   Wieslaw Wojtas, chairman of the factory chapter of the outlawed
Solidarity trade union movement, read a speech listing workers'
demands, including across-the-board pay raises of $50 a month, she
said.
   The average wage in Poland is about $90 a month.
   She said another demand was an end to harassment of union
activists. The union threatened a strike at an undefined date if
its demands are not met, she said.
   The union had called for the demonstration in leaflets
distributed over the past two weeks, said Ms. Kubema.
   It began at 2 p.m., the end of the first shift, with a whistle
from the factory's locomotive repair shop, she said. At that time,
there were about 10,000 workers at the plant.
   After Wojtas' speech, she said, workers chanted ``Solidarity,
Solidarity!'' and sang the national anthem, holding up their hands
in V-for-victory signs.
   She said there were no arrests at the rally, but lawyer
Wladyslaw Liwak, secretary of the Solidarity committee at the
factory, was detained at his home.
   Solidarity was banned after the 1981 martial law crackdown in
Poland, but local units continued to function clandestinely at many
factories.
   In a shift of union strategy last year, new units were organized
publicly, and dozens of them have unsuccessfully gone to court
seeking legal registration under a 1982 labor law.
   Government price increases of 40 percent took effect this year,
part of the government's program of economic reform. At the same
time, workers in socialized enterprises received an automatic $15
monthly pay raise.
   Authorities expressed concern that factory managers, under
worker pressure, will be too generous about awarding additional
wage increases. They warned managers they could lose their jobs
unless wage increases are merited by higher productivity.
</TEXT>
