<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseSpending     04-21 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Cuts Star Wars Spending, Approves MX, Midgetman
Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee voted Thursday to cut
spending for President Reagan's ``Star Wars'' program, but also
generally granted administration requests for the Midgetman and MX
missiles, congressional sources said.
   The votes by the Armed Services subcommittee on strategic
weapons and nuclear deterrence came behind closed doors as the
panel began working on a bill authorizing the Pentagon budget for
the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   The panel voted to approve $4.6 billion for the Strategic
Defense Initiative, as Reagan's Star Wars plan is formally known,
according to the sources, who spoke on condition they not be
identified.
   Reagan had sought $4.8 billion for Star Wars, which is
authorized for $3.9 billion in the current fiscal year.
   The panel also voted to generally approve Reagan's request of
about $200 million for research into the single-warhead Midgetman
and $800 million for research into basing the 10-warhead MX weapon
aboard trains on western military reservations, the sources said.
   The subcommittee decisions, if they are eventually affirmed by
the entire Armed Services Committee and then the full Senate, will
set up another fight with the House.
   Although both chambers are controlled by Democrats, Reagan's
defense budget requests have generally fared better in the more
conservative Senate and Thursday's votes continued that trend.
   The defense bills which separately pass each chamber will
eventually go to a House-Senate conference committee to iron out
differences.
   The House will next week begin considering a defense budget bill
which authorizes $4 billion for Star Wars, $600 million less than
the Senate subcommittee voted Thursday.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, says he expects the full House to approve the $4 billion
figure after a fight by liberals who want to reduce it more and
conservatives who want to raise it.
   The House measure also raises spending on the Midgetman from
Reagan's request of $200 to about $500 million, while reducing the
MX request from $800 million to $500 million.
   The Midgetman is the single-warhead missile which is backed by
congressional Democrats but opposed by the Pentagon. Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci said he wanted to eliminate the Midgetman
program, but agreed to include $200 million at the request of
Congress to keep the program alive until Reagan's successor can
make a decision about the fate of the program.
</TEXT>
