<1ST_LINE>r i AM-USOBombing     04-21 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USO Bombing,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warrant Issued For Woman In USO Club Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian authorities issued an arrest
warrant Thursday for the leader of a Japanese terrorist group
linked to the car bombing that killed an American servicewoman and
four Italians outside a USO club.
   Meanwhile, investigators said a man arrested with explosives in
New Jersey spent time in Italy in the weeks prior to the April 14
bombing.
   The arrest warrant accuses Fusako Shigenobu, a 42-year-old
Japanese woman, of massacre, attack on the security of the state
and the transport and detention of explosive materials.
   Japanese officials say Shigenobu is the leader of the Japanese
Red Army, a terrorist group with ties to pro-Iranian terror groups
in Lebanon.
   Naples investigators say she acted as an accomplice in the April
14 attack, when a car filled with explosives blew up outside the
USO club in downtown Naples.
   The investigators allege that another Japanese Red Army
terrorist, Junzo Okudaira, was the man who parked the car in front
of the club. A warrant for his arrest was issued the day after the
attack.
   The chief investigator, Romano Argenio, told reporters Thursday
that several witnesses had spotted Okudaira and Shigenobu in Naples
in the days before the bombing.
   Argenio said three other men were believed involved in the
attack.
   Police in Milan said Thursday that Yu Kikumara, a Japanese man
whose car was found with explosives when he was stopped on a New
Jersey turnpike last week, spent a few days in a Milan hotel in
late February.
   FBI experts traveled to Naples trying to determine whether he
was linked to the terrorists who bombed the USO club.
   The blast killed four Italians and Angela S. Santos, a U.S. Navy
radioman 3rd class from Ocala, Fla.
</TEXT>
