<HEAD>Hijackers Wanted To Hide Hostages In Beirut, Report Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hijackers of a Kuwaiti airliner originally
planned to land in Lebanon, blow up the plane and keep the
passengers hostage in Beirut, a PLO mediator in the hijacking was
quoted as saying Thursday.
   Malaz Abdo, deputy director of the Palestine Liberation
Organization office in Cyprus, said the plan failed because Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad refused to let the plane land in the
Lebanese capital, according to by Rome's Paese Sera newspaper.
   Syria is the main power-broker in Lebanon, which has been torn
by 12 years of civil war.
   Abdo acted as a mediator in negotiations with the hijackers when
the Kuwait Airways jet landed in Larnaca, Cyprus. Paese Sera
released excerpts of an interview to be published Friday.
   The jumbo jet was hijacked April 5 between Bangkok, Thailand,
and Kuwait and landed in Iran, Cyprus and finally in Algeria, where
the 31 remaining passengers were freed on Wednesday. The hijackers
killed two hostages during the ordeal.
   According to Abdo's account given by the Communist-aligned
daily, the terrorists wanted to land the plane in Beirut, unload
the passengers, hold them in hideouts in the city and blow up the
aircraft.
   But Assad, whose troops control the area, spoke by telephone
with the emir of Kuwait, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, and agreed
to prevent the plane from landing in Beirut, the report said. No
other details were given.
   The plane went to Larnaca after first being forced to land in
Iran. The hijackers had demanded the release of 17 prisoners in
Kuwait.
</TEXT>
