<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FCCDial-a-Porn     04-21 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC Dial-a-Porn,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Fines Two Dial-A-Porn Companies $1.2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmits a0842 to CORRECT cycle designation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two California dial-a-porn operators were
fined $600,000 each by the FCC on Thursday for transmitting obscene
material across state lines and for not restricting access to their
messages to children and non-consenting adults.
   ``Some so-called dial-a-porn providers are blatantly
disregarding the law which required that access by minors be
restricted pursuant to commission regulation,'' FCC Chairman Dennis
R. Patrick said in announcing the fines. ``We intend to enforce
this law.''
   The companies, Audio Enterprises Inc. of Mill Valley and
Intercambio Inc. of San Jose, were fined for interstate
transmission of obscene material and failure to restrict such
transmissions from minors and non-consenting adults. The maximum
fine is $50,000 for each day of violation.
   ``The ultimate in sleeze deserves the ultimate ... penalty,''
FCC Commissioner James H. Quello said. ``They need to know we mean
business.''
   Gerald Brock, chief of the FCC common carrier bureau, said the
$600,000 fines were based on the amount of money the companies made
during the commission's monitoring process.
   In an 11-month period, AT&T received $5.5 million from calls
made to one Audio Enterprises Inc. line, Patrick said. Of that
amount, Audio Enterprises received $650,000, he said. Intercambio
Inc. received $297,000 from its operation.
   The decision was the result of an FCC investigation triggered by
complaints alleging that unimpeded access to the sexually explicit
messages resulted in the molestation of one 10-year-old girl and so
disturbed a 16-year-old boy that he had to enter weekly psychiatric
theraphy.
   The companies have 30 days to pay or seek reduction of the fines.
   Current FCC regulations direct the dial-a-porn companies to
restrict their messages through access codes, message scrambling or
use of credit card numbers.
   Upon being notified last December of the complaints, both
companies said they did not have the capacity to provide access
screening and denied that the messages were obscene. Intercambio
also argued that it had not violated the regulation because it
never intended to transmit to minors or on an interstate basis.
   In a statement, AT&T said its policy was ``to terminate service
at the FCC's direction for any customer found in violation of laws
concerning minor access to pornographic messages.''
</TEXT>
