<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Taxes 1stLd-Writethru a0821 04-21 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0821,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Taxes Down This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: His biggest, to CORRECT figure to
$31,264</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush and his wife
Barbara paid $86,684 in 1987 income taxes on a total income of
$308,396, according to a tax return released by his office on
Thursday.
   That compares to the $115,486 that the Bushes reported paying
for 1986 on total income of $348,594.
   Bush's tax bill amounted to 28 percent of his total income in
1987, down from the 33 percent he paid in 1986, showing that he, as
President Reagan and many other Americans, benefited from the
sweeping tax-law changes that took effect for 1987 taxes.
   Bush's income included his $112,633 salary as vice president and
$2,048 in additional reimbursment from the government.
   His biggest chunk of outside income came from the blind trust he
and his wife set up when he took office, totaling $169,600 _
including $26,075 in capital gains, $31,264 in interest and
dividends and $112,261 in supplemental income.
   Precisely where this money came from was not detailed, under
terms of the blind trust agreement. Aides have said previously that
the trust is valued at about $1 million.
   Bush also reported $20,773 in ``passive income'' from his
interest in a liquefied natural gas barge.
   Bush's salary was up from the $97,900 he received in 1986,
reflecting a general raise in federal salaries.
   The main reason his total income was lower was because he had a
much lower level of capital gains _ income from sales of assets,
property or stock.
   In 1986, Bush reported total capital gains of $430,165,
apparently reflecting a decision by the trustees of his blind trust
to sell off assets before the new tax law changes took effect and
increased the tax on such gains.
   Bush has made returning to a lower rate of taxation on capital
gains a prime campaign theme, saying the decision to tax capital
gains at the same rate as other earnings stifles business
investment. Bush has proposed a capital gains tax of 15 percent.
   The Bushes claimed total deductions for 1987 of $53,314,
including $12,225 in contributions to 35 charities. The
contributions included $1,000 gifts to the Yale Alumni Fund and the
United Negro College Fund.
   Bush had made $89,588 in tax payments, including $32,588
withheld from his salary _ suggesting a refund of $2,904. However,
the vice president elected to have the money held and applied to
his 1988 taxes.
   Bush also reported $1,575 in royalties in 1987 on his book,
``Looking Forward,'' published by Doubleday last September.
   The vice president claimed $3,574 in deductions for business
meals and entertainment and $6,880 in miscellaneous business
deductions.
   Bush has released his tax returns annually.
   In January, he also released 14 years of previous returns in a
challenge to then-rival Sen. Bob Dole to do the same. Those returns
showed that 1986 was his biggest income year, and that over the
14-year period he paid taxes ranging from 3 percent to 41 percent
of his annual income.
   Bush's interest income included $66 from the White House credit
union.
   President Reagan released his tax return earlier this month. It
showed that he and his wife Nancy paid $86,638 in taxes on total
income of $345,359 _ down from their $92,460 tax bill on 1986 total
income of $336,640.
   The Internal Revenue Service estimates that by next year, when
the tax-law changes are fully in place, about three-quarters of all
Americans will have smaller tax bills than they had in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
