<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     04-21 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Courts Blue-Collar Support In Northwest Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson launched a fresh attack Thursday
on Attorney General Edwin Meese III, played down talk of his own
potential as a vice presidential candidate and courted blue-collar
workers in a campaign visit here.
   Campaigning in advance of Tuesday's Pennsylvania primary, the
Democratic presidential contender cited the longstanding legal
controversy surrounding Meese.
   ``I want a Justice Department that stands for justice ... an
attorney general that goes back and forth to court as a prosecutor
for the people and not as a defender for himself,'' he said in a
speech.
   At a news conference afterward, Jackon declined to comment on
his chances of being named the vice presidential nominee.
   Some of Jackson's top associates, including campaign chairman
Willie Brown and campaign manager Gerald Austin, have been raising
the possibility of Jackson as a running mate for Michael Dukakis _
if Dukakis emerged victorious in the struggle for the nomination.
   Jackson he said he intends to do nothing to damage the party's
chances of winning the presidency in November.
   ``I seek to be a healer in this process, and a builder,'' he
said.
   The candidate delivered the message of ``economic justice'' that
has been a mainstay of his campaign.
   ``Profits are up, wages are down, factories are closing, and
workers are abandoned,'' he told a crowd of about 4,000 people who
huddled together and shivered in a downtown park as a cold wind
blew off nearby Lake Erie.
   ``Let's rebuild America and put the workers back to work
...Don't let the voices of the status quo break your spirit,'' he
said.
   In other campaign contests, Jackson has been boosted by a
coalition of economically struggling workers, farmers and students,
and he was going after that mix here.
   ``I think that jobs for blue-collar workers is a very important
issue at this time,'' said Barbara Seidler, 54, of Erie, a
registered Republican.
   ``I believe he is for the people,'' said Charles Booth, 53, an
Erie machine shop manager. ``He knows what the people really need.''
   Jackson said he supports changes in the National Labor Relations
Board to make the agency a mediation service and not ``a
strike-breaking board.''
   Jackson also brushed aside his defeat at Dukakis' hands in the
New York primary on Tuesday. ``I always run against great odds,''
he said, adding that his campaign in Pennsylvania was ``very much
alive.''
   From Erie, Jackson headed for Philadelphia, where he toured a
drug-infested area.
</TEXT>
