<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KoreanAirliner 1stLd-Writethru a0782 04-21 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korean Airliner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Argues That KAL Crew Were Negligent In Making Doomed Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs first 2 grafs to clarify who lawyer represents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of the Korean Air Lines plane shot
down by Soviet fighters in 1983 negligently made the flight knowing
the navigation system was not working, a lawyer for the victims'
relatives argued Thursday.
   Donald Madole, lead counsel for a committee that represents the
relatives of those killed in the Sept. 1, 1983 crash of Flight 007,
said there was abundant evidence to show that the crew chose to
continue the flight even though it determined in Alaska that the
navigation system was not properly set before takeoff from
Anchorage.
   A total of 269 passengers and crew died when the flight, which
originated in New York City, was shot down over the Sea of Japan
after straying off course into Soviet air space.
   The plane ``ended up 320 miles off course'' because the inertial
navigation system (INS) had been improperly set during a fueling
stop in Anchorage, Madole said.
   ``From the moment that airplane took off it was never, never on
course,'' he told U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr.
   ``The crew deliberately attempted to conceal their failure to
either properly stabilize the INS or set it up properly,'' Madole
said.
   The pilot and crew knew the journey without navigation guides
would lead the plane into a dangerous area where it could be shot
down without warning if it strayed into Soviet airspace, Madole
said.
   ``Obviously the crew knew the danger and chanced it anyway,'' he
said.
   But KAL attorney George Tompkins said these allegations were
based on ``opinion, surmise, conjecture'' rather than evidence.
   ``There is no need for a trial in this case,'' Tompkins told
Robinson, who has presided over five years of litigation arising
from the crash.
   Madole said the plaintiffs should be given a chance to press
their claim of punitive damages at a trial.
   Even before the flight had left the coast of Alaska for the long
journey across open seas, the crew had violated a number of
aviation regulations, Madole said.
   The plane should have flown directly over the radio beacon at
Bethel, Alaska to check its position when the crew determined it
was 15 miles off course, Madole said. But the crew members ignored
their duty and didn't fly the plane over the radio beacon because
they knew the navigational system was not functioning.
   Once the plane passed over the coast, ``there is no white
highway line across the Pacific,'' Madole said.
   The pilot, Capt. Chun Byung-in, wanted to avoid returning to
Anchorage to reset the nevigation system because such an emergency
landing would force him to dump 100,000 pounds of jet fuel. Chun
knew this costly and time-consuming detour would anger airline
officials and passengers, Madole said.
   He cited the deposition testimony of former KAL pilot Park Yong
Man who said he and Chun had spoken the night before the ill-fated
flight about four other incidents that year in which KAL crews had
made emergency landings to reset navigation systems.
   Chun had told Park ``if it happened to him he would go on'' to
avoid losing face with his superiors and friends, Madole said. ``It
would be a terrible disgrace in Korea if they have to come back.''
   Authorities have not been able to determine exactly how the
plane ended up 320 miles off course because the cockpit and flight
data recorders were never recovered. But aviation experts theorize
that incorrect data was punched into the computerized navigation
system before the plane took off from Anchorage.
   If the judge dismisses the case, the airline would only be
liable for $75,000 per passenger under international aviation
conventions. But the plaintiffs are seeking to collect far greater
amounts by holding the airline liable for punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0224 </DOCNO>
