<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Dumps Snow over Southwest; Rain Hits Northern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A spring storm dumped snow on parts of Arizona, Utah and Wyoming
on Thursday, and more snow was forecast from the mountains of
southern California to Wyoming.
   Rain, changing to snow in the mountains, reached from the
Pacific Northwest across the northern Rockies into the northern
Plains.
   Flagstaff, Ariz. received 8 inches of snow, with four inches
falling in one hour.
   Heavy snow also hit mountains in southern Utah, with 14 inches
recorded at Brian Head Ski Resort by Thursday morning and 8 inches
at Long Valley Junction. In northern Montana, 2 inches of snow were
recorded in parts of the Big Horn Mountains, and an advisory for
more snow extending into Friday was posted for the Big Horn
Mountains and the Laramie Valley.
   A winter storm warning was posted Thursday for the higher
elevations of the San Diego County Mountains of southern
California, with up to 10 inches expected, and for the mountains of
central and northern Arizona. Heavy rain was forecast for lower
elevations.
   Elsewhere, there was also scattered snow in northern Maine, and
thunderstorms developed over southeast Iowa and west central
Illinois.
   The nation's morning low was 18 degrees at Williston, N.D.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 32 degrees at Brookings,
S.D., Custer, S.D., Rapid City, S.D. and Great Falls, Mont., to 90
at Sanderson, Texas.
   Rain was forecast Friday for much of the country, including
northern Maine, the Ohio, Tennessee and central Mississippi
Valleys, with the possibility of thunderstorms in Arkansas and the
Tennessee Valley. Rain also was forecast for southern Michigan and
Wisconsin and stretching from Montana and South Dakota to Colorado
and Kansas. Farther west, rain was predicted for the eastern Great
Basin, the Northern Plateau and the Pacific Northwest.
   Strong and gusty winds were forecast for the central Plains and
the central Mississippi Valley.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 40s and 50s across the northern
part of the country from the Pacific Northwest to the upper
Mississippi Valley to New England and New Jersey; in the 80s from
Florida to South Carolina, the Tennessee Valley and lower
Mississippi Valley, and Oklahoma and northern Texas, and in the 90s
over southern Texas. Elsewhere, highs are predicted mostly in the
60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
