<2ND_LINE>AM-Tiger Cage Intruder,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coach Bails Out Man Who Threatened to Loose Tiger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who threatened to loose a
500-pound Bengal tiger on the Louisiana State University campus
unless given a job ``snapped'' and deserves compassion, the
school's basketball coach said Thursday.
   Coach Dale Brown signed a $10,000 bail bond to free from jail
Moacyr ``Gato'' Cezar, who locked himself in the outer cage of the
LSU mascot for more than four hours Wednesday. Cezar, 48, was
charged with criminal mischief and robbery.
   Brown last summer had befriended Cezar, who worked in LSU's
basketball dorm and had demanded to speak to the coach during the
standoff.
   ``What happened to Gato could have happened to any of us,''
Brown said after Cezar was freed from jail and taken to a hospital
for psychiatric evaluation. ``His personal problems were
overwhelming and he snapped.''
   School officials won't make any decisions about Cezar's future
until the charge is settled, said university spokesman Jim Crain.
The man filled out a job application during Wednesday's standoff,
but officials made no guarantees.
   Cezar, a former star Brazilian basketball player, was befriended
by Brown when the coach visited Sao Paolo last summer.
   He was a teacher in Brazil and came to this country on a
temporary visa. He supervised the LSU basketball dormitory while
taking courses to improve his English.
   Cezar, a father of two, needed money to send to his family and
wanted a work permit because his visa was expiring, Brown said.
   ``He is a frustrated, proud man who was just looking for a job,
who didn't want charity,'' said Brown.
   Cezar seized the cage keys from a student trainer Wednesday,
threatening the man with what turned out to be a toy gun, officials
said. He entered only the barred outer cage that surrounds the main
cage containing the tiger.
   An LSU basketball player Jose Vargas, a native of the Dominican
Republic, talked Cezar out of the cage.
   At one point during the standoff, some of the hundreds of
students who came to watch chanted: ``Tiger bait! Tiger bait!'' _
the cry raised at LSU sporting events when opposing teams enter.
   ``To those of you who shouted `Tiger bait,' what can I say?''
Brown said. ``May you never experience sadness and loneliness and
may you find a love that you couldn't give last night.''
</TEXT>
