<HEAD>Baby, Reported Kidnapped, Found Dead; Parents Questioned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with mother charged with murder;
PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `A $5,000 ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-month-old baby found dead in a trash can
Thursday was drowned by his mother the day she told police two men
had snatched him from his stroller on a Brooklyn street, police
said.
   Lucrezia Gentile, 36, was charged with murder in the death of
her son, Stephen, said police spokesman Sgt. Maurice Howard. She
was awaiting arraignment Thursday night.
   The infant's body was discovered not far from the family home
after a day of questioning in which the mother was given a
polygraph test and told detectives where to find the baby, said
Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo.
   ``We believe that Lucrezia Gentile drowned her 2-month-old son
Stephen in the bathtub of their residence at approximately 9:30
a.m. yesterday,'' Colangelo said.
   Mrs. Gentile then ``dressed the baby, placed him in a white
plastic bag, put him in his stroller, walked several blocks ... and
placed the baby in a green trash can,'' he said.
   Mrs. Gentile, whose husband, John Gentile, 32, is a part-time
employee of the U.S. Marshal's office, had told police the baby was
taken from his stroller Wednesday by two men in a sedan who had
stopped her to ask directions.
   She said the abduction occurred as she was on her way to the
grammar school attended by her 7-year-old son. About an hour
earlier, Mrs. Gentile had said, a woman had called to say the son
was ill at the school.
   Sgt. Peter Sweeney, a police spokesman, had said shortly before
the baby was found that no ranson demand had been made and police
had no leads on who took the baby or why.
   A $5,000 reward was posted earlier Thursday by Thomas McDonald,
a retired firefighter and longtime resident of the Gentiles'
neighborhood.
   ``I want the return of the baby, that's the important thing,''
McDonald had said. ``I just hope they don't compound kidnapping
with murder.''
   ``I feel violated and so do my neighbors,'' said McDonald. ``You
should see the parents today, holding onto their children,
hollering at their children. The parents are scared.''
   Gentile has worked as a guard for the U.S. marshal's office for
about a year, said Chief Deputy Marshal Mike Pizzi. Gentile had
retired with a disability from the Conrail police force in 1984.
