<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JunkBondsSubpoena     04-21 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Junk Bonds Subpoena,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head Of Drexel's `Junk Bond' Business Subpoenaed In Congressional
Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Drexel Burnham Lambert's ``junk
bond'' business, who is under scrutiny in the Wall Street insider
trading scandals, was subpoenaed by a congressional panel Thursday
to testify next week, sources said.
   Michael R. Milken, the Beverly Hills, Calif.-based architect of
the nation's $100 billion ``junk bond'' market of debt securities
that frequently are used to finance hostile takeover attempts, is
scheduled to testify April 27 before the House Energy and Commerce
Committee's subcommittee on oversight and investigations, said the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The chief executive officer of the investment banking firm,
Frederick Joseph, is scheduled to testify next Thursday, but a
subpoena was not considered necessary in his case, one source said.
   ``Milken did not want to appear,'' the source said, adding that
the subcommittee, led by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., then decided
to issue a subpoena for him.
   Kevin Madigan, the attorney at Drexel's Beverly Hills office who
sources said received the subpoena for Milken, was not in his
office Thursday afternoon and queries were directed to Steve
Anreder, the firm's spokesman in New York.
   Asked about the subpoena, Anreder said, ``We can't confirm it,
but we anticipate hearing next week.''
   The subcommittee has been investigating Drexel for the last six
months, looking into its operations, its high-yield junk-bond
department in Beverly Hills, the corporate finance department, the
mergers and acquisitions department and the executive committee, a
source said.
   A notice to subcommittee members from Michael Barrett, the
panel's chief counsel and staff director, said that next
Wednesday's hearing would be held to receive testimony from Milken
``relating to the subcommittee's investigation into the operations
of the nation's securities markets and the effectiveness of the
federal securities laws.''
   Drexel and Milken have been under a cloud since the government's
disclosure that Wall Street's onetime top takeover speculator, Ivan
F. Boesky, admitted involvement in insider trading and aided the
government's investigation of others allegedly involved in such
illegal activity. Boesky paid the Securities and Exchange
Commission a record $100 million following his downfall in 1986.
   Both the SEC and the U.S. attorney's office have been conducting
investigations of Drexel.
   Neither Drexel nor Milken has been charged with a crime and both
repeatedly have asserted their innocence.
   Milken, whose annual earnings have been estimated from between
$40 million to $80 million, is responsible for one of Drexel's most
profitable and innovative operations.
</TEXT>
