<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Manigat     04-21 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Manigat,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manigat Defends Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat said
Thursday that Haiti still is gripped by a ``climate of fear'' and
building democracy will be difficult.
   ``No change can be made without resistance. Change does not take
place in one day,'' Manigat said during his first news conference
since taking office Feb. 7.
   Manigat also said that a government investigation into the
violence that forced the cancellation of the Nov. 19 presidential
election is going slowly. The investigaton had not reached any
conclusions about who was behind the rampage that left 34 people
dead, he said.
   ``We are simply lacking witnesses who have the courage to
testify,'' Manigat said. ``The climate of fear from the time of the
Duvaliers still exists.''
   Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier took power in 1957 and ruled
until 1971, when his son Jean-Claude took control. The younger
Duvalier fled to exile in France on Feb. 7, 1986, in the face of
widespread opposition.
   Manigat was elected Jan. 17 in a government-run election
boycotted by the main opposition parties.
   The Nov. 19 balloting was called off after gunmen shot into
lines of voters at polling stations and other assailants hacked
people to death.
   Witnesses said soldiers took part in the shooting, and main
opposition candidates said the military organized the bloodshed to
ruin the election, the first free balloting in three decades.
   Manigat tacitly anknowledged critics' complaints that the army
still runs Haiti.
   ``This government has had an unquestionable desire to change
things, but we can't break big interests and bad habits
overnight,'' he said.
   But Manigat he contended that his government is an improvement.
   ``We in the government are men of dialogue. Nobody will make us
fall into the trap of the Duvaliers, pushing us to repressive
tactics to stay in power,'' he said.
   He repeated his intention ``to put the army at the service of
development.''
   Manigat had no comment on the U.S. indictment in Miami last
month of army Col. Jean-Claude Paul on drug trafficking charges.
Paul is commander of the powerful Dessalines battalion of 700
soldiers quartered next to the National Palace.
</TEXT>
