<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-FilmPrize     04-21 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Film Prize,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmaker Honored for Anti-Stalin Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A filmmaker from Josef Stalin's home republic of
Georgia has been awarded the Lenin Prize for a triology of movies
portraying Stalin's terror, Tass said Thursday.
   Tengiz Abuladze was honored with the top cultural prize for the
films ``Molba,'' ``Drevo Zhelaniya,'' and the 1984 film that
stunned Soviets with its portrayal of the Stalin period,
``Pokayaniye.''
   Censors withheld ``Pokayaniye'' for two years. When it was
released in late 1986, it shocked millions of Soviet viewers and
became one of the first major signs of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
effort to loosen some restrictions on cultural expression.
   Georgy Markov, chairman of the government committee awarding the
prizes in literature, art and architecture, told Tass the three
films helped Soviet society deal with the legacy of Stalin's
decades in power.
   Millions of Soviets were shot, imprisoned or exiled in the
dictator's purges.
   The honor accorded Abuladze was another indication of official
intent to continue exposing the excesses of Stalin's rule.
   An evaluation of Stalin's place in Soviet history remains a
topic of debate in the official press. This year officials
exonerated Stalin rival Nikolai I. Bukharin and more than 20 others
shot after a show trial in 1938.
</TEXT>
