<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras-Demonstration     04-21 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Demonstration,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Break Up Anti-Government Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot troops hurled tear gas
grenades and fired in the air Thursday night to break up a group of
demonstrators headed for the U.S. Embassy.
   The protesters had been part of a crowd of 1,500 to 2,000 people
who marched peacefully to the National Congress earlier Thursday to
demonstrate against the Honduran government and U.S. policy in this
Central American country.
   Two weeks ago protesters attacked the U.S. Embassy compound,
burning and sacking the U.S. Consulate. Five people were killed in
that riot, which was fueled by indignation over the deportation of
an alleged drug trafficker to the United States.
   Thursday night, about 200 people shouting ``Embassy, Embassy''
broke off from a larger group of protesters and headed for the U.S.
diplomatic mission on the eastern outskirts of this capital.
   About 50 soldiers and police threw tear-gas grenades, dispersing
the protesters.
   The demonstrators regrouped, cutting off a small contingent of
what appeared to be young and ill-trained troops, who fired long
bursts of fire from their M-16s into the air. The sound of shots
sparked panic in the neighborhood.
   Some demonstrators taunted and threw stones at the troopers, who
at intervals would advance behind metal shields.
   At least one person was seen arrested. There were no immediate
reports of injuries.
   During the milelong march earlier Thursday, protesters chanted
slogans calling for the expulsion of the approximately 1,100 U.S.
troops based in Honduras, the removal of U.S.-backed Nicaraguan
rebels from Honduras and the defense of the Honduran Constitution.
   They condemned the government of President Jose Azcona and what
they called his subservience to Washington.
   ``Yankee garbage, out of Honduras,'' and ``If the Yankees don't
get out, in Honduras they will die,'' shouted the demonstrators.
Both chants rhyme in Spanish.
   The marchers, most of them students, walked to the National
Congress, where they listened to speeches condemning Azcona and the
United States.
   About 500 demonstrators proceeded from there to the nearby
Central Penitentiary, where they shouted for the release of inmates
they consider political prisoners.
   A group then tried to go to the U.S. Embassy.
   One of the issues the marchers protested was the forced
extradition of suspected drug trafficker Juan Ramon Matta. Honduran
police, working with U.S. agents, arrested Matta at his Tegucigalpa
home on April 5 had him flown to the United States.
   The Honduran Constitution prohibits the extradition of Honduran
citizens.
   Matta is in federal prison in Marion, Ill..
   The U.S. Embassy estimates damage to the consulate building in
the April 7 riot at between $4 million and $6 million and has asked
for reimbursement from the government.
</TEXT>
