<DOCNO> AP880421-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NewCaledonia     04-21 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Gendarmes Killed in New Caledonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least three French police officers
were killed Friday in the South Pacific territory of New Caledonia,
apparently by Melanesian separatists, the Australian Broadcasting
Corp. said.
   The station, reporting from Noumea, the capital, quoted
government radio as saying the gendarmes were shot on the outer
island of Ouvea, 90 miles away.
   It said a town hall was set alight earlier Friday in the
French-ruled territory and a small bomb exploded in Noumea. There
were no immediate reports of casualties in the earlier attacks.
   The territory's indigenous Melanesians have vowed to boycott
Sunday's regional elections which coincide with the French
presidential election. Many of the Melanesians, known as Kanaks,
are seeking independence for New Caledonia.
   Australian Broadcasting Corp. said a group of about 20 Kanaks
armed with guns and machetes were involved in the killings.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attacks.
   More than 20 people have died in five years of riots, slayings
and clashes involving predominantly French settlers and Kanaks,
whose ancestors first arrived 4,000 years ago.
   New Caledonia, France's largest possession in the South Pacific,
is about 1,000 east of Australia.
   A Melanesian separatist leader, Jean-Marie Tjibaou, told a news
conference in Sydney last month his group planned a
``confrontation'' before the elections.
   But he said ``outright war'' was not possible because of the
French military presence on the island nation of 145,000. Kanaks
make up 43 percent of the population in the nickel-rich territory.
   Tjibaou heads the Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front.
   Other major ethnic groups in New Caledonia are Wallisians,
Tahitians and Indonesians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 2326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0750,0799</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Prints Interview with Ousted Party Official</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 3rd, ``The respected...'' with second
report of Ligachev ouster; picks up 4th pvs: Unconfirmed reports...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fired Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N. Yeltsin
has defended the outspoken criticism of the slow pace of reform
that cost him his job, telling the official press that he did what
he thought was right.
   In another published report, Yegor K. Ligachev, the Kremlin No.
2 man considered a conservative counterforce to Yeltsin in Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's leadership, was reported to be in trouble with the
Soviet leader.
   The respected Madrid newspaper El Pais reported Thursday that
Ligachev had been removed from his duties as the party's chief
arbiter on ideological issues and head of party workers at an April
16 meeting.
   The New York Times reported Friday that the Politburo voted to
reduce Ligachev's powers and ordered him to take a two-month
vacation. It said Ligachev was forced to give up his role as a
supervisor of Soviet press and television.
   The paper said that Viktor M. Chebrikov, head of the KGB, had
defended Ligachev during the Politburo meeting, which it said took
place Tuesday.
   Unconfirmed reports circulating in Moscow said Ligachev recently
had been given a reprimand by Gorbachev, but it was unclear when or
why.
   The interview with Yeltsin, along with a large picture of him
and his grandson, was published in the first German-language
edition of the newspaper Moscow News, which appeared Thursday in
Moscow. The article was not in the weekly Russian language edition
that came out Wednesday.
   ``I spoke in a straightforward manner and said what I felt and
thought was correct,'' Yeltsin said in the interview, his first in
the official press since his firing. ``Someone said correctly: each
must think independently so that later not all suddenly see the
light at once.''
   He declined to say what he told the Communist Party Central
Committee at an Oct. 21 meeting that led to his firing three weeks
later. Yeltsin was hospitalized with heart trouble in November, and
since has been reassigned as a first deputy minister of
construction.
   Even though Moscow News is intended primarily for foreigners,
the appearance of an interview with Yeltsin was unusual and could
be a signal that he has recovered some prestige following his
denunciation by Gorbachev in mid-November for putting ``personal
ambitions above the interests of the party.''
   Yeltsin, 57, was considered to be among the staunchest
supporters of Gorbachev's efforts to reform the Soviet economy and
allow more openness. In his speech to the Central Committee, he
criticized the slow pace of reform and the party's style of
leadership.
   Some unconfirmed reports have said he attacked Ligachev
personally.
   Yeltsin was replaced as Moscow party chief by Lev N. Zaikov. In
February, Yeltsin was stripped of his position as a candidate, or
non-voting, member of the ruling Politburo.
   Yeltsin's firing was taken by some Moscow intellectuals as an
indication of the limits of Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or
greater openness. Gorbachev acknowledged that in a speech to
writers and artists in January, but denied that it signaled a
slowing of his reform efforts.
   Yeltsin was brought to Moscow by Gorbachev from the Ural
Mountain industrial city of Sverdlovsk to replace Viktor Grishin,
reported to be Gorbachev's main rival for the Communist Party
leadership in 1985.
   Moscow News said 102,000 copies of the first German-language
edition were printed in West Germany and sold at kiosks.
   It said editors in Moscow provide all the material for the
paper, which is composed, printed and distributed in West Germany.
It is printed in a larger format than the editions printed in five
other languages.
   In its story on Ligachev, El Pais cited unidentified informed
Soviet sources as saying the Politburo turned over his duties to
Gorbachev ally Alexander Yakovlev, secretary of the party's Central
Committee and the party's chief director of propaganda, press and
cultural matters.
   The paper's Moscow correspondent described the action as a
``failure of the political operation against Gorbachev'' by
conservative party figures who attracted attention following the
publication of a newspaper article defending Stalinist policies.
   Ligachev was said to have endorsed the article and guided
through its publication in the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya. The
Communist Party newspaper Pravda published a strongly worded
condemnaton of the critical article April 5.
   Ligachev has indicated in speeches on ideology during the past
year that he favors a less permissive attitude toward openness in
publishing than Gorbachev.
   Conservative writers have cited Ligachev's speeches in attacking
the increasingly critical articles that are appearing in Soviet
newspapers, including Moscow News.
</TEXT>
