<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JoggerGuilty     04-21 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jogger Guilty,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Jury Finds Man Guilty In Death Of Girlfriend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who led the search for his
girlfriend after she disappeared while they jogged in a park was
convicted of voluntary manslaughter Wednesday in her slaying.
   Bradley Page, 27, could receive up to 11 years in prison at
sentencing June 1 in the 1984 slaying of 21-year-old Roberta
``Bibi'' Lee, who was found bludgeoned to death and buried n a
shallow grave in Redwood Regional Park.
   Page remained free on his own recognizance.
   He was acquitted two years ago of murdering Lee but was ordered
retried after the jury deadlocked 8-4 in favor of a manslaughter
conviction.
   The trial centered on a statement Page gave police in which he
said he had bashed Lee's head repeatedly with a rock after a
lover's quarrel and dragged her body into the woods, then made love
to the corpse before scooping dirt and leaves over it with a hubcap.
   Page took the stand to renounce his confession as the ramblings
of a young man exhausted by hours of grueling questioning. He had
told officers he thought he had two personalities, one of which
could have committed the crime and blocked it out.
   According to testimony, the couple and a friend had gone jogging
in the park. The friend became separated from Lee and Page, but
waited for them at a park gate. Page arrived alone and said Lee had
gone down a different path.
   He said he had looked for her unsuccessfully for about 15
minutes.
   When one of Lee's roommates called Page the next day to say Lee
had not returned, he reported her disappearance to police and
during the next five weeks distributed flyers with Lee's picture
and description to news agencies.
   A month later, her half-nude body was found buried in a thicket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
