<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolicemanKilled     04-21 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Policeman Killed,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shot Policeman Dies After Ambulance Bypasses Closest Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty policeman died in surgery of a
gunshot wound Wednesday after the ambulance bypassed the nearest
hospital, which was waiting for him, authorities said.
   Officer Paul Dunbar Jr., 31, was found with a gunshot wound in
his chest in front of a home, said police spokeswoman Allene Ray.
No arrests were made.
   City officials were reviewing telephone and radio contact
between Emergency Medical Service dispatchers and the ambulance
crew that picked up Dunbar to determine why he was not taken to
Henry Ford Hospital a mile away.
   Ford Hospital initially was notified of the shooting and was
prepared to treat Dunbar, but he never arrived, hospital spokesman
Brian Cheatham said.
   Dunbar ended up at Detroit Receiving Hospital, three miles away,
where he died in surgery at 4 a.m., said a secretary in the
hospital's public relations office who declined to give her name.
   Cheatham declined to speculate whether the delay might have cost
the officer his life. ``That's a tough call,'' he said.
   Richard Dolley, assistant chief of the city-owned EMS, referred
questions to Robert Berg, a spokesman for Mayor Coleman A. Young.
Berg did not immediately return telephone calls Thursday.
</TEXT>
