<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait thanked Algeria for negotiating a
peaceful end to the hijacking of one of its jetliners, but critics
led by the United States said the hijackers should not have been
allowed to go free.
   Kuwait's official news agency KUNA said the nine Shiite Moslem
hijackers _ who had killed two Kuwaiti hostages _ were promised
safe passage to Tehran, Iran or Beirut, Lebanon. It said the gunmen
departed from Algiers shortly after freeing the 31 remaining
hostages in the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 before dawn Wednesday.
   Throughout the ordeal, which began April 5, the hijackers
demanded that the Persian Gulf sheikdom free 17 pro-Iranian
extremists imprisoned for the 1983 bombings of the U.S. and French
embassies there.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III says he may
appoint an acting deputy while the search continues for someone to
fill the No. 2 slot in his embattled Justice Department after two
people have rejected the post.
   The position is being vacated Friday by Deputy Attorney General
Arnold Burns, who resigned in protest March 29 out of concern that
the nearly year-long criminal investigation of Meese was hurting
department operations.
   Meese's latest choice, former American Bar Association president
John Shepherd, said Wednesday he was concerned with the ``personal
and financial sacrifices'' required of him and his family for the
brief appointment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government statistics may be signaling the
beginning of the end of a mid-1980s trend that saw booming growth
in coastal states outstrip the rest of the country, economists say.
   Residents of densely populated coastal states like Connecticut,
New Jersey, Massachussets and California continued to have the
highest average incomes in the nation last year, the Commerce
Department said Wednesday.
   States like Mississippi, West Virginia, Utah and Louisiana that
are dependent on farming, mining or oil were at or near the bottom.
But, Rudolph E. DePass, an analyst with the Commerce Department,
says the figures show growth is accelerating in the Southwest and
Rocky Mountain regions and slowing elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is likely to join the House in
approving major changes in the nation's welfare system, despite the
near certainty that a presidential veto lies at the end of the long
road to congressional consensus.
   The 25-year drive to overhaul welfare took a significant step
forward Wednesday when the Senate Finance Committee voted 17-3 to
send a comprehensive reform measure to the floor.
   The five-year, $2.8 billion ``Family Security Act'' reflects a
hard-won bipartisan consensus that welfare parents should work to
support their children, that the goverment should help make this
possible and that government aid should be a last resort.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PUNTA DE TRALCA, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A volunteer program backed by the
local Roman Catholic Church has been launched to prepare Chileans
for their first election in 15 years and, organizers hope, calm the
country's stormy political waters.
   However, the effort already has stirred up controversy of its
own, drawing fire from backers of the right-wing military
government which charges that it favors the opposition.
   Leaders of the program, called the Crusade for Citizen
Participation, say they hope to recruit 200,000 volunteers across
the country for a door-to-door campaign starting in July. They say
the aim is to promote voter registration and to provide electors
with non-partisan information about their options.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minor, everyday stress like public speaking can
be as damaging to the heart as strenuous exercise in people who
have cardiac disease, and even can trigger heart attacks, according
to research published today.
   The researchers found that the common stresses can cause silent
ischemia, a painless but ominous disruption in the flow of blood to
the heart's own muscle.
   The study, published in the New England Journal of Medicine,
shows that ``previously unrecognized mental activities have very
important consequences,'' said Dr. Carl J. Pepine of the University
of Florida.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a state where thousands of empty miles promise
little more than highway hypnosis, and today's culinary special may
be a bowl of truck-stop chili, relief is in sight for the
culturally bereft.
   A new guidebook takes some of the mystery out of the seemingly
endless ribbons of roadway in the Lone Star state by detailing
motels, restaurants, gas stations, convenience stores and bank
machines at every Texas freeway exit.
   ``Just gathering the information was a monumental effort,'' said
Bill Cima, who probed the delights of 2,400 exits during a
four-month, 7,000-mile jaunt to assemble ``Sunset Highway Services
Directory, Exit-By-Exit.''
</TEXT>
