<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Canada-Languages Adv25   04-21 1204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Languages, Adv 25,1250</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs April 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Emotive French vs. English Debate Flares Anew in Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic Cartoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For three centuries, language has divided
Canada's two founding cultures. The novelist Hugh MacLennan
prophetically called it the ``Two Solitudes'' of English and French.
   Despite some progress toward bilingualism at a federal level as
promised in the 1982 constitution, language tensions have flared
anew from French-speaking Quebec to the western prairies, where
English is dominant.
   A fluently bilingual Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, about to
start his re-election campaign, has suddenly found himself diverted
into quelling anglophone and francophone unrest.
   Three issues have converged to create the new turmoil:
   _The province of Saskatchewan has repealed an 1886 act requiring
it to issue laws in both English and French. Alberta is expected to
do the same.
   _The Supreme Court is about to rule on Quebec's controversial
ban on English signs. Quebec is 81-percent French but the vocal
English minority in ``la belle province'' claims the ban violates
freedom of speech and is unconstitutional.
   _Mulroney faces opposition from members of his own Progressive
Conservative Party in the west over a proposed new Official
Languages Act that would strengthen bilingualism in federal courts
and institutions.
   ``The populace will be seething and smarting as it pays for
bureaucrats who communicate with one another in a language (French)
which close to four out of five Canadians cannot understand,'' said
Ted Byfield, publisher of Western Report magazine.
   Trying to balance historic sensitivities in Quebec with the need
to keep his base of support in the west, Mulroney told Parliament
that Canada's first prime minister in 1867 had to handle the
linguistic rift ``and I'm sure it will be the case 120 years from
now.''
   ``Language issues will always be there to trouble and upset us
and even to divide us,'' he said.
   At stake for Mulroney is the Meech Lake Accord he negotiated
with all 10 provinces last year, bringing Quebec into the
constitutional fold as a ``distinct society'' and purporting to
protect the rights of linguistic minorities elsewhere.
   Several provinces have balked at ratifying the deal and now
complain that the accord reached at Meech Lake in Quebec rings
hollow when put to the test.
   Premier Robert Bourassa of Quebec came in for particularly harsh
criticism during visits in mid-April to Saskatchewan and Alberta,
neighbors on the prairies.
   He refused to condemn the provinces for not honoring a Feb. 25
Supreme Court decision that said their laws should be issued in
both English and French under an 1886 statute.
   The historic failure to provide laws in French had prompted a
French-speaking priest, the Rev. Andre Mercure, to contest a
Saskatchewan speeding ticket. He died before the case reached the
Supreme Court, but it was a pyrrhic victory for the province's
25,000 francophones since the court suggested that Saskatchewan and
Alberta could repeal the old law and replace it with an
English-only policy.
   That's exactly what Premier Grant Devine of Saskatchewan has
done, arguing that the province cannot afford to re-enact all laws
in French. In the province of just over 1 million people, only
25,000 speak French, and they also speak English.
   Pressed to intervene, Bourassa told reporters: ``I am not a
federal politician. I was not elected to represent Alberta or
Saskatchewan.''
   George Ares, a francophone leader in Saskatchewan, blasted the
premier as ``a traitor'' to the French cause outside Quebec.
   ``He's backpedalling,'' added Aurele Theriault, director of the
Federation of Francophones Outside Quebec (Federation des
francophones hors Quebec).
   Bourassa chose to praise Devine for pledging to translate some
laws into French and permit use of the language in the courts and
Legislature, while setting up language classes for civil servants.
   Mulroney, meanwhile, told Devine that his actions had national
implications and offered federal funds for expanding bilingualism
in the province.
   Bourassa is also under pressure at home, where he pledged in his
1985 election campaign to lift the ban on bilingual signs. But when
an English department store, Zeller's, was firebombed last year
after adding English to its signs, Bourassa retreated for the sake
of what he termed ``social peace.''
   With the Supreme Court ruling on signs pending, federal
Languages Commissioner D'Iberville Fortier stirred the controversy
by accusing the French in Quebec of ``humiliating'' their English
neighbors.
   Royal Orr, president of the English-rights pressure group
Alliance Quebec, maintained that a new language crisis could prompt
the exodus of 100,000 Quebec English speakers, who are a major
economic force in the province.
   ``Frankly, I don't think Quebec can sustain that kind of loss.''
   On another front, Quebec's culture minister, Lise Bacon,
proposed new film distribution laws tightly restricting the number
of English-language movies that can be screened in the province.
   Meanwhile, the government insists that its new Official
Languages Act is merely an attempt to comply with the constitution,
not a means of enforcing compulsory bilingualism in regions where
it's not wanted.
   But opponents claim every federal court and agency will be
required to have bilingual judges and staff, and those unable to
speak French will be bypassed for jobs and promotions.
   ``It's a tragedy,'' said Alex Kindy, a Conservative member of
Parliament from Calgary, Alberta. ``I think Quebec is moving more
and more towards unilingualism and the rest of Canada is going to
be forced to be more and more bilingual.''
   To French-Canadians, whose ancestors arrived in North America
before the British, language preservation is their birthright.
   ``If the rights of francophones had been respected since the
last century, maybe there wouldn't be so few of us now,'' said
Andre Cyr of the Acadian Federation of Nova Scotia, which has about
31,000 French speakers.
   ``Francophones have just as much right to be here as
anglophones. We founded the country too.''
   Ironically, all three major political parties support
bilingualism as do major newspapers. But in the world's second most
spacious country, the language issue falls victim to demographics.
   Of Canada's 25 million people, about 6.2 million speak French.
   But 5.3 million of those live in one province, Quebec, where
French is the sole official language and a majority never speak
English.
   New Brunswick, the province bordering Maine, is one-third French
and the nation's only officially bilingual province. Of Ontario's
9.3 million people, 425,000 are francophones.
   West of Winnipeg in Manitoba, however, not even one in 10 of the
area's 6.7 million people lists French as their native tongue.
   Former Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau promoted
bilingualism to defuse the separatist movement in his native
Quebec, and English and French were declared the official federal
languages in 1969. Federal documents are issued in both languages,
government departments have bilingual names, and unilingual civil
servants are paid to take language classes.
   In cities such as Toronto, anglophone parents have enrolled
200,000 children in French immersion schools, the most promising
sign of real change.
   But in most regions, from Newfoundland to British Columbia,
bilingualism has been slow to take root.
   Rene Levesque, the late premier of Quebec, once said French
speakers in the rest of Canada were ``dead ducks'' who would
inevitably lose out to the English majority.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 25</NOTE>
