<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:GreekMusic Adv26   04-21 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Greek Music, Adv 26,0725</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, April 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Little Greek Music From an Irish Cellist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ross Daly was a shaggy-haired Irish
cellist when he left California on a musical journey that followed
the hippy trail to Afghanistan and India.
   Eighteen years later, he's an internationally acclaimed
performer of traditional Middle East music _ the plaintive kind
that Westerners used to call ``weird'' and ``outlandish.''
   ``It wasn't enough, being in London and learning the sitar in a
vacuum,'' the 36-year-old musician said. ``I wanted to find out how
Eastern music really worked. That meant exploring, and it took a
long time.''
   On the road, Daly took lessons from traditional musicians
wherever he could find them _ in workers' cafes or at Moslem
weddings, even at the whirling dervishes' monastery at Konya in
Turkey.
   ``There's a kind of camaraderie among musicians. They'd show me
things, maybe not all the tricks, but enough to get me started on
playing in an authentic way,'' he said.
   Daly performs and composes on a dozen exotic stringed
instruments, from the stubby Turkish ``oud,'' a member of the lute
family, to the resonant Afghan ``rambaba'' and his favorite
old-fashioned Cretan ``lyra.''
   His two latest albums, one solo and another with an
international group he formed and called Lavyrinthos _ the Greek
spelling for ``labyrinth'' _ received first-rate reviews both in
Greece and abroad.
   ``Ross is important for what he does to preserve the Middle East
musical tradition ... and because he doesn't just imitate, he
innovates as well,'' said Lucy Duran, an American musicologist who
heads Britain's National Sound Archive, in an interview.
   A childhood spent in Japan, England and the United States gave
Daly what he said was ``an eclectic approach to music that meant I
wasn't stuck in the Western classical groove.''
   His American music school training was useful for studying the
structure of Oriental music and then dissecting its regional
variations.
   ``We talk about Greek music being different from Turkish, or
Syrian from Egyptian, but in fact they're all part of a common
musical tradition that stretches all the way from Bulgaria to India
and goes back centuries,'' he said.
   That's what Daly and his group _ which includes Turkish,
Armenian, Greek and American musicians _ tries to illustrate in
performances that attract sell-out audiences in Athens clubs and
cultural centers. Their music strips down traditional Oriental
themes to reveal haunting, melancholy melodies or mesmeric rhythms.
   ``We don't use amplifiers and we like to play to no more than a
couple of hundred people. ... That means we can't really be
considered a good commercial proposition for a mass market,'' Daly
said.
   But after a dramatic rise in record sales over the past six
months, Daly is preparing another album and also working on a
documentary feature about traditional east Mediterranean music for
British television.
   His time is split between performances and recording sessions in
Athens, a home on the island of Crete and concert trips to Western
Europe. But he still travels in the Middle East several months a
year to work on his repertoire and add to his collection of several
hundred Oriental instruments.
   Among Greek composers and instrumentalists, who regret the loss
of skilled techniques as the local music-making tradition declines,
Daly is admired for his performing talents as well as his original
work.
   ``He's a tremendously sensitive musician who's developed a deep
feeling for our music. He extracts its essence in his
compositions,'' said composer Manos Hadjidakis, who won an Academy
Award for scoring the film ``Never on Sunday.'' In Crete, Daly
sometimes puts on a traditional black shirt to play the lyra at a
village wedding which may last for 24 hours of feasting, drinking
and dancing.
   He is famed for his ability to extract a rich, melodic tone from
the pear-shaped, toy-size instrument which has three-strings and is
played with a bow.
   ``People think the lyra is a peculiarly Cretan instrument but
I've found it all over Asia Minor and it must have been around
since Byzantine times. I fell for it as soon as I heard it,'' Daly
said.
   End Adv PM Tues April 26
</TEXT>
