<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Knox Adv22   04-21 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Knox, Adv 22,0851</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Tour Of Duty' Struggling in Jungles of Hawaii _ and the Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Terence Knox signed on to play Sgt. Zeke
Anderson in CBS' Vietnam war series ``Tour of Duty,'' it sounded
like a dream job _ a starring role in a network show shot on
location in beautiful Hawaii.
   ``It's not what it's cracked up to be. It's work,'' said Knox on
a recent visit to drizzly New York.
   ``I hasten to say that what we go through is nothing compared to
what the veterans went through in real warfare, but I can at least
appreciate it a little bit, at least a Peeping Tom's perspective on
being away from home in a hot place where it rains a lot and where
you don't really see civilians.''
   ``Civilians'' for Knox and the rest of the cast and crew are the
tourists who stay at the same Honolulu hotel. There is no
fraternizing.
   ``People come in waves of like two weeks in Hawaii, so there's
no meaningful relationship to be struck up here,'' joked the young
and single Knox. ``Especially when people are in a zany kind of
get-a-tan-in-two-days mentality. I mean, you can't even seduce
anyone when they're thinking about a suntan.''
   A typical 14-hour shooting day is often spent crawling around in
dusty tunnels or muddy swamps. Sometimes across the island, the CBS
detective series ``Magnum, P.I.'' would be filming, in a decidedly
more genteel atmosphere where series stars don't have to worry
about being killed off in the name of authenticity. Kevin Conroy
was the first casualty among the regulars on ``Tour.''
   ``None of us is immune. I'm glibly sitting here munching french
bread in a restaurant today, but we'll see,'' said Knox, whose job
is presumably safe since he has top billing.
   Knox is deeply dedicated to the series, and frustrated by the
lack of audience. ``Tour'' premiered last fall with a
sophisticated, film-quality style, good writing and fine
performances. But it has not prospered in the ratings.
   It spent most of the season opposite ``The Cosby Show'' on
Thursday night at the unseemly early hour of 8 p.m. Eastern time.
Its ratings improved somewhat in its new Saturday 9 p.m. time
period. CBS executives, who will announce the network's fall
schedule in May, say they remain confident in the show.
   ``I still believe that if you work hard enough at something, it
deserves a shot,'' Knox said. ``You just won't believe how hard
some of that stuff is to do and how dangerous _ nothing compared to
what the real veterans went through. The technical advisers come
out there who are veterans _ without exception before the end of
their episode, they come up and say, `We had no idea you guys
worked this hard.'''
   The way Knox plays him, Sgt. Anderson is a no-nonsense guy who
has re-upped for the second time after finding a kind of success on
the battlefield he couldn't find in civilian life. Anderson has no
interest in politics, he just wants to get his men out alive.
   Veterans groups praised CBS when it announced plans for ``Tour
of Duty'' last year. The response from viewers who are veterans has
been ``overwhelmingly positive,'' Knox said. He said the show gets
a lot of mail from veterans who say they were unable to talk about
their experiences until they saw ``Tour of Duty.''
   ``CBS didn't undertake this show as therapy for anybody,'' Knox
said. ``It was entertainment, going to be quality entertainment,
and it has remained that. But in addition, it has become a great
bringing together of these forces, people who had never talked
about it (the war) before.''
   Before ``Tour,'' Knox's best-known role was Dr. Peter White on
NBC's ``St. Elsewhere,'' a role he thought would be a six-episode
shot. But it developed into one of the most popular subplots on the
critically praised series, when White turned out to be a rapist. He
was later killed off.
   ``It made life hell in the singles bars for awhile,'' Knox said
with a laugh.
   Before ``St. Elsewhere,'' he said, his biggest role was in a
minor film ``starring a $70,000 Mack truck and myself _ and the
truck was better than I was.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   NIGHT OF MANY GUEST STARS _ There'll be a lot of resume-updating
after the final, two-hour episode of ``Magnum, P.I.'' which CBS
will air May 1. There are 18, count 'em, 18 guest stars, among them
biggies Howard Duff and Gwen Verdon. Most, including Verdon, are
reprising roles from the show's eight-year run. They are, in
alphabetical order: Brandon Call, Julie Cobb, Elisha Cook, Phyllis
Davis, Gillian Dobb, Howard Duff, Fay Hauser, Lance LeGault,
Kathleen Lloyd, Jeff MacKay, Patrice Martinez, Joe Regalbuto,
Shavar Ross, Joe Santos, Jean Bruce Scott, Gwen Verdon, Hal
Williams and Amy Yasbeck.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, April 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
