<DOCNO> AP880421-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-IranLife Adv25-1stAdd   04-21 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran Life, Adv 25-1st Add,0588</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>TEHRAN: luxuries, however.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Private wealth has been widely left untouched by Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's Islamic revolution and free enterprise is
encouraged by the Koran, the Islamic holy book. The black market
has become so much a part of the economy that the ``free'' exchange
rates are regularly quoted by the national news agency, IRNA.
   And although the United States remains the ``Great Satan,'' the
U.S. dollar is the preferred currency and at the free-exchange rate
one dollar fetches 1,165 rials, 17 times the official rate.
   ``I know of a woman who still flies to Paris every spring to buy
a new collection of clothes, spending perhaps $15,000 or more,''
said one European resident at a dinner party replete with whiskey,
rock music and dancing _ all forbidden _ in Shemiram, the elegant
section in northern Tehran.
   Shemiram has been spared by Iraqi missiles so far. But even
there, some villas and apartments are empty because their owners
have fled to Caspian Sea resorts or the Elburz mountains, where
Islamic rules require men and women to ski on separate trails.
   The Shemiram section also includes the residence of the
86-year-old Khomeini, who looks in relatively good shape, according
to diplomats who recently saw him at his mosque.
   Growing popular discontent with the unequal sharing of the war's
financial burdens may have been at a root of his recent Fatwa, or
binding religious guideline, that strengthened the hands of the
government.
   Up to now, key economic reforms have been blocked on religious
grounds by the Council for the Protection of the Constitution, a
watchdog body dominated by Islamic fundamentalists.
   Tax collection has been sluggish. Deputy Finance Minister Ali
Majedi said recently taxation capacity was twice that currently
collected. A Western diplomat termed his estimate a gross
understatement.
   ``God knows that even the filthy capitalist system in the West
is not like that,'' a legislator, Sahed Ali Akbar Tahaili, recently
complained in the Majlis, the 270-seat parliament. He was referring
to a huge tax debt run up by one of the various foundations
controlled by religious authorities.
   ``When someone moves to another state in the United States, all
his records are checked to make sure he has paid all his taxes,''
the legislator added.
   The new parliament formed after the April 8 general elections is
widely predicted to step up pressure for reforms, with the position
of its pragmatist speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, strengthened further.
   Reformers may face an uphill battle. Official figures cited by
the newspaper Etela'at suggest that black market trends are
determined by speculative money worth tens of billions of dollars.
   There is little doubt, however, that the role of the mullahs,
the religious dignitaries, will be reduced by Khomeini's Fatwa. The
Fatwa says the government may even prevent Hadj, the annual Moslem
pilgrimage to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, if the national interests
demand a temporary suspension.
   Iranians already have noticed a certain relaxation in the
enforcement of religious laws. Women wearing make-up or nail polish
or who let part of their hair peek out from under a headdress are
normally no longer stopped on the street by the Pasdaran, the
revolutionary guards.
   But the chador, the all-encompassing outer garment, remains a
must for women, even when skiing.
   ``When they come downhill, they look like bats,'' said the wife
of a European ambassador.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 25</NOTE>
