<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Seaside-Krier Adv24   04-21 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Seaside-Krier, Adv 24,0430</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>To Build or Not to Build?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-New Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEASIDE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 20 years Leon Krier has talked
architecture, taught architecture, delineated architecture,
designed architecture. Everything but built architecture.
   ``I do not build because I am an architect,'' he once wrote,
meaning he would not compromise his principles and build in a world
being rendered uninhabitable by industrialization, technology and
modern architecture.
   When his plan for a school in France came in 200 percent over
budget, Krier gave up the commission rather than change his design.
   But now this consummate purist is building _ a wood cottage for
vacation time in this new Florida panhandle resort.
   ``He finally took a deep breath and plunged into the abyss,''
says Robert Davis, Seaside's developer. ``I'm honored he's willing
to make an exception for Seaside.''
   ``Seaside comes along at just the right moment,'' Krier, a
Luxembourg native, said in a telephone interview from his home in
London. ``There's nothing new like it.''
   As far as Krier is concerned, all the problems of architecture
were solved before the Industrial Revolution; modern architecture
and technology have served mainly to ruin the world's cities.
   Seaside, on the other hand, reflects his preference for small
settlements, human scale, pedestrian activity and traditional
buildings.
   Although Krier has no track record, ``his plans have been
influential far beyond their unexecuted state for the way in which
they have re-established a lost vision'' of a romantic past,
according to architectural critic Ada Louise Huxtable.
   Krier also is a bit of a gadfly. At an architects' conference
three years ago, Krier pointedly questioned Philip Johnson, dean of
American architects, about a skyscraper he'd designed in Boston.
   The building, Johnson admitted, was ``2 million square feet of
space that should not be in this part of Boston.'' Implicitly
acknowledging Krier's purity, he added, ``I am a whore and I am
paid very well for high-rise buildings.''
   In return for helping to lay out Seaside's plan and design the
town tower, Davis gave Krier a building lot. But he attached one
condition: Krier had to build on it.
   The three-room cottage, designed to resemble a classical temple,
should be ready this summer.
   Krier wants to see how it turns out before completing his design
for the tower. After years of designing on paper, he joked, ``I
want to see how many mistakes I've made.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Fashion-Menswear Adv24   04-21 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fashion-Menswear, Adv 24,0475</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Menswear Loosens Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fashion Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maturing baby boomers are changing the rules for
menswear as they look for clothes somewhere between jeans and
T-shirt and the pinstripe suit.
   ``Most of the younger guys who are working grew up on MTV and
rock 'n' roll,'' said award-winning designer Bill Robinson, whose
label is starting its third year.
   This generation, he says, is ``breaking down barriers of how and
where you wear things.''
   The experimentation is evident in clothes now being shown for
fall, soon to be sent to stores across the country.
   The look includes round, softer shoulders on sportcoats;
high-waisted sweaters meant to be tucked in; mock turtlenecks to be
worn under vests; buttery ``antique leathers'' and suedes. Browns,
grays and blacks are popular, but some designers are throwing in
reds, yellows and what one called ``vegetable colors.''
   ``I think men are ready to wear color,'' said Ronaldus Shamask,
a relative newcomer to menswear whose minimalistic designs in such
shades as mustard, teal and wine have won acclaim. ``Men are
becoming much more comfortable with experimenting.''
   The classic Polo line by Ralph Lauren, who's been designing
menswear for more than 20 years, is trying out American Indian
styles, suede shirts and ``antique ski and expedition clothing.''
   Even the business suit is ``loosening up,'' said Tom Julian,
associate fashion director of the Men's Fashion Association. ``Men
are more aware (of fashion) today.''
   Jack Herschlag, executive director of the National Association
of Men's Sportswear Buyers, says suits are appearing in a variety
of silhouettes this fall and even the double-breasted suit will
attempt a comeback.
   Men are moving away from the investment-dressing era and into a
stage of experimentation, Herschlag says.
   He and others in the field attribute the development partly to
the influence of movies and TV shows like ``thirtysomething'' and
``L.A. Law'' that feature smartly dressed young professionals.
   Business is helped when men see role models like Bill Cosby
``looking groovy'' on TV, says Robinson, who describes his clothes
as souped-up versions of American classics.
   ``It's not silly; it's not meant to make a statement,'' insisted
Shamask's sales director, Harlan Bratcher. ``It's more for people
who are tired of playing games. It's more: `This is me.'''
   That's not to say the new looks are for everyone.
   Those who are sticking with jeans should know that this fall
marks the beginning of the ``post-acidwashed era,'' Herschlag said.
   ``The pendulum is swinging back to very, very dark colors,''
said Julian.
   And the conservative business suit is not dead yet.
   ``There'll always be a Brooks Brothers element in the society,''
Robinson said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
