<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
approved a six-month experiment limiting program trading on the New
York Stock Exchange on days when the market takes a big swing
either up or down.
   The SEC ordered Wednesday that use of the exchange's
computerized SuperDOT system be suspended for the practice called
``index arbitrage'' when the Dow Jones Industrial Average rises or
falls by 50 points.
   Traders use index arbitrage to make money by taking advantage of
momentary price discrepancies between stock index futures and the
underlying stocks.
