<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     04-21 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Markets Distressed Over Evidence of Higher Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with Commerce Department report on March durable
goods orders, due at 8:30 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising consumer prices are contributing to worries in the
financial markets that inflation is accelerating.
   The government said Wednesday that consumer prices jumped 0.5
percent in March, reflecting a record increase in clothing costs
and higher food and gasoline prices that triggered the biggest
inflation jump in 14 months.
   Analysts said the sharp increase in the Labor Department's
Consumer Price Index, which translated into a 6.4 percent annual
growth rate, demonstrated that the weak dollar and unexpectedly
strong consumer demand were threatening to ignite a new bout of
spiraling costs.
   They speculated those pressures soon would prompt the Federal
Reserve to nudge interest rates higher.
   The bond market, a good indicator of inflation sentiment,
reacted negatively to the CPI report. Bond prices fell and the
yield on the Treasury's key 30-year bond rose to 9.05 percent,
although prices later recovered somewhat.
   Stocks also fell Wednesday, pushing the Dow Jones industrial
average down 14.09 points to 1,985.41, its third straight decline.
   The financial markets first were jolted last week when an
unexpectedly high U.S. trade deficit for February sent the dollar
plunging. A government report that wholesale prices jumped in March
intensified investor worries.
   The Reagan administration, which is counting on the Federal
Reserve to keep the economy growing through the November election,
contended Wednesday that the inflation fears were overblown.
   ``Despite large increases for consumer and producer prices in
March, the smaller increases in prices in previous
months...indicate that inflation remains under control,'' said
presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Some private economists disputed that view.
   ``The CPI rise reflects an increasingly widespread inflationary
environment,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co.
``The good news on inflation is over for this year and the question
now really is `how high will prices go?'''
   The March CPI increase followed a modest 0.2 percent February
rise and was the biggest monthly gain since a 0.7 percent increase
in January 1987.
   In another economic report, the Labor Deparment said Americans'
average weekly earnings, after discounting for inflation, fell 0.3
percent in March, the second consecutive monthly decline. The
changes left Americans' inflation-adjusted earnings 1.2 percent
below a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
