<DOCNO> AP880421-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-21 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Continue Sliding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking and quiet days in the Persian Gulf
following Monday's combat have helped sustain a slide in oil
futures prices.
   At the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for May delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled at
$17.74 per barrel on Wednesday, down 29 cents from Tuesday, when
they fell 49 cents.
   Among refined products, May contracts for wholesale unleaded
gasoline ended at 51.42 cents per gallon, down 0.72 cent, while
wholesale heating oil contracts closed at 49.31 cents per gallon,
off 0.37 cent.
   Madison Galbraith, senior energy specialist at Merrill Lynch
Energy Futures, said the selling that began late Monday continued
as no reports of renewed hostilities emerged from the Persian Gulf.
   Prices surged early Monday amid reports that U.S. Navy vessels
had destroyed two offshore Iranian oil platforms, sunk an Iranian
patrol boat and bombed two Iranian navy frigates while Iran had
fired on at least two U.S. vessels.
   Traders often fear that fighting in the area might hamper oil
shipments, which could tend to drive prices higher. But because
producers outside the area widely are expected to cover any
shortfall, the combat-induced rally was short-lived.
   Prices began dropping late Monday and continued falling on
Tuesday and Wednesday as traders cashed in gains made during
Monday's climb.
   Some of the selling also was due to technical factors, Galbreath
said.
</TEXT>
