<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Airlines     04-21 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Airlines,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aeromexico Strike and Bankruptcy Raises Tourism Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for a banner year in Mexico's
crucial tourism industry may have been grounded by the bankruptcy
of the government's Aeromexico airline.
   A federal judge declared Aeromexico bankrupt on Monday and
ordered it into receivership, leaving its more than 9,200 workers
jobless. The airline already had canceled most of its flights
because of a strike triggered by Aeromexico's plans for a
cost-cutting restructuring.
   ``The disappearance of Aeromexico will affect negatively the
tourism sector and will hinder (it) from reaching the estimates of
transportation of foreign visitors to the different national
destinations,'' Tourism Secretary Antonio Enriquez Savignac told
reporters Tuesday night.
   Tourism vies with the ``maquiladora'' assembly plant industry _
in which foreign companies set up factories in Mexico to take
advantage of cheap labor _ _ as the nation's No. 2 source of
foreign exchange after petroleum.
   Estimates had been that tourism would bring in as much as $2.4
billion this year, the highest since 1982, when the peso's drop in
value against the dollar started a slide in tourism revenue.
   Aeromexico filed for bankruptcy after ground and technical
workers went on strike April 12 in protest of management plans to
reduce the fleet and route system to bring the money-losing airline
into the black.
   Enriquez Savignac said Aeromexico and Mexicana, the other
state-run airline which is unaffected by the bankruptcy or strike,
carry 57 percent of the foreign tourists arriving by air.
   Aeromexico was the only carrier serving 15 Mexican cities.
   Representatives of the Aeromexico Technicians and Workers Union,
which represents 7,250 striking workers, announced plans to seek a
meeting with President Miguel de la Madrid.
   ``We will ask the president for a restructuring of the
company,'' Miguel Angel Mejorada, the union's secretary for
internal matters, said in a phone interview.
   He said the union still had not received formal notification of
the judge's bankruptcy decision, which had been announced by the
federal Communications and Transportation Department.
   The airline's 2,000 pilots and cabin attendants have their own
unions that did not support the strike, which forced cancellation
of all 223 daily flights to 42 domestic and international
destinations.
   The union has charged that the decision to seek bankruptcy was
politically motivated and not made on economic grounds.
   No plans have been announced for a replacement for Aeromexico.
Mexicana on Tuesday started accepting Aeromexico tickets for routes
in which they operated with parallel service.
   Aeromexico started business in 1934 and has been owned by the
government since 1957. Mexicana has been controlled by the
government since 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
