<DOCNO> AP880421-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Saatchi-Northwest     04-21 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saatchi-Northwest,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Lifts No-Smoking Assignment From Ad Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines is putting another
advertising agency in charge of creating commercials for its
smoke-free flights to relieve tobacco industry pressures on the
agency that created the first ads for its program.
   Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Compton, a huge New York-based agency,
created the first ads for Northwest's no-smoking program and
remains the airline's agency for other general advertising.
   The commercials showed passengers applauding Northwest's plans
to ban smoking on nearly all its domestic flights.
   Shortly after the ads started airing last month, Saatchi was
fired from its longtime job making cookie and candy ads for RJR
Nabisco Inc., which also makes cigarettes.
   Northwest said Wednesday it was moving the no-smoking program
assignment to the Kolesar and Hartwell agency, based in
Minneapolis. The agency already handles Northwest's ads in media
aimed at the travel trade.
   The job involves about $2 million of the estimated $50 million
in Northwest billings handled by Saatchi.
   RJR had cited ``philosophical differences'' for pulling its
cookie and candy assignments from Saatchi, but those familiar with
the decision said privately that RJR executives were troubled
Saatchi had created the no-smoking ads and failed to tell them
about it.
   ``We are extremely disappointed that a reactionary faction of
the tobacco industry continues to put literally dozens of Saatchi &
Saatchi professional careers in jeopardy,'' A.B. Magary, executive
vice president for marketing for Northwest Airlines, said in
explaining why it moved the no-smoking assignment to another agency.
   He said that while the St. Paul, Minn.-based airline was happy
with Saatchi's work, it wanted to make sure that Saatchi ``can
continue to serve us with total objectivity and enthusiasm.''
   Magary declined in an interview to be more specific about what
pressures Saatchi was under from the tobacco industry, but said the
airline had been told the agency continued to feel pressured.
   Magary said Northwest offered to reassign the no-smoking job to
another agency ``in hopes of solving their problem and they
accepted our offer to do it.''
   He said it was up to the agency to elaborate on whatever
pressures they feel they continue to be under.
   But agency spokesmen declined the opportunity to do so.
   ``We understand Northwest's decision with regard to the
no-smoking assignment,'' said Michael Keeshan, executive vice
president and management director in charge of the Northwest
account at Saatchi.
   But he declined to say whether Saatchi supported or solicited
the action, adding only that, ``We are anxious to put this matter
behind us.''
   Saatchi also is the advertising agency for Lorillard Inc.'s True
cigarettes.
   Sara R. Ridgway, a spokeswoman for Lorillard, said the cigarette
company was not putting any pressure on Saatchi in the wake of the
Northwest no-smoking ads. She said Lorillard was happy with
Saatchi's work and planned to retain its relationship with the
agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
