<DOCNO> AP880421-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AT&TMeeting Bjt   04-21 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T Meeting, Bjt,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Profit Up 10.6 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AT&T-Affirmative Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX2 of April 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected Chairman Robert E. Allen says
American Telephone & Telegraph Co. has a ``new sense of urgency''
and is committed to sustaining its strong first-quarter profit
increases.
   ``No officer of AT&T is feeling content and complacent,'' Allen
told shareholders Wednesday at the company's annual meeting.
   Allen, 53, was elevated to chairman and chief executive by the
board of directors late Tuesday, a day after the death from colon
cancer of his 62-year-old predecessor, James E. Olson.
   Also on Wednesday, AT&T announced a 10.6 percent increase in its
first quarter earnings. Its earnings per share rose 15 percent
because of a redemption of preferred shares that lessened the
amount that had to be skimmed off for preferred dividends.
   Asked at a news conference whether AT&T could keep up the 15
percent growth in earnings per share for the rest of 1988, Allen
said: ``That's our firm commitment.''
   At the meeting, shareholders rejected a white supremacist
group's resolution that sought to phase out AT&T's affirmative
action but also rejected a proposal to expand affirmative action.
   Allen, who was president and chief operating officer, is a
thoughtful, soft-spoken contrast to the forceful Olson. But the two
men were close and Olson had groomed him as a successor.
   ``This is a bittersweet moment for me,'' Allen told shareholders
with a slight quaver in his voice. ``I sincerely wish it were under
different circumstances.''
   Allen tackled questions about whether he had the steel to
continue Olson's legacy. He said he was proud of his style of
developing trusting relations with colleagues.
   ``First and foremost, I'm a team player,'' Allen told reporters.
   AT&T said its profit rose to $492 million, or 46 cents a share,
from $445 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 2.8 percent to $8.35 billion from $8.12 billion.
   AT&T's earnings statement indicated continuing difficulties in
selling computers and office equipment. Revenue was flat in the
category of data products, network equipment and business
communications products.
   In contrast, revenue from services, mainly long-distance, was up
8.2 percent.
   While noting that AT&T had done a good job of cutting costs,
Allen said the company must work harder on increasing sales.
   ``No business can live by cost control alone. It must grow,'' he
told reporters.
   Rawleigh Warner, the retired chief of Mobil Corp. and an AT&T
director, told shareholders that Olson spoke with him by phone two
weeks ago and said that ``should anything happen to him, Bob Allen
was his natural successor.''
   Allen had served as president and chief operating officer since
1986. Before that he had held top finance jobs in the company and
had a long career in the Bell telephone companies.
   The resolution against affirmative action was sponsored by the
National Alliance, a white supremacist organization based in
Arlington, Va. Herbert Poinsett of Norcross, Ga., spoke on its
behalf, contending that blacks are less intelligent and affirmative
action hurts the morale of whites.
   The resolution earned votes of 8.6 percent of the shares.
   Allen said AT&T considered the proposal ``highly objectionable''
and tried three times to get the Securities and Exchange Commission
to keep it off the ballot.
   The resolution calling for more affirmative action was
introduced by Alex S. Tillman, a black manager at Bell Laboratories
in Murray Hill, N.J. He said taking better advantage of the talents
of minorities and women made good business sense for AT&T.
   It earned votes of 6 percent of the shares.
</TEXT>
