<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexasThrifts Bjt   04-21 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Thrifts, Bjt,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Plan Texas Thrift Industry Revamping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to clean up the state's troubled savings
and loan institutions has gotten an overwhelming response from
thrifts ready to participate, according to a spokesman for federal
regulators.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank in Dallas said Wednesday it would
announce later this month the first consolidations in the Southwest
Plan for Texas thrifts.
   The FHLB announced the program in February and requested
proposals from interested parties by March 31.
   ``We have received about 150 proposals from parties interested
in participating in the Southwest Plan,'' said David Colgren, FHLB
spokesman in Dallas. ``This is an overwhelming response of parties
interested in the plan.''
   Of 279 Texas thrifts, 104 were insolvent as of Sept. 30, 1987,
according to the FHLB. Those endangered institutions will be
consolidated, closed or sold, said Colgren.
   M. Danny Wall, FHLB chairman, has said that roughly half the
problems of the nation's thrift industry are in Texas, which has
been hit hard by an energy and real estate slump in recent years.
   Investors would provide up to $1 billion in capital for the
plan. Much of the expense will be paid by the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp., which was expected to provide $7 billion at
first and up to $2 billion annually.
   ``We believe, overall, we need a fair and equitable analysis for
each proposal,'' Colgren said. ``That analysis must balance the
interests of FSLIC and private investors. We anticipate the first
consolidations to be available in late April.''
   Colgren would not say how many S&Ls would be involved in the
first announcement but added that ``a geometric progression of
consolidations'' would be made thereafter.
   Industry officials had said earlier that the state's thrift
crisis increases with every delay, along with the cost of remedies.
   But Colgren said: ``We will not rush into any deal that is bad
for FSLIC and bad for the industry. We do not want to create more
problems. Otherwise, today's solutions become tomorrow's problems.''
   On Monday, FHLB officials reported that the FSLIC's insurance
fund shortfall almost doubled in 1987 to an estimated $11.6 billion.
   ``We anticipate the Southwest Plan to cost FSLIC somewhere
between $6 and 7 billion,'' said Colgren. `` Through FSLIC
recapitalization signed by the president in August of last year, we
will raise $10.8 billion over the next three years...''
   ``Through FSLIC notes, and other sources, we anticipate having
about $20 billion to work with,'' he said.
   Insolvent Texas thrifts will have lost at least $895 million in
operating expenses in the first four months of this year, according
to one analysis.
   ``We believe through consolidation of the industry through the
Southwest Plan, interest from private investors, reducing the cost
of funds that Texas institutions must pay to attract deposits _ the
`Texas premium' _ and using FSLIC sources, we can solve the
problems in Texas,'' Colgren said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880421-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoTalks Bjt   04-21 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, Bjt,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Wants Japanese-Style Pay For Japanese-Style Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers would
consider Chrysler Corp.'s bid to adopt corporate-wide
Japanese-style production methods if its executives accept a less
lucrative Japanese-style pay system, a union official says.
   Workers and union officials joined UAW Vice President Marc Stepp
on Wednesday in sharply criticizing the multimillion-dollar wages
received by top Chrysler executives, particularly Chairman Lee
Iacocca, as the union and No. 3 automaker continued talks over a
new labor contract.
   ``What we're wanting is what's fair and equitable for all of our
members in relation to the standing of the corporation,'' said
Thomas Jackie Russell, president of UAW Local 1413 in Huntsville,
Ala. ``When we hear the type money these guys are making, then that
indicates the standings of the corporation.''
   Negotiations entered their fourth day today over a contract to
replace the one expiring Sept. 14. The pact would cover 66,000
active and laid off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees.
   Stepp, the union's chief negotiator, targeted Iacocca the day
after Chrysler disclosed the chairman received $17.9 million in
1987 in salary, cash and stock bonuses and money earned exercising
stock options.
   Iacocca in 1987 was the highest-paid auto company executive for
a second straight year. In 1986, when he earned $20.6 million,
Iacocca also was the nation's highest-paid executive.
   ``Executive compensations have gotten completely out of hand,''
Stepp said. ``It makes it extremely difficult for us to sit down in
a rational manner and try to negotiate a decent contract.''
   Word of Iacocca's pay prompted calls from workers demanding that
union officials seek higher pay or other benefits in their
contract, Stepp said.
   Under the Japanese system cited by Stepp, managers earn six to
eight times more than workers. American managers earn about 18
times more and, in Iacocca's case, 27 times more, Stepp said.
   Chrysler workers earn $14.43 an hour including cost-of-living
adjustments, or gross base pay of about $30,000.
   Stepp also said that before Japanese workers are laid off or
their pay is cut, Japanese managers take a pay cut.
   Stepp raised the pay comparisons a day after Anthony St. John,
Chrysler's chief negotiator, said the automaker has asked union
leaders to support its efforts to adopt so-called Modern Operating
Agreements at all plants. Russell's Local 1413 is one of six plants
where MOAs are in effect.
   The Japanese-style MOA production system organizes workers into
teams, uses them in a variety of jobs instead of a single defined
task and reduces the number of workers needed to cover for
absentees, inspect products and correct mistakes.
   St. John also asked for a committee comprising union, company
and outside representatives to study the effectiveness of job
security provisions in the new contract. The committee also would
look at ways to increase productivity and improve quality, another
weapon in the push for MOA adoption.
   Stepp said the union would consider that proposal if the
committee also could study and adjust top executives' compensation
to bring it into line with the Japanese managers-to-workers pay
ratio.
   ``We think it is only fair that since they ask us to go to a
Japanese production system such as MOAs and team concept...it is
fair for them to go to the Japanese system in terms of
compensation,'' Stepp said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
