<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BananaRepublic     04-21 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banana Republic,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Founders Leave Safari Clothing Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founders of the Banana Republic chain
of ``adventure clothing'' stores have resigned from the company
because of differences with its owner, The Gap Inc.
   Mel and Patricia Ziegler, who founded Banana Republic in 1978
and sold it to The Gap five years later, announced Wednesday they
were leaving because of ``fundamental creative and cultural
differences'' with Gap management.
   The company also announced it was discontinuing ``Trips''
magazine, San Francisco-based Banana Republic's latest venture. The
magazine was an offbeat look at the world of travel, which touted
itself in its March inaugural issue as the only honest travel
industry magazine.
   In a prepared statement, Mel Ziegler said Banana Republic's
acquisition by The Gap ``allowed us to take our concept further and
faster than we ever imagined. We never expected to stay with this
forever. It's time for us to get on to something new.''
   Mel Ziegler, formerly a writer with the San Francisco Chronicle,
and Patricia Ziegler, an illustrator at the paper, left the
Chronicle to found Banana Republic.
   The Zieglers also developed a successful mail-order business,
with a quarterly catalogue mailed to about 3 million people.
   Since selling The Gap, the Zieglers continued to run it with
creative autonomy until March, Gap officials said.
   In March, The Gap installed its president, Millard Drexler, as
chief executive of Banana Republic, which has 99 stores nationwide.
Banana Republic's sales had been slumping for nearly a year,
although The Gap does not release earnings figures for its
subsidiaries.
   Donald Fisher, chairman of The Gap, said he had accepted the
Zieglers' resignations with regret.
   ``They built a very intelligent and fun business that brought
touches of theater, art, humor, and literature to retailing and
mail order,'' Fisher said.
</TEXT>
