<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-URWContract     04-21 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-URW Contract,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear, Rubber Workers Tentatively Agree on Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Rubber Workers and Goodyear Tire &
Rubber Co. early this morning reached a tentative three-year
contract agreement which will be considered at a union meeting
today as a possible model for pacts with Firestone Tire & Rubber
Co. and Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co.
   The contract was reached at 2:30 a.m. Union contracts with
Goodyear, Firestone and Uniroyal Goodrich expired at midnight.
   A majority of the Goodyear's 15,000 union members and a majority
of the 11 plants represented by the union must approve the pact in
order to achieve ratification, said John Perduyn, public
information director for Goodyear.
   The contract provides for wage and benefit increases, though
precise figures will not be available until the contract is
presented to union members. The agreement provides for cost of
living adjustments in each year of the contract, along with
increases in pension benefits and medical benefits, Perduyn said.
   Frank Tully, Goodyear vice president of human resources and
chief company spokesman at negotiations, said the contract, ``is
equitable in that it provides an excellent wage and benefit package
while not jeopardizing the company's competitive position.''
   The contract provides for Goodyear and the URW to meet to
discuss job security, Perduyn said. The pact also provides for a
successor clause that ensures continuation of the contract if a
plant is sold.
   International URW president Milan Stone said the URW's Big Three
Advisory Committee will review the proposed agreement today for
consideration as a pattern settlement for the rubber industry. The
advisory committee and the URW's International Executive Board must
approve any tentative contract before it can be presented to union
members for a vote.
   The URW in April targeted Goodyear as the pattern-setting
company for negotiations in reaching the three-year master contract
for all three tire companies. Of the 26,000 union members affected
by the contract, 15,000 work for Goodyear, 6,500 for Uniroyal
Goodrich, and 4,700 for Firestone.
   Talks began in mid-March for a master contract covering workers
at Goodyear plants in Akron, St. Marys and Marysville, Ohio;
Topeka, Kansas; Gadsden Ala.; Union City, Tenn.; Danville, Va.; New
Bedford, Mass; Sun Prarie, Wisc.; Lincoln, Neb.; and Madisonville,
Ky.
   An agreement on economic issues for Uniroyal Goodrich workers
was ratified earlier this year, with the company promising the URW
locals it will keep open three plants in Indiana and Alabama
through the term of the new contract in exchange for a wage freeze
through April 1990.
</TEXT>
