<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 0947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-Fitness     04-21 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Fitness,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Wants Healthier Workers, Plans Expansion of Fitness Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. plans to expand a program
aimed at improving the health and fitness of workers, especially
those who suffer from obesity, high blood pressure, mental stress
or substance abuse.
   ``It's already in place in some areas right now. It will be
intensified in July,'' said Dr. George Mackey, GM's health director.
   GM and the United Auto Workers union will run the program, which
will cover roughly 450,000 workers in the United States, Mackey
said Wednesday.
   The No. 1 automaker decided to push the program after reviewing
the results of pilot projects that began in 1985 at four auto
plants. Mackey said the plants were in Warren, Pontiac and Livonia.
   Screening and counseling could cost up to $24 million if all
employees participate, says Jack Erfurt, a researcher for the
Institute of Labor and Industrial Relations at the University of
Michigan.
   GM's potential savings, however, could be much greater. Erfurt
estimates 80 percent of GM's workers suffer some type of health
problem.
   The first step will involve blood pressure checks and a review
of each employee's medical history. Employees can either enter
classes for fitness, losing weight or stoping smoking; adopt
self-help programs, or choose one-on-one counseling.
   Six months later, health care workers will contact employees to
check progress.
   In the pilot program, GM paid the entire cost of initial
screening and two-thirds of the follow-up programs, with employees
paying the remainder. GM's share amounted to roughly $53 per worker
each year, Erfurt said.
   The results of GM's pilot project were mixed. In two plants,
less than 10 percent of the workers entered the health classes, he
said.
   In the other two factories, nearly half the employees did so,
but those workers could choose among self-help programs, counseling
or full-scale classes _ unlike employees in the other two plants.
   GM has supported various health programs for years, mostly on a
plant-by-plant basis, but this one is broader and more ambitious,
Erfurt said.
</TEXT>
