<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Lower on Money Supply Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were slightly lower on the London
Stock Exchange at midday Thursday following the release of figures
showing that British money supply and bank lending grew much faster
than expected in March.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 2.7
points, or 0.01 percent, at 1,784.1 at midday local time.
   Volume was light at 236 million shares.
   Share prices opened lower, largely in response to overnight
declines in New York and Tokyo, but attempted a rally in early
trading, moving up to an intraday high of 1786.9.
   The release of disappointing money supply and bank lending data
at 10:30 a.m. local time pushed prices to their lowest levels of
8.5 points down on the 100-share index, traders said.
