<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FordEXP     04-21 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ford EXP,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Two-Seater Dies; Ford to Discontinue EXP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will eliminate its two-seat Escort
EXP model late this summer, making way for increased production of
two- and four-door cars, the company said.
   Ford recalled 50 workers who had been indefinitely laid off from
the Wayne assembly plant after announcing the production change
Wednesday, said Jeff Washington, president of the United Auto
Workers Local 900, which represents 3,100 hourly workers at the
plant.
   The elimination of the EXP will allow increased production of
the Escort, the Escort wagon and the Escort GT, Ford said Wednesday.
   Ford told the Wayne workers it could make more money by building
more Escort GTs, which are high-performance cars based on the
Escort economy car, Washington said.
   The move follows a decision earlier this year by General Motors
Corp. to cease production of the Pontiac Fiero, a rear-engine,
plastic-body, two-seat sports car. GM's decision will result in the
elimination of 1,109 jobs in Pontiac.
   Ford sold 54,502 EXPs in 1981, its best year for the model. In
1987 Ford sold 24,427 EXPs out of 392,360 Escorts.
</TEXT>
