<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston     04-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette, Coniston Square Off at Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of shareholders turned out for
Gillette Co.'s annual meeting today, where the consumer products
giant squared off against Coniston Group in a highly visible
takeover battle.
   The two companies waged a proxy war at the meeting, held at
Gillette's manufacturing center in this town 20 miles north of
Boston.
   Coniston sought four seats on Gillette's board of directors, but
Gillette hoped a coalition of loyal shareholders and last-minute
support from large institutions would render enough votes to repel
the New York group.
   Results of the election are expected later this month.
   Since Coniston went public Feb. 11 with plans to seek control of
Gillette, the two rivals have traded barbs in the press and the
courts.
   Coniston's board candidates have pledged to support the
divestiture of the worldwide empire Gillette built around personal
care products in an effort to increase profitability and boost the
company's stock price.
   Coniston contends Gillette is still mired by the nearly $580
million paid to Revlon Group Inc. in 1986 to abandon its repeated
takeover attempts.
   Gillette, however, has pointed out to its nearly 27,000
shareholders a steady rise in earnings since the company laid off
2,400 workers and the sale of several unprofitable divisions after
signing a 10-year no-takeover pact with Revlon in 1986.
   Last week, Gillette said it might close some North American
plants to further streamline operations.
   The takeover contest will likely be decided by institutional
investors, which own between 60 percent to 65 percent of the 115.5
million Gillette shares outstanding.
   Coniston, which has run newspapers ads attacking Gillette's
``greenmail'' payment to Revlon, claims to have the support of
several major shareholders, including two California pension plans
with about 2.1 million shares and a New York state retirement plan
with nearly 2 million shares.
   Gillette proxy solicitor John Wilcox declined to name
supporters, but he suggested many large shareholders will wait
until the last moment to make a decision.
   Gillette spokesman David Fausch said that since the Coniston bid
does not seek a complete change in control, some large shareholders
may be willing to take a risk for greater profits.
   ``They look at the short-term gains,'' said Fausch. ``This is
only four people on a 12-member board saying they'll push for a
sale. It's not a complete switch in management.''
</TEXT>
