<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     04-21 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0276</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied sharply today,
rebounding from its recent slump.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 29.18 to
2,014.59 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 793 up, 418 down and
477 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 53.25 million shares at
midmorning.
   Analysts said a relatively steady showing by the dollar in
foreign exchange and the U.S. bond market helped to attract some
buyers to stocks.
   Fears of further increases in interest rates appeared to
diminish amid signs that the Federal Reserve wasn't taking any
immediate action to tighten credit.
   Brokers also said traders found some ``bargains'' among the many
stocks that haven't responded much so far to generally strong
earnings reports for the first quarter.
   Columbia Gas System led the active list, down ] at 28{ on top of
a 1-point loss Wednesday, when the company cut its quarterly
dividend from 79.5 cents a share to 50 cents a share.
   Bankamerica, also among the volume leaders, rose { to 11. The
company reported higher first-quarter profits.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up 1[ at 43;
General Electric, up ] at 39|; American Telephone & Telegraph, up |
at 27[, and International Business Machines, up ] at 113\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.60 to 146.73. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was off .07 at 297.65.
