<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Staley-Tate     04-21 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Staley-Tate,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staley Rejects Tate & Lyle Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giant corn processor Staley
Continental Inc. today rejected as inadequate a $1.33 billion
takeover bid by British sugar refiner Tate & Lyle PLC.
   Staley Chairman Donald E. Nordlund said the company's board of
directors has instructed management to explore various alternatives
to enhance shareholder value.
   Tate & Lyle is offering $32 a share in cash. In early trading on
the New York Stock Exchange, Staley's stock jumped 50 cents to
$37.25 a share.
   Nordlund said among the alternatives the company would consider
would be a financial restructuring or recapitalization, issuing
stock to a third party, selling all or part of the company, a joint
venture or a leveraged buyout.
   Staley, based in the Chicago suburb of Rolling Meadows, is a
holding company formed in 1985. It owns A.E. Staley Manufacturing
Co., the nation's second-largest refiner of corn sweeteners, and
CFS Continental Inc., a food-service supplier.
   Tate & Lyle, Britain's second-largest sugar refiner, owns nearly
5 percent of Staley's 30.4 million outstanding shares. The
acquisition of Staley would give the company a foothold in the U.S.
corn sweetener market and make it the only supplier of all three
types of sugar _ corn, beet and cane _ in the United States.
   Tate & Lyle could not be reached immediately for comment.
  
</TEXT>
