<DOCNO> AP880421-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Oil     04-21 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Oil,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schlumberger Posts 19.2 Percent Quarterly Income Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schlumberger Ltd. said Thursday its
first-quarter earnings jumped by 19.2 percent over the same period
last year, boosted by an almost two-thirds growth in revenue from
its oil exploration services.
   The world's largest oilfield services company reported a profit
of $101.01 million, or 37 cents per share, on sales of $1.3 billion
in the three months ended March 31. That compared with $4.99
million, or 2 cents per share, on $1.1 billion in revenue during
the same period of 1987.
   Strong world economies helped increase sales, despite weakness
in oil prices during the quarter, said Euan Baird, Schlumberger's
chairman.
   ``In particular, Schulmberger Industries, the electronics and
metering businesses, posted record profits, revenue and orders,''
he said.
   In addition, Baird said the company benefitted from a 24 percent
gain in sales by the company's oilfield services division, and a 61
percent revenue gain by another division that provides services to
locate and evaluate oil and gas.
   Schlumberger is controlled by the founding French family. It is
based in New York and incorporated in the Netherlands Antilles.
