<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ForeignRetailers Adv25   04-21 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Foreign Retailers, Adv 25,0960</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Editions of Monday April 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Huge American Market Continues to Draw Foreign Retailers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1800s, the story goes, immigrants coming
to America believed the streets were paved with gold. Nowadays, it
is foreign retailers who are arriving on these shores in search of
their fortunes.
   They are lured by the size of the U.S. market and the American
passion for foreign styles and goods. Several are already reporting
success.
   ``We could get a large slice of the apple'' by selling in
America, said Sophie Mirman, who helped introduce the Sock Shop, a
chain of British hosiery stores, to this country.
   The most prominent of the new arrivals is Campeau Corp. The
Canadian concern bought out Allied Stores Corp. in 1986 and is in
the process of taking over Federated Department Stores Inc.
   To help finance its purchase of Federated, Campeau is selling
Allied's Brooks Brothers chain to another foreign retailer, Marks
and Spencer PLC of Britain.
   Meanwhile, the Australian developer Hooker Corp. moved into
retailing with the purchase last year of the Bonwit Teller, B.
Altman and Sakowitz chains.
   Buying an American company is not the only way to get here. Some
smaller companies are striking out on their own. Sock Shop is among
them; so are Fil a Fil, La Sweaterie and Tricots Caroll, apparel
retailers from France.
   A foreign presence in the U.S. retailing industry is nothing
new. In 1973, Batus Inc., the U.S. arm of Britain's BAT Industries
PLC, swept in with the purchase of Saks Fifth Avenue and the
now-closed Gimbels chain.
   And the fashionable streets of cities like New York, Washington,
Palm Beach and Los Angeles have been graced for years by names such
as Gucci, Courreges and Yves St. Laurent.
   But what is different about many of these latest arrivals is
they are appealing to a larger and different market segment. Many
offer moderately-priced merchandise, giving more consumers a chance
to buy and wear clothes with foreign labels.
   With such prices, the new transplants ``have enormous
development potential in this market,'' said Charles Aug, whose
company, Garrick-Aug Associates Store Leasing Inc., scouts foreign
retailers and helps them set up shop here.
   Many of the retailers are drawn to the United States in hopes of
equaling the success of the Italian retailer Benetton, Aug said.
   Benetton has grown to 760 stores in the United States _ out of
more than 4,500 worldwide _ since the first U.S. store with its
now-familiar bright green sign opened in Manhattan in 1979, said
Sally Fischer, a spokeswoman for the Italian retailer.
   Said Aug: ``The rapid growth of Benetton generated the interest
of the other European merchants to come over here and start
moving.''
   Benetton stores are operated under licensing agreements with the
Italian company. The stores sell only Benetton fashions, and buy
the clothes from Benetton, Ms. Fischer said.
   Other retailers break into the U.S. market through franchises,
in which they can profit from an American operation without having
the expense and problems of opening and managing stores.
   Printemps, a Denver fashion retailer, is a franchisee of Au
Printemps, a French department store chain. The U.S. store, which
opened in November, operates autonomously of its namesake, but
turns over to Au Printemps a percentage of its sales, said Frank
Ball, president of the American company.
   The Denver store sells French fashions, but is ``Americanized
for practicality,'' said Ball. ``We've used the name, but (the
Denver store is) not a reflection of the store in France.''
   Some retailers own their U.S. outlets. Sock Shop opened three
stores in Manhattan in December, and ``we're delighted with the way
they're going,'' said Ms. Mirman, chairman of the company.
   Because of its size, the United States was one of several
markets Sock Shop wanted to explore, Ms. Mirman said. The company
hopes to open nine more outlets this year and eventually expand
beyond New York.
   The retailers generally get some assistance from American
advisers or brokers before setting up shop. Ms. Mirman said Sock
Shop's entry into the United States was facilitated by a minority
stockholder who lived in New York. La Sweaterie was brought into
the American market through a joint venture with David Genser, the
company's president here.
   Unlike many other foreign retailers, La Sweaterie did not try
New York first, opening instead in the Boston area, where Genser
lives. The retailer now has 29 stores in the United States,
including several in California.
   The weakness of the dollar since 1985 has helped some
foreigners, Aug said, explaining, ``Installation costs would be a
fraction of what it would have cost them a few years ago.''
   But the lower dollar can be a double-edged sword.
   ``It's cheaper to set up shop, but that's offset by the fact
that the market for goods at these price points does not grow ...
when the dollar is buying less,'' said Max Garelick, president of
Rodier U.S.A., the American arm of the French clothing chain Rodier.
   Genser agreed. ``It has hurt us,'' he said of the dollar's
decline. ``All of our clothes are made in France,'' and become more
expensive as the U.S. currency slides.
   One way to fight the impact of currency fluctuations is to
become a more American company. Benetton has started manufacturing
some of its merchandise in Rocky Mount, N.C., Ms. Fischer said.
   ``But the style will remain something that's Italian and French
_ what European companies have to offer,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday April 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
