<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade on improved prospects for rain in dry
growing regions.
   Reports of good progress in the Brazilian soybean harvest and
weak demand for soybean products on European markets added to the
losses in soybean futures, which were down more than 7{ cents a
bushel in early trading.
   But rain was the major factor affecting all the grain markets,
said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``There are forecasts for systems to come in and get some
moisture to the western corn belt states of Iowa and Nebraska, and
that's important because they've been dry,'' Loewy said.
   ``There's also the prospect for some of this moisture getting up
into the spring wheat areas'' of the northern Plains, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.15\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1} cents lower with May at $2.03\ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
2{ cents lower with May at $1.65 a bushel; soybeans were 5\ cents
to 7{ cents lower with May at $6.61{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent lower to .20 cent higher with June at
70.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with April at 79.35 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent lower
to .45 cent higher with June at 49.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .17 cent lower to .05 cent higher with May at 53.40
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
