<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-GM     04-21 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-GM,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM First-Quarter Earnings Up 18.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Thursday its
first-quarter earnings rose 18.4 percent, helped by a change in
accounting methods.
   The nation's largest automaker said it earned $1.09 billion, or
$3.11 a share, on sales of $26.44 billion. GM earned $922.5
million, or $2.62 a share, on sales of $26.1 billion in
first-quarter 1987.
   GM was the first of the Big Three auto companies to report its
earnings for the first quarter. Ford Motor Co., which outearned GM
in 1986 and 1987, and Chrysler Corp. will report earnings next week.
   First-quarter results were fattened by $224 million, or 70 cents
a share, by a Jan. 1 accounting change, GM said. Without the
change, GM's first-quarter earnings would have been $868 million,
down 5.9 percent from a year ago.
   GM said Wednesday earnings rose for two of its subsidiaries, GM
Hughes Electronics Corp. and Electronic Data Systems Corp., but
fell for the third, General Motors Acceptance Corp. because of low
interest rates to consumers.
   GM's worldwide vehicle sales were down 5.2 percent from
first-quarter 1987, but its U.S. sales of domestic and imported
cars rose more than 12 percent. Quarterly truck sales jumped 24
percent.
   GM said its share of the U.S. car market grew 4.1 percentage
points in the first quarter from the final quarter of 1987 and it
gained 2.2 points in truck market share.
   Overseas sales rose 15.5 percent in the first quarter, GM said.
   The automaker's operating earnings fell 4.3 percent to $657.6
million in the first quarter from $687.4 million a year ago.
   GM said it made improvements in manufacturing efficiency and
engineering, but the gains were not enough to offset lower sales,
GMAC's lower earnings and other cost increases.
   ``We're going to continue to cut costs and improve the
efficiency of our plants and the quality of our products,'' the
company said in a statement attributed to company Chairman Roger
Smith and President Robert Stempel.
   In 1987, GM trimmed $3.7 billion from its costs under the first
phase of a four-year plan that calls for $4 billion in cost cuts in
1988. GM said it cut $1.3 billion from its costs in first-quarter
1988.
   The company said it was encouraged by U.S. sales, which rose
against year ago figures for each month of the third quarter. GM's
lineup includes its new mid-size siblings, the Pontiac Grand Prix,
Buick Regal and Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme. GM said it had record
truck sales during the quarter.
</TEXT>
