<HEAD>Salomon Reports Higher Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Inc. reported Thursday its first quarter
profit rose 16 percent over a year ago, reflecting strength in the
company's securities and commodities units.
   The giant financial services company said it netted $173
million, or $1.19 a share, during the first three months of this
year, compared with $149 million, or $1.13 a share, in the same
period of 987.
   Quarterly revenue, however, fell to $1.61 billion from $1.72
billion.
   Pre-tax earnings at the company's Salomon Brothers brokerage
unit rose to $253 million from $248 million in 1987, which
``reverses a nine-month period of declining profitability,''
Chairman John Gutfreund said.
   In Salomon's commodities operations, Phibro Energy's earnings
before taxes totaled $27 million, up from $24 million.
   Salomon's Philipp Brothers unit reported its pre-tax profit was
up five-fold, to $15 million from $3 million. Salomon Commercial
Finance earned $45 million, compared with $36 million.
   ``After a difficult restructuring period and the streamlining of
the securities organization last fall, and post-crash turmoil in
financial markets, our expectations of improved profitability are
being realized,'' Gutfreund said in a statement.
