<HEAD>London Shares Up 5.1 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed higher in light trading
Thursday after the market turned bullish when Wall Street opened
higher.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed up 5.1
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,791.9.
   Volume was a light 397.9 million shares, compared with
Wednesday's 451.4 million shares.
   On Wall Street Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average opened
higher and moved up more than 30 points by the time London trading
wound down.
   Some traders in London had predicted that Wall Street would open
sharply higher because stock index futures closed at a premium
Wednesday in New York and would trigger computer-generated buy
programs.
   ``We were expecting Wall Street to come in stronger to give us
the lead we've been looking for all week,'' one equities salesman
said.
   Earlier Thursday, the Bank of England reported
larger-than-expected bank lending figures which disappointed the
market and caused a brief afternoon sell-off, dealers said.
   Traders cautioned that volume was extremely low, which can
magnify price movements.
   ``It only takes one or two trades to knock prices around in a
market such as this one,'' a dealer said.
</TEXT>
