<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Publishing     04-21 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Publishing,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Up at Time, Times Mirror; Loss Reported at Houghton Mifflin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. said Thursday its first-quarter profit jumped 43
percent while another publishing and broadcast concern, Times
Mirror Co., said its earnings climbed 29 percent from a year
earlier.
   Meanwhile, the publisher Houghton Mifflin Co., said normal
seasonal sluggishness in educational book orders produced a wider
loss for the company in the first quarter.
   Time, which is based in New York, said its magazine, books,
programming and cable television operations each turned in improved
results.
   It reported a profit of $66 million, or $1.13 a share, for the
three months ended March 31, compared with earnings of $46 million,
or 76 cents a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 13.4 percent to $1.07 billion from
$939 million a year earlier.
   Time said the pretax operating profit from its magazine group
rose 19 percent to $70 million because of a rise in advertising
sales that was attributed in part to the Olympics and an increase
in circulation revenue.
   Time publishes Time, Life, People, Sports Illustrated, Money and
Fortune magazines, among others.
   Time's books group broke even in contrast to an operating loss
of $3 million a year earlier. The group's results reflect a
seasonal loss at the Scott, Foresman educational book subsidiary,
improved profits at the Oxmoor House and Little Brown units and a
smaller profit at Time-Life Books.
   Operating income from the Time programming segment rose 8
percent to $39 million, as Home Box Office Inc. reported subscriber
growth and the release of several successful HBO videocassettes,
including the film ``Platoon.''
   In cable television, Time's operating profit from its 82
percent-owned American Television and Communications Corp. unit
rose 24 percent to $42 million, mostly due to new subscribers and
price increases.
   Times-Mirror, which is based in Los Angeles, said its results
were boosted by strong cable television perfomance and sales of
assets.
   The company reported net earnings of $75.1 million, or 58 cents
per share, up from $58.2 million, or 45 cents per share, in the
first quarter of 1987.
   Revenue for the quarter ended March 27 was $797.1 million, up
11.4 percent from $715.8 million in 1987.
   Operating profit improved 17 percent, paced by a 20 percent rise
in cable television revenues, absence of losses at the Denver Post,
which was sold in December 1987, and sales of timberlands and the
Times Mirror Press.
   Times-Mirror publishes the Los Angeles Times, Newsday, New York
Newsday, the Hartford Courant, the Baltimore Sun Newspapers and
others. It has interests in broadcast and cable television, book,
magazine and other publishing.
   Houghton Mifflin, which is based in Boston, said its loss
widened to $10.3 million in the first three months of 1988 from
$6.7 million a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter fell 4.7 percent to $37.8 million from
$39.7 million a year earlier.
   Harold T. Miller, chairman and chief executive, said the loss
reflected the normal seasonal ordering pattern of educational
institutions, and said he expects the sluggishness to continue
through the second quarter.
   Educational publishing sales were off 9 percent in the quarter,
while early book returns pushed down net sales in the college
division by an unspecified amount.
   General publishing sales were up 3 percent, led by strong sales
of juvenile books.
</TEXT>
