<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-ConsumerProducts     04-21 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Consumer Products,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco, Colgate Report Higher Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc., the nation's largest consumer products
company, reported Thursday its first-quarter earnings increased
24.1 percent while Colgate-Palmolive Co. said it had a 16 percent
net income gain.
   RJR Nabisco, based in Atlanta, said it earned $273 million, or
$1.09 per share, on $3.8 billion in sales for the quarter ended
March 31. That compares to $220 million, or 84 cents per share, on
$3.5 billion in sales in the comparable quarter of 1987.
   RJR's first quarter results included a gain on the sale of the
distiller Heublein Inc. The company said the gain was offset by
expenses related to restructuring activities and the cost of
retirement of high-interest debt.
   Tobacco sales were up to $1.5 billion from $1.4 billion despite
lower domestic volume, the company said. RJR credited dollar
exchange rates internationally and higher prices domestically for
the increase.
   Food sales were $2.28 billion, up from $2.1 billion, the company
said.
   ``We are especially pleased that these gains were achieved while
we continue to invest in strengthening our businesses for future
growth,'' Chairman F. Ross Johnson said.
   RJR manufactures such products as Winston cigarettes and
Nabisco, Del Monte and Planters foodstuffs.
   New York-based Colgate-Palmolive's earnings climbed to $65.4
million, or 96 cents per share, on sales of $1.45 billion in the
most recent quarter. The company had $56.4 million in earnings in
1987's first three months, or 81 cents per share, on sales of $1.31
billion.
   Colgate Chairman Reuben Mark attributed his company's growth to
the introduction of new products as well as improved performance by
international divisions.
   Colgate's products include Fab laundry detergents, Colgate oral
care products and Hill's pet products.
</TEXT>
