<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Helmsleys 3rdLd-Writethru   04-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helmsleys, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helmsley Attorneys Charge Intimidation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7, ``The federal,'' with two grafs to CORRECT that $4
million is amount of allegedly improper deductions, not amount of
tax liability</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire couple Harry and Leona Helmsley, in
a repeat of last week's state court appearance, pleaded innocent
today to federal charges stemming from an alleged $4 million tax
scam.
   Their pleas of ``not guilty'' _ the only words they spoke during
arraignment in U.S. District Court _ were followed by a date with
federal marshals for fingerprinting and mug shots.
   The 79-year-old Helmsley and his wife, whose combined estimated
net worth of $1.4 billion makes them among the world's richest
couples, sat in court with several defendants in the ``Pizza
Connection II'' heroin smuggling trial.
   At the government's recommendation, the Helmsleys were released
without bail, but must surrender their passports pending trial. The
same applied to two former Helmsley employees who are co-defendants
and also pleaded innocent.
   The couple's lawyers have charged that the wealth and prominence
of the Helmsleys, who have vast commercial real estate holdings
including a string of hotels, was a factor in their indictment.
   ``The fact that the prosecutors themselves have stated that
their investigations were triggered by articles in a New York
newspaper has led many to conclude that both the state and the
federal indictment are motivated by the prominence of the
Helmsleys,'' lawyers Stephen E. Kaufman and Gerald A. Feffer said
in a statement.
   The federal charges, a 47-count indictment that accuses the
Helmsleys of improperly claiming $4 million in deductions, are part
of an ``unfair and groundless'' attack, the lawyers said.
   The indictment alleges that the couple masked expenditures for
home renovations and other personal purchases as business expenses.
   The attorneys accused prosecutors of leaks involving the case;
singling out the Helmsleys due to their high profiles; and basing
state and federal charges on false allegations.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and state Attorney General Robert
Abrams last week announced twin indictments for tax fraud against
Helmsley and his wife, the self-proclaimed ``hotel queen.''
   The couple was named with two Helmsley employees in a 188-count
state indictment and the federal indictment for masking the
renovations and several purchases as business expenses.
   They pleaded innocent April 14 in state court after they were
booked and fingerprinted. The federal indictment additionally
charges Mrs. Helmsley, 67, and Frank Turco, 45, of Lutz, Fla., with
attempted extortion of Helmsley employees and contractors.
   In addition to Turco, former Helmsley financial manager Joseph
Licari, 51, of Oyster Bay Cove was named in both indictments.
</TEXT>
