<HEAD>Textron Reports Higher First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. said its first-quarter
earnings dropped 36 percent because of a $20 million arbitrator's
award against an insurance subisidiary and early payment of
high-interest debt.
   The aerospace, commercial products and financial services
company reported Thursday it earned $38.7 million, or 43 cents per
share, down from $60.2 million, or 72 cents per share, during the
first three months of 1987.
   Revenue for the quarter ended April 2, 1988, was unchanged from
the year-earlier period at $1.8 billion.
   The earnings drop was attributed to the $20 million award
against Balboa Insurance Co. of Irvine, Calif., a subsidiary of
Textron's Avco Financial Services. The consumer dispute involved
auto insurance Balboa sold for a Mutual of Omaha subsidiary.
   Earnings also were reduced by a one-time $9.7 million
expenditure for early redemtion of $130 million in high-interest
debt.
   Without those charges, income from continuing operations was up
11 percent.
   Referring to gains in aerospace propulsion and finance divisions
and a reduction in the company's federal tax rate, Chairman B.F.
Dolan said, ``the favorable first quarter earnings from continuing
operations get us off to an excellent start this year.''
</TEXT>
