<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Amex     04-21 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Amex,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Express Reports Drop In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. said Thursday its
first-quarter profit fell 15 percent from the same period of 1987,
when the giant financial services company recorded a big one-time
tax-related gain.
   The company, however, said its Travel Related Services division,
which runs its credit card business, had record earnings. Shearson
Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. also posted strong income during the
period, the first to include E.F. Hutton results, it said.
   For the first three months of this year, American Express netted
$266 million, or 62 cents a share, on revenue of $5.3 billion. That
compared with a restated profit of $314 million, or 71 cents, and
$4.1 billion in revenue a year ago.
   Last year's net income included $49 million of deferred income
tax benefits recorded to comply with new accounting rules.
Excluding those benefits, the first quarter earnings that year
would have totaled $265 million, about the same as this year.
   Chairman James D. Robinson III called ``most impressive'' the
latest quarterly results of American Express' Travel Related
Services and IDS Financial Services units.
   At Travel Related Services, earnings climbed 18 percent to a
record $171 million from $145 million. Revenue totaled $1.6
billion, up 17 percent from last year. The company said its
credit-card charge volume and average travelers checks outstanding
all posted ``double-digit gains.''
   IDS Financial Services had a 19 percent jump in earnings to a
record $31 million from $26 million, American Express said. The
company said annuity and life insurance operations led the increase
and that earnings also were helped by higher management fees.
   Shearson Lehman Brothers Holdings reported net income of $811
milion, compared with $78 million last year. The results included
E.F. Hutton, which was acquired by the securities firm late last
year. Revenue totaled $2.5 billion, up from $1.7 billion.
   American Express said its share of Shearson Lehman's first
quarter net was $52 million, reflecting the company's reduced
equity interest.
   American Express Bank reported first quarter net income of $27
million, after absorbing a one-time after-tax charge of $3.8
million related to staff reductions in New York. In 1987, first
quarter net income totaled $56 million, including a $19 million
gain from accounting changes.
   ``Although American Express Bank's net was down from a year ago,
its emphasis on private banking and other fee-generating activities
continues to yield positive results,'' Robinson said.
   The company said its banking unit ``continued its orderly exit
from cross-border term lending.'' Its provision for loan losses,
particulary those from troubled Third World countries, rose 56
percent to $7.8 million from $5 million.
</TEXT>
