<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-21 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Plunge On Rain Forecasts, Brazilian Harvest Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as rain dampened the dry
fields of the western Corn Belt and the South American soybean
harvest accelerated. Grains also closed lower.
   Rain in western Iowa and Nebraska, where spring planting has
just begun, melted fears that dry conditions would delay
germination of seeds, analysts said.
   Soybean prices came under additional pressure from the Brazilian
soybean harvest, now more than 50 percent complete, and the
beginning of the Argentine soybean harvest, said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc in New York.
   ``They should be 80 to 85 percent finished in May,'' he said of
the South American harvest. ``Then our crush and export rate will
tail off, and you don't get as much domestic meal feeding anyway as
we get into the warmer weather.''
   Further pressure on the soy complex came from an American
Soybean Association statement that it did not expect the
Agriculture Department to offer the Soviet Union 170 thousand
metric tons of U.S. soybean oil under its Export Enhancement
Program, Loewy said.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.14{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.02{ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to
3{ cents lower with May at $1.63{ a bushel; soybeans were 7\ cents
to 10{ cents lower with May at $6.59{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
