<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-BankAmerica 1stLd-Writethru   04-21 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-BankAmerica, 1st Ld-Writethru,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Reports 62 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS total assets figure, settlement of $28 million lawsuit
and plans to cut 5,000 jobs this year in final three grafs. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp. said Thursday its
earnings jumped 62 percent in the first quarter, marking the third
straight quarter of profitability for the recovering banking giant.
   BankAmerica, parent of Bank of America and the nation's
third-largest bank holding company, said its first-quarter earnings
totaled $109 million, or 56 cents per share, up from $67 million,
or 34 cents per share, in the first three months of 1987.
   Operating profit, which excludes one-time gains or losses, also
was on the positive side for the third straight quarter, said Frank
Newman, chief financial officer. He declined to give a dollar value
for operating profit.
   BankAmerica returned to profitability in the third quarter of
1987 after six straight quarters of red ink blamed on loan losses,
high expenses and reserves set aside for foreign debt. Net losses
from 1985 through the first half of 1987 totaled $1.92 billion.
   ``BankAmerica's solid performance in the first quarter clearly
demonstrates that our recovery is continuing,'' said A.W. Clausen,
the bank's chairman. ``We're making steady progress toward our
goals, but many challenges still lie ahead.''
   Net interest income for the quarter ended March 31 reached $775
million, up from $729 million in the same period last year.
Non-interest income during the first quarter this year was $424
million, down from $715 million in the first quarter of 1987.
   Net credit losses were $92 million, down from $315 million in
the first quarter of 1987.
   BankAmerica's assets stood at $94.3 billion.
   Last month's $28 million settlement of a class-action suit by
stockholders who said the company concealed information about its
financial problems was provided for earlier and did not affect
first-quarter results, the company said.
   The company is expected to eliminate about 5,000 jobs this year
from its workforce of approximately 59,500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
