<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-McDonald's     04-21 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-McDonald's,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 18 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp., which operates the
nation's biggest chain of fast-food restaurants, said Thursday its
first-quarter profit rose 18 percent from a year ago as its revenue
climbed 15 percent.
   First-quarter earnings rose to $125.8 million, or 67 cents a
share, for the first three months of 1988 compared with earnings of
$106.9 million, or 56 cents per share, in 1987.
   Total revenue for the first-quarter climbed to $1.23 billion
from $1.07 billion in 1987.
   Systemwide sales, which represents sales at franchised and
affiliated restaurants as well as those that the company operates,
rose 15 percent to $3.59 billion in the first quarter from $3.12
billion in 1987.
   McDonald's recently opened its 10,000th restaurant in Dale City,
Va.
   The company said the systemwide sales increase resulted from
higher sales from existing restaurants, new restaurant expansion
and the effect of stronger foreign currencies against the dollar.
   Domestic sales, helped by new product introductions such as
``Cheddar Melt'' hamburgers, climbed by 10 percent to $2.53
billion, the company said.
   The company, which recently opened restaurants in Yugoslavia and
South Korea, said the decline in the dollar helped it post a 30
percent gain in sale outside the United States to $1.06 billion
during the quarter from $811.6 million a year earlier.
   Without the decline in the dollar, foreign sales would have
risen only 17 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
