<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-21 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Narrowly Higher; Gold Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved narrowly higher against most
major currencies Thursday in uneventful trading.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $454.65 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
$456 late Wednesday.
   Traders said the dollar remained in a narrow range throughout
the session, and volume was light.
   ``It's the same pattern we've seen the last couple of days,''
said James McGroarty, a vice president at Discount Corp.
   He noted that the dollar continued to ``take somewhat of a back
seat against the British pound,'' with the pound testing the $1.90
mark against the U.S. currency.
   A report of faster-than-expected growth in Britain's money
supply led market participants in London to believe sterling
interest rates will not be lowered.
   ``That makes the pound an attractive alternative to the
dollar,'' McGroarty said.
   Ian Spence, chief dealer at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.,
noted that market participants remain bearish about the U.S.
currency. But most traders believe fears of central bank
intervention keep investors from trying to aggressively sell their
dollar holdings.
   The dollar also rose earlier in uneventful European dealings.
Foreign exchange dealers said an absence of fundamental news kept
the U.S. currency in a narrow range for mostly technical reasons.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 124.30. Later in London, it
was quoted at a slightly lower 124.18 yen. In New York, the dollar
closed at 124.27 yen, up from 124.15 yen on Wednesday.
   One British pound cost $1.8990 in the British capital, slightly
more expensive for buyers than $1.8930 late Wednesday. In New York
it cost $1.8973 to buy one pound, more expensive than Wednesday's
$1.89125.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.66715 West German marks, up from
1.66485; 1.37675 Swiss francs, up from 1.3764; 5.6605 French
francs, up from 5.6540; 1,238.625 Italian lire, up from 1,237.875,
and 1.23505 Canadian dollars, up from 1.22905.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.6660 West German marks, up from 1.6635; 1.3755 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3745; 5.6550 French francs, up from 5.6490;
1.8675 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8630; 1,238.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,234.50; and 1.2329 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2283.
   Gold prices fell. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold closed
at $455.40 a troy ounce, down from $457 an ounce Wednesday.
   In London, gold was quoted at a bid price of $454.50 a troy
ounce late Thursday, compared with late Wednesday's bid price of
$456.50. In Zurich, the bid price was $454.50, down from $457.50
late Wednesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.04 to close at
a bid $454.90.
   Silver finished at $6.450 a troy ounce on New York's Comex, up
from $6.439 on Wednesday. In London, the metal was quoted at a bid
price of $6.46 a troy ounce, unchanged from late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
