<FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Trade 2ndLd-Writethru   04-21 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT
^Eds: New with bill passing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today passed sweeping trade
legislation, ignoring fresh veto threats from President Reagan and
defiantly upholding the measure's embattled plant closings
provisions.
   ``Our future is not in the past,'' House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, said as he urged approval of the bill with the plant
closings feature intact. ``We can regain our competitiveness ... We
can be No. 1 again.''
   The bill passed by a vote of 312-107.
   President Reagan, on the road in Massachusetts, said he would
veto the legislation if it arrived on his desk with the plant
closings provision included in it.
   He also sent a letter to House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel,
R-Ill., saying, ``I want a trade bill.''
   ``I will work vigorously to secure one,'' Reagan said. ``And I
will urge the leadership to schedule prompt action on a bill
immediately after Congress sustains my forthcoming veto'' of the
current trade bill.
   The House rejected 253-167 a move by Michel to return the trade
bill to a House-Senate conference committee with orders to drop the
plant closings provision.
   Critics of the provision warned that it would not only trigger a
veto but that if it went into law it would cripple American
business by drying up capital for investment, frightening off
customers and causing other problems.
   The measure would require all but the smallest employers to
provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The provision completely overshadowed the centerpiece features
of the legislation which would streamline the system under which
the United States imposes import curbs to aid industries threatened
by foreign competition and retaliate against international trade
violations.
   Scores of other features range from repeal of the windfall
profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in agricultural
subsidies.
   Republicans portrayed the measure as doomed to a veto with the
plant closings provision still part of it.
   ``I'm more interested in plant openings than plant closings,''
said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
   ``We can exorcise this demon,'' said Rep. William Frenzel,
R-Minn.
   The legislation would overhaul the system under which the
government retaliates against international trade violations and
uses import curbs to aid American industries hurt by surging
foreign competition.
   These provisions have figured little in battles over the bill in
recent weeks, however. The White House has issued numerous threats
of a presidential veto if the plant-closings provisions remain.
   Efforts to whisk the bill through the House Rules Committee on
Wednesday were stalled for hours over Democratic concerns that
Michel would muster the strength on the floor to send the measure
back to the committee.
   ``It is my hope that through this motion we will be able to get
a trade bill that can actually be enacted into law,'' Michel said
after the Rules Committee cleared the way for him to go ahead with
his plan.
   The idea of a veto over plant closings is proving less than
appetizing to lawmakers with a host of narrow election-year items
tucked into the trade bill, ranging from repeal of the windfall
profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in agricultural
subsidies.
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III came to Capitol Hill on
Wednesday to try to rally Republican House members to oppose the
measure if the measures on plant closings remained in.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters Wednesday
the administration was ``pessimistic'' about chances that lawmakers
would send the president legislation he would sign.
   ``I would say we are not too optimistic at this point,''
Fitzwater said. ``The indications have been that the Congress is
not going to relent on plant closings as well as some of the other
provisions, so I would say that we are pretty pessimistic that we
will get a bill that we could sign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
