<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     04-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $850.6 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 421 money market mutual
funds fell $850.6 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said Thursday.
   The decline to $273.93 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $2.02 billion drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 210 general purpose funds rose $1.01 billion to $83.24
billion while assets of 97 broker-dealer funds rose 246.1 million
to $117.55 billion.
   But the trade group said assets of 114 institutional funds fell
$2.10 billion to $73.14 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds slipped
in the week ended Tuesday to 6.09 percent from 6.10 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield edged up to 6.07 percent from 6.06
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
41 days, down from 42 days the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
5.68 percent as of Wednesday from 5.67 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, fell to 5.13 percent from 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.85
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 6.82 percent
the previous week. Yields were 7.17 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
7.14 percent; 7.59 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.57 percent;
and 8.04 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.01 percent.
</TEXT>
