<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-21 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Fall With Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade as rain dampened the dry fields of the western Corn
Belt and the South American soybean harvest accelerated. Grains
also finished lower.
   On other markets, energy futures advanced; stock-index futures
plunged; precious metals were mixed; and livestock and meat futures
were mixed.
   Rain in western Iowa and Nebraska, where spring planting has
just begun, melted fears that dry conditions would delay
germination of seeds, analysts said.
   Soybean prices came under additional pressure from the Brazilian
soybean harvest, now more than 50 percent complete, and the
beginning of the Argentine soybean harvest, said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc in New York.
   ``They should be 80 to 85 percent finished in May,'' he said of
the South American harvest. ``Then our crush and export rate will
tail off, and you don't get as much domestic meal feeding anyway as
we get into the warmer weather.''
   Further pressure on the soy complex came from an American
Soybean Association statement that it did not expect the
Agriculture Department to offer the Soviet Union 170,000 metric
tons of U.S. soybean oil under its Export Enhancement Program,
Loewy said.
   Wheat settled { cent to 1 cent lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $3.14} a bushel; corn was 1} cents to 2\ cents
lower with May at $2.02\ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 3{ cents
lower with May at $1.63\ a bushel; soybeans were 7\ cents to 11
cents lower with May at $6.59{ a bushel.
   Energy futures staged a broad rally on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on reports that seven non-OPEC countries would meet with
OPEC's price committee next week in Venice to discuss production
cuts.
   ``It seems the announcement and confirmation that the cartel
would be meeting with non-OPEC producers was a very positive
sign,'' said Nauman Barakat of Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 36 cents to 38 cents
higher with June at $18.36 a barrel; heating oil was .76 cent to
1.23 cents higher with May at 50.54 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .70 cent to 1.03 cents higher with May at 52.45 cents
a gallon.
   Stock-index futures plunged late in the afternoon on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on news that the federal budget deficit for
March was a lower-than-expected $29 billion, analysts said.
   ``It was just like the good old days, very volatile,'' said John
Mitchell, executive director of financial futures for Elders
Futures Inc. in Chicago, referring to the relative calm in futures
trading since the stock market crash.
   Technically-based selling accelerated the dive, he said.
   The contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 1.7 points lower at 256.20.
   Gold futures finished modestly lower on the Commodity Exchange
in New York, basically following the lead of platinum futures,
which posted steeper losses, analysts said. Silver was marginally
higher.
   The markets reflected concerns that the Federal Reserve wants to
force interest rates higher to bring in more foreign investors to
prop up the dollar and ward off a recession, said Jack Barbanel, an
analyst with Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   Recession fears have been absent recently from the metals
markets, which have generally been trading higher on expecations of
increased inflation.
   But Barbanel said traditional indicators of inflation _ such as
widespread price increases for goods and services _ have not
surfaced.
   ``One has to seriously question this whole idea about
inflation,'' he said. ``The Fed may be using inflation as a
scapegoat to say we have to tighten money and get the interest
rates up higher.''
   Platinum settled $5.40 to $5.90 lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with July at $526.70 a troy ounce. On the Comex, gold was
$1.60 to $2.20 lower with June at $457.20 a troy ounce; silver was
1 cent higher across the board with May at $6.46 a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in
position-evening ahead of two USDA cattle-on-feed reports due out
after Friday's close.
   Analysts expect the monthly seven-state and quarterly 13-state
reports to show active placement of cattle onto feedlots, but only
moderate marketings, which would translate into greater cattle
supplies in coming months.
   Pork futures finished mostly lower on lower cash prices, said
Tom Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington
Heights, Ill.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent lower to .60 cent higher with June
at 70.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .10
cent higher with April at 79.40 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with June at 48.85 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .28 cent lower to .05 cent higher with May at
53.12 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
