<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Staley-Tate 2ndLd-Writethru   04-21 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Staley-Tate, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staley Rejects Tate & Lyle Offer But Leaves Door Open</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after the 2nd graf with Tate & Lyle arranging
financing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn syrup maker Staley Continental
Inc. rejected as inadequate a $1.33 billion takeover bid from a
British company Thursday but indicated it might entertain a better
offer.
   Tate & Lyle PLC, which made the $32-a-share cash tender offer
April 8, declined comment on Staley's decision but one analyst said
he expected the British sugar refiner to increase its bid.
   Tate & Lyle did announce it has arranged a $1.3 billion loan
agreement wiht a group of 14 banks to finance a takeover.
   Staley stock rose 75 cents to $37.50 a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading.
   Staley, the nation's second-largest refiner of corn sweeteners,
said it would consider various alternatives for enhancing
shareholder value. The options include a financial restructuring or
recapitalization, issuing stock to a third party, selling all or
part of the company, a joint venture or a leveraged buyout, Staley
Chairman Donald E. Nordlund said in a letter to stockholders.
   Spokesman David Satterfield said Staley had held discussions
with at least one other party but added that the company wanted to
remain independent.
   ``I think the board has asked management to look at all the
various alternatives because as part of its fiduciary
responsibility they've got to be able to make the best judgment
possible for shareholders,'' Satterfield said.
   One option likely to present itself is a higher offer from Tate
& Lyle, said John M. McMillan, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``I think they officially put the `for sale' sign on the
company,'' McMillan said. ``But from a shareholder's point of view,
they said all the right things: That they're contemplating
alternative moves designed to enhance the value of Staley's stock
beyond the $32 that Tate and Lyle offered.''
   McMillan said Staley probably was worth about $40 a share. But
he said he doubted a bidding war would develop.
   ``I don't think there's a line of bidders that want to get into
the U.S. sweetener industry,'' he said. ``It's a competitive market
and it takes special managerial skills.''
   Tate & Lyle is Britain's second-largest sugar refiner. An
acquisition of Staley would give it a foothold in the U.S. corn
sweetener market and make it the only supplier of all three types
of sugar _ corn, beet and cane _ in the United States.
   Tate & Lyle's owns nearly 5 percent of Staley's 30.4 million
outstanding shares of common stock and is offering to buy all
outstanding shares of all classes of stock in a deal it valued at
$1.33 billion.
   Tate & Lyle's chairman, Neil M. Shaw, has said he would move the
company's headquarters from suburban Chicago back to Decatur, the
site of Staley's largest corn-processing plant and the company's
home until three years ago.
   Staley Continental is a holding company formed in early 1985 for
the A.E. Staley Manufacturing Co. and CFS Continental Inc., a
food-service supplier.
</TEXT>
