<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade 3rdLd-Writethru   04-21 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Trade Bill by Wide Margin Despite Veto Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: The bill, to show it is a product of
House-Senate conference committee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday passed a sweeping trade
bill, delivering a sharp blow to President Reagan as supporters of
the hotly disputed measure piled up enough votes to override his
threatened veto.
   ``Our future isn't in the past,'' House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, declared as he fought a move to return the bill to a
House-Senate conference committee and drop a plant-closings
provision that Reagan said he could not approve. ``We can regain
our competitiveness. ... We can be No.1 again.''
   The final tally, 312-107, contradicted numerous forecasts that
the bill's sponsors would fail to produce the two-thirds vote
needed to override a veto.
   But many lawmakers, even if they had their doubts, appeared to
have no taste in an election year for going on record against a
measure billed as a plan to upgrade American competitiveness.
   The bill was a House-Senate compromise on two competing measures
that passed both chambers last year. The measure now goes to the
Senate, where Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., planned to
begin debate Friday. He was shooting for a vote on final passage
early next week.
   The House passed the measure after defeating, 253-167, a move by
Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., to throw the bill back to
the conference committee and drop the plant-closings provision.
   Reagan, on the road in Massachusetts, said he would veto the
bill if it came to him with the plant-closings provision intact. He
also sent a letter to Michel, saying, ``I want a trade bill.''
   ``I will work vigorously to secure one,'' Reagan said. ``And I
will urge the leadership to schedule prompt action on a bill
immediately after the Congress sustains my forthcoming veto'' of
the current trade bill.
   Controversy over the plant-closings provision overshadowed
central features of the bill, which would streamline the way the
United States imposes import curbs to aid U.S. industries and
retaliate against international trade violations.
   Scores of other provisions ranged from repeal of the windfall
profits tax to billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies.
   Dueling over plant closings provision went on almost to the last
minute.
   ``I am more interested in plant openings than plant closings,''
said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
   However, Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., said it would be a
mistake to allow such an important measure to become hung up on one
provision. ``It is so modest, so watered down, so full of
exceptions'' that it probably will not have as much effect as
lawmakers intended, he said.
   Debate focused heavily on the provision that would require all
but the smallest employers to give 60-day notice of upcoming plant
closings and large-scale layoffs. The measure contains a number of
exceptions for companies that sudenly find themselves in an
emergency.
   The centerpiece provisions would streamline the system under
which the United States imposes import curbs and other means to aid
industries threatened by foreign competition and retaliate against
international trade violatrions.
   Scores of other provisions range from repeal of the windfall
profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in new
agricultural subsidies.
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., said the bill for the first time ``establishes a policy
that will make America a winner in international competitive
markets.''
   But Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., whose amendment to roll
back Japanese trade surpluses was dropped earlier, said the measure
did not go far enough in forcing open foreign markets.
   Rep. Edward R. Madigan, R-Ill., said that with the ink barely
dry he had discovered that the 1,000-page bill would increase the
amount of Caribbean ethanol allowed in duty-free.
   ``I thought we were going to try to create jobs, I thought we
were going to create markets,'' Madigan said. ``But here we are
trying to give away some of our own jobs and give away some of our
own markets, just exactly the oppsosite of what we said we were
trying to do.''
   But Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., said ``This bill will put pressure
on our trading competitors to open up their markets and play fairly
and squarely with the trading system that we already have.''
   Republican critics of the plant-closings provision cited
business fears that plant-closings notice would reduce credit,
frighten customers, cut productivity and perhaps lead to sabotage
among disappointed employees facing layoffs. They also said it had
no direct connection with the trade issue.
</TEXT>
