<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NBCSurvey     04-21 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC Survey,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Employee Survey Finds Anxiety About GE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of NBC employees are skeptical of
General Electric Co.'s commitment to continue ownership of the
network, according to results of a survey conducted by NBC and
described in a letter sent to employees by NBC President Robert C.
Wright on Thursday.
   ``GE is viewed with skepticism and uncertainty. More employees
feel that GE will not continue its NBC ownership, even with NBC
performing well, than believe GE will be around for the long
haul,'' Wright said.
   He said even more employees believe GE will not allow NBC to
operate independently, and many don't like the effect the new
corporate owner has had on their working environment.
   GE, which is based in Fairfield, Conn., acquired NBC in 1986 as
part of its purchase of the RCA Corp., based in New York. Wright
was a GE executive before taking over as NBC president and chief
executive officer.
   A ``high percentage'' of employees do not feel their jobs are
secure, Wright said. Nevertheless, he said, they feel better off
than people in similar jobs in other areas of the industry.
   ``While almost half of the employees say they are not encouraged
by the direction they see NBC taking today, a majority of employees
say they are not likely to leave the company because of
dissatisfaction,'' Wright said in the letter.
   ``All of this anxiety is understandable,'' he wrote.
   ``Change is always stressful and the vast changes that are
taking place in the broadcasting business have understandably
resulted in considerable employee anxiety and insecurity. The
survey clearly reflects this.''
   Nonetheless, Wright said most employees said they were happy
with their jobs and a majority were felt their salaries compared
favorably to the rest of the industry.
   Wright concluded the letter by assuring employees that ``you
have been heard.'' He said next month employees would be asked to
participate in discussions of problems mentioned in the survey.
   ``Creating an atmosphere in which we can go forward with far
less doubt about NBC's goals and intentions is the first priority
of our management team for the coming year,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
