<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InsiderTrading     04-21 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radiologist Couple Settles Insider Trading Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New Jersey bank director and her
husband have settled insider trading charges by paying more than
$1.25 million in profits and fines to the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the SEC said Thursday.
   The commission said Rita Leone and Armand Leone Sr.,
radiologists from Franklin Lakes, N.J., surrendered the money
without admitting or denying the allegations, which stem from her
former position as a director in now defunct First Jersey National
Corp., acquired by National Westminster USA last year.
   The couple agreed to pay $774,302 in profits from the trades and
a one-time penalty of $480,916 under the Insider Trading Sanctions
Act of 1984, the SEC said in a statement released in New York.
   The SEC alleged that Mrs. Leone, through her privileged position
at the bank, learned last summer of the impending merger with
National Westminster and shared the secret with her husband. He in
turn allegedly leaked it to others, who weren't identified by the
SEC.
   The couple bought thousands of shares of First Jersey National
in the over-the-counter market in the weeks prior to the merger
announcement at a price of about $54 a share, well below the $77
market price when the merger was announced Aug. 5, the SEC alleged.
The final merger price was $82 a share.
   The agency said it investigated after the surveillance
department of the National Association of Securities Dealers, which
monitors over-the-counter trading, noticed unusually heavy trading
activity in First Jersey National prior to the merger announcement.
   National Westminster is the U.S. subsidiary of National
Westminister Bank PLC. Its acquisition of First Jersey created a
$15.8 billion bank holding company with 250 branches in New Jersey,
New York and the metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
