<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Union Carbide,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 53 Percent Profit Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. on Thursday reported
its first-quarter profit rose 53 percent because of increased
volume, higher selling prices and relatively stable raw material
prices in the chemicals and plastics business.
   The Danbury-based chemical giant reported net income was $101
million, or 75 cents a share, for the first quarter from $66
million, or 51 cents a share, in the same period in 1987.
   The company said sales for the quarter rose 16 percent to $1.95
billion from $1.6 billion in the same period last year.
   The current upswing in the chemicals and plastics industry is
unprecedented in recent times because it is not driven by an energy
crisis, high inflation, or major inventory building, said Chairman
Robert D. Kennedy.
