<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Continental-FirstChicago     04-21 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental-First Chicago,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Chicago To Buy Part Of Continental's Chicago Retail
Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First National Bank of Chicago said Thursday it
would acquire downtown Chicago portions of Continental Illinois
National Bank and Trust Co.'s retail banking business.
   Terms of the definitive agreement signed Thursday were not
disclosed.
   The sale will result in the transfer to First Chicago of
consumer deposits now totaling $579 million and outstanding
consumer loan balances totaling $101 million, First Chicago stated.
   About 88,000 Continental retail banking accounts will be
included in the sale, which is subject to regulatory approval.
   First Chicago said Continental customers affected by the sale
are being notified and will not have to many any change in their
accounts.
   Continental Illinois Chairman Thomas C. Theobald said the sale
of the retail operations was part of his company's strategy of
concentrating on its business and private banking operations.
   First Chicago Chairman Barry F. Sullivan said in a news release:
``This is a good strategic move for both organizations. It provides
the opportunity for First Chicago to add these accounts,
efficiently expanding our consumer banking customer base and
complementing our 1987 acquisition of First United Financial
Services Inc., and our pending purchase of Gary-Wheaton
Corporation.''
   First Chicago also has agreed in principle to lease
Continental's retail banking center at Clark and Division streets
in Chicago.
   Thursday's agreement includes most of Continental's retail
checking accounts, regular savings and money market accounts,
student loans and lines of credit, including home equity lines. It
also also covers certificates of deposit that are linked to other
accounts being transferred and secured and unsecured consumer
installment loans.
   Continental Illinois Corp., Continental Illinois National Bank
and Trust Co.'s holding company, posted a $610 million net loss
last year, its worst since since 1984.
   In 1984, Continental needed a $4.5 billion government bailout to
survive an unprecedented run on its deposits.
</TEXT>
