<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Slightly Higher In Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closing figures. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose marginally against the
Japanese yen in morning trading on Friday, while stock prices
posted moderate gains in light activity.
   The dollar opened at 124.29 yen, almost unchanged from its close
Thursday of 124.30, and edged up slightly. At midmorning it was
changing hands at 124.40 yen.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said a
lack of fresh news kept the dollar stable in early foreign exchange
activity. Trading also was uneventful on overseas markets, which
close before the Tokyo exchange opens.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, down 35.93 points on Thursday, gained 51.34 to
close the morning session at 26,879.50.
   ``Overnight stability on overseas stock markets and the
relatively stable yen-dollar exchange rates combined to fuel a
moderate advance,'' said Seiichiro Kita of Daiwa Securities Co., a
major Japanese brokerage.
   Kita said some market participants were taking a cautious
position because of uncertainty over prospects for U.S. interest
rates, ``but otherwise the market's firmness will continue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
